window.AUDIOBOOK_DATA = {"title":{"zh":"圣诞欢歌","en":"A Christmas Carol"},"author":{"zh":"查尔斯·狄更斯","en":"Charles Dickens"},"staves":[{"id":"Stave_I","title":{"zh":"第一章","en":"STAVE I."},"sections":[{"id":"I_01","number":1,"zh":{"text":"第一章\n马利的鬼魂\n首先要交代的是：马利死了。\n这一点千真万确，毫无疑问。\n他的丧葬登记簿上，签着牧师、教堂执事、殡葬承办人和主丧人的名字。\n斯克鲁奇也签了名；而斯克鲁奇的名字在交易所里是响当当的，凡是他肯出手担保的事，没有不算数的。\n老马利死得透透的，跟门钉一样。\n听着！\n我并不是说，凭我自己的见识，我懂得门钉究竟有什么特别该死的地方。\n说实话，我自己倒情愿把棺材钉看作这一行里最死的物件。\n可先人的智慧都凝在这句俗话里了；我这双不敬神的手是断不该去搅扰它的，否则这国家就完了。\n所以，请容许我郑重其事地再说一遍：马利死得透透的，跟门钉一样。\n斯克鲁奇知道他死了吗？\n那还用说。\n不然又怎么可能呢？\n斯克鲁奇跟他合伙做生意，也不知有多少年头了。\n斯克鲁奇是他唯一的遗嘱执行人、唯一的财产管理人、唯一的受让人、唯一的剩余遗产继承人、唯一的朋友、唯一的送葬人。\n然而，纵使遇上这桩伤心事，斯克鲁奇也并没有悲痛得不成样子；就在出殡那天，他照样是个精明能干的生意人，还趁机做成了一笔稳赚不赔的买卖，权当替丧事添了几分庄重。\n提起马利的葬礼，又把我拉回到开头那句话上。\n马利确确实实是死了，这是毫无疑问的。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_I_小节01.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":1.237,"text":"第一章"},{"start":1.187,"end":2.775,"text":"马利的鬼魂"},{"start":2.775,"end":5.825,"text":"首先要交代的是：马利死了。"},{"start":5.825,"end":8.587,"text":"这一点千真万确，毫无疑问。"},{"start":8.587,"end":15.3,"text":"他的丧葬登记簿上，签着牧师、教堂执事、殡葬承办人和主丧人的名字。"},{"start":15.3,"end":23.912,"text":"斯克鲁奇也签了名；而斯克鲁奇的名字在交易所里是响当当的，凡是他肯出手担保的事，没有不算数的。"},{"start":23.912,"end":26.875,"text":"老马利死得透透的，跟门钉一样。"},{"start":26.875,"end":27.887,"text":"听着！"},{"start":27.887,"end":33.9,"text":"我并不是说，凭我自己的见识，我懂得门钉究竟有什么特别该死的地方。"},{"start":33.9,"end":39.312,"text":"说实话，我自己倒情愿把棺材钉看作这一行里最死的物件。"},{"start":39.312,"end":47.875,"text":"可先人的智慧都凝在这句俗话里了；我这双不敬神的手是断不该去搅扰它的，否则这国家就完了。"},{"start":47.875,"end":53.512,"text":"所以，请容许我郑重其事地再说一遍：马利死得透透的，跟门钉一样。"},{"start":53.512,"end":55.975,"text":"斯克鲁奇知道他死了吗？"},{"start":55.975,"end":57.35,"text":"那还用说。"},{"start":57.35,"end":59.075,"text":"不然又怎么可能呢？"},{"start":59.075,"end":63.325,"text":"斯克鲁奇跟他合伙做生意，也不知有多少年头了。"},{"start":63.325,"end":73.612,"text":"斯克鲁奇是他唯一的遗嘱执行人、唯一的财产管理人、唯一的受让人、唯一的剩余遗产继承人、唯一的朋友、唯一的送葬人。"},{"start":73.612,"end":88.387,"text":"然而，纵使遇上这桩伤心事，斯克鲁奇也并没有悲痛得不成样子；就在出殡那天，他照样是个精明能干的生意人，还趁机做成了一笔稳赚不赔的买卖，权当替丧事添了几分庄重。"},{"start":88.387,"end":92.325,"text":"提起马利的葬礼，又把我拉回到开头那句话上。"},{"start":92.325,"end":95.937,"text":"马利确确实实是死了，这是毫无疑问的。"}]},"en":{"text":"STAVE I.\nMARLEY'S GHOST.\nMarley was dead: to begin with.\nThere is no doubt whatever about that.\nThe register of his burial was signed by the clergyman, the clerk, the undertaker, and the chief mourner.\nScrooge signed it: and Scrooge's name was good upon 'Change, for anything he chose to put his hand to.\nOld Marley was as dead as a door-nail.\nMind!\nI don't mean to say that I know, of my own knowledge, what there is particularly dead about a door-nail.\nI might have been inclined, myself, to regard a coffin-nail as the deadest piece of ironmongery in the trade.\nBut the wisdom of our ancestors is in the simile; and my unhallowed hands shall not disturb it, or the Country's done for.\nYou will therefore permit me to repeat, emphatically, that Marley was as dead as a door-nail.\nScrooge knew he was dead?\nOf course he did.\nHow could it be otherwise?\nScrooge and he were partners for I don't know how many years.\nScrooge was his sole executor, his sole administrator, his sole assign, his sole residuary legatee, his sole friend and sole mourner.\nAnd even Scrooge was not so dreadfully cut up by the sad event, but that he was an excellent man of business on the very day of the funeral, and solemnised it with an undoubted bargain.\nThe mention of Marley's funeral brings me back to the point I started from.\nThere is no doubt that Marley was dead.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_I_小节01.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":1.812,"text":"STAVE I."},{"start":1.762,"end":3.7,"text":"MARLEY'S GHOST."},{"start":3.7,"end":6.662,"text":"Marley was dead: to begin with."},{"start":6.662,"end":9.4,"text":"There is no doubt whatever about that."},{"start":9.4,"end":16.012,"text":"The register of his burial was signed by the clergyman, the clerk, the undertaker, and the chief mourner."},{"start":16.012,"end":22.712,"text":"Scrooge signed it: and Scrooge's name was good upon 'Change, for anything he chose to put his hand to."},{"start":22.712,"end":25.712,"text":"Old Marley was as dead as a door-nail."},{"start":25.712,"end":27.225,"text":"Mind!"},{"start":27.225,"end":33.475,"text":"I don't mean to say that I know, of my own knowledge, what there is particularly dead about a door-nail."},{"start":33.475,"end":40.2,"text":"I might have been inclined, myself, to regard a coffin-nail as the deadest piece of ironmongery in the trade."},{"start":40.2,"end":47.85,"text":"But the wisdom of our ancestors is in the simile; and my unhallowed hands shall not disturb it, or the Country's done for."},{"start":47.85,"end":53.912,"text":"You will therefore permit me to repeat, emphatically, that Marley was as dead as a door-nail."},{"start":53.912,"end":56.262,"text":"Scrooge knew he was dead?"},{"start":56.262,"end":58.2,"text":"Of course he did."},{"start":58.2,"end":60.4,"text":"How could it be otherwise?"},{"start":60.4,"end":64.325,"text":"Scrooge and he were partners for I don't know how many years."},{"start":64.325,"end":73.425,"text":"Scrooge was his sole executor, his sole administrator, his sole assign, his sole residuary legatee, his sole friend and sole mourner."},{"start":73.425,"end":83.525,"text":"And even Scrooge was not so dreadfully cut up by the sad event, but that he was an excellent man of business on the very day of the funeral, and solemnised it with an undoubted bargain."},{"start":83.525,"end":87.95,"text":"The mention of Marley's funeral brings me back to the point I started from."},{"start":87.95,"end":90.837,"text":"There is no doubt that Marley was dead."}]}},{"id":"I_02","number":2,"zh":{"text":"这一点务必弄个明白，否则我接下来要讲的故事便没有什么稀奇可言了。\n倘若我们不曾深信哈姆雷特的父亲在戏开场之前就已经死了，那么他趁着夜里刮东风时到自家城墙上去散步，也就不见得比任何别的中年绅士在天黑后冒冒失失跑到风口里去——比方说跑到圣保罗大教堂的墓地——存心吓唬他那意志薄弱的儿子，来得更稀奇了。\n斯克鲁奇始终没把老马利的名字涂掉。\n多年以后，那名字仍旧高悬在货栈门楣上：斯克鲁奇与马利商行。\n这家字号就叫斯克鲁奇与马利。\n有些初来打交道的人，有时管斯克鲁奇叫斯克鲁奇，有时又叫他马利，可他对两个名字一概答应：在他看来全都一样。\n哦！\n可斯克鲁奇这个人，攥起钱来真是抠得要命！他是个会盘剥、会榨取、会攫夺、会刮削、会紧抓不放、贪得无厌的老罪人！\n硬邦邦、冷冰冰，活像一块燧石，可任凭什么钢铁也从他身上敲不出一星半点慷慨的火花；他守口如瓶、孤芳自赏、形单影只，像一只蚌。\n他内心的那股寒气冻僵了他衰老的面容，冻得他尖鼻子发紫，腮帮子干瘪，步态僵硬；冻得他双眼通红，薄嘴唇发青；连他那刺耳的嗓音里也透着一股精明的冷意。\n他的脑袋上、眉毛上，还有那硬如铁丝的下巴上，都结着一层白霜。\n他无论走到哪儿，总把自己那份低温随身带着；三伏天里他能把账房冻成冰窖，到了圣诞节也不肯回升一度。\n外界的冷暖对斯克鲁奇几乎不起作用。\n再暖的天暖不了他，再冷的天也冻不着他。\n任凭什么风刮起来都没有他刻薄，任凭什么雪落下来都没有他那么死心眼，任凭什么雨倾盆而下都不及他那样油盐不进。\n坏天气拿他一点办法也没有。\n最大的雨、雪、冰雹和雨夹雪，论起来也只有一桩比他强。\n它们常常慷慨地\"倾倒\"下来，斯克鲁奇却从来一毛不拔。\n从没有人在街上拦住他，喜笑颜开地说一声：\"亲爱的斯克鲁奇，您好哇？什么时候来看看我呀？\"没有乞丐求他赏一个小钱，没有孩子问他几点钟了，他这辈子也从没有哪个男人或女人向他打听过去某处该怎么走。\n就连瞎子牵的狗似乎都认得他；一见他走过来，便拽着主人躲进门洞、钻进小巷，然后摇起尾巴，仿佛在说：\"瞎了眼倒比长着一只毒眼强呢，黑心的主人！\"","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_I_小节02.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":5.875,"text":"这一点务必弄个明白，否则我接下来要讲的故事便没有什么稀奇可言了。"},{"start":5.825,"end":28.125,"text":"倘若我们不曾深信哈姆雷特的父亲在戏开场之前就已经死了，那么他趁着夜里刮东风时到自家城墙上去散步，也就不见得比任何别的中年绅士在天黑后冒冒失失跑到风口里去——比方说跑到圣保罗大教堂的墓地——存心吓唬他那意志薄弱的儿子，来得更稀奇了。"},{"start":28.125,"end":31.65,"text":"斯克鲁奇始终没把老马利的名字涂掉。"},{"start":31.65,"end":37.4,"text":"多年以后，那名字仍旧高悬在货栈门楣上：斯克鲁奇与马利商行。"},{"start":37.4,"end":40.525,"text":"这家字号就叫斯克鲁奇与马利。"},{"start":40.525,"end":50.2,"text":"有些初来打交道的人，有时管斯克鲁奇叫斯克鲁奇，有时又叫他马利，可他对两个名字一概答应：在他看来全都一样。"},{"start":50.2,"end":51.1,"text":"哦！"},{"start":51.1,"end":55.287,"text":"可斯克鲁奇这个人，攥起钱来真是抠得要命！"},{"start":55.287,"end":62.337,"text":"他是个会盘剥、会榨取、会攫夺、会刮削、会紧抓不放、贪得无厌的老罪人！"},{"start":62.337,"end":74.937,"text":"硬邦邦、冷冰冰，活像一块燧石，可任凭什么钢铁也从他身上敲不出一星半点慷慨的火花；他守口如瓶、孤芳自赏、形单影只，像一只蚌。"},{"start":74.937,"end":89.65,"text":"他内心的那股寒气冻僵了他衰老的面容，冻得他尖鼻子发紫，腮帮子干瘪，步态僵硬；冻得他双眼通红，薄嘴唇发青；连他那刺耳的嗓音里也透着一股精明的冷意。"},{"start":89.65,"end":95.287,"text":"他的脑袋上、眉毛上，还有那硬如铁丝的下巴上，都结着一层白霜。"},{"start":95.287,"end":104.912,"text":"他无论走到哪儿，总把自己那份低温随身带着；三伏天里他能把账房冻成冰窖，到了圣诞节也不肯回升一度。"},{"start":104.912,"end":108.487,"text":"外界的冷暖对斯克鲁奇几乎不起作用。"},{"start":108.487,"end":112.375,"text":"再暖的天暖不了他，再冷的天也冻不着他。"},{"start":112.375,"end":121.837,"text":"任凭什么风刮起来都没有他刻薄，任凭什么雪落下来都没有他那么死心眼，任凭什么雨倾盆而下都不及他那样油盐不进。"},{"start":121.837,"end":124.75,"text":"坏天气拿他一点办法也没有。"},{"start":124.75,"end":130.537,"text":"最大的雨、雪、冰雹和雨夹雪，论起来也只有一桩比他强。"},{"start":130.537,"end":135.575,"text":"它们常常慷慨地\"倾倒\"下来，斯克鲁奇却从来一毛不拔。"},{"start":135.575,"end":141.312,"text":"从没有人在街上拦住他，喜笑颜开地说一声：\"亲爱的斯克鲁奇，您好哇？"},{"start":141.312,"end":151.862,"text":"什么时候来看看我呀？\"没有乞丐求他赏一个小钱，没有孩子问他几点钟了，他这辈子也从没有哪个男人或女人向他打听过去某处该怎么走。"},{"start":151.862,"end":165.212,"text":"就连瞎子牵的狗似乎都认得他；一见他走过来，便拽着主人躲进门洞、钻进小巷，然后摇起尾巴，仿佛在说：\"瞎了眼倒比长着一只毒眼强呢，黑心的主人！"}]},"en":{"text":"This must be distinctly understood, or nothing wonderful can come of the story I am going to relate.\nIf we were not perfectly convinced that Hamlet's Father died before the play began, there would be nothing more remarkable in his taking a stroll at night, in an easterly wind, upon his own ramparts, than there would be in any other middle-aged gentleman rashly turning out after dark in a breezy spot--say Saint Paul's Churchyard for instance--literally to astonish his son's weak mind.\nScrooge never painted out Old Marley's name.\nThere it stood, years afterwards, above the warehouse door: Scrooge and Marley.\nThe firm was known as Scrooge and Marley.\nSometimes people new to the business called Scrooge Scrooge, and sometimes Marley, but he answered to both names: it was all the same to him.\nOh!\nBut he was a tight-fisted hand at the grindstone, Scrooge! a squeezing, wrenching, grasping, scraping, clutching, covetous old sinner!\nHard and sharp as flint, from which no steel had ever struck out generous fire; secret, and self-contained, and solitary as an oyster.\nThe cold within him froze his old features, nipped his pointed nose, shrivelled his cheek, stiffened his gait; made his eyes red, his thin lips blue; and spoke out shrewdly in his grating voice.\nA frosty rime was on his head, and on his eyebrows, and his wiry chin.\nHe carried his own low temperature always about with him; he iced his office in the dog-days; and didn't thaw it one degree at Christmas.\nExternal heat and cold had little influence on Scrooge.\nNo warmth could warm, nor wintry weather chill him.\nNo wind that blew was bitterer than he, no falling snow was more intent upon its purpose, no pelting rain less open to entreaty.\nFoul weather didn't know where to have him.\nThe heaviest rain, and snow, and hail, and sleet, could boast of the advantage over him in only one respect.\nThey often \"came down\" handsomely, and Scrooge never did.\nNobody ever stopped him in the street to say, with gladsome looks, \"My dear Scrooge, how are you? when will you come to see me?\" No beggars implored him to bestow a trifle, no children asked him what it was o'clock, no man or woman ever once in all his life inquired the way to such and such a place, of Scrooge.\nEven the blindmen's dogs appeared to know him; and when they saw him coming on, would tug their owners into doorways and up courts; and then would wag their tails as though they said, \"no eye at all is better than an evil eye, dark master!\"","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_I_小节02.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":6.112,"text":"This must be distinctly understood, or nothing wonderful can come of the story I am going to relate."},{"start":6.062,"end":26.65,"text":"If we were not perfectly convinced that Hamlet's Father died before the play began, there would be nothing more remarkable in his taking a stroll at night, in an easterly wind, upon his own ramparts, than there would be in any other middle-aged gentleman rashly turning out after dark in a breezy spot--say Saint Paul's Churchyard for instance--literally to astonish his son's weak mind."},{"start":26.65,"end":30.075,"text":"Scrooge never painted out Old Marley's name."},{"start":30.075,"end":35.787,"text":"There it stood, years afterwards, above the warehouse door: Scrooge and Marley."},{"start":35.787,"end":38.825,"text":"The firm was known as Scrooge and Marley."},{"start":38.825,"end":47.5,"text":"Sometimes people new to the business called Scrooge Scrooge, and sometimes Marley, but he answered to both names: it was all the same to him."},{"start":47.5,"end":48.725,"text":"Oh!"},{"start":48.725,"end":53.037,"text":"But he was a tight-fisted hand at the grindstone, Scrooge!"},{"start":53.037,"end":59.25,"text":"a squeezing, wrenching, grasping, scraping, clutching, covetous old sinner!"},{"start":59.25,"end":68.312,"text":"Hard and sharp as flint, from which no steel had ever struck out generous fire; secret, and self-contained, and solitary as an oyster."},{"start":68.312,"end":80.837,"text":"The cold within him froze his old features, nipped his pointed nose, shrivelled his cheek, stiffened his gait; made his eyes red, his thin lips blue; and spoke out shrewdly in his grating voice."},{"start":80.837,"end":86.137,"text":"A frosty rime was on his head, and on his eyebrows, and his wiry chin."},{"start":86.137,"end":94.337,"text":"He carried his own low temperature always about with him; he iced his office in the dog-days; and didn't thaw it one degree at Christmas."},{"start":94.337,"end":98.437,"text":"External heat and cold had little influence on Scrooge."},{"start":98.437,"end":102.175,"text":"No warmth could warm, nor wintry weather chill him."},{"start":102.175,"end":110.537,"text":"No wind that blew was bitterer than he, no falling snow was more intent upon its purpose, no pelting rain less open to entreaty."},{"start":110.537,"end":113.4,"text":"Foul weather didn't know where to have him."},{"start":113.4,"end":121.025,"text":"The heaviest rain, and snow, and hail, and sleet, could boast of the advantage over him in only one respect."},{"start":121.025,"end":125.537,"text":"They often \"came down\" handsomely, and Scrooge never did."},{"start":125.537,"end":131.775,"text":"Nobody ever stopped him in the street to say, with gladsome looks, \"My dear Scrooge, how are you?"},{"start":131.775,"end":133.9,"text":"when will you come to see me?"},{"start":133.9,"end":144.925,"text":"No beggars implored him to bestow a trifle, no children asked him what it was o'clock, no man or woman ever once in all his life inquired the way to such and such a place, of Scrooge."},{"start":144.925,"end":158.212,"text":"Even the blindmen's dogs appeared to know him; and when they saw him coming on, would tug their owners into doorways and up courts; and then would wag their tails as though they said, \"no eye at all is better than an evil eye, dark master!"}]}},{"id":"I_03","number":3,"zh":{"text":"可斯克鲁奇何尝在乎？\n这正是他求之不得的。\n挤在熙熙攘攘的人生道路上独自侧身而行，把一切人间的温情都警告得远远避开——在那些识相的人看来，这正是斯克鲁奇的\"乐子\"。\n且说从前有一回——在一年中所有的好日子里，偏偏是在圣诞前夜——老斯克鲁奇正坐在账房里忙活。\n天气又冷、又阴、又刺骨，还罩着浓雾；他听得见外面院子里的人哈着白气来来去去，捶打着胸口，在石板路上跺着脚取暖。\n城里的钟才刚敲过三点，可天已经黑透了——这一整天就没亮堂过——邻近几家账房的窗子里都点起了蜡烛，像一团团红晕涂抹在那看得见摸得着的褐色雾气上。\n雾从每一道缝隙、每一个钥匙孔里灌进来，外头浓得化不开，以至于尽管院子窄得不能再窄，对面那几幢房子也只剩下模模糊糊的影子。\n望着那昏暗的云气低低垂落，把一切都遮蔽起来，真叫人以为大自然就住在近旁，正在大锅大灶地酿造着什么。\n斯克鲁奇账房的门敞开着，好让他能盯住他那伙计——伙计正在外面一间阴森的小屋里抄写信件，那小屋活像一口水槽。\n斯克鲁奇生着一炉小得可怜的火，可伙计那炉火更小，小得只剩一块煤的光景。\n可伙计又添不得煤，因为斯克鲁奇把煤箱锁在自己屋里；伙计但凡拿着煤铲走进来，东家准会扬言说，看来他俩非散伙不可了。\n于是伙计裹上他那条白围巾，凑到烛火前想暖一暖身子；只可惜他想象力不算丰富，这一番努力终归落了空。\n\"圣诞快乐，舅舅！\n上帝保佑您！\"一个欢快的声音嚷道。\n这是斯克鲁奇外甥的声音，他来得那样快，斯克鲁奇直到这一声才察觉他已经到了跟前。\n\"呸！\"斯克鲁奇说，\"全是胡扯！\"\n斯克鲁奇这位外甥在雾里霜里疾走过来，浑身都热气腾腾，红光满面；他面色红润俊朗，双眼炯炯有神，呵出的气又冒起了白烟。\n\"圣诞节是胡扯，舅舅！\"斯克鲁奇的外甥说。\n\"您准不是这个意思，我敢肯定。\"\n\"我就是这个意思，\"斯克鲁奇说。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_I_小节03.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":2.787,"text":"可斯克鲁奇何尝在乎？"},{"start":2.737,"end":5,"text":"这正是他求之不得的。"},{"start":5,"end":15.962,"text":"挤在熙熙攘攘的人生道路上独自侧身而行，把一切人间的温情都警告得远远避开——在那些识相的人看来，这正是斯克鲁奇的\"乐子\"。"},{"start":15.962,"end":24.45,"text":"且说从前有一回——在一年中所有的好日子里，偏偏是在圣诞前夜——老斯克鲁奇正坐在账房里忙活。"},{"start":24.45,"end":35.875,"text":"天气又冷、又阴、又刺骨，还罩着浓雾；他听得见外面院子里的人哈着白气来来去去，捶打着胸口，在石板路上跺着脚取暖。"},{"start":35.875,"end":49.15,"text":"城里的钟才刚敲过三点，可天已经黑透了——这一整天就没亮堂过——邻近几家账房的窗子里都点起了蜡烛，像一团团红晕涂抹在那看得见摸得着的褐色雾气上。"},{"start":49.15,"end":60.6,"text":"雾从每一道缝隙、每一个钥匙孔里灌进来，外头浓得化不开，以至于尽管院子窄得不能再窄，对面那几幢房子也只剩下模模糊糊的影子。"},{"start":60.6,"end":70.225,"text":"望着那昏暗的云气低低垂落，把一切都遮蔽起来，真叫人以为大自然就住在近旁，正在大锅大灶地酿造着什么。"},{"start":70.225,"end":80.575,"text":"斯克鲁奇账房的门敞开着，好让他能盯住他那伙计——伙计正在外面一间阴森的小屋里抄写信件，那小屋活像一口水槽。"},{"start":80.575,"end":87.4,"text":"斯克鲁奇生着一炉小得可怜的火，可伙计那炉火更小，小得只剩一块煤的光景。"},{"start":87.4,"end":98.5,"text":"可伙计又添不得煤，因为斯克鲁奇把煤箱锁在自己屋里；伙计但凡拿着煤铲走进来，东家准会扬言说，看来他俩非散伙不可了。"},{"start":98.5,"end":108.725,"text":"于是伙计裹上他那条白围巾，凑到烛火前想暖一暖身子；只可惜他想象力不算丰富，这一番努力终归落了空。"},{"start":108.725,"end":110.712,"text":"圣诞快乐，舅舅！"},{"start":110.712,"end":113.837,"text":"上帝保佑您！\"一个欢快的声音嚷道。"},{"start":113.837,"end":121.362,"text":"这是斯克鲁奇外甥的声音，他来得那样快，斯克鲁奇直到这一声才察觉他已经到了跟前。"},{"start":121.362,"end":122.287,"text":"呸！"},{"start":122.287,"end":124.825,"text":"斯克鲁奇说，\"全是胡扯！"},{"start":124.825,"end":136.487,"text":"斯克鲁奇这位外甥在雾里霜里疾走过来，浑身都热气腾腾，红光满面；他面色红润俊朗，双眼炯炯有神，呵出的气又冒起了白烟。"},{"start":136.487,"end":140.425,"text":"圣诞节是胡扯，舅舅！\"斯克鲁奇的外甥说。"},{"start":140.425,"end":142.975,"text":"您准不是这个意思，我敢肯定。"},{"start":142.975,"end":145.675,"text":"我就是这个意思，\"斯克鲁奇说。"}]},"en":{"text":"But what did Scrooge care?\nIt was the very thing he liked.\nTo edge his way along the crowded paths of life, warning all human sympathy to keep its distance, was what the knowing ones call \"nuts\" to Scrooge.\nOnce upon a time--of all the good days in the year, on Christmas Eve--old Scrooge sat busy in his counting-house.\nIt was cold, bleak, biting weather: foggy withal: and he could hear the people in the court outside go wheezing up and down, beating their hands upon their breasts, and stamping their feet upon the pavement-stones to warm them.\nThe city clocks had only just gone three, but it was quite dark already: it had not been light all day: and candles were flaring in the windows of the neighbouring offices, like ruddy smears upon the palpable brown air.\nThe fog came pouring in at every chink and keyhole, and was so dense without, that although the court was of the narrowest, the houses opposite were mere phantoms.\nTo see the dingy cloud come drooping down, obscuring everything, one might have thought that Nature lived hard by, and was brewing on a large scale.\nThe door of Scrooge's counting-house was open that he might keep his eye upon his clerk, who in a dismal little cell beyond, a sort of tank, was copying letters.\nScrooge had a very small fire, but the clerk's fire was so very much smaller that it looked like one coal.\nBut he couldn't replenish it, for Scrooge kept the coal-box in his own room; and so surely as the clerk came in with the shovel, the master predicted that it would be necessary for them to part.\nWherefore the clerk put on his white comforter, and tried to warm himself at the candle; in which effort, not being a man of a strong imagination, he failed.\n\"A merry Christmas, uncle!\nGod save you!\" cried a cheerful voice.\nIt was the voice of Scrooge's nephew, who came upon him so quickly that this was the first intimation he had of his approach.\n\"Bah!\" said Scrooge, \"Humbug!\"\nHe had so heated himself with rapid walking in the fog and frost, this nephew of Scrooge's, that he was all in a glow; his face was ruddy and handsome; his eyes sparkled, and his breath smoked again.\n\"Christmas a humbug, uncle!\" said Scrooge's nephew.\n\"You don't mean that, I am sure.\"\n\"I do,\" said Scrooge.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_I_小节03.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":2.4,"text":"But what did Scrooge care?"},{"start":2.35,"end":4.887,"text":"It was the very thing he liked."},{"start":4.887,"end":14.225,"text":"To edge his way along the crowded paths of life, warning all human sympathy to keep its distance, was what the knowing ones call \"nuts\" to Scrooge."},{"start":14.225,"end":21.075,"text":"Once upon a time--of all the good days in the year, on Christmas Eve--old Scrooge sat busy in his counting-house."},{"start":21.075,"end":34.037,"text":"It was cold, bleak, biting weather: foggy withal: and he could hear the people in the court outside go wheezing up and down, beating their hands upon their breasts, and stamping their feet upon the pavement-stones to warm them."},{"start":34.037,"end":46.537,"text":"The city clocks had only just gone three, but it was quite dark already: it had not been light all day: and candles were flaring in the windows of the neighbouring offices, like ruddy smears upon the palpable brown air."},{"start":46.537,"end":56.337,"text":"The fog came pouring in at every chink and keyhole, and was so dense without, that although the court was of the narrowest, the houses opposite were mere phantoms."},{"start":56.337,"end":65.325,"text":"To see the dingy cloud come drooping down, obscuring everything, one might have thought that Nature lived hard by, and was brewing on a large scale."},{"start":65.325,"end":74.825,"text":"The door of Scrooge's counting-house was open that he might keep his eye upon his clerk, who in a dismal little cell beyond, a sort of tank, was copying letters."},{"start":74.825,"end":81.462,"text":"Scrooge had a very small fire, but the clerk's fire was so very much smaller that it looked like one coal."},{"start":81.462,"end":92.062,"text":"But he couldn't replenish it, for Scrooge kept the coal-box in his own room; and so surely as the clerk came in with the shovel, the master predicted that it would be necessary for them to part."},{"start":92.062,"end":101.662,"text":"Wherefore the clerk put on his white comforter, and tried to warm himself at the candle; in which effort, not being a man of a strong imagination, he failed."},{"start":101.662,"end":104.225,"text":"A merry Christmas, uncle!"},{"start":104.225,"end":107.687,"text":"God save you!\" cried a cheerful voice."},{"start":107.687,"end":114.987,"text":"It was the voice of Scrooge's nephew, who came upon him so quickly that this was the first intimation he had of his approach."},{"start":114.987,"end":118.187,"text":"Bah!\" said Scrooge, \"Humbug!"},{"start":118.187,"end":130.4,"text":"He had so heated himself with rapid walking in the fog and frost, this nephew of Scrooge's, that he was all in a glow; his face was ruddy and handsome; his eyes sparkled, and his breath smoked again."},{"start":130.4,"end":134.5,"text":"Christmas a humbug, uncle!\" said Scrooge's nephew."},{"start":134.5,"end":137.287,"text":"You don't mean that, I am sure."},{"start":137.287,"end":139.812,"text":"I do,\" said Scrooge."}]}},{"id":"I_04","number":4,"zh":{"text":"\"圣诞快乐！你有什么资格快乐？你有什么理由快乐？\n你穷得叮当响。\"\n\"得了吧，\"外甥乐呵呵地回敬道。\n\"那您又有什么资格阴沉着脸？有什么理由这样乖戾？\n您可富得很哪。\"\n斯克鲁奇一时想不出更好的回答，便又说了声\"呸！\"接着补上一句\"胡扯\"。\n\"别生气嘛，舅舅。\"外甥说。\n\"我住在这么一个满是傻瓜的世界里，\"舅舅回道，\"叫我还能怎么样？\n圣诞快乐！\n去他的圣诞快乐！\n圣诞节对你来说算个什么——还不就是个没钱也得付账的日子；是个让你发觉自己又老了一岁、却没富上一个钟头的日子；是个让你结清账簿、看着整整十二个月里每一笔进项都明摆着跟你作对的日子？\n要是能随了我的心愿，\"斯克鲁奇愤愤地说，\"凡是嘴里挂着'圣诞快乐'的蠢货，统统该用他自己的布丁煮熟了，心口插上一根冬青木桩埋掉。\n就该这样！\"\n\"舅舅！\"外甥恳求道。\n\"外甥！\"舅舅板着脸回道，\"你过你的圣诞节，让我过我的。\"\n\"过圣诞节！\"斯克鲁奇的外甥重复道。\n\"可您根本就不过呀。\"\n\"那就让我不过好了，\"斯克鲁奇说。\n\"愿它给你带来天大的好处吧！\n它一向给你带来过多大的好处呀！\"","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_I_小节04.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":1.5,"text":"圣诞快乐！"},{"start":1.45,"end":3.225,"text":"你有什么资格快乐？"},{"start":3.225,"end":4.95,"text":"你有什么理由快乐？"},{"start":4.95,"end":6.687,"text":"你穷得叮当响。"},{"start":6.687,"end":9.6,"text":"得了吧，\"外甥乐呵呵地回敬道。"},{"start":9.6,"end":12.112,"text":"那您又有什么资格阴沉着脸？"},{"start":12.112,"end":14.025,"text":"有什么理由这样乖戾？"},{"start":14.025,"end":15.575,"text":"您可富得很哪。"},{"start":15.575,"end":21.475,"text":"斯克鲁奇一时想不出更好的回答，便又说了声\"呸！\"接着补上一句\"胡扯\"。"},{"start":21.475,"end":24.162,"text":"别生气嘛，舅舅。\"外甥说。"},{"start":24.162,"end":29.275,"text":"我住在这么一个满是傻瓜的世界里，\"舅舅回道，\"叫我还能怎么样？"},{"start":29.275,"end":30.675,"text":"圣诞快乐！"},{"start":30.675,"end":32.525,"text":"去他的圣诞快乐！"},{"start":32.525,"end":48.662,"text":"圣诞节对你来说算个什么——还不就是个没钱也得付账的日子；是个让你发觉自己又老了一岁、却没富上一个钟头的日子；是个让你结清账簿、看着整整十二个月里每一笔进项都明摆着跟你作对的日子？"},{"start":48.662,"end":59.862,"text":"要是能随了我的心愿，\"斯克鲁奇愤愤地说，\"凡是嘴里挂着'圣诞快乐'的蠢货，统统该用他自己的布丁煮熟了，心口插上一根冬青木桩埋掉。"},{"start":59.862,"end":61.175,"text":"就该这样！"},{"start":61.175,"end":63.375,"text":"舅舅！\"外甥恳求道。"},{"start":63.375,"end":67.837,"text":"外甥！\"舅舅板着脸回道，\"你过你的圣诞节，让我过我的。"},{"start":67.837,"end":71.1,"text":"过圣诞节！\"斯克鲁奇的外甥重复道。"},{"start":71.1,"end":73,"text":"可您根本就不过呀。"},{"start":73,"end":75.7,"text":"那就让我不过好了，\"斯克鲁奇说。"},{"start":75.7,"end":78.275,"text":"愿它给你带来天大的好处吧！"},{"start":78.275,"end":81.387,"text":"它一向给你带来过多大的好处呀！"}]},"en":{"text":"\"Merry Christmas! what right have you to be merry? what reason have you to be merry?\nYou're poor enough.\"\n\"Come, then,\" returned the nephew gaily.\n\"What right have you to be dismal? what reason have you to be morose?\nYou're rich enough.\"\nScrooge having no better answer ready on the spur of the moment, said, \"Bah!\" again; and followed it up with \"Humbug.\"\n\"Don't be cross, uncle,\" said the nephew.\n\"What else can I be\" returned the uncle, \"when I live in such a world of fools as this?\nMerry Christmas!\nOut upon merry Christmas!\nWhat's Christmas time to you but a time for paying bills without money; a time for finding yourself a year older, and not an hour richer; a time for balancing your books and having every item in 'em through a round dozen of months presented dead against you?\nIf I could work my will,\" said Scrooge, indignantly, \"every idiot who goes about with 'Merry Christmas,' on his lips, should be boiled with his own pudding, and buried with a stake of holly through his heart.\nHe should!\"\n\"Uncle!\" pleaded the nephew.\n\"Nephew!\" returned the uncle, sternly, \"keep Christmas in your own way, and let me keep it in mine.\"\n\"Keep it!\" repeated Scrooge's nephew.\n\"But you don't keep it.\"\n\"Let me leave it alone, then,\" said Scrooge.\n\"Much good may it do you!\nMuch good it has ever done you!\"","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_I_小节04.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":2.1,"text":"Merry Christmas!"},{"start":2.05,"end":4.3,"text":"what right have you to be merry?"},{"start":4.3,"end":6.725,"text":"what reason have you to be merry?"},{"start":6.725,"end":8.662,"text":"You're poor enough."},{"start":8.662,"end":12.05,"text":"Come, then,\" returned the nephew gaily."},{"start":12.05,"end":14.35,"text":"What right have you to be dismal?"},{"start":14.35,"end":17.012,"text":"what reason have you to be morose?"},{"start":17.012,"end":18.912,"text":"You're rich enough."},{"start":18.912,"end":26.775,"text":"Scrooge having no better answer ready on the spur of the moment, said, \"Bah!\" again; and followed it up with \"Humbug."},{"start":26.775,"end":30.162,"text":"Don't be cross, uncle,\" said the nephew."},{"start":30.162,"end":35.475,"text":"What else can I be\" returned the uncle, \"when I live in such a world of fools as this?"},{"start":35.475,"end":37.475,"text":"Merry Christmas!"},{"start":37.475,"end":39.987,"text":"Out upon merry Christmas!"},{"start":39.987,"end":53.562,"text":"What's Christmas time to you but a time for paying bills without money; a time for finding yourself a year older, and not an hour richer; a time for balancing your books and having every item in 'em through a round dozen of months presented dead against you?"},{"start":53.562,"end":66.137,"text":"If I could work my will,\" said Scrooge, indignantly, \"every idiot who goes about with 'Merry Christmas,' on his lips, should be boiled with his own pudding, and buried with a stake of holly through his heart."},{"start":66.137,"end":67.675,"text":"He should!"},{"start":67.675,"end":70.187,"text":"Uncle!\" pleaded the nephew."},{"start":70.187,"end":77.137,"text":"Nephew!\" returned the uncle, sternly, \"keep Christmas in your own way, and let me keep it in mine."},{"start":77.137,"end":80.237,"text":"Keep it!\" repeated Scrooge's nephew."},{"start":80.237,"end":82.175,"text":"But you don't keep it."},{"start":82.175,"end":85.775,"text":"Let me leave it alone, then,\" said Scrooge."},{"start":85.775,"end":88.05,"text":"Much good may it do you!"},{"start":88.05,"end":90.537,"text":"Much good it has ever done you!"}]}},{"id":"I_05","number":5,"zh":{"text":"\"有不少东西，本可以给我带来好处，我却没能从中得益，这我承认，\"外甥回道，\"圣诞节也算一桩。\n可我敢说，每逢圣诞节到来——撇开它那神圣的名号和来历应得的崇敬不谈，倘若属于它的种种当真能跟那分得开的话——我向来都把它看作一段好时光：一段仁慈、宽厚、行善、欢愉的时光；在一年那长长的历法里，我所知道的就只有这么一个时候，男男女女仿佛不约而同地敞开了原本紧闭的心扉，把比自己境遇差的人也当成了同赴坟墓的旅伴，而不是另走一路的异类。\n所以，舅舅，尽管它从没往我口袋里塞过一星半点金子银子，我却相信它确曾使我受益，将来也定会使我受益；所以我要说一声：上帝保佑它！\"\n水槽似的小屋里那伙计不由自主地鼓起掌来；旋即觉出这有失体统，连忙去捅火，反倒把最后一星孱弱的火苗也永远地捅灭了。\n\"我再听见你出一点声音，\"斯克鲁奇说，\"你就连饭碗一块儿丢了去过你的圣诞节吧。\n先生，您倒真是个能言善辩的演说家，\"他转向外甥又添了一句。\n\"真奇怪您怎么不去当议员。\"\n\"别恼啊，舅舅。\n来吧！\n明天上我们家吃顿饭。\"\n斯克鲁奇说他宁可下地狱也不去——是的，他当真这么说了。\n他把那句话说全了，说他宁可先看着自己下到那十八层地狱里去。\n\"可这是为什么呀？\"斯克鲁奇的外甥嚷道。\n\"为什么？\"\n\"你当初干吗要结婚？\"斯克鲁奇说。\n\"因为我爱上了人家呀。\"\n\"因为你爱上了人家！\"斯克鲁奇咆哮起来，仿佛这是世上唯一比圣诞快乐更荒唐的事情。\n\"再见！\"\n\"不，舅舅，可在我结婚之前您也从没来看过我呀。\n怎么倒拿这个当作如今不来的理由呢？\"","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_I_小节05.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":8.025,"text":"有不少东西，本可以给我带来好处，我却没能从中得益，这我承认，\"外甥回道，\"圣诞节也算一桩。"},{"start":7.975,"end":39.025,"text":"可我敢说，每逢圣诞节到来——撇开它那神圣的名号和来历应得的崇敬不谈，倘若属于它的种种当真能跟那分得开的话——我向来都把它看作一段好时光：一段仁慈、宽厚、行善、欢愉的时光；在一年那长长的历法里，我所知道的就只有这么一个时候，男男女女仿佛不约而同地敞开了原本紧闭的心扉，把比自己境遇差的人也当成了同赴坟墓的旅伴，而不是另走一路的异类。"},{"start":39.025,"end":51.812,"text":"所以，舅舅，尽管它从没往我口袋里塞过一星半点金子银子，我却相信它确曾使我受益，将来也定会使我受益；所以我要说一声：上帝保佑它！"},{"start":51.812,"end":63.05,"text":"水槽似的小屋里那伙计不由自主地鼓起掌来；旋即觉出这有失体统，连忙去捅火，反倒把最后一星孱弱的火苗也永远地捅灭了。"},{"start":63.05,"end":69.325,"text":"我再听见你出一点声音，\"斯克鲁奇说，\"你就连饭碗一块儿丢了去过你的圣诞节吧。"},{"start":69.325,"end":74.537,"text":"先生，您倒真是个能言善辩的演说家，\"他转向外甥又添了一句。"},{"start":74.537,"end":77.062,"text":"真奇怪您怎么不去当议员。"},{"start":77.062,"end":78.725,"text":"别恼啊，舅舅。"},{"start":78.725,"end":79.837,"text":"来吧！"},{"start":79.837,"end":81.937,"text":"明天上我们家吃顿饭。"},{"start":81.937,"end":86.912,"text":"斯克鲁奇说他宁可下地狱也不去——是的，他当真这么说了。"},{"start":86.912,"end":92.775,"text":"他把那句话说全了，说他宁可先看着自己下到那十八层地狱里去。"},{"start":92.775,"end":96.112,"text":"可这是为什么呀？\"斯克鲁奇的外甥嚷道。"},{"start":96.112,"end":97.237,"text":"为什么？"},{"start":97.237,"end":100.412,"text":"你当初干吗要结婚？\"斯克鲁奇说。"},{"start":100.412,"end":102.625,"text":"因为我爱上了人家呀。"},{"start":102.625,"end":109.687,"text":"因为你爱上了人家！\"斯克鲁奇咆哮起来，仿佛这是世上唯一比圣诞快乐更荒唐的事情。"},{"start":109.687,"end":110.725,"text":"再见！"},{"start":110.725,"end":114.7,"text":"不，舅舅，可在我结婚之前您也从没来看过我呀。"},{"start":114.7,"end":118,"text":"怎么倒拿这个当作如今不来的理由呢？"}]},"en":{"text":"\"There are many things from which I might have derived good, by which I have not profited, I dare say,\" returned the nephew: \"Christmas among the rest.\nBut I am sure I have always thought of Christmas time, when it has come round--apart from the veneration due to its sacred name and origin, if anything belonging to it can be apart from that--as a good time: a kind, forgiving, charitable, pleasant time: the only time I know of, in the long calendar of the year, when men and women seem by one consent to open their shut-up hearts freely, and to think of people below them as if they really were fellow-passengers to the grave, and not another race of creatures bound on other journeys.\nAnd therefore, uncle, though it has never put a scrap of gold or silver in my pocket, I believe that it _has_ done me good, and _will_ do me good; and I say, God bless it!\"\nThe clerk in the tank involuntarily applauded: becoming immediately sensible of the impropriety, he poked the fire, and extinguished the last frail spark for ever.\n\"Let me hear another sound from _you_\" said Scrooge, \"and you'll keep your Christmas by losing your situation.\nYou're quite a powerful speaker, sir,\" he added, turning to his nephew.\n\"I wonder you don't go into Parliament.\"\n\"Don't be angry, uncle.\nCome!\nDine with us to-morrow.\"\nScrooge said that he would see him--yes, indeed he did.\nHe went the whole length of the expression, and said that he would see him in that extremity first.\n\"But why?\" cried Scrooge's nephew.\n\"Why?\"\n\"Why did you get married?\" said Scrooge.\n\"Because I fell in love.\"\n\"Because you fell in love!\" growled Scrooge, as if that were the only one thing in the world more ridiculous than a merry Christmas.\n\"Good afternoon!\"\n\"Nay, uncle, but you never came to see me before that happened.\nWhy give it as a reason for not coming now?\"","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_I_小节05.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":9,"text":"There are many things from which I might have derived good, by which I have not profited, I dare say,\" returned the nephew: \"Christmas among the rest."},{"start":8.95,"end":36.6,"text":"But I am sure I have always thought of Christmas time, when it has come round--apart from the veneration due to its sacred name and origin, if anything belonging to it can be apart from that--as a good time: a kind, forgiving, charitable, pleasant time: the only time I know of, in the long calendar of the year, when men and women seem by one consent to open their shut-up hearts freely, and to think of people below them as if they really were fellow-passengers to the grave, and not another race"},{"start":36.6,"end":39.575,"text":"of creatures bound on other journeys."},{"start":39.575,"end":52.45,"text":"And therefore, uncle, though it has never put a scrap of gold or silver in my pocket, I believe that it _has_ done me good, and _will_ do me good; and I say, God bless it!"},{"start":52.45,"end":62.4,"text":"The clerk in the tank involuntarily applauded: becoming immediately sensible of the impropriety, he poked the fire, and extinguished the last frail spark for ever."},{"start":62.4,"end":69.675,"text":"Let me hear another sound from _you_\" said Scrooge, \"and you'll keep your Christmas by losing your situation."},{"start":69.675,"end":74.875,"text":"You're quite a powerful speaker, sir,\" he added, turning to his nephew."},{"start":74.875,"end":77.587,"text":"I wonder you don't go into Parliament."},{"start":77.587,"end":79.962,"text":"Don't be angry, uncle."},{"start":79.962,"end":81.337,"text":"Come!"},{"start":81.337,"end":83.587,"text":"Dine with us to-morrow."},{"start":83.587,"end":87.625,"text":"Scrooge said that he would see him--yes, indeed he did."},{"start":87.625,"end":93.062,"text":"He went the whole length of the expression, and said that he would see him in that extremity first."},{"start":93.062,"end":96.175,"text":"But why?\" cried Scrooge's nephew."},{"start":96.175,"end":97.512,"text":"Why?"},{"start":97.512,"end":100.662,"text":"Why did you get married?\" said Scrooge."},{"start":100.662,"end":102.85,"text":"Because I fell in love."},{"start":102.85,"end":110.475,"text":"Because you fell in love!\" growled Scrooge, as if that were the only one thing in the world more ridiculous than a merry Christmas."},{"start":110.475,"end":112.2,"text":"Good afternoon!"},{"start":112.2,"end":116.737,"text":"Nay, uncle, but you never came to see me before that happened."},{"start":116.737,"end":119.737,"text":"Why give it as a reason for not coming now?"}]}},{"id":"I_06","number":6,"zh":{"text":"\"再见，\"斯克鲁奇说。\n\"我不向您要什么，也不求您什么；咱们为什么就不能做朋友呢？\"\n\"再见，\"斯克鲁奇说。\n\"我打心眼里感到难过，见您这般固执。\n咱们从没拌过嘴，我也从没招惹过您。\n可我这一回是冲着圣诞节才来试一试的，我要把这份圣诞节的好兴致一直保持到底。\n所以，祝您圣诞快乐，舅舅！\"\n\"再见！\"斯克鲁奇说。\n\"也祝您新年快乐！\"\n\"再见！\"斯克鲁奇说。\n尽管如此，他外甥还是没说一句气话便离开了房间。\n他在外间门口停了停，向那伙计道了声节日的问候；伙计虽然冻得发僵，到底比斯克鲁奇热乎，热诚地回了礼。\n\"又是一个活宝，\"斯克鲁奇听见了，咕哝道，\"我那伙计，一礼拜挣十五先令，拖家带口的，居然也来谈什么圣诞快乐。\n我看我该进疯人院去了。\"\n这个\"疯子\"放斯克鲁奇的外甥出去时，又放进来两个人。\n那是两位体态富态、面目可亲的绅士，此刻摘了帽子站在斯克鲁奇的账房里。\n他们手里拿着簿册和文件，向他欠了欠身。\n\"这里是斯克鲁奇与马利商行吧，没错？\"其中一位绅士说，一面查看他手里的名单。\n\"我是有幸跟斯克鲁奇先生，还是跟马利先生说话呢？\"\n\"马利先生已经死了七年了，\"斯克鲁奇答道。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_I_小节06.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":2.25,"text":"再见，\"斯克鲁奇说。"},{"start":2.2,"end":6.862,"text":"我不向您要什么，也不求您什么；咱们为什么就不能做朋友呢？"},{"start":6.862,"end":9.012,"text":"再见，\"斯克鲁奇说。"},{"start":9.012,"end":12.237,"text":"我打心眼里感到难过，见您这般固执。"},{"start":12.237,"end":15.45,"text":"咱们从没拌过嘴，我也从没招惹过您。"},{"start":15.45,"end":22.5,"text":"可我这一回是冲着圣诞节才来试一试的，我要把这份圣诞节的好兴致一直保持到底。"},{"start":22.5,"end":25.375,"text":"所以，祝您圣诞快乐，舅舅！"},{"start":25.375,"end":27.525,"text":"再见！\"斯克鲁奇说。"},{"start":27.525,"end":29.262,"text":"也祝您新年快乐！"},{"start":29.262,"end":31.412,"text":"再见！\"斯克鲁奇说。"},{"start":31.412,"end":36.225,"text":"尽管如此，他外甥还是没说一句气话便离开了房间。"},{"start":36.225,"end":45.45,"text":"他在外间门口停了停，向那伙计道了声节日的问候；伙计虽然冻得发僵，到底比斯克鲁奇热乎，热诚地回了礼。"},{"start":45.45,"end":54.962,"text":"又是一个活宝，\"斯克鲁奇听见了，咕哝道，\"我那伙计，一礼拜挣十五先令，拖家带口的，居然也来谈什么圣诞快乐。"},{"start":54.962,"end":57.4,"text":"我看我该进疯人院去了。"},{"start":57.4,"end":61.737,"text":"这个\"疯子\"放斯克鲁奇的外甥出去时，又放进来两个人。"},{"start":61.737,"end":68.287,"text":"那是两位体态富态、面目可亲的绅士，此刻摘了帽子站在斯克鲁奇的账房里。"},{"start":68.287,"end":72.125,"text":"他们手里拿着簿册和文件，向他欠了欠身。"},{"start":72.125,"end":78.887,"text":"这里是斯克鲁奇与马利商行吧，没错？\"其中一位绅士说，一面查看他手里的名单。"},{"start":78.887,"end":83.125,"text":"我是有幸跟斯克鲁奇先生，还是跟马利先生说话呢？"},{"start":83.125,"end":86.675,"text":"马利先生已经死了七年了，\"斯克鲁奇答道。"}]},"en":{"text":"\"Good afternoon,\" said Scrooge.\n\"I want nothing from you; I ask nothing of you; why cannot we be friends?\"\n\"Good afternoon,\" said Scrooge.\n\"I am sorry, with all my heart, to find you so resolute.\nWe have never had any quarrel, to which I have been a party.\nBut I have made the trial in homage to Christmas, and I'll keep my Christmas humour to the last.\nSo A Merry Christmas, uncle!\"\n\"Good afternoon!\" said Scrooge.\n\"And A Happy New Year!\"\n\"Good afternoon!\" said Scrooge.\nHis nephew left the room without an angry word, notwithstanding.\nHe stopped at the outer door to bestow the greetings of the season on the clerk, who, cold as he was, was warmer than Scrooge; for he returned them cordially.\n\"There's another fellow,\" muttered Scrooge; who overheard him: \"my clerk, with fifteen shillings a-week, and a wife and family, talking about a merry Christmas.\nI'll retire to Bedlam.\"\nThis lunatic, in letting Scrooge's nephew out, had let two other people in.\nThey were portly gentlemen, pleasant to behold, and now stood, with their hats off, in Scrooge's office.\nThey had books and papers in their hands, and bowed to him.\n\"Scrooge and Marley's, I believe,\" said one of the gentlemen, referring to his list.\n\"Have I the pleasure of addressing Mr. Scrooge, or Mr. Marley?\"\n\"Mr. Marley has been dead these seven years,\" Scrooge replied.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_I_小节06.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":2.85,"text":"Good afternoon,\" said Scrooge."},{"start":2.8,"end":8.012,"text":"I want nothing from you; I ask nothing of you; why cannot we be friends?"},{"start":8.012,"end":10.762,"text":"Good afternoon,\" said Scrooge."},{"start":10.762,"end":15.262,"text":"I am sorry, with all my heart, to find you so resolute."},{"start":15.262,"end":19.2,"text":"We have never had any quarrel, to which I have been a party."},{"start":19.2,"end":24.9,"text":"But I have made the trial in homage to Christmas, and I'll keep my Christmas humour to the last."},{"start":24.9,"end":27.762,"text":"So A Merry Christmas, uncle!"},{"start":27.762,"end":30.612,"text":"Good afternoon!\" said Scrooge."},{"start":30.612,"end":32.75,"text":"And A Happy New Year!"},{"start":32.75,"end":35.6,"text":"Good afternoon!\" said Scrooge."},{"start":35.6,"end":40.137,"text":"His nephew left the room without an angry word, notwithstanding."},{"start":40.137,"end":49.725,"text":"He stopped at the outer door to bestow the greetings of the season on the clerk, who, cold as he was, was warmer than Scrooge; for he returned them cordially."},{"start":49.725,"end":59.987,"text":"There's another fellow,\" muttered Scrooge; who overheard him: \"my clerk, with fifteen shillings a-week, and a wife and family, talking about a merry Christmas."},{"start":59.987,"end":62.212,"text":"I'll retire to Bedlam."},{"start":62.212,"end":67.5,"text":"This lunatic, in letting Scrooge's nephew out, had let two other people in."},{"start":67.5,"end":74.5,"text":"They were portly gentlemen, pleasant to behold, and now stood, with their hats off, in Scrooge's office."},{"start":74.5,"end":78.475,"text":"They had books and papers in their hands, and bowed to him."},{"start":78.475,"end":84.35,"text":"Scrooge and Marley's, I believe,\" said one of the gentlemen, referring to his list."},{"start":84.35,"end":88.65,"text":"Have I the pleasure of addressing Mr. Scrooge, or Mr. Marley?"},{"start":88.65,"end":93.075,"text":"Mr. Marley has been dead these seven years,\" Scrooge replied."}]}},{"id":"I_07","number":7,"zh":{"text":"\"他正是七年前的今晚咽的气。\"\n\"那么我们毫不怀疑，他那份慷慨自有他在世的合伙人替他承继了，\"那位绅士说着，递上证明文件。\n这话倒一点不假——因为他俩本是一路货色。\n一听到\"慷慨\"这个不祥的字眼，斯克鲁奇皱起眉头，摇了摇头，把文件退了回去。\n\"斯克鲁奇先生，值此一年一度的欢庆佳节，\"那位绅士拿起笔说，\"我们尤其应当稍稍接济一下那些穷困潦倒的人，眼下这时节他们正受着大罪呢。\n成千上万的人缺衣少食，连寻常的必需品都没有；数十万的人连寻常的暖和都享不着，先生。\"\n\"难道没有监狱吗？\"斯克鲁奇问。\n\"监狱多得很，\"那位绅士又放下笔说。\n\"那济贫院呢？\"斯克鲁奇追问。\n\"还在办着吗？\"\n\"还在办。\n只可惜，\"那位绅士答道，\"我真希望能说它们停办了。\"\n\"踏轮监狱和《济贫法》也都照旧在使劲推行喽？\"斯克鲁奇说。\n\"都忙得很呢，先生。\"\n\"哦！\n听您头一句话，我还当是出了什么岔子，把这些大有用处的好东西给停下来了呢，\"斯克鲁奇说。\n\"那我可太放心了。\"\n\"我们想着，这些地方实在没能给众生的身心带来多少基督徒的慰藉，\"那位绅士回道，\"所以我们几个人正张罗着募一笔款子，给穷人买点酒肉，添些取暖的东西。\n我们之所以拣这个时候，是因为在一年里，唯有这时候匮乏最让人切肤，丰足最叫人欢欣。\n我该给您记上多少呢？\"","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_I_小节07.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":2.925,"text":"他正是七年前的今晚咽的气。"},{"start":2.875,"end":11.825,"text":"那么我们毫不怀疑，他那份慷慨自有他在世的合伙人替他承继了，\"那位绅士说着，递上证明文件。"},{"start":11.825,"end":15.875,"text":"这话倒一点不假——因为他俩本是一路货色。"},{"start":15.875,"end":22.637,"text":"一听到\"慷慨\"这个不祥的字眼，斯克鲁奇皱起眉头，摇了摇头，把文件退了回去。"},{"start":22.637,"end":35.1,"text":"斯克鲁奇先生，值此一年一度的欢庆佳节，\"那位绅士拿起笔说，\"我们尤其应当稍稍接济一下那些穷困潦倒的人，眼下这时节他们正受着大罪呢。"},{"start":35.1,"end":42.862,"text":"成千上万的人缺衣少食，连寻常的必需品都没有；数十万的人连寻常的暖和都享不着，先生。"},{"start":42.862,"end":45.762,"text":"难道没有监狱吗？\"斯克鲁奇问。"},{"start":45.762,"end":49.187,"text":"监狱多得很，\"那位绅士又放下笔说。"},{"start":49.187,"end":52.062,"text":"那济贫院呢？\"斯克鲁奇追问。"},{"start":52.062,"end":53.525,"text":"还在办着吗？"},{"start":53.525,"end":54.762,"text":"还在办。"},{"start":54.762,"end":59.362,"text":"只可惜，\"那位绅士答道，\"我真希望能说它们停办了。"},{"start":59.362,"end":64.237,"text":"踏轮监狱和《济贫法》也都照旧在使劲推行喽？\"斯克鲁奇说。"},{"start":64.237,"end":66.387,"text":"都忙得很呢，先生。"},{"start":66.387,"end":67.287,"text":"哦！"},{"start":67.287,"end":74.45,"text":"听您头一句话，我还当是出了什么岔子，把这些大有用处的好东西给停下来了呢，\"斯克鲁奇说。"},{"start":74.45,"end":76.325,"text":"那我可太放心了。"},{"start":76.325,"end":89.55,"text":"我们想着，这些地方实在没能给众生的身心带来多少基督徒的慰藉，\"那位绅士回道，\"所以我们几个人正张罗着募一笔款子，给穷人买点酒肉，添些取暖的东西。"},{"start":89.55,"end":97.212,"text":"我们之所以拣这个时候，是因为在一年里，唯有这时候匮乏最让人切肤，丰足最叫人欢欣。"},{"start":97.212,"end":99.25,"text":"我该给您记上多少呢？"}]},"en":{"text":"\"He died seven years ago, this very night.\"\n\"We have no doubt his liberality is well represented by his surviving partner,\" said the gentleman, presenting his credentials.\nIt certainly was; for they had been two kindred spirits.\nAt the ominous word \"liberality,\" Scrooge frowned, and shook his head, and handed the credentials back.\n\"At this festive season of the year, Mr. Scrooge,\" said the gentleman, taking up a pen, \"it is more than usually desirable that we should make some slight provision for the poor and destitute, who suffer greatly at the present time.\nMany thousands are in want of common necessaries; hundreds of thousands are in want of common comforts, sir.\"\n\"Are there no prisons?\" asked Scrooge.\n\"Plenty of prisons,\" said the gentleman, laying down the pen again.\n\"And the Union workhouses?\" demanded Scrooge.\n\"Are they still in operation?\"\n\"They are.\nStill,\" returned the gentleman, \"I wish I could say they were not.\"\n\"The Treadmill and the Poor Law are in full vigour, then?\" said Scrooge.\n\"Both very busy, sir.\"\n\"Oh!\nI was afraid, from what you said at first, that something had occurred to stop them in their useful course,\" said Scrooge.\n\"I'm very glad to hear it.\"\n\"Under the impression that they scarcely furnish Christian cheer of mind or body to the multitude,\" returned the gentleman, \"a few of us are endeavouring to raise a fund to buy the Poor some meat and drink, and means of warmth.\nWe choose this time, because it is a time, of all others, when Want is keenly felt, and Abundance rejoices.\nWhat shall I put you down for?\"","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_I_小节07.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":3.725,"text":"He died seven years ago, this very night."},{"start":3.675,"end":11.1,"text":"We have no doubt his liberality is well represented by his surviving partner,\" said the gentleman, presenting his credentials."},{"start":11.1,"end":15.212,"text":"It certainly was; for they had been two kindred spirits."},{"start":15.212,"end":22.187,"text":"At the ominous word \"liberality,\" Scrooge frowned, and shook his head, and handed the credentials back."},{"start":22.187,"end":35.025,"text":"At this festive season of the year, Mr. Scrooge,\" said the gentleman, taking up a pen, \"it is more than usually desirable that we should make some slight provision for the poor and destitute, who suffer greatly at the present time."},{"start":35.025,"end":41.862,"text":"Many thousands are in want of common necessaries; hundreds of thousands are in want of common comforts, sir."},{"start":41.862,"end":45,"text":"Are there no prisons?\" asked Scrooge."},{"start":45,"end":49.475,"text":"Plenty of prisons,\" said the gentleman, laying down the pen again."},{"start":49.475,"end":53.1,"text":"And the Union workhouses?\" demanded Scrooge."},{"start":53.1,"end":55.425,"text":"Are they still in operation?"},{"start":55.425,"end":56.937,"text":"They are."},{"start":56.937,"end":61.387,"text":"Still,\" returned the gentleman, \"I wish I could say they were not."},{"start":61.387,"end":66.437,"text":"The Treadmill and the Poor Law are in full vigour, then?\" said Scrooge."},{"start":66.437,"end":69.1,"text":"Both very busy, sir."},{"start":69.1,"end":70.325,"text":"Oh!"},{"start":70.325,"end":77.612,"text":"I was afraid, from what you said at first, that something had occurred to stop them in their useful course,\" said Scrooge."},{"start":77.612,"end":79.85,"text":"I'm very glad to hear it."},{"start":79.85,"end":91.925,"text":"Under the impression that they scarcely furnish Christian cheer of mind or body to the multitude,\" returned the gentleman, \"a few of us are endeavouring to raise a fund to buy the Poor some meat and drink, and means of warmth."},{"start":91.925,"end":99.562,"text":"We choose this time, because it is a time, of all others, when Want is keenly felt, and Abundance rejoices."},{"start":99.562,"end":101.912,"text":"What shall I put you down for?"}]}},{"id":"I_08","number":8,"zh":{"text":"\"一文也不记！\"斯克鲁奇答道。\n\"您是想隐去姓名吧？\"\n\"我只想清静清静，\"斯克鲁奇说。\n\"既然两位问我想要什么，这就是我的回答。\n我自己过圣诞节不寻什么乐子，也没那个闲钱让游手好闲的人快活。\n我方才提到的那些机构，我可是出过力供养的；它们花费已经够大；那些日子过不下去的人，就该上那儿去。\"\n\"许多人去不了那儿；许多人宁可去死。\"\n\"既然他们宁可去死，\"斯克鲁奇说，\"那就让他们死好了，也好减一减这过剩的人口。\n再说——恕我直言——这种事我可不晓得。\"\n\"可您本是可以晓得的呀，\"那位绅士说。\n\"那不干我的事，\"斯克鲁奇回道。\n\"一个人把自己分内的事弄明白，别去管旁人的闲事，也就尽够了。\n我自己的事就忙不过来呢。\n再见吧，两位先生！\"\n那两位绅士看得明白，再争下去也是白搭，便告辞了。\n斯克鲁奇重新埋头干他的活儿，自我感觉好了几分，那脾气也比平日里诙谐了些。\n这工夫，雾和黑暗越发浓重了，街上有人举着燃旺的火把跑来跑去，揽生意似的要替马车在前头引路开道。\n一座古老的教堂钟楼——那只粗哑的老钟向来爱从墙上那扇哥特式窗洞里偷偷觑着斯克鲁奇——此刻也隐没在雾里看不见了，只在那高处的云层中敲着报时的钟点和刻钟，敲完之后还颤巍巍地余音不绝，活像那冻僵的钟脑袋在上头牙齿打颤。\n寒气越发逼人。\n大街上，就在院子拐角处，几个工人正在修煤气管，生起了一大盆炭火，一群衣衫褴褛的男人和小子围在四周：一个个对着火光烤着手、眨着眼，乐在其中。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_I_小节08.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":2.862,"text":"一文也不记！\"斯克鲁奇答道。"},{"start":2.812,"end":4.825,"text":"您是想隐去姓名吧？"},{"start":4.825,"end":7.925,"text":"我只想清静清静，\"斯克鲁奇说。"},{"start":7.925,"end":11.512,"text":"既然两位问我想要什么，这就是我的回答。"},{"start":11.512,"end":17.4,"text":"我自己过圣诞节不寻什么乐子，也没那个闲钱让游手好闲的人快活。"},{"start":17.4,"end":26.437,"text":"我方才提到的那些机构，我可是出过力供养的；它们花费已经够大；那些日子过不下去的人，就该上那儿去。"},{"start":26.437,"end":29.75,"text":"许多人去不了那儿；许多人宁可去死。"},{"start":29.75,"end":36.537,"text":"既然他们宁可去死，\"斯克鲁奇说，\"那就让他们死好了，也好减一减这过剩的人口。"},{"start":36.537,"end":40.262,"text":"再说——恕我直言——这种事我可不晓得。"},{"start":40.262,"end":43.337,"text":"可您本是可以晓得的呀，\"那位绅士说。"},{"start":43.337,"end":46.275,"text":"那不干我的事，\"斯克鲁奇回道。"},{"start":46.275,"end":51.725,"text":"一个人把自己分内的事弄明白，别去管旁人的闲事，也就尽够了。"},{"start":51.725,"end":54.35,"text":"我自己的事就忙不过来呢。"},{"start":54.35,"end":56.412,"text":"再见吧，两位先生！"},{"start":56.412,"end":61.287,"text":"那两位绅士看得明白，再争下去也是白搭，便告辞了。"},{"start":61.287,"end":68.087,"text":"斯克鲁奇重新埋头干他的活儿，自我感觉好了几分，那脾气也比平日里诙谐了些。"},{"start":68.087,"end":77.537,"text":"这工夫，雾和黑暗越发浓重了，街上有人举着燃旺的火把跑来跑去，揽生意似的要替马车在前头引路开道。"},{"start":77.537,"end":98.05,"text":"一座古老的教堂钟楼——那只粗哑的老钟向来爱从墙上那扇哥特式窗洞里偷偷觑着斯克鲁奇——此刻也隐没在雾里看不见了，只在那高处的云层中敲着报时的钟点和刻钟，敲完之后还颤巍巍地余音不绝，活像那冻僵的钟脑袋在上头牙齿打颤。"},{"start":98.05,"end":100.012,"text":"寒气越发逼人。"},{"start":100.012,"end":113.375,"text":"大街上，就在院子拐角处，几个工人正在修煤气管，生起了一大盆炭火，一群衣衫褴褛的男人和小子围在四周：一个个对着火光烤着手、眨着眼，乐在其中。"}]},"en":{"text":"\"Nothing!\" Scrooge replied.\n\"You wish to be anonymous?\"\n\"I wish to be left alone,\" said Scrooge.\n\"Since you ask me what I wish, gentlemen, that is my answer.\nI don't make merry myself at Christmas, and I can't afford to make idle people merry.\nI help to support the establishments I have mentioned: they cost enough: and those who are badly off must go there.\"\n\"Many can't go there; and many would rather die.\"\n\"If they would rather die,\" said Scrooge, \"they had better do it, and decrease the surplus population.\nBesides--excuse me--I don't know that.\"\n\"But you might know it,\" observed the gentleman.\n\"It's not my business,\" Scrooge returned.\n\"It's enough for a man to understand his own business, and not to interfere with other people's.\nMine occupies me constantly.\nGood afternoon, gentlemen!\"\nSeeing clearly that it would be useless to pursue their point, the gentlemen withdrew.\nScrooge resumed his labours with an improved opinion of himself, and in a more facetious temper than was usual with him.\nMeanwhile the fog and darkness thickened so, that people ran about with flaring links, proffering their services to go before horses in carriages, and conduct them on their way.\nThe ancient tower of a church, whose gruff old bell was always peeping slily down at Scrooge out of a gothic window in the wall, became invisible, and struck the hours and quarters in the clouds, with tremulous vibrations afterwards, as if its teeth were chattering in its frozen head up there.\nThe cold became intense.\nIn the main street, at the corner of the court, some labourers were repairing the gas-pipes, and had lighted a great fire in a brazier, round which a party of ragged men and boys were gathered: warming their hands and winking their eyes before the blaze in rapture.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_I_小节08.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":1.562,"text":"Nothing!"},{"start":1.512,"end":3.587,"text":"Scrooge replied."},{"start":3.587,"end":5.812,"text":"You wish to be anonymous?"},{"start":5.812,"end":9.212,"text":"I wish to be left alone,\" said Scrooge."},{"start":9.212,"end":13.662,"text":"Since you ask me what I wish, gentlemen, that is my answer."},{"start":13.662,"end":19.112,"text":"I don't make merry myself at Christmas, and I can't afford to make idle people merry."},{"start":19.112,"end":26.137,"text":"I help to support the establishments I have mentioned: they cost enough: and those who are badly off must go there."},{"start":26.137,"end":29.687,"text":"Many can't go there; and many would rather die."},{"start":29.687,"end":36.137,"text":"If they would rather die,\" said Scrooge, \"they had better do it, and decrease the surplus population."},{"start":36.137,"end":39.112,"text":"Besides--excuse me--I don't know that."},{"start":39.112,"end":42.4,"text":"But you might know it,\" observed the gentleman."},{"start":42.4,"end":45.762,"text":"It's not my business,\" Scrooge returned."},{"start":45.762,"end":51.375,"text":"It's enough for a man to understand his own business, and not to interfere with other people's."},{"start":51.375,"end":54.1,"text":"Mine occupies me constantly."},{"start":54.1,"end":56.525,"text":"Good afternoon, gentlemen!"},{"start":56.525,"end":61.675,"text":"Seeing clearly that it would be useless to pursue their point, the gentlemen withdrew."},{"start":61.675,"end":68.687,"text":"Scrooge resumed his labours with an improved opinion of himself, and in a more facetious temper than was usual with him."},{"start":68.687,"end":79.05,"text":"Meanwhile the fog and darkness thickened so, that people ran about with flaring links, proffering their services to go before horses in carriages, and conduct them on their way."},{"start":79.05,"end":95.637,"text":"The ancient tower of a church, whose gruff old bell was always peeping slily down at Scrooge out of a gothic window in the wall, became invisible, and struck the hours and quarters in the clouds, with tremulous vibrations afterwards, as if its teeth were chattering in its frozen head up there."},{"start":95.637,"end":98.075,"text":"The cold became intense."},{"start":98.075,"end":112.587,"text":"In the main street, at the corner of the court, some labourers were repairing the gas-pipes, and had lighted a great fire in a brazier, round which a party of ragged men and boys were gathered: warming their hands and winking their eyes before the blaze in rapture."}]}},{"id":"I_09","number":9,"zh":{"text":"那只无人理会的消防栓，溢出来的水阴沉沉地凝住了，结成一团孤僻冷漠的坚冰。\n店铺里冬青枝和红浆果在橱窗的灯火热气中噼啪作响，那一片明亮把过路人苍白的脸都映得红润起来。\n家禽铺和杂货铺的买卖成了一场盛大的玩笑：一派辉煌的盛景，叫人简直没法相信，讨价还价、买进卖出这等乏味的勾当竟跟它沾得上边。\n市长大人在那威严的市长官邸的深堡里，吩咐他手下五十名厨子和管家，要按着市长门第该有的气派来过圣诞节；就连那个上礼拜一才因为在街上醉醺醺、凶巴巴而被他罚了五先令的小裁缝，这会儿也在自家阁楼上搅着明天要吃的布丁，他那干瘦的老婆抱着娃娃出门买牛肉去了。\n雾更浓，天更冷！\n那是一种钻心刺骨、无孔不入、咬人入髓的冷。\n当年善良的圣邓斯坦倘若不用他惯使的家伙，单凭这么一阵子天气去捏一捏恶魔的鼻子，那魔鬼准会扯开嗓子鬼哭狼嚎个痛快。\n有个鼻子又小又嫩的人，那鼻子让饥饿的寒气啃啮咂磨着，就像骨头让狗啃一样，他弯下腰凑到斯克鲁奇的钥匙孔前，要给他唱一支圣诞颂歌助助兴；可才刚唱出头一句——\"上帝保佑您，快活的先生！\n愿您万事都顺心！\"\n斯克鲁奇便抄起戒尺，那架势凶猛得叫那唱歌的人吓得撒腿就逃，把钥匙孔留给了雾，留给了那更对斯克鲁奇脾胃的寒霜。\n到末了，关账房的时辰总算到了。\n斯克鲁奇老大不情愿地从凳子上下来，算是默认了这个钟点；那水槽小屋里巴望已久的伙计立刻吹熄蜡烛，戴上帽子。\n\"我看你明天是想歇一整天吧？\"斯克鲁奇说。\n\"要是方便的话，先生。\"\n\"不方便，\"斯克鲁奇说，\"也不公道。\n要是我为这事扣你半个克朗，你准会觉着自己吃了大亏，是不是？\"\n那伙计淡淡地笑了笑。\n\"可话说回来，\"斯克鲁奇说，\"我白付一天工钱让你不干活，你倒不觉着是我吃了亏。\"\n那伙计说，这一年到头也就这么一回。\n\"每年十二月二十五号就来掏人腰包一次，这借口可站不住脚！\"斯克鲁奇说着，把大衣一直扣到下巴颏儿。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_I_小节09.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":7.3,"text":"那只无人理会的消防栓，溢出来的水阴沉沉地凝住了，结成一团孤僻冷漠的坚冰。"},{"start":7.25,"end":16.612,"text":"店铺里冬青枝和红浆果在橱窗的灯火热气中噼啪作响，那一片明亮把过路人苍白的脸都映得红润起来。"},{"start":16.612,"end":28.7,"text":"家禽铺和杂货铺的买卖成了一场盛大的玩笑：一派辉煌的盛景，叫人简直没法相信，讨价还价、买进卖出这等乏味的勾当竟跟它沾得上边。"},{"start":28.7,"end":51.737,"text":"市长大人在那威严的市长官邸的深堡里，吩咐他手下五十名厨子和管家，要按着市长门第该有的气派来过圣诞节；就连那个上礼拜一才因为在街上醉醺醺、凶巴巴而被他罚了五先令的小裁缝，这会儿也在自家阁楼上搅着明天要吃的布丁，他那干瘦的老婆抱着娃娃出门买牛肉去了。"},{"start":51.737,"end":53.8,"text":"雾更浓，天更冷！"},{"start":53.8,"end":57.987,"text":"那是一种钻心刺骨、无孔不入、咬人入髓的冷。"},{"start":57.987,"end":69.425,"text":"当年善良的圣邓斯坦倘若不用他惯使的家伙，单凭这么一阵子天气去捏一捏恶魔的鼻子，那魔鬼准会扯开嗓子鬼哭狼嚎个痛快。"},{"start":69.425,"end":86.075,"text":"有个鼻子又小又嫩的人，那鼻子让饥饿的寒气啃啮咂磨着，就像骨头让狗啃一样，他弯下腰凑到斯克鲁奇的钥匙孔前，要给他唱一支圣诞颂歌助助兴；可才刚唱出头一句——\"上帝保佑您，快活的先生！"},{"start":86.075,"end":87.9,"text":"愿您万事都顺心！"},{"start":87.9,"end":98.637,"text":"斯克鲁奇便抄起戒尺，那架势凶猛得叫那唱歌的人吓得撒腿就逃，把钥匙孔留给了雾，留给了那更对斯克鲁奇脾胃的寒霜。"},{"start":98.637,"end":101.912,"text":"到末了，关账房的时辰总算到了。"},{"start":101.912,"end":112.375,"text":"斯克鲁奇老大不情愿地从凳子上下来，算是默认了这个钟点；那水槽小屋里巴望已久的伙计立刻吹熄蜡烛，戴上帽子。"},{"start":112.375,"end":116.125,"text":"我看你明天是想歇一整天吧？\"斯克鲁奇说。"},{"start":116.125,"end":118.362,"text":"要是方便的话，先生。"},{"start":118.362,"end":121.5,"text":"不方便，\"斯克鲁奇说，\"也不公道。"},{"start":121.5,"end":126.775,"text":"要是我为这事扣你半个克朗，你准会觉着自己吃了大亏，是不是？"},{"start":126.775,"end":129.062,"text":"那伙计淡淡地笑了笑。"},{"start":129.062,"end":136.125,"text":"可话说回来，\"斯克鲁奇说，\"我白付一天工钱让你不干活，你倒不觉着是我吃了亏。"},{"start":136.125,"end":139.725,"text":"那伙计说，这一年到头也就这么一回。"},{"start":139.725,"end":148.137,"text":"每年十二月二十五号就来掏人腰包一次，这借口可站不住脚！\"斯克鲁奇说着，把大衣一直扣到下巴颏儿。"}]},"en":{"text":"The waterplug being left in solitude, its overflowings sullenly congealed, and turned to misanthropic ice.\nThe brightness of the shops where holly sprigs and berries crackled in the lamp-heat of the windows, made pale faces ruddy as they passed.\nPoulterers' and grocers' trades became a splendid joke: a glorious pageant, with which it was next to impossible to believe that such dull principles as bargain and sale had anything to do.\nThe Lord Mayor, in the stronghold of the mighty Mansion House, gave orders to his fifty cooks and butlers to keep Christmas as a Lord Mayor's household should; and even the little tailor, whom he had fined five shillings on the previous Monday for being drunk and blood-thirsty in the streets, stirred up to-morrow's pudding in his garret, while his lean wife and the baby sallied out to buy the beef.\nFoggier yet, and colder!\nPiercing, searching, biting cold.\nIf the good Saint Dunstan had but nipped the Evil Spirit's nose with a touch of such weather as that, instead of using his familiar weapons, then indeed he would have roared to lusty purpose.\nThe owner of one scant young nose, gnawed and mumbled by the hungry cold as bones are gnawed by dogs, stooped down at Scrooge's keyhole to regale him with a Christmas carol: but at the first sound of-- \"God bless you merry gentleman!\nMay nothing you dismay!\"\nScrooge seized the ruler with such energy of action, that the singer fled in terror, leaving the keyhole to the fog and even more congenial frost.\nAt length the hour of shutting up the counting-house arrived.\nWith an ill-will Scrooge dismounted from his stool, and tacitly admitted the fact to the expectant clerk in the Tank, who instantly snuffed his candle out, and put on his hat.\n\"You'll want all day to-morrow, I suppose?\" said Scrooge.\n\"If quite convenient, Sir.\"\n\"It's not convenient,\" said Scrooge, \"and it's not fair.\nIf I was to stop half-a-crown for it, you'd think yourself ill used, I'll be bound?\"\nThe clerk smiled faintly.\n\"And yet,\" said Scrooge, \"you don't think _me_ ill-used, when I pay a day's wages for no work.\"\nThe clerk observed that it was only once a year.\n\"A poor excuse for picking a man's pocket every twenty-fifth of December!\" said Scrooge, buttoning his great-coat to the chin.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_I_小节09.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":7.287,"text":"The waterplug being left in solitude, its overflowings sullenly congealed, and turned to misanthropic ice."},{"start":7.237,"end":15.262,"text":"The brightness of the shops where holly sprigs and berries crackled in the lamp-heat of the windows, made pale faces ruddy as they passed."},{"start":15.262,"end":26.212,"text":"Poulterers' and grocers' trades became a splendid joke: a glorious pageant, with which it was next to impossible to believe that such dull principles as bargain and sale had anything to do."},{"start":26.212,"end":47.512,"text":"The Lord Mayor, in the stronghold of the mighty Mansion House, gave orders to his fifty cooks and butlers to keep Christmas as a Lord Mayor's household should; and even the little tailor, whom he had fined five shillings on the previous Monday for being drunk and blood-thirsty in the streets, stirred up to-morrow's pudding in his garret, while his lean wife and the baby sallied out to buy the beef."},{"start":47.512,"end":50.237,"text":"Foggier yet, and colder!"},{"start":50.237,"end":53.637,"text":"Piercing, searching, biting cold."},{"start":53.637,"end":64.475,"text":"If the good Saint Dunstan had but nipped the Evil Spirit's nose with a touch of such weather as that, instead of using his familiar weapons, then indeed he would have roared to lusty purpose."},{"start":64.475,"end":77.837,"text":"The owner of one scant young nose, gnawed and mumbled by the hungry cold as bones are gnawed by dogs, stooped down at Scrooge's keyhole to regale him with a Christmas carol: but at the first sound of-- \"God bless you merry gentleman!"},{"start":77.837,"end":80.037,"text":"May nothing you dismay!"},{"start":80.037,"end":88.825,"text":"Scrooge seized the ruler with such energy of action, that the singer fled in terror, leaving the keyhole to the fog and even more congenial frost."},{"start":88.825,"end":92.587,"text":"At length the hour of shutting up the counting-house arrived."},{"start":92.587,"end":102.612,"text":"With an ill-will Scrooge dismounted from his stool, and tacitly admitted the fact to the expectant clerk in the Tank, who instantly snuffed his candle out, and put on his hat."},{"start":102.612,"end":107.05,"text":"You'll want all day to-morrow, I suppose?\" said Scrooge."},{"start":107.05,"end":109.787,"text":"If quite convenient, Sir."},{"start":109.787,"end":113.987,"text":"It's not convenient,\" said Scrooge, \"and it's not fair."},{"start":113.987,"end":119.387,"text":"If I was to stop half-a-crown for it, you'd think yourself ill used, I'll be bound?"},{"start":119.387,"end":121.925,"text":"The clerk smiled faintly."},{"start":121.925,"end":129.287,"text":"And yet,\" said Scrooge, \"you don't think _me_ ill-used, when I pay a day's wages for no work."},{"start":129.287,"end":132.537,"text":"The clerk observed that it was only once a year."},{"start":132.537,"end":140.312,"text":"A poor excuse for picking a man's pocket every twenty-fifth of December!\" said Scrooge, buttoning his great-coat to the chin."}]}},{"id":"I_10","number":10,"zh":{"text":"\"不过我看也只好让你歇一整天了。\n第二天早上可得格外早些来！\"\n那伙计满口答应了；斯克鲁奇咕哝着走出门去。\n账房一眨眼就关上了，那伙计白围巾的长头垂到腰底下（因为他可没有什么大衣），在康希尔街上排在一长串孩子的末尾，为庆贺这圣诞前夜，滑了二十趟冰，然后撒开腿拼命往卡姆登镇的家跑，去玩捉迷藏。\n斯克鲁奇照例上他那家郁郁寡欢的小酒馆吃了一顿郁郁寡欢的晚饭；把所有报纸都读了个遍，又拿他的银行存折消磨掉这一晚剩下的工夫，便回家睡觉去了。\n他住的那套房间，原是他那已故合伙人的。\n那是黑沉沉的一套房子，坐落在一个院落深处一堆阴森森的楼房里，搁在那地方实在不相称，叫人忍不住胡思乱想：这房子准是当年还年轻的时候，跟别的房子玩捉迷藏一路跑到了这儿，再也找不着出去的路了。\n如今它已经够老、够凄凉的了，除了斯克鲁奇没人住，别的房间全租出去做办事处了。\n院子里黑得很，连对这儿每块石头都了如指掌的斯克鲁奇，也不得不伸手摸索着走。\n雾和霜紧裹着这房子那黑黢黢的老门洞，仿佛天气之神正坐在门槛上愁眉不展地默想。\n且说有这么个事实：这门上的门环并没有什么特别之处，只不过个头很大罢了。\n还有个事实是：斯克鲁奇住在这儿这些年，朝朝暮暮都瞧见它；再有，论起所谓的想象力，斯克鲁奇比伦敦城里任何人都少，甚至——这话说得够大胆——连那市政团体、参事和同业公会的人都算上。\n还要请你记住：自打那天下午最后一次提起他那死了七年的合伙人之后，斯克鲁奇就再没朝马利身上动过一个念头。\n那么，倘若有谁能解释，就请他给我讲讲：斯克鲁奇把钥匙插进门锁的当口，怎么会在那门环上——它可没经过任何中间的变化过程——看见的不是门环，而是马利的脸。\n马利的脸。\n它不像院子里别的东西那样浸在深不可测的暗影里，反倒自带一圈幽暗的光，像黑地窖里一只发了臭的龙虾。\n它并不怒气冲冲，也不凶神恶煞，只是照着马利生前惯常的样子望着斯克鲁奇：一副幽灵般的眼镜推到了幽灵般的额头上。\n那头发奇怪地飘动着，仿佛被呼吸或热气拂着；那双眼睛虽然睁得大大的，却纹丝不动。\n这一点，再加上它那青灰的死色，叫人毛骨悚然；可那股可怕劲儿，倒像是不由那张脸做主、由不得它自个儿控制似的，并不是它本身表情的一部分。\n斯克鲁奇定睛盯着这怪象，它却又变回了一只门环。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_I_小节10.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":3.075,"text":"不过我看也只好让你歇一整天了。"},{"start":3.025,"end":5.8,"text":"第二天早上可得格外早些来！"},{"start":5.8,"end":10.112,"text":"那伙计满口答应了；斯克鲁奇咕哝着走出门去。"},{"start":10.112,"end":27.762,"text":"账房一眨眼就关上了，那伙计白围巾的长头垂到腰底下（因为他可没有什么大衣），在康希尔街上排在一长串孩子的末尾，为庆贺这圣诞前夜，滑了二十趟冰，然后撒开腿拼命往卡姆登镇的家跑，去玩捉迷藏。"},{"start":27.762,"end":40.975,"text":"斯克鲁奇照例上他那家郁郁寡欢的小酒馆吃了一顿郁郁寡欢的晚饭；把所有报纸都读了个遍，又拿他的银行存折消磨掉这一晚剩下的工夫，便回家睡觉去了。"},{"start":40.975,"end":44.875,"text":"他住的那套房间，原是他那已故合伙人的。"},{"start":44.875,"end":61.275,"text":"那是黑沉沉的一套房子，坐落在一个院落深处一堆阴森森的楼房里，搁在那地方实在不相称，叫人忍不住胡思乱想：这房子准是当年还年轻的时候，跟别的房子玩捉迷藏一路跑到了这儿，再也找不着出去的路了。"},{"start":61.275,"end":68.487,"text":"如今它已经够老、够凄凉的了，除了斯克鲁奇没人住，别的房间全租出去做办事处了。"},{"start":68.487,"end":75.4,"text":"院子里黑得很，连对这儿每块石头都了如指掌的斯克鲁奇，也不得不伸手摸索着走。"},{"start":75.4,"end":83.025,"text":"雾和霜紧裹着这房子那黑黢黢的老门洞，仿佛天气之神正坐在门槛上愁眉不展地默想。"},{"start":83.025,"end":89.45,"text":"且说有这么个事实：这门上的门环并没有什么特别之处，只不过个头很大罢了。"},{"start":89.45,"end":105.937,"text":"还有个事实是：斯克鲁奇住在这儿这些年，朝朝暮暮都瞧见它；再有，论起所谓的想象力，斯克鲁奇比伦敦城里任何人都少，甚至——这话说得够大胆——连那市政团体、参事和同业公会的人都算上。"},{"start":105.937,"end":114.862,"text":"还要请你记住：自打那天下午最后一次提起他那死了七年的合伙人之后，斯克鲁奇就再没朝马利身上动过一个念头。"},{"start":114.862,"end":128.287,"text":"那么，倘若有谁能解释，就请他给我讲讲：斯克鲁奇把钥匙插进门锁的当口，怎么会在那门环上——它可没经过任何中间的变化过程——看见的不是门环，而是马利的脸。"},{"start":128.287,"end":129.662,"text":"马利的脸。"},{"start":129.662,"end":138.712,"text":"它不像院子里别的东西那样浸在深不可测的暗影里，反倒自带一圈幽暗的光，像黑地窖里一只发了臭的龙虾。"},{"start":138.712,"end":149.137,"text":"它并不怒气冲冲，也不凶神恶煞，只是照着马利生前惯常的样子望着斯克鲁奇：一副幽灵般的眼镜推到了幽灵般的额头上。"},{"start":149.137,"end":157.462,"text":"那头发奇怪地飘动着，仿佛被呼吸或热气拂着；那双眼睛虽然睁得大大的，却纹丝不动。"},{"start":157.462,"end":169.575,"text":"这一点，再加上它那青灰的死色，叫人毛骨悚然；可那股可怕劲儿，倒像是不由那张脸做主、由不得它自个儿控制似的，并不是它本身表情的一部分。"},{"start":169.575,"end":174.112,"text":"斯克鲁奇定睛盯着这怪象，它却又变回了一只门环。"}]},"en":{"text":"\"But I suppose you must have the whole day.\nBe here all the earlier next morning!\"\nThe clerk promised that he would; and Scrooge walked out with a growl.\nThe office was closed in a twinkling, and the clerk, with the long ends of his white comforter dangling below his waist (for he boasted no great-coat), went down a slide on Cornhill, at the end of a lane of boys, twenty times, in honour of its being Christmas-eve, and then ran home to Camden Town as hard as he could pelt, to play at blindman's-buff.\nScrooge took his melancholy dinner in his usual melancholy tavern; and having read all the news-papers, and beguiled the rest of the evening with his banker's-book, went home to bed.\nHe lived in chambers which had once belonged to his deceased partner.\nThey were a gloomy suite of rooms, in a lowering pile of building up a yard, where it had so little business to be, that one could scarcely help fancying it must have run there when it was a young house, playing at hide-and-seek with other houses, and have forgotten the way out again.\nIt was old enough now, and dreary enough, for nobody lived in it but Scrooge, the other rooms being all let out as offices.\nThe yard was so dark that even Scrooge, who knew its every stone, was fain to grope with his hands.\nThe fog and frost so hung about the black old gateway of the house, that it seemed as if the Genius of the Weather sat in mournful meditation on the threshold.\nNow, it is a fact, that there was nothing at all particular about the knocker on the door, except that it was very large.\nIt is also a fact, that Scrooge had seen it night and morning during his whole residence in that place; also that Scrooge had as little of what is called fancy about him as any man in the City of London, even including--which is a bold word--the corporation, aldermen, and livery.\nLet it also be borne in mind that Scrooge had not bestowed one thought on Marley, since his last mention of his seven-years' dead partner that afternoon.\nAnd then let any man explain to me, if he can, how it happened that Scrooge, having his key in the lock of the door, saw in the knocker, without its undergoing any intermediate process of change: not a knocker, but Marley's face.\nMarley's face.\nIt was not in impenetrable shadow as the other objects in the yard were, but had a dismal light about it, like a bad lobster in a dark cellar.\nIt was not angry or ferocious, but looked at Scrooge as Marley used to look: with ghostly spectacles turned up upon its ghostly forehead.\nThe hair was curiously stirred, as if by breath or hot-air; and though the eyes were wide open, they were perfectly motionless.\nThat, and its livid colour, made it horrible; but its horror seemed to be, in spite of the face and beyond its control, rather than a part of its own expression.\nAs Scrooge looked fixedly at this phenomenon, it was a knocker again.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_I_小节10.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":3.037,"text":"But I suppose you must have the whole day."},{"start":2.987,"end":5.95,"text":"Be here all the earlier next morning!"},{"start":5.95,"end":10.475,"text":"The clerk promised that he would; and Scrooge walked out with a growl."},{"start":10.475,"end":30.525,"text":"The office was closed in a twinkling, and the clerk, with the long ends of his white comforter dangling below his waist (for he boasted no great-coat), went down a slide on Cornhill, at the end of a lane of boys, twenty times, in honour of its being Christmas-eve, and then ran home to Camden Town as hard as he could pelt, to play at blindman's-buff."},{"start":30.525,"end":40.937,"text":"Scrooge took his melancholy dinner in his usual melancholy tavern; and having read all the news-papers, and beguiled the rest of the evening with his banker's-book, went home to bed."},{"start":40.937,"end":45.075,"text":"He lived in chambers which had once belonged to his deceased partner."},{"start":45.075,"end":60.387,"text":"They were a gloomy suite of rooms, in a lowering pile of building up a yard, where it had so little business to be, that one could scarcely help fancying it must have run there when it was a young house, playing at hide-and-seek with other houses, and have forgotten the way out again."},{"start":60.387,"end":68.5,"text":"It was old enough now, and dreary enough, for nobody lived in it but Scrooge, the other rooms being all let out as offices."},{"start":68.5,"end":75.025,"text":"The yard was so dark that even Scrooge, who knew its every stone, was fain to grope with his hands."},{"start":75.025,"end":84.075,"text":"The fog and frost so hung about the black old gateway of the house, that it seemed as if the Genius of the Weather sat in mournful meditation on the threshold."},{"start":84.075,"end":91.525,"text":"Now, it is a fact, that there was nothing at all particular about the knocker on the door, except that it was very large."},{"start":91.525,"end":106.587,"text":"It is also a fact, that Scrooge had seen it night and morning during his whole residence in that place; also that Scrooge had as little of what is called fancy about him as any man in the City of London, even including--which is a bold word--the corporation, aldermen, and livery."},{"start":106.587,"end":115.087,"text":"Let it also be borne in mind that Scrooge had not bestowed one thought on Marley, since his last mention of his seven-years' dead partner that afternoon."},{"start":115.087,"end":129.062,"text":"And then let any man explain to me, if he can, how it happened that Scrooge, having his key in the lock of the door, saw in the knocker, without its undergoing any intermediate process of change: not a knocker, but Marley's face."},{"start":129.062,"end":130.975,"text":"Marley's face."},{"start":130.975,"end":139.375,"text":"It was not in impenetrable shadow as the other objects in the yard were, but had a dismal light about it, like a bad lobster in a dark cellar."},{"start":139.375,"end":147.75,"text":"It was not angry or ferocious, but looked at Scrooge as Marley used to look: with ghostly spectacles turned up upon its ghostly forehead."},{"start":147.75,"end":155.862,"text":"The hair was curiously stirred, as if by breath or hot-air; and though the eyes were wide open, they were perfectly motionless."},{"start":155.862,"end":165.45,"text":"That, and its livid colour, made it horrible; but its horror seemed to be, in spite of the face and beyond its control, rather than a part of its own expression."},{"start":165.45,"end":170.212,"text":"As Scrooge looked fixedly at this phenomenon, it was a knocker again."}]}},{"id":"I_11","number":11,"zh":{"text":"要说他没吓一跳，要说他的血脉没感到一阵从襁褓时起就素不相识的可怕悸动，那是假话。\n可他还是把手按在那把刚撒开的钥匙上，稳稳地一拧，走了进去，点上了蜡烛。\n他临关门前，确实迟疑了一下，停了一停；也确实先小心翼翼地往门背后瞧了瞧，仿佛半指望着会被马利那条翘出门厅的辫子吓一跳。\n可门背后什么也没有，只有固定门环的那些螺丝和螺帽；于是他说了声\"呸，呸！\"砰地把门关上。\n那声响像打雷似的在整座屋子里回荡。\n楼上每一个房间，楼下酒商地窖里每一只酒桶，仿佛都各自荡起一阵独立的回声。\n斯克鲁奇可不是个会被回声吓住的人。\n他闩好门，穿过门厅，登上楼梯：走得也慢，一路还剪着烛花。\n你尽可以含含糊糊地说什么赶一辆六马大车上一段气派的老楼梯，或是硬闯一项乱七八糟的新议会法案；可我要说的是，你简直能把一辆灵车弄上那道楼梯，还横着抬，辕木冲墙、车门朝着栏杆：而且毫不费劲。\n那楼梯宽绰得很，还绰绰有余；这或许就是为什么斯克鲁奇恍惚觉得，幽暗中有一辆开动的灵车正走在他前头。\n就算从街上搬来六盏煤气灯，也照不亮这门道，所以你尽可想象，靠斯克鲁奇那截小蜡烛，这儿是何等昏暗。\n斯克鲁奇只管往上走，对此毫不在意：黑暗不花钱，斯克鲁奇就喜欢黑暗。\n可是在关上那扇沉重的房门之前，他还是把各个房间都走了一遍，看看是否一切如常。\n他对那张脸的记忆，恰好还够让他生出这么个念头。\n起居室、卧室、堆杂物的小屋。\n全都该是什么样就是什么样。\n桌子底下没人，沙发底下没人；炉栅里一炉小火；调羹和钵子都备好了；炉架上还搁着那只盛麦片粥的小锅（斯克鲁奇有点伤风）。\n床底下没人；壁橱里没人；他那件睡袍里也没人，那睡袍正以一副可疑的姿势贴墙挂着。\n堆杂物的小屋一如往常。\n旧炉档、旧鞋子、两只鱼篓、一个三条腿的脸盆架，还有一根拨火棍。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_I_小节11.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":8.575,"text":"要说他没吓一跳，要说他的血脉没感到一阵从襁褓时起就素不相识的可怕悸动，那是假话。"},{"start":8.525,"end":15.1,"text":"可他还是把手按在那把刚撒开的钥匙上，稳稳地一拧，走了进去，点上了蜡烛。"},{"start":15.1,"end":26.425,"text":"他临关门前，确实迟疑了一下，停了一停；也确实先小心翼翼地往门背后瞧了瞧，仿佛半指望着会被马利那条翘出门厅的辫子吓一跳。"},{"start":26.425,"end":34.862,"text":"可门背后什么也没有，只有固定门环的那些螺丝和螺帽；于是他说了声\"呸，呸！\"砰地把门关上。"},{"start":34.862,"end":38.587,"text":"那声响像打雷似的在整座屋子里回荡。"},{"start":38.587,"end":45.775,"text":"楼上每一个房间，楼下酒商地窖里每一只酒桶，仿佛都各自荡起一阵独立的回声。"},{"start":45.775,"end":49.462,"text":"斯克鲁奇可不是个会被回声吓住的人。"},{"start":49.462,"end":55.237,"text":"他闩好门，穿过门厅，登上楼梯：走得也慢，一路还剪着烛花。"},{"start":55.237,"end":72.725,"text":"你尽可以含含糊糊地说什么赶一辆六马大车上一段气派的老楼梯，或是硬闯一项乱七八糟的新议会法案；可我要说的是，你简直能把一辆灵车弄上那道楼梯，还横着抬，辕木冲墙、车门朝着栏杆：而且毫不费劲。"},{"start":72.725,"end":82.562,"text":"那楼梯宽绰得很，还绰绰有余；这或许就是为什么斯克鲁奇恍惚觉得，幽暗中有一辆开动的灵车正走在他前头。"},{"start":82.562,"end":91.8,"text":"就算从街上搬来六盏煤气灯，也照不亮这门道，所以你尽可想象，靠斯克鲁奇那截小蜡烛，这儿是何等昏暗。"},{"start":91.8,"end":98.25,"text":"斯克鲁奇只管往上走，对此毫不在意：黑暗不花钱，斯克鲁奇就喜欢黑暗。"},{"start":98.25,"end":105.462,"text":"可是在关上那扇沉重的房门之前，他还是把各个房间都走了一遍，看看是否一切如常。"},{"start":105.462,"end":109.862,"text":"他对那张脸的记忆，恰好还够让他生出这么个念头。"},{"start":109.862,"end":113.037,"text":"起居室、卧室、堆杂物的小屋。"},{"start":113.037,"end":115.562,"text":"全都该是什么样就是什么样。"},{"start":115.562,"end":126.612,"text":"桌子底下没人，沙发底下没人；炉栅里一炉小火；调羹和钵子都备好了；炉架上还搁着那只盛麦片粥的小锅（斯克鲁奇有点伤风）。"},{"start":126.612,"end":135.112,"text":"床底下没人；壁橱里没人；他那件睡袍里也没人，那睡袍正以一副可疑的姿势贴墙挂着。"},{"start":135.112,"end":137.725,"text":"堆杂物的小屋一如往常。"},{"start":137.725,"end":143.912,"text":"旧炉档、旧鞋子、两只鱼篓、一个三条腿的脸盆架，还有一根拨火棍。"}]},"en":{"text":"To say that he was not startled, or that his blood was not conscious of a terrible sensation to which it had been a stranger from infancy, would be untrue.\nBut he put his hand upon the key he had relinquished, turned it sturdily, walked in, and lighted his candle.\nHe _did_ pause, with a moment's irresolution, before he shut the door; and he _did_ look cautiously behind it first, as if he half-expected to be terrified with the sight of Marley's pigtail sticking out into the hall.\nBut there was nothing on the back of the door, except the screws and nuts that held the knocker on; so he said \"Pooh, pooh!\" and closed it with a bang.\nThe sound resounded through the house like thunder.\nEvery room above, and every cask in the wine-merchant's cellars below, appeared to have a separate peal of echoes of its own.\nScrooge was not a man to be frightened by echoes.\nHe fastened the door, and walked across the hall, and up the stairs: slowly too: trimming his candle as he went.\nYou may talk vaguely about driving a coach-and-six up a good old flight of stairs, or through a bad young Act of Parliament; but I mean to say you might have got a hearse up that staircase, and taken it broadwise, with the splinter-bar towards the wall, and the door towards the balustrades: and done it easy.\nThere was plenty of width for that, and room to spare; which is perhaps the reason why Scrooge thought he saw a locomotive hearse going on before him in the gloom.\nHalf a dozen gas-lamps out of the street wouldn't have lighted the entry too well, so you may suppose that it was pretty dark with Scrooge's dip.\nUp Scrooge went, not caring a button for that: darkness is cheap, and Scrooge liked it.\nBut before he shut his heavy door, he walked through his rooms to see that all was right.\nHe had just enough recollection of the face to desire to do that.\nSitting room, bed-room, lumber-room.\nAll as they should be.\nNobody under the table, nobody under the sofa; a small fire in the grate; spoon and basin ready; and the little saucepan of gruel (Scrooge had a cold in his head) upon the hob.\nNobody under the bed; nobody in the closet; nobody in his dressing-gown, which was hanging up in a suspicious attitude against the wall.\nLumber-room as usual.\nOld fire-guard, old shoes, two fish-baskets, washing-stand on three legs, and a poker.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_I_小节11.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":8.937,"text":"To say that he was not startled, or that his blood was not conscious of a terrible sensation to which it had been a stranger from infancy, would be untrue."},{"start":8.887,"end":15.812,"text":"But he put his hand upon the key he had relinquished, turned it sturdily, walked in, and lighted his candle."},{"start":15.812,"end":30.225,"text":"He _did_ pause, with a moment's irresolution, before he shut the door; and he _did_ look cautiously behind it first, as if he half-expected to be terrified with the sight of Marley's pigtail sticking out into the hall."},{"start":30.225,"end":39.45,"text":"But there was nothing on the back of the door, except the screws and nuts that held the knocker on; so he said \"Pooh, pooh!\" and closed it with a bang."},{"start":39.45,"end":42.775,"text":"The sound resounded through the house like thunder."},{"start":42.775,"end":50.262,"text":"Every room above, and every cask in the wine-merchant's cellars below, appeared to have a separate peal of echoes of its own."},{"start":50.262,"end":53.937,"text":"Scrooge was not a man to be frightened by echoes."},{"start":53.937,"end":61.7,"text":"He fastened the door, and walked across the hall, and up the stairs: slowly too: trimming his candle as he went."},{"start":61.7,"end":78.75,"text":"You may talk vaguely about driving a coach-and-six up a good old flight of stairs, or through a bad young Act of Parliament; but I mean to say you might have got a hearse up that staircase, and taken it broadwise, with the splinter-bar towards the wall, and the door towards the balustrades: and done it easy."},{"start":78.75,"end":87.712,"text":"There was plenty of width for that, and room to spare; which is perhaps the reason why Scrooge thought he saw a locomotive hearse going on before him in the gloom."},{"start":87.712,"end":95.437,"text":"Half a dozen gas-lamps out of the street wouldn't have lighted the entry too well, so you may suppose that it was pretty dark with Scrooge's dip."},{"start":95.437,"end":101.45,"text":"Up Scrooge went, not caring a button for that: darkness is cheap, and Scrooge liked it."},{"start":101.45,"end":106.937,"text":"But before he shut his heavy door, he walked through his rooms to see that all was right."},{"start":106.937,"end":111.137,"text":"He had just enough recollection of the face to desire to do that."},{"start":111.137,"end":114.425,"text":"Sitting room, bed-room, lumber-room."},{"start":114.425,"end":116.5,"text":"All as they should be."},{"start":116.5,"end":127.9,"text":"Nobody under the table, nobody under the sofa; a small fire in the grate; spoon and basin ready; and the little saucepan of gruel (Scrooge had a cold in his head) upon the hob."},{"start":127.9,"end":136.187,"text":"Nobody under the bed; nobody in the closet; nobody in his dressing-gown, which was hanging up in a suspicious attitude against the wall."},{"start":136.187,"end":138.387,"text":"Lumber-room as usual."},{"start":138.387,"end":145.575,"text":"Old fire-guard, old shoes, two fish-baskets, washing-stand on three legs, and a poker."}]}},{"id":"I_12","number":12,"zh":{"text":"十分满意了，他才关上房门，把自己锁在里头；还上了双重锁，这可不是他平日的习惯。\n就这么严严实实地防住了意外，他解下领巾；换上睡袍、拖鞋，戴上睡帽；坐到炉火跟前喝他的麦片粥。\n那炉火着实小得可怜；这么个苦寒的夜里，简直顶不了什么用。\n他不得不紧挨着它坐下，俯身守着，才能从这么一小撮燃料里，榨出一丁点儿暖意来。\n那壁炉是个老物件，很久以前由某个荷兰商人砌的，四周镶满了古色古香的荷兰瓷砖，画的都是《圣经》故事。\n有该隐和亚伯；有法老的女儿，有示巴女王，有踏着羽绒被似的云朵从空中降下的天使，有亚伯拉罕，有伯沙撒，有坐着黄油小船出海的使徒，几百个人物，本可引开他的心思；可马利那张死了七年的脸，却像古时先知的杖一样冒了出来，把这一切全吞没了。\n倘若每一块光溜溜的瓷砖起初都是空白的，能凭他那些支离破碎的念头在面上幻出一幅画来，那么每一块上头准都会有一个老马利脑袋的翻版。\n\"胡扯！\"斯克鲁奇说着，在屋里踱起步来。\n来回走了几趟，他又坐了下来。\n他把头往椅背上一靠，目光碰巧落在一只铃上，一只废弃不用的铃，挂在这屋里，当初为着某种如今已记不清的用处，跟这楼最高一层的一个房间相通。\n他正瞧着，万分惊愕、又带着一种说不清道不明的古怪恐惧，眼看着这只铃晃动起来。\n起先它晃得那样轻，几乎没出一点声音；可不一会儿就大声响了起来，屋里每一只铃也都跟着响了。\n这大概持续了半分钟，或是一分钟，可在他觉来却像一个钟头。\n那些铃像开始时一样，又一齐歇了。\n接着是一阵铿铿锵锵的声响，从底下深处传来；仿佛有谁正拖着一条沉重的铁链，从酒商地窖的酒桶上拖过去。\n斯克鲁奇这才记起，听人说过凶宅里的鬼魂都是拖着铁链的。\n地窖门轰隆一声猛地开了，接着他听见那声响大得多了，就在楼下几层；随后上了楼梯；随后直冲他的房门而来。\n\"还是胡扯！\"斯克鲁奇说。\n\"我才不信呢。\"\n可是当那东西毫不停顿地穿过那扇沉重的房门、当着他的眼进了屋时，他的脸色变了。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_I_小节12.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":7.762,"text":"十分满意了，他才关上房门，把自己锁在里头；还上了双重锁，这可不是他平日的习惯。"},{"start":7.712,"end":17.15,"text":"就这么严严实实地防住了意外，他解下领巾；换上睡袍、拖鞋，戴上睡帽；坐到炉火跟前喝他的麦片粥。"},{"start":17.15,"end":22.5,"text":"那炉火着实小得可怜；这么个苦寒的夜里，简直顶不了什么用。"},{"start":22.5,"end":29.725,"text":"他不得不紧挨着它坐下，俯身守着，才能从这么一小撮燃料里，榨出一丁点儿暖意来。"},{"start":29.725,"end":38.987,"text":"那壁炉是个老物件，很久以前由某个荷兰商人砌的，四周镶满了古色古香的荷兰瓷砖，画的都是《圣经》故事。"},{"start":38.987,"end":60.562,"text":"有该隐和亚伯；有法老的女儿，有示巴女王，有踏着羽绒被似的云朵从空中降下的天使，有亚伯拉罕，有伯沙撒，有坐着黄油小船出海的使徒，几百个人物，本可引开他的心思；可马利那张死了七年的脸，却像古时先知的杖一样冒了出来，把这一切全吞没了。"},{"start":60.562,"end":72.087,"text":"倘若每一块光溜溜的瓷砖起初都是空白的，能凭他那些支离破碎的念头在面上幻出一幅画来，那么每一块上头准都会有一个老马利脑袋的翻版。"},{"start":72.087,"end":75.975,"text":"胡扯！\"斯克鲁奇说着，在屋里踱起步来。"},{"start":75.975,"end":78.712,"text":"来回走了几趟，他又坐了下来。"},{"start":78.712,"end":91.187,"text":"他把头往椅背上一靠，目光碰巧落在一只铃上，一只废弃不用的铃，挂在这屋里，当初为着某种如今已记不清的用处，跟这楼最高一层的一个房间相通。"},{"start":91.187,"end":98.987,"text":"他正瞧着，万分惊愕、又带着一种说不清道不明的古怪恐惧，眼看着这只铃晃动起来。"},{"start":98.987,"end":107.35,"text":"起先它晃得那样轻，几乎没出一点声音；可不一会儿就大声响了起来，屋里每一只铃也都跟着响了。"},{"start":107.35,"end":112.862,"text":"这大概持续了半分钟，或是一分钟，可在他觉来却像一个钟头。"},{"start":112.862,"end":116.087,"text":"那些铃像开始时一样，又一齐歇了。"},{"start":116.087,"end":126.025,"text":"接着是一阵铿铿锵锵的声响，从底下深处传来；仿佛有谁正拖着一条沉重的铁链，从酒商地窖的酒桶上拖过去。"},{"start":126.025,"end":131.575,"text":"斯克鲁奇这才记起，听人说过凶宅里的鬼魂都是拖着铁链的。"},{"start":131.575,"end":141.162,"text":"地窖门轰隆一声猛地开了，接着他听见那声响大得多了，就在楼下几层；随后上了楼梯；随后直冲他的房门而来。"},{"start":141.162,"end":143.7,"text":"还是胡扯！\"斯克鲁奇说。"},{"start":143.7,"end":145.175,"text":"我才不信呢。"},{"start":145.175,"end":152.937,"text":"可是当那东西毫不停顿地穿过那扇沉重的房门、当着他的眼进了屋时，他的脸色变了。"}]},"en":{"text":"Quite satisfied, he closed his door, and locked himself in; double-locked himself in, which was not his custom.\nThus secured against surprise, he took off his cravat; put on his dressing-gown and slippers, and his night-cap; and sat down before the fire to take his gruel.\nIt was a very low fire indeed; nothing on such a bitter night.\nHe was obliged to sit close to it, and brood over it, before he could extract the least sensation of warmth from such a handful of fuel.\nThe fire-place was an old one, built by some Dutch merchant long ago, and paved all round with quaint Dutch tiles, designed to illustrate the Scriptures.\nThere were Cains and Abels; Pharaoh's daughters, Queens of Sheba, Angelic messengers descending through the air on clouds like feather-beds, Abrahams, Belshazzars, Apostles putting off to sea in butter-boats, hundreds of figures, to attract his thoughts; and yet that face of Marley, seven years dead, came like the ancient Prophet's rod, and swallowed up the whole.\nIf each smooth tile had been a blank at first, with power to shape some picture on its surface from the disjointed fragments of his thoughts, there would have been a copy of old Marley's head on every one.\n\"Humbug!\" said Scrooge; and walked across the room.\nAfter several turns, he sat down again.\nAs he threw his head back in the chair, his glance happened to rest upon a bell, a disused bell, that hung in the room, and communicated for some purpose now forgotten with a chamber in the highest story of the building.\nIt was with great astonishment, and with a strange, inexplicable dread, that as he looked, he saw this bell begin to swing.\nIt swung so softly in the outset that it scarcely made a sound; but soon it rang out loudly, and so did every bell in the house.\nThis might have lasted half a minute, or a minute, but it seemed an hour.\nThe bells ceased as they had begun, together.\nThey were succeeded by a clanking noise, deep down below; as if some person were dragging a heavy chain over the casks in the wine-merchant's cellar.\nScrooge then remembered to have heard that ghosts in haunted houses were described as dragging chains.\nThe cellar-door flew open with a booming sound, and then he heard the noise much louder, on the floors below; then coming up the stairs; then coming straight towards his door.\n\"It's humbug still!\" said Scrooge.\n\"I won't believe it.\"\nHis colour changed though, when, without a pause, it came on through the heavy door, and passed into the room before his eyes.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_I_小节12.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":7.637,"text":"Quite satisfied, he closed his door, and locked himself in; double-locked himself in, which was not his custom."},{"start":7.587,"end":17.475,"text":"Thus secured against surprise, he took off his cravat; put on his dressing-gown and slippers, and his night-cap; and sat down before the fire to take his gruel."},{"start":17.475,"end":21.975,"text":"It was a very low fire indeed; nothing on such a bitter night."},{"start":21.975,"end":30.325,"text":"He was obliged to sit close to it, and brood over it, before he could extract the least sensation of warmth from such a handful of fuel."},{"start":30.325,"end":39.975,"text":"The fire-place was an old one, built by some Dutch merchant long ago, and paved all round with quaint Dutch tiles, designed to illustrate the Scriptures."},{"start":39.975,"end":61.662,"text":"There were Cains and Abels; Pharaoh's daughters, Queens of Sheba, Angelic messengers descending through the air on clouds like feather-beds, Abrahams, Belshazzars, Apostles putting off to sea in butter-boats, hundreds of figures, to attract his thoughts; and yet that face of Marley, seven years dead, came like the ancient Prophet's rod, and swallowed up the whole."},{"start":61.662,"end":72.675,"text":"If each smooth tile had been a blank at first, with power to shape some picture on its surface from the disjointed fragments of his thoughts, there would have been a copy of old Marley's head on every one."},{"start":72.675,"end":76.85,"text":"Humbug!\" said Scrooge; and walked across the room."},{"start":76.85,"end":80.3,"text":"After several turns, he sat down again."},{"start":80.3,"end":92.387,"text":"As he threw his head back in the chair, his glance happened to rest upon a bell, a disused bell, that hung in the room, and communicated for some purpose now forgotten with a chamber in the highest story of the building."},{"start":92.387,"end":100.45,"text":"It was with great astonishment, and with a strange, inexplicable dread, that as he looked, he saw this bell begin to swing."},{"start":100.45,"end":108.762,"text":"It swung so softly in the outset that it scarcely made a sound; but soon it rang out loudly, and so did every bell in the house."},{"start":108.762,"end":113.45,"text":"This might have lasted half a minute, or a minute, but it seemed an hour."},{"start":113.45,"end":116.887,"text":"The bells ceased as they had begun, together."},{"start":116.887,"end":125.425,"text":"They were succeeded by a clanking noise, deep down below; as if some person were dragging a heavy chain over the casks in the wine-merchant's cellar."},{"start":125.425,"end":131.4,"text":"Scrooge then remembered to have heard that ghosts in haunted houses were described as dragging chains."},{"start":131.4,"end":141.7,"text":"The cellar-door flew open with a booming sound, and then he heard the noise much louder, on the floors below; then coming up the stairs; then coming straight towards his door."},{"start":141.7,"end":144.862,"text":"It's humbug still!\" said Scrooge."},{"start":144.862,"end":146.7,"text":"I won't believe it."},{"start":146.7,"end":154.85,"text":"His colour changed though, when, without a pause, it came on through the heavy door, and passed into the room before his eyes."}]}},{"id":"I_13","number":13,"zh":{"text":"它一进来，那将熄的火苗腾地窜了起来，仿佛在喊：\"我认得他！\n是马利的鬼魂！\"随即又落了下去。\n还是那张脸：一模一样。\n马利还是那条辫子、那件惯常的背心、紧腿裤和长靴；靴子上的穗子根根直竖，跟他的辫子、他的衣襟下摆、他头上的头发一样。\n他拖着的那条链子绕在他腰间。\n链子很长，像尾巴似的盘在他身上；那链子（斯克鲁奇凑近细看过）是用钱箱、钥匙、挂锁、账簿、契据，还有钢打的沉甸甸的钱袋连成的。\n他的身子是透明的：所以斯克鲁奇打量他时，一眼能透过他的背心，看见他后襟上那两颗纽扣。\n斯克鲁奇常听人说马利这人没心肝，可直到此刻他才信了。\n不，便是此刻他也还是不信。\n尽管他把那幽灵从头到脚看了个透，瞧见它站在面前；尽管他感到了它那死寒的眼睛里透出的阵阵阴冷；还看清了裹在它头上、下巴上那条折叠手帕的纹路——这块包布是他先前没留意到的：他仍旧将信将疑，跟自己的感官较着劲。\n\"喂！\"斯克鲁奇说，还是那样刻薄、那样冷淡。\n\"你找我有什么事？\"\n\"事大着呢！\"——是马利的声音，错不了。\n\"你是谁？\"\n\"问我从前是谁吧。\"\n\"那你从前是谁呢？\"斯克鲁奇提高了嗓门。\n\"作为一个鬼魂，你倒挺讲究。\"他本想说\"对一个鬼魂来说\"，临了换了这么个说法，觉得更贴切些。\n\"我生前是你的合伙人，雅各布·马利。\"\n\"你能——你能坐下吗？\"斯克鲁奇半信半疑地望着他问。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_I_小节13.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":5.587,"text":"它一进来，那将熄的火苗腾地窜了起来，仿佛在喊：\"我认得他！"},{"start":5.537,"end":8.925,"text":"是马利的鬼魂！\"随即又落了下去。"},{"start":8.925,"end":11.325,"text":"还是那张脸：一模一样。"},{"start":11.325,"end":22.6,"text":"马利还是那条辫子、那件惯常的背心、紧腿裤和长靴；靴子上的穗子根根直竖，跟他的辫子、他的衣襟下摆、他头上的头发一样。"},{"start":22.6,"end":25.675,"text":"他拖着的那条链子绕在他腰间。"},{"start":25.675,"end":38.862,"text":"链子很长，像尾巴似的盘在他身上；那链子（斯克鲁奇凑近细看过）是用钱箱、钥匙、挂锁、账簿、契据，还有钢打的沉甸甸的钱袋连成的。"},{"start":38.862,"end":47.312,"text":"他的身子是透明的：所以斯克鲁奇打量他时，一眼能透过他的背心，看见他后襟上那两颗纽扣。"},{"start":47.312,"end":52.487,"text":"斯克鲁奇常听人说马利这人没心肝，可直到此刻他才信了。"},{"start":52.487,"end":55.3,"text":"不，便是此刻他也还是不信。"},{"start":55.3,"end":75.125,"text":"尽管他把那幽灵从头到脚看了个透，瞧见它站在面前；尽管他感到了它那死寒的眼睛里透出的阵阵阴冷；还看清了裹在它头上、下巴上那条折叠手帕的纹路——这块包布是他先前没留意到的：他仍旧将信将疑，跟自己的感官较着劲。"},{"start":75.125,"end":76.012,"text":"喂！"},{"start":76.012,"end":79.687,"text":"斯克鲁奇说，还是那样刻薄、那样冷淡。"},{"start":79.687,"end":81.287,"text":"你找我有什么事？"},{"start":81.287,"end":82.65,"text":"事大着呢！"},{"start":82.65,"end":85.125,"text":"是马利的声音，错不了。"},{"start":85.125,"end":86.312,"text":"你是谁？"},{"start":86.312,"end":88.25,"text":"问我从前是谁吧。"},{"start":88.25,"end":92.075,"text":"那你从前是谁呢？\"斯克鲁奇提高了嗓门。"},{"start":92.075,"end":100.212,"text":"作为一个鬼魂，你倒挺讲究。\"他本想说\"对一个鬼魂来说\"，临了换了这么个说法，觉得更贴切些。"},{"start":100.212,"end":103.737,"text":"我生前是你的合伙人，雅各布·马利。"},{"start":103.737,"end":108.112,"text":"你能——你能坐下吗？\"斯克鲁奇半信半疑地望着他问。"}]},"en":{"text":"Upon its coming in, the dying flame leaped up, as though it cried \"I know him!\nMarley's Ghost!\" and fell again.\nThe same face: the very same.\nMarley in his pig-tail, usual waistcoat, tights, and boots; the tassels on the latter bristling, like his pigtail, and his coat-skirts, and the hair upon his head.\nThe chain he drew was clasped about his middle.\nIt was long, and wound about him like a tail; and it was made (for Scrooge observed it closely) of cashboxes, keys, padlocks, ledgers, deeds, and heavy purses wrought in steel.\nHis body was transparent: so that Scrooge, observing him, and looking through his waistcoat, could see the two buttons on his coat behind.\nScrooge had often heard it said that Marley had no bowels, but he had never believed it until now.\nNo, nor did he believe it even now.\nThough he looked the phantom through and through, and saw it standing before him; though he felt the chilling influence of its death-cold eyes; and marked the very texture of the folded kerchief bound about its head and chin, which wrapper he had not observed before: he was still incredulous, and fought against his senses.\n\"How now!\" said Scrooge, caustic and cold as ever.\n\"What do you want with me?\"\n\"Much!\"--Marley's voice, no doubt about it.\n\"Who are you?\"\n\"Ask me who I _was_.\"\n\"Who _were_ you then?\" said Scrooge, raising his voice.\n\"You're particular--for a shade.\" He was going to say \"_to_ a shade,\" but substituted this, as more appropriate.\n\"In life I was your partner, Jacob Marley.\"\n\"Can you--can you sit down?\" asked Scrooge, looking doubtfully at him.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_I_小节13.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":5.75,"text":"Upon its coming in, the dying flame leaped up, as though it cried \"I know him!"},{"start":5.7,"end":8.675,"text":"Marley's Ghost!\" and fell again."},{"start":8.675,"end":11.725,"text":"The same face: the very same."},{"start":11.725,"end":22.425,"text":"Marley in his pig-tail, usual waistcoat, tights, and boots; the tassels on the latter bristling, like his pigtail, and his coat-skirts, and the hair upon his head."},{"start":22.425,"end":25.675,"text":"The chain he drew was clasped about his middle."},{"start":25.675,"end":38.25,"text":"It was long, and wound about him like a tail; and it was made (for Scrooge observed it closely) of cashboxes, keys, padlocks, ledgers, deeds, and heavy purses wrought in steel."},{"start":38.25,"end":46.85,"text":"His body was transparent: so that Scrooge, observing him, and looking through his waistcoat, could see the two buttons on his coat behind."},{"start":46.85,"end":52.9,"text":"Scrooge had often heard it said that Marley had no bowels, but he had never believed it until now."},{"start":52.9,"end":55.95,"text":"No, nor did he believe it even now."},{"start":55.95,"end":73.612,"text":"Though he looked the phantom through and through, and saw it standing before him; though he felt the chilling influence of its death-cold eyes; and marked the very texture of the folded kerchief bound about its head and chin, which wrapper he had not observed before: he was still incredulous, and fought against his senses."},{"start":73.612,"end":78,"text":"How now!\" said Scrooge, caustic and cold as ever."},{"start":78,"end":79.887,"text":"What do you want with me?"},{"start":79.887,"end":81.35,"text":"Much!"},{"start":81.35,"end":84.337,"text":"Marley's voice, no doubt about it."},{"start":84.337,"end":85.9,"text":"Who are you?"},{"start":85.9,"end":89.337,"text":"Ask me who I _was_.\""},{"start":89.337,"end":94.587,"text":"Who _were_ you then?\" said Scrooge, raising his voice."},{"start":94.587,"end":97.062,"text":"You're particular--for a shade."},{"start":97.062,"end":103.712,"text":"He was going to say \"_to_ a shade,\" but substituted this, as more appropriate."},{"start":103.712,"end":107.025,"text":"In life I was your partner, Jacob Marley."},{"start":107.025,"end":111.862,"text":"Can you--can you sit down?\" asked Scrooge, looking doubtfully at him."}]}},{"id":"I_14","number":14,"zh":{"text":"\"我能。\"\n\"那就坐吧。\"\n斯克鲁奇问这话，是因为他拿不准这么透明的一个鬼魂还有没有本事坐到椅子上；又觉着万一坐不成，少不得要来一番尴尬的解释。\n可那鬼魂在壁炉对面坐了下来，仿佛对此早已习以为常。\n\"你不信我，\"那鬼魂说道。\n\"我不信，\"斯克鲁奇说。\n\"除了你自己的感官，你还想要什么证据来证明我真实存在呢？\"\n\"我不知道，\"斯克鲁奇说。\n\"你为什么怀疑你的感官呢？\"\n\"因为，\"斯克鲁奇说，\"一丁点儿小事就能扰乱它们。\n肠胃稍微有点毛病，它们就会骗人。\n你也许只是一块没消化的牛肉、一抹芥末、一星干酪渣、一片没煮透的土豆。\n不管你是什么，你身上的肉汁味儿，可比坟墓味儿重多了！\"\n斯克鲁奇向来没什么开玩笑的习惯，这会儿他心里头也丝毫不觉着有什么诙谐。\n实情是，他想耍点机灵，借此分散自己的注意力，把恐惧压下去；因为那幽灵的声音连他骨头里的骨髓都搅得发慌。\n斯克鲁奇觉着，要是这么默不作声地坐着、盯着那双呆滞凝固的眼睛哪怕一会儿，准会叫他魂飞魄散。\n还有一桩很可怕的事，就是这幽灵自带着一团地狱般的气息。\n斯克鲁奇自己感觉不到，可这分明是真的；因为那鬼魂虽然坐得纹丝不动，它的头发、衣襟和穗子却仍旧飘动着，像被炉膛里冒出的热气掀动一般。\n\"你瞧见这根牙签了吗？\"斯克鲁奇出于刚才说的缘由，赶忙又转守为攻；他巴望着，哪怕只一秒钟，也好把那幽灵石头似的目光从自己身上引开。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_I_小节14.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":1.125,"text":"我能。"},{"start":1.075,"end":2.425,"text":"那就坐吧。"},{"start":2.425,"end":13.1,"text":"斯克鲁奇问这话，是因为他拿不准这么透明的一个鬼魂还有没有本事坐到椅子上；又觉着万一坐不成，少不得要来一番尴尬的解释。"},{"start":13.1,"end":18.375,"text":"可那鬼魂在壁炉对面坐了下来，仿佛对此早已习以为常。"},{"start":18.375,"end":20.787,"text":"你不信我，\"那鬼魂说道。"},{"start":20.787,"end":23.012,"text":"我不信，\"斯克鲁奇说。"},{"start":23.012,"end":27.925,"text":"除了你自己的感官，你还想要什么证据来证明我真实存在呢？"},{"start":27.925,"end":30.275,"text":"我不知道，\"斯克鲁奇说。"},{"start":30.275,"end":32.462,"text":"你为什么怀疑你的感官呢？"},{"start":32.462,"end":36.65,"text":"因为，\"斯克鲁奇说，\"一丁点儿小事就能扰乱它们。"},{"start":36.65,"end":39.887,"text":"肠胃稍微有点毛病，它们就会骗人。"},{"start":39.887,"end":46.375,"text":"你也许只是一块没消化的牛肉、一抹芥末、一星干酪渣、一片没煮透的土豆。"},{"start":46.375,"end":50.725,"text":"不管你是什么，你身上的肉汁味儿，可比坟墓味儿重多了！"},{"start":50.725,"end":56.962,"text":"斯克鲁奇向来没什么开玩笑的习惯，这会儿他心里头也丝毫不觉着有什么诙谐。"},{"start":56.962,"end":66.475,"text":"实情是，他想耍点机灵，借此分散自己的注意力，把恐惧压下去；因为那幽灵的声音连他骨头里的骨髓都搅得发慌。"},{"start":66.475,"end":75.137,"text":"斯克鲁奇觉着，要是这么默不作声地坐着、盯着那双呆滞凝固的眼睛哪怕一会儿，准会叫他魂飞魄散。"},{"start":75.137,"end":80.5,"text":"还有一桩很可怕的事，就是这幽灵自带着一团地狱般的气息。"},{"start":80.5,"end":93.3,"text":"斯克鲁奇自己感觉不到，可这分明是真的；因为那鬼魂虽然坐得纹丝不动，它的头发、衣襟和穗子却仍旧飘动着，像被炉膛里冒出的热气掀动一般。"},{"start":93.3,"end":105.712,"text":"你瞧见这根牙签了吗？\"斯克鲁奇出于刚才说的缘由，赶忙又转守为攻；他巴望着，哪怕只一秒钟，也好把那幽灵石头似的目光从自己身上引开。"}]},"en":{"text":"\"I can.\"\n\"Do it then.\"\nScrooge asked the question, because he didn't know whether a ghost so transparent might find himself in a condition to take a chair; and felt that in the event of its being impossible, it might involve the necessity of an embarrassing explanation.\nBut the ghost sat down on the opposite side of the fire-place, as if he were quite used to it.\n\"You don't believe in me,\" observed the Ghost.\n\"I don't,\" said Scrooge.\n\"What evidence would you have of my reality, beyond that of your senses?\"\n\"I don't know,\" said Scrooge.\n\"Why do you doubt your senses?\"\n\"Because,\" said Scrooge, \"a little thing affects them.\nA slight disorder of the stomach makes them cheats.\nYou may be an undigested bit of beef, a blot of mustard, a crumb of cheese, a fragment of an underdone potato.\nThere's more of gravy than of grave about you, whatever you are!\"\nScrooge was not much in the habit of cracking jokes, nor did he feel, in his heart, by any means waggish then.\nThe truth is, that he tried to be smart, as a means of distracting his own attention, and keeping down his terror; for the spectre's voice disturbed the very marrow in his bones.\nTo sit, staring at those fixed, glazed eyes, in silence for a moment, would play, Scrooge felt, the very deuce with him.\nThere was something very awful, too, in the spectre's being provided with an infernal atmosphere of its own.\nScrooge could not feel it himself, but this was clearly the case; for though the Ghost sat perfectly motionless, its hair, and skirts, and tassels, were still agitated as by the hot vapour from an oven.\n\"You see this toothpick?\" said Scrooge, returning quickly to the charge, for the reason just assigned; and wishing, though it were only for a second, to divert the vision's stony gaze from himself.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_I_小节14.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":1.65,"text":"I can."},{"start":1.6,"end":3.175,"text":"Do it then."},{"start":3.175,"end":16.4,"text":"Scrooge asked the question, because he didn't know whether a ghost so transparent might find himself in a condition to take a chair; and felt that in the event of its being impossible, it might involve the necessity of an embarrassing explanation."},{"start":16.4,"end":22.112,"text":"But the ghost sat down on the opposite side of the fire-place, as if he were quite used to it."},{"start":22.112,"end":25.437,"text":"You don't believe in me,\" observed the Ghost."},{"start":25.437,"end":27.975,"text":"I don't,\" said Scrooge."},{"start":27.975,"end":32.512,"text":"What evidence would you have of my reality, beyond that of your senses?"},{"start":32.512,"end":35.15,"text":"I don't know,\" said Scrooge."},{"start":35.15,"end":37.425,"text":"Why do you doubt your senses?"},{"start":37.425,"end":41.35,"text":"Because,\" said Scrooge, \"a little thing affects them."},{"start":41.35,"end":44.95,"text":"A slight disorder of the stomach makes them cheats."},{"start":44.95,"end":52.525,"text":"You may be an undigested bit of beef, a blot of mustard, a crumb of cheese, a fragment of an underdone potato."},{"start":52.525,"end":56.837,"text":"There's more of gravy than of grave about you, whatever you are!"},{"start":56.837,"end":64.275,"text":"Scrooge was not much in the habit of cracking jokes, nor did he feel, in his heart, by any means waggish then."},{"start":64.275,"end":74.812,"text":"The truth is, that he tried to be smart, as a means of distracting his own attention, and keeping down his terror; for the spectre's voice disturbed the very marrow in his bones."},{"start":74.812,"end":83.825,"text":"To sit, staring at those fixed, glazed eyes, in silence for a moment, would play, Scrooge felt, the very deuce with him."},{"start":83.825,"end":90.35,"text":"There was something very awful, too, in the spectre's being provided with an infernal atmosphere of its own."},{"start":90.35,"end":103.125,"text":"Scrooge could not feel it himself, but this was clearly the case; for though the Ghost sat perfectly motionless, its hair, and skirts, and tassels, were still agitated as by the hot vapour from an oven."},{"start":103.125,"end":115.087,"text":"You see this toothpick?\" said Scrooge, returning quickly to the charge, for the reason just assigned; and wishing, though it were only for a second, to divert the vision's stony gaze from himself."}]}},{"id":"I_15","number":15,"zh":{"text":"\"瞧见了，\"那鬼魂答道。\n\"你又没看着它，\"斯克鲁奇说。\n\"可我还是看得见它，\"那鬼魂说，\"尽管没看着。\"\n\"得！\"斯克鲁奇回道。\n\"我只消把它一吞下去，往后这辈子就得让一大群妖怪缠着受罪，而且全是我自己变出来的。\n胡扯，我跟你说——胡扯！\"\n听了这话，那精灵发出一声骇人的尖叫，把链子摇得哗啦作响，那声音凄惨吓人到极点，斯克鲁奇紧紧抓住椅子，免得自己晕厥倒下去。\n可当那幽灵把裹在头上的绷带取下——仿佛在屋里戴着太热了似的——它的下巴颏儿一下子耷拉到胸口上时，他的恐惧又何止大了多少倍！\n斯克鲁奇扑通跪倒在地，双手捂住了脸。\n\"开恩哪！\"他说。\n\"可怕的幽灵，你为什么来烦扰我？\"\n\"满脑子俗念的人哪！\"那鬼魂答道，\"你究竟信不信我？\"\n\"我信，\"斯克鲁奇说。\n\"我不能不信。\n可精灵们为什么要在人世间游走，又为什么要来找我呢？\"\n\"每一个人，\"那鬼魂回道，\"都得让自己心里头那个精灵走出去，在同胞中间四处游走，走南闯北；倘若那精灵生前不肯出去走，死后就注定非走不可。\n它命中注定要在世上四处飘荡——哎，我好苦哇！——眼看着它没法分享、本可在世时分享并化作幸福的种种！\"\n那幽灵又叫了一声，摇着链子，绞着它那双影子似的手。\n\"你被锁住了，\"斯克鲁奇哆嗦着说。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_I_小节15.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":2.412,"text":"瞧见了，\"那鬼魂答道。"},{"start":2.362,"end":5.062,"text":"你又没看着它，\"斯克鲁奇说。"},{"start":5.062,"end":9.275,"text":"可我还是看得见它，\"那鬼魂说，\"尽管没看着。"},{"start":9.275,"end":10.187,"text":"得！"},{"start":10.187,"end":11.837,"text":"斯克鲁奇回道。"},{"start":11.837,"end":19.75,"text":"我只消把它一吞下去，往后这辈子就得让一大群妖怪缠着受罪，而且全是我自己变出来的。"},{"start":19.75,"end":22.275,"text":"胡扯，我跟你说——胡扯！"},{"start":22.275,"end":34.025,"text":"听了这话，那精灵发出一声骇人的尖叫，把链子摇得哗啦作响，那声音凄惨吓人到极点，斯克鲁奇紧紧抓住椅子，免得自己晕厥倒下去。"},{"start":34.025,"end":45.212,"text":"可当那幽灵把裹在头上的绷带取下——仿佛在屋里戴着太热了似的——它的下巴颏儿一下子耷拉到胸口上时，他的恐惧又何止大了多少倍！"},{"start":45.212,"end":48.962,"text":"斯克鲁奇扑通跪倒在地，双手捂住了脸。"},{"start":48.962,"end":50.9,"text":"开恩哪！\"他说。"},{"start":50.9,"end":53.85,"text":"可怕的幽灵，你为什么来烦扰我？"},{"start":53.85,"end":58.55,"text":"满脑子俗念的人哪！\"那鬼魂答道，\"你究竟信不信我？"},{"start":58.55,"end":60.625,"text":"我信，\"斯克鲁奇说。"},{"start":60.625,"end":62.137,"text":"我不能不信。"},{"start":62.137,"end":66.65,"text":"可精灵们为什么要在人世间游走，又为什么要来找我呢？"},{"start":66.65,"end":79.775,"text":"每一个人，\"那鬼魂回道，\"都得让自己心里头那个精灵走出去，在同胞中间四处游走，走南闯北；倘若那精灵生前不肯出去走，死后就注定非走不可。"},{"start":79.775,"end":84.2,"text":"它命中注定要在世上四处飘荡——哎，我好苦哇！"},{"start":84.2,"end":89.475,"text":"眼看着它没法分享、本可在世时分享并化作幸福的种种！"},{"start":89.475,"end":94.487,"text":"那幽灵又叫了一声，摇着链子，绞着它那双影子似的手。"},{"start":94.487,"end":97.512,"text":"你被锁住了，\"斯克鲁奇哆嗦着说。"}]},"en":{"text":"\"I do,\" replied the Ghost.\n\"You are not looking at it,\" said Scrooge.\n\"But I see it,\" said the Ghost, \"notwithstanding.\"\n\"Well!\" returned Scrooge.\n\"I have but to swallow this, and be for the rest of my days persecuted by a legion of goblins, all of my own creation.\nHumbug, I tell you--humbug!\"\nAt this, the spirit raised a frightful cry, and shook its chain with such a dismal and appalling noise, that Scrooge held on tight to his chair, to save himself from falling in a swoon.\nBut how much greater was his horror, when the phantom taking off the bandage round its head, as if it were too warm to wear in-doors, its lower jaw dropped down upon its breast!\nScrooge fell upon his knees, and clasped his hands before his face.\n\"Mercy!\" he said.\n\"Dreadful apparition, why do you trouble me?\"\n\"Man of the worldly mind!\" replied the Ghost, \"do you believe in me or not?\"\n\"I do,\" said Scrooge.\n\"I must.\nBut why do spirits walk the earth, and why do they come to me?\"\n\"It is required of every man,\" the Ghost returned, \"that the spirit within him should walk abroad among his fellow-men, and travel far and wide; and if that spirit goes not forth in life, it is condemned to do so after death.\nIt is doomed to wander through the world--oh, woe is me!--and witness what it cannot share, but might have shared on earth, and turned to happiness!\"\nAgain the spectre raised a cry, and shook its chain, and wrung its shadowy hands.\n\"You are fettered,\" said Scrooge, trembling.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_I_小节15.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":2.862,"text":"I do,\" replied the Ghost."},{"start":2.812,"end":6,"text":"You are not looking at it,\" said Scrooge."},{"start":6,"end":9.837,"text":"But I see it,\" said the Ghost, \"notwithstanding."},{"start":9.837,"end":12.275,"text":"Well!\" returned Scrooge."},{"start":12.275,"end":20.037,"text":"I have but to swallow this, and be for the rest of my days persecuted by a legion of goblins, all of my own creation."},{"start":20.037,"end":22.9,"text":"Humbug, I tell you--humbug!"},{"start":22.9,"end":34.35,"text":"At this, the spirit raised a frightful cry, and shook its chain with such a dismal and appalling noise, that Scrooge held on tight to his chair, to save himself from falling in a swoon."},{"start":34.35,"end":44.75,"text":"But how much greater was his horror, when the phantom taking off the bandage round its head, as if it were too warm to wear in-doors, its lower jaw dropped down upon its breast!"},{"start":44.75,"end":49.637,"text":"Scrooge fell upon his knees, and clasped his hands before his face."},{"start":49.637,"end":51.837,"text":"Mercy!\" he said."},{"start":51.837,"end":54.95,"text":"Dreadful apparition, why do you trouble me?"},{"start":54.95,"end":60.087,"text":"Man of the worldly mind!\" replied the Ghost, \"do you believe in me or not?"},{"start":60.087,"end":62.612,"text":"I do,\" said Scrooge."},{"start":62.612,"end":64.187,"text":"I must."},{"start":64.187,"end":68.4,"text":"But why do spirits walk the earth, and why do they come to me?"},{"start":68.4,"end":81.725,"text":"It is required of every man,\" the Ghost returned, \"that the spirit within him should walk abroad among his fellow-men, and travel far and wide; and if that spirit goes not forth in life, it is condemned to do so after death."},{"start":81.725,"end":90.35,"text":"It is doomed to wander through the world--oh, woe is me!--and witness what it cannot share, but might have shared on earth, and turned to happiness!"},{"start":90.35,"end":96.225,"text":"Again the spectre raised a cry, and shook its chain, and wrung its shadowy hands."},{"start":96.225,"end":99.737,"text":"You are fettered,\" said Scrooge, trembling."}]}},{"id":"I_16","number":16,"zh":{"text":"\"告诉我为什么？\"\n\"我戴的是我生前亲手打造的链子，\"那鬼魂答道。\n\"我一环一环、一码一码地把它打成；我是自愿把它系上身的，也是自愿戴着它的。\n难道它的式样你看着眼生吗？\n斯克鲁奇抖得越来越厉害。\n\"要不你想知道，\"那鬼魂接着说，\"你自己身上背着的那盘结实链子，有多重、有多长？\n七个圣诞前夜以前，它就跟这一条一般沉、一般长了。\n打那以后，你一直在它上头下工夫。\n那是一条沉甸甸的链子！\"\n斯克鲁奇朝地板四下瞟了瞟，只当会看见自己被五六十英寻长的铁缆围着：可他什么也没瞧见。\n\"雅各布，\"他哀求道。\n\"老雅各布·马利，再多跟我说些吧。\n跟我说几句宽心的话吧，雅各布。\"\n\"我没有宽心的话可给你，\"那鬼魂答道。\n\"宽慰来自别的境界，埃比尼泽·斯克鲁奇，由别的使者传给别一类的人。\n我也不能把我想说的告诉你。\n我获准多说的，也就一丁点儿了。\n我不能歇息，不能停留，哪儿也不能逗留。\n我的精灵生前从没走出过我们那间账房——记住我的话！——生前我的精灵从没游出过我们那个换钱小洞的窄小界限；如今一段段累人的旅途正横在我面前！\"","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_I_小节16.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":1.587,"text":"告诉我为什么？"},{"start":1.537,"end":5.737,"text":"我戴的是我生前亲手打造的链子，\"那鬼魂答道。"},{"start":5.737,"end":12.75,"text":"我一环一环、一码一码地把它打成；我是自愿把它系上身的，也是自愿戴着它的。"},{"start":12.75,"end":15.575,"text":"难道它的式样你看着眼生吗？"},{"start":15.575,"end":18.112,"text":"斯克鲁奇抖得越来越厉害。"},{"start":18.112,"end":25.175,"text":"要不你想知道，\"那鬼魂接着说，\"你自己身上背着的那盘结实链子，有多重、有多长？"},{"start":25.175,"end":29.925,"text":"七个圣诞前夜以前，它就跟这一条一般沉、一般长了。"},{"start":29.925,"end":33.05,"text":"打那以后，你一直在它上头下工夫。"},{"start":33.05,"end":35.387,"text":"那是一条沉甸甸的链子！"},{"start":35.387,"end":43.262,"text":"斯克鲁奇朝地板四下瞟了瞟，只当会看见自己被五六十英寻长的铁缆围着：可他什么也没瞧见。"},{"start":43.262,"end":45.325,"text":"雅各布，\"他哀求道。"},{"start":45.325,"end":48.537,"text":"老雅各布·马利，再多跟我说些吧。"},{"start":48.537,"end":51.437,"text":"跟我说几句宽心的话吧，雅各布。"},{"start":51.437,"end":54.737,"text":"我没有宽心的话可给你，\"那鬼魂答道。"},{"start":54.737,"end":61.025,"text":"宽慰来自别的境界，埃比尼泽·斯克鲁奇，由别的使者传给别一类的人。"},{"start":61.025,"end":63.387,"text":"我也不能把我想说的告诉你。"},{"start":63.387,"end":66.2,"text":"我获准多说的，也就一丁点儿了。"},{"start":66.2,"end":69.75,"text":"我不能歇息，不能停留，哪儿也不能逗留。"},{"start":69.75,"end":73.875,"text":"我的精灵生前从没走出过我们那间账房——记住我的话！"},{"start":73.875,"end":82.312,"text":"生前我的精灵从没游出过我们那个换钱小洞的窄小界限；如今一段段累人的旅途正横在我面前！"}]},"en":{"text":"\"Tell me why?\"\n\"I wear the chain I forged in life,\" replied the Ghost.\n\"I made it link by link, and yard by yard; I girded it on of my own free will, and of my own free will I wore it.\nIs its pattern strange to _you_?\"\nScrooge trembled more and more.\n\"Or would you know,\" pursued the Ghost, \"the weight and length of the strong coil you bear yourself?\nIt was full as heavy and as long as this, seven Christmas Eves ago.\nYou have laboured on it, since.\nIt is a ponderous chain!\"\nScrooge glanced about him on the floor, in the expectation of finding himself surrounded by some fifty or sixty fathoms of iron cable: but he could see nothing.\n\"Jacob,\" he said, imploringly.\n\"Old Jacob Marley, tell me more.\nSpeak comfort to me, Jacob.\"\n\"I have none to give,\" the Ghost replied.\n\"It comes from other regions, Ebenezer Scrooge, and is conveyed by other ministers, to other kinds of men.\nNor can I tell you what I would.\nA very little more, is all permitted to me.\nI cannot rest, I cannot stay, I cannot linger anywhere.\nMy spirit never walked beyond our counting-house--mark me!--in life my spirit never roved beyond the narrow limits of our money-changing hole; and weary journeys lie before me!\"","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_I_小节16.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":1.7,"text":"Tell me why?"},{"start":1.65,"end":5.65,"text":"I wear the chain I forged in life,\" replied the Ghost."},{"start":5.65,"end":13.25,"text":"I made it link by link, and yard by yard; I girded it on of my own free will, and of my own free will I wore it."},{"start":13.25,"end":16.7,"text":"Is its pattern strange to _you_?"},{"start":16.7,"end":19.375,"text":"Scrooge trembled more and more."},{"start":19.375,"end":25.25,"text":"Or would you know,\" pursued the Ghost, \"the weight and length of the strong coil you bear yourself?"},{"start":25.25,"end":29.975,"text":"It was full as heavy and as long as this, seven Christmas Eves ago."},{"start":29.975,"end":32.725,"text":"You have laboured on it, since."},{"start":32.725,"end":35.025,"text":"It is a ponderous chain!"},{"start":35.025,"end":44.7,"text":"Scrooge glanced about him on the floor, in the expectation of finding himself surrounded by some fifty or sixty fathoms of iron cable: but he could see nothing."},{"start":44.7,"end":47.875,"text":"Jacob,\" he said, imploringly."},{"start":47.875,"end":50.825,"text":"Old Jacob Marley, tell me more."},{"start":50.825,"end":53.575,"text":"Speak comfort to me, Jacob."},{"start":53.575,"end":56.862,"text":"I have none to give,\" the Ghost replied."},{"start":56.862,"end":63.9,"text":"It comes from other regions, Ebenezer Scrooge, and is conveyed by other ministers, to other kinds of men."},{"start":63.9,"end":66.412,"text":"Nor can I tell you what I would."},{"start":66.412,"end":69.887,"text":"A very little more, is all permitted to me."},{"start":69.887,"end":74.6,"text":"I cannot rest, I cannot stay, I cannot linger anywhere."},{"start":74.6,"end":85.062,"text":"My spirit never walked beyond our counting-house--mark me!--in life my spirit never roved beyond the narrow limits of our money-changing hole; and weary journeys lie before me!"}]}},{"id":"I_17","number":17,"zh":{"text":"斯克鲁奇有个习惯，每逢沉思起来，总爱把双手插进裤兜里。\n这会儿他一面琢磨着鬼魂方才那番话，一面也这么做了，可眼睛没敢抬起来，膝盖也没从地上起来。\n\"你这事儿想必办得很慢吧，雅各布，\"斯克鲁奇用一种生意人的口吻说道，虽说带着几分谦卑和恭敬。\n\"慢！\"那鬼魂重复了一句。\n\"死了七年，\"斯克鲁奇沉吟道。\n\"这一向都在赶路？\"\n\"一刻不停，\"那鬼魂说。\n\"没有歇息，没有安宁。\n悔恨的折磨永无止境。\"\n\"你赶得快吗？\"斯克鲁奇说。\n\"乘着风的翅膀，\"那鬼魂答道。\n\"那这七年里，你该已经走过好大一片地方了吧，\"斯克鲁奇说。\n那鬼魂一听这话，又叫了起来，在这死寂的夜里把链子摇得那样瘆人，本区是大有理由控告它扰乱治安的。\n\"哦，我这被囚禁、被捆缚、戴着双重镣铐的可怜虫，\"那幽灵嚷道，\"竟不懂得：不朽的生灵纵然世世代代不停劳作，也得等这大地化入永恒，它能成就的善才会全数显现。\n竟不懂得：任凭哪一个基督徒的精灵，在它那小小的天地里行善——无论那天地多么小——都会发觉自己这短促的尘世一生，远不够施展它那浩大的济世之力。\n竟不懂得：再多的悔恨，也补不回一生中错过的那些机缘！\n可我当年就是这样的人哪！\n哦！我当年就是这样的人哪！\"\n\"可你向来是个出色的生意人哪，雅各布，\"斯克鲁奇结结巴巴地说，这会儿他开始把这话往自己身上套了。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_I_小节17.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":5.425,"text":"斯克鲁奇有个习惯，每逢沉思起来，总爱把双手插进裤兜里。"},{"start":5.375,"end":13.7,"text":"这会儿他一面琢磨着鬼魂方才那番话，一面也这么做了，可眼睛没敢抬起来，膝盖也没从地上起来。"},{"start":13.7,"end":22.037,"text":"你这事儿想必办得很慢吧，雅各布，\"斯克鲁奇用一种生意人的口吻说道，虽说带着几分谦卑和恭敬。"},{"start":22.037,"end":22.962,"text":"慢！"},{"start":22.962,"end":25.187,"text":"那鬼魂重复了一句。"},{"start":25.187,"end":28.075,"text":"死了七年，\"斯克鲁奇沉吟道。"},{"start":28.075,"end":29.85,"text":"这一向都在赶路？"},{"start":29.85,"end":32.325,"text":"一刻不停，\"那鬼魂说。"},{"start":32.325,"end":34.425,"text":"没有歇息，没有安宁。"},{"start":34.425,"end":36.875,"text":"悔恨的折磨永无止境。"},{"start":36.875,"end":39.337,"text":"你赶得快吗？\"斯克鲁奇说。"},{"start":39.337,"end":42.35,"text":"乘着风的翅膀，\"那鬼魂答道。"},{"start":42.35,"end":47.412,"text":"那这七年里，你该已经走过好大一片地方了吧，\"斯克鲁奇说。"},{"start":47.412,"end":56.675,"text":"那鬼魂一听这话，又叫了起来，在这死寂的夜里把链子摇得那样瘆人，本区是大有理由控告它扰乱治安的。"},{"start":56.675,"end":71.625,"text":"哦，我这被囚禁、被捆缚、戴着双重镣铐的可怜虫，\"那幽灵嚷道，\"竟不懂得：不朽的生灵纵然世世代代不停劳作，也得等这大地化入永恒，它能成就的善才会全数显现。"},{"start":71.625,"end":84.462,"text":"竟不懂得：任凭哪一个基督徒的精灵，在它那小小的天地里行善——无论那天地多么小——都会发觉自己这短促的尘世一生，远不够施展它那浩大的济世之力。"},{"start":84.462,"end":89.55,"text":"竟不懂得：再多的悔恨，也补不回一生中错过的那些机缘！"},{"start":89.55,"end":91.625,"text":"可我当年就是这样的人哪！"},{"start":91.625,"end":92.525,"text":"哦！"},{"start":92.525,"end":94.512,"text":"我当年就是这样的人哪！"},{"start":94.512,"end":102.612,"text":"可你向来是个出色的生意人哪，雅各布，\"斯克鲁奇结结巴巴地说，这会儿他开始把这话往自己身上套了。"}]},"en":{"text":"It was a habit with Scrooge, whenever he became thoughtful, to put his hands in his breeches pockets.\nPondering on what the Ghost had said, he did so now, but without lifting up his eyes, or getting off his knees.\n\"You must have been very slow about it, Jacob,\" Scrooge observed, in a business-like manner, though with humility and deference.\n\"Slow!\" the Ghost repeated.\n\"Seven years dead,\" mused Scrooge.\n\"And travelling all the time?\"\n\"The whole time,\" said the Ghost.\n\"No rest, no peace.\nIncessant torture of remorse.\"\n\"You travel fast?\" said Scrooge.\n\"On the wings of the wind,\" replied the Ghost.\n\"You might have got over a great quantity of ground in seven years,\" said Scrooge.\nThe Ghost, on hearing this, set up another cry, and clanked its chain so hideously in the dead silence of the night, that the Ward would have been justified in indicting it for a nuisance.\n\"Oh, captive, bound, and double-ironed,\" cried the phantom, \"not to know, that ages of incessant labour by immortal creatures, for this earth must pass into eternity before the good of which it is susceptible is all developed.\nNot to know that any Christian spirit working kindly in its little sphere, whatever it may be, will find its mortal life too short for its vast means of usefulness.\nNot to know that no space of regret can make amends for one life's opportunities misused!\nYet such was I!\nOh! such was I!\"\n\"But you were always a good man of business, Jacob,\" faultered Scrooge, who now began to apply this to himself.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_I_小节17.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":6.475,"text":"It was a habit with Scrooge, whenever he became thoughtful, to put his hands in his breeches pockets."},{"start":6.425,"end":13.787,"text":"Pondering on what the Ghost had said, he did so now, but without lifting up his eyes, or getting off his knees."},{"start":13.787,"end":21.875,"text":"You must have been very slow about it, Jacob,\" Scrooge observed, in a business-like manner, though with humility and deference."},{"start":21.875,"end":24.6,"text":"Slow!\" the Ghost repeated."},{"start":24.6,"end":27.9,"text":"Seven years dead,\" mused Scrooge."},{"start":27.9,"end":30.175,"text":"And travelling all the time?"},{"start":30.175,"end":33.025,"text":"The whole time,\" said the Ghost."},{"start":33.025,"end":35.65,"text":"No rest, no peace."},{"start":35.65,"end":38.337,"text":"Incessant torture of remorse."},{"start":38.337,"end":41.425,"text":"You travel fast?\" said Scrooge."},{"start":41.425,"end":44.875,"text":"On the wings of the wind,\" replied the Ghost."},{"start":44.875,"end":50.125,"text":"You might have got over a great quantity of ground in seven years,\" said Scrooge."},{"start":50.125,"end":61.1,"text":"The Ghost, on hearing this, set up another cry, and clanked its chain so hideously in the dead silence of the night, that the Ward would have been justified in indicting it for a nuisance."},{"start":61.1,"end":74.75,"text":"Oh, captive, bound, and double-ironed,\" cried the phantom, \"not to know, that ages of incessant labour by immortal creatures, for this earth must pass into eternity before the good of which it is susceptible is all developed."},{"start":74.75,"end":84.562,"text":"Not to know that any Christian spirit working kindly in its little sphere, whatever it may be, will find its mortal life too short for its vast means of usefulness."},{"start":84.562,"end":90.312,"text":"Not to know that no space of regret can make amends for one life's opportunities misused!"},{"start":90.312,"end":92.375,"text":"Yet such was I!"},{"start":92.375,"end":93.6,"text":"Oh!"},{"start":93.6,"end":95.487,"text":"such was I!"},{"start":95.487,"end":102.912,"text":"But you were always a good man of business, Jacob,\" faultered Scrooge, who now began to apply this to himself."}]}},{"id":"I_18","number":18,"zh":{"text":"\"生意！\"那鬼魂又绞着手嚷道。\n\"人类才是我的生意。\n众人的福祉才是我的生意；仁爱、慈悲、宽容、善心，这些才统统是我的生意。\n我做买卖的那点营生，在我那囊括万有的生意之海里，不过是一滴水罢了！\"\n它把链子举到一臂之遥，仿佛那就是它一切徒劳悲恸的根源，随即又把它重重摔在地上。\n\"在这一年周而复始的时节，\"那幽灵说，\"我受的苦最深。\n我当年为什么要垂着眼睛从同胞的人群中走过，从不抬眼望一望那颗指引东方三贤来到陋室的福星呢？\n难道就没有一户穷苦人家，是它的光本可以引着我去的吗！\"\n斯克鲁奇听那幽灵这么没完没了地说下去，心里慌乱到了极点，浑身抖个不住。\n\"听我说！\"那鬼魂嚷道。\n\"我的时辰快到了。\"\n\"我听着，\"斯克鲁奇说。\n\"可你别太为难我！\n别说那些花里胡哨的话，雅各布！\n求你了！\"\n\"我怎么会以一副你看得见的形象出现在你面前，这我不能说。\n我已经在你身边隐着身坐了一天又一天，许多许多天了。\"\n这可不是个让人舒坦的念头。\n斯克鲁奇打了个寒噤，抹了抹额上的汗。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_I_小节18.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":3.237,"text":"生意！\"那鬼魂又绞着手嚷道。"},{"start":3.187,"end":5.262,"text":"人类才是我的生意。"},{"start":5.262,"end":12.812,"text":"众人的福祉才是我的生意；仁爱、慈悲、宽容、善心，这些才统统是我的生意。"},{"start":12.812,"end":19,"text":"我做买卖的那点营生，在我那囊括万有的生意之海里，不过是一滴水罢了！"},{"start":19,"end":27.15,"text":"它把链子举到一臂之遥，仿佛那就是它一切徒劳悲恸的根源，随即又把它重重摔在地上。"},{"start":27.15,"end":31.812,"text":"在这一年周而复始的时节，\"那幽灵说，\"我受的苦最深。"},{"start":31.812,"end":40.737,"text":"我当年为什么要垂着眼睛从同胞的人群中走过，从不抬眼望一望那颗指引东方三贤来到陋室的福星呢？"},{"start":40.737,"end":45.612,"text":"难道就没有一户穷苦人家，是它的光本可以引着我去的吗！"},{"start":45.612,"end":52.337,"text":"斯克鲁奇听那幽灵这么没完没了地说下去，心里慌乱到了极点，浑身抖个不住。"},{"start":52.337,"end":54.712,"text":"听我说！\"那鬼魂嚷道。"},{"start":54.712,"end":56.512,"text":"我的时辰快到了。"},{"start":56.512,"end":58.775,"text":"我听着，\"斯克鲁奇说。"},{"start":58.775,"end":60.562,"text":"可你别太为难我！"},{"start":60.562,"end":63.487,"text":"别说那些花里胡哨的话，雅各布！"},{"start":63.487,"end":64.65,"text":"求你了！"},{"start":64.65,"end":69.712,"text":"我怎么会以一副你看得见的形象出现在你面前，这我不能说。"},{"start":69.712,"end":74.225,"text":"我已经在你身边隐着身坐了一天又一天，许多许多天了。"},{"start":74.225,"end":76.925,"text":"这可不是个让人舒坦的念头。"},{"start":76.925,"end":80.5,"text":"斯克鲁奇打了个寒噤，抹了抹额上的汗。"}]},"en":{"text":"\"Business!\" cried the Ghost, wringing its hands again.\n\"Mankind was my business.\nThe common welfare was my business; charity, mercy, forbearance, and benevolence, were, all, my business.\nThe dealings of my trade were but a drop of water in the comprehensive ocean of my business!\"\nIt held up its chain at arm's length, as if that were the cause of all its unavailing grief, and flung it heavily upon the ground again.\n\"At this time of the rolling year,\" the spectre said, \"I suffer most.\nWhy did I walk through the crowds of fellow-beings with my eyes turned down, and never raise them to that blessed Star which led the Wise Men to a poor abode?\nWere there no poor homes to which its light would have conducted _me_!\"\nScrooge was very much dismayed to hear the spectre going on at this rate, and began to quake exceedingly.\n\"Hear me!\" cried the Ghost.\n\"My time is nearly gone.\"\n\"I will,\" said Scrooge.\n\"But don't be hard upon me!\nDon't be flowery, Jacob!\nPray!\"\n\"How it is that I appear before you in a shape that you can see, I may not tell.\nI have sat invisible beside you many and many a day.\"\nIt was not an agreeable idea.\nScrooge shivered, and wiped the perspiration from his brow.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_I_小节18.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":4.175,"text":"Business!\" cried the Ghost, wringing its hands again."},{"start":4.125,"end":6.625,"text":"Mankind was my business."},{"start":6.625,"end":15.037,"text":"The common welfare was my business; charity, mercy, forbearance, and benevolence, were, all, my business."},{"start":15.037,"end":20.512,"text":"The dealings of my trade were but a drop of water in the comprehensive ocean of my business!"},{"start":20.512,"end":28.437,"text":"It held up its chain at arm's length, as if that were the cause of all its unavailing grief, and flung it heavily upon the ground again."},{"start":28.437,"end":33.237,"text":"At this time of the rolling year,\" the spectre said, \"I suffer most."},{"start":33.237,"end":41.825,"text":"Why did I walk through the crowds of fellow-beings with my eyes turned down, and never raise them to that blessed Star which led the Wise Men to a poor abode?"},{"start":41.825,"end":46.937,"text":"Were there no poor homes to which its light would have conducted _me_!"},{"start":46.937,"end":53.312,"text":"Scrooge was very much dismayed to hear the spectre going on at this rate, and began to quake exceedingly."},{"start":53.312,"end":55.9,"text":"Hear me!\" cried the Ghost."},{"start":55.9,"end":58.262,"text":"My time is nearly gone."},{"start":58.262,"end":60.812,"text":"I will,\" said Scrooge."},{"start":60.812,"end":63.187,"text":"But don't be hard upon me!"},{"start":63.187,"end":65.812,"text":"Don't be flowery, Jacob!"},{"start":65.812,"end":67.187,"text":"Pray!"},{"start":67.187,"end":72.1,"text":"How it is that I appear before you in a shape that you can see, I may not tell."},{"start":72.1,"end":75.875,"text":"I have sat invisible beside you many and many a day."},{"start":75.875,"end":78.45,"text":"It was not an agreeable idea."},{"start":78.45,"end":82.587,"text":"Scrooge shivered, and wiped the perspiration from his brow."}]}},{"id":"I_19","number":19,"zh":{"text":"\"这还只是我赎罪当中不轻的一桩呢，\"那鬼魂接着说。\n\"我今晚来，是要警告你：你还有一线机会和指望，能逃脱我这样的下场。\n这机会和指望，是我替你谋来的，埃比尼泽。\"\n\"你向来待我是个好朋友，\"斯克鲁奇说。\n\"谢谢你啦！\"\n\"你将要被三个精灵造访，\"那鬼魂又说道。\n斯克鲁奇的脸顿时拉了下来，几乎跟那鬼魂方才的一样低。\n\"这就是你说的那机会和指望吗，雅各布？\"他声音发颤地追问。\n\"正是。\"\n\"我——我看我还是不要的好，\"斯克鲁奇说。\n\"没有他们来访，\"那鬼魂说，\"你就别指望躲得开我所走的这条路。\n等着头一个明天来吧，钟敲一点的时候。\"\n\"我能不能一下子把他们都打发了，一了百了，雅各布？\"斯克鲁奇试探着说。\n\"等着第二个第二天晚上同一时辰来。\n第三个再下一晚来，等十二点最后一响的余颤歇尽的时候。\n你别指望再见着我了；可你要当心，为你自己着想，把咱俩之间发生的事记牢！\"\n说完这些话，那幽灵从桌上取过它那块包布，像先前一样缠在了头上。\n斯克鲁奇是从那牙齿发出的咔嗒一声听出来的——那是绷带把上下颚一合时弄出的脆响。\n他壮着胆子又把眼睛抬了起来，只见他这位超凡的来客直挺挺地立在他对面，链子在它胳膊上盘了一圈又一圈。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_I_小节19.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":4.625,"text":"这还只是我赎罪当中不轻的一桩呢，\"那鬼魂接着说。"},{"start":4.575,"end":10.275,"text":"我今晚来，是要警告你：你还有一线机会和指望，能逃脱我这样的下场。"},{"start":10.275,"end":14.187,"text":"这机会和指望，是我替你谋来的，埃比尼泽。"},{"start":14.187,"end":17.287,"text":"你向来待我是个好朋友，\"斯克鲁奇说。"},{"start":17.287,"end":18.55,"text":"谢谢你啦！"},{"start":18.55,"end":22.162,"text":"你将要被三个精灵造访，\"那鬼魂又说道。"},{"start":22.162,"end":27.275,"text":"斯克鲁奇的脸顿时拉了下来，几乎跟那鬼魂方才的一样低。"},{"start":27.275,"end":32.5,"text":"这就是你说的那机会和指望吗，雅各布？\"他声音发颤地追问。"},{"start":32.5,"end":33.562,"text":"正是。"},{"start":33.562,"end":37.175,"text":"我——我看我还是不要的好，\"斯克鲁奇说。"},{"start":37.175,"end":42.4,"text":"没有他们来访，\"那鬼魂说，\"你就别指望躲得开我所走的这条路。"},{"start":42.4,"end":45.887,"text":"等着头一个明天来吧，钟敲一点的时候。"},{"start":45.887,"end":52.037,"text":"我能不能一下子把他们都打发了，一了百了，雅各布？\"斯克鲁奇试探着说。"},{"start":52.037,"end":55.062,"text":"等着第二个第二天晚上同一时辰来。"},{"start":55.062,"end":59.925,"text":"第三个再下一晚来，等十二点最后一响的余颤歇尽的时候。"},{"start":59.925,"end":66.312,"text":"你别指望再见着我了；可你要当心，为你自己着想，把咱俩之间发生的事记牢！"},{"start":66.312,"end":72.425,"text":"说完这些话，那幽灵从桌上取过它那块包布，像先前一样缠在了头上。"},{"start":72.425,"end":79.762,"text":"斯克鲁奇是从那牙齿发出的咔嗒一声听出来的——那是绷带把上下颚一合时弄出的脆响。"},{"start":79.762,"end":89.9,"text":"他壮着胆子又把眼睛抬了起来，只见他这位超凡的来客直挺挺地立在他对面，链子在它胳膊上盘了一圈又一圈。"}]},"en":{"text":"\"That is no light part of my penance,\" pursued the Ghost.\n\"I am here to-night to warn you, that you have yet a chance and hope of escaping my fate.\nA chance and hope of my procuring, Ebenezer.\"\n\"You were always a good friend to me,\" said Scrooge.\n\"Thank'ee!\"\n\"You will be haunted,\" resumed the Ghost, \"by Three Spirits.\"\nScrooge's countenance fell almost as low as the Ghost's had done.\n\"Is that the chance and hope you mentioned, Jacob?\" he demanded, in a faultering voice.\n\"It is.\"\n\"I--I think I'd rather not,\" said Scrooge.\n\"Without their visits,\" said the Ghost, \"you cannot hope to shun the path I tread.\nExpect the first to-morrow, when the bell tolls one.\"\n\"Couldn't I take 'em all at once, and have it over, Jacob?\" hinted Scrooge.\n\"Expect the second on the next night at the same hour.\nThe third upon the next night when the last stroke of twelve has ceased to vibrate.\nLook to see me no more; and look that, for your own sake, you remember what has passed between us!\"\nWhen it had said these words, the spectre took its wrapper from the table, and bound it round its head, as before.\nScrooge knew this, by the smart sound its teeth made, when the jaws were brought together by the bandage.\nHe ventured to raise his eyes again, and found his supernatural visitor confronting him in an erect attitude, with its chain wound over and about its arm.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_I_小节19.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":4.2,"text":"That is no light part of my penance,\" pursued the Ghost."},{"start":4.15,"end":9.625,"text":"I am here to-night to warn you, that you have yet a chance and hope of escaping my fate."},{"start":9.625,"end":13.137,"text":"A chance and hope of my procuring, Ebenezer."},{"start":13.137,"end":16.687,"text":"You were always a good friend to me,\" said Scrooge."},{"start":16.687,"end":18.187,"text":"Thank'ee!"},{"start":18.187,"end":22.687,"text":"You will be haunted,\" resumed the Ghost, \"by Three Spirits."},{"start":22.687,"end":26.925,"text":"Scrooge's countenance fell almost as low as the Ghost's had done."},{"start":26.925,"end":32.85,"text":"Is that the chance and hope you mentioned, Jacob?\" he demanded, in a faultering voice."},{"start":32.85,"end":34.387,"text":"It is."},{"start":34.387,"end":37.9,"text":"I--I think I'd rather not,\" said Scrooge."},{"start":37.9,"end":43.125,"text":"Without their visits,\" said the Ghost, \"you cannot hope to shun the path I tread."},{"start":43.125,"end":46.862,"text":"Expect the first to-morrow, when the bell tolls one."},{"start":46.862,"end":52.462,"text":"Couldn't I take 'em all at once, and have it over, Jacob?\" hinted Scrooge."},{"start":52.462,"end":55.912,"text":"Expect the second on the next night at the same hour."},{"start":55.912,"end":60.837,"text":"The third upon the next night when the last stroke of twelve has ceased to vibrate."},{"start":60.837,"end":67.35,"text":"Look to see me no more; and look that, for your own sake, you remember what has passed between us!"},{"start":67.35,"end":74.3,"text":"When it had said these words, the spectre took its wrapper from the table, and bound it round its head, as before."},{"start":74.3,"end":80.862,"text":"Scrooge knew this, by the smart sound its teeth made, when the jaws were brought together by the bandage."},{"start":80.862,"end":89.9,"text":"He ventured to raise his eyes again, and found his supernatural visitor confronting him in an erect attitude, with its chain wound over and about its arm."}]}},{"id":"I_20","number":20,"zh":{"text":"那幽灵步步往后退；它每退一步，那扇窗子便自个儿往上抬高一点，等它退到窗前，窗子已经大敞了。\n它招手叫斯克鲁奇过去，斯克鲁奇便走了过去。\n等他俩相距不到两步时，马利的鬼魂举起手来，警告他别再走近。\n斯克鲁奇停住了。\n与其说是出于听话，不如说是出于惊讶和恐惧：因为那只手一抬，他便察觉空中起了一阵杂乱的声响；那是断断续续的悲叹和懊悔之声；是说不出的凄苦、满含自责的哀号。\n那幽灵听了片刻，也加入了这哀伤的挽歌；随即飘出窗外，飘进那凄清漆黑的夜里。\n斯克鲁奇跟到窗前：好奇心叫他不顾一切了。\n他朝外望去。\n空中满是幽灵，焦躁慌乱地东飘西荡，一边飘一边呻吟。\n它们每一个都像马利的鬼魂那样戴着链子；有那么少数几个（兴许是些作过孽的政府）彼此连在一起；没有一个是自由的。\n其中许多，斯克鲁奇生前都跟他们本人相识。\n有一个穿白背心的老鬼魂，他跟他相当熟，那鬼脚踝上拴着一只硕大无比的铁保险柜，正凄惨地哭着，只因瞧见底下门阶上一个抱着婴儿的可怜女人，却帮不上半点忙。\n他们个个的苦楚，分明都在于：他们想插手人间的事去行善，却已经永远失去了那份能力。\n这些生灵究竟是化进了雾里，还是雾把它们裹了起来，他说不上来。\n可它们和它们那些精灵的声音一同隐没了；夜色又变回他先前走回家来时的模样。\n斯克鲁奇关上窗子，又去查看那扇鬼魂进来的门。\n它依旧上着双重锁，正如他亲手锁上的那样，门闩也丝毫没动过。\n他想说一声\"胡——扯！\"可才吐出头一个字音就打住了。\n也不知是因为方才那番惊吓，还是这一天的劳累，还是因为窥见了那看不见的世界，还是因为那鬼魂沉闷的谈话，再不然就是夜深了，总之他实在太需要歇息；便径直上床，衣服也没脱，转眼就睡着了。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_I_小节20.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":9.112,"text":"那幽灵步步往后退；它每退一步，那扇窗子便自个儿往上抬高一点，等它退到窗前，窗子已经大敞了。"},{"start":9.062,"end":13.412,"text":"它招手叫斯克鲁奇过去，斯克鲁奇便走了过去。"},{"start":13.412,"end":19.412,"text":"等他俩相距不到两步时，马利的鬼魂举起手来，警告他别再走近。"},{"start":19.412,"end":21.337,"text":"斯克鲁奇停住了。"},{"start":21.337,"end":36.225,"text":"与其说是出于听话，不如说是出于惊讶和恐惧：因为那只手一抬，他便察觉空中起了一阵杂乱的声响；那是断断续续的悲叹和懊悔之声；是说不出的凄苦、满含自责的哀号。"},{"start":36.225,"end":43.5,"text":"那幽灵听了片刻，也加入了这哀伤的挽歌；随即飘出窗外，飘进那凄清漆黑的夜里。"},{"start":43.5,"end":47.5,"text":"斯克鲁奇跟到窗前：好奇心叫他不顾一切了。"},{"start":47.5,"end":49.15,"text":"他朝外望去。"},{"start":49.15,"end":54.825,"text":"空中满是幽灵，焦躁慌乱地东飘西荡，一边飘一边呻吟。"},{"start":54.825,"end":64.95,"text":"它们每一个都像马利的鬼魂那样戴着链子；有那么少数几个（兴许是些作过孽的政府）彼此连在一起；没有一个是自由的。"},{"start":64.95,"end":68.95,"text":"其中许多，斯克鲁奇生前都跟他们本人相识。"},{"start":68.95,"end":83.6,"text":"有一个穿白背心的老鬼魂，他跟他相当熟，那鬼脚踝上拴着一只硕大无比的铁保险柜，正凄惨地哭着，只因瞧见底下门阶上一个抱着婴儿的可怜女人，却帮不上半点忙。"},{"start":83.6,"end":91.275,"text":"他们个个的苦楚，分明都在于：他们想插手人间的事去行善，却已经永远失去了那份能力。"},{"start":91.275,"end":97.075,"text":"这些生灵究竟是化进了雾里，还是雾把它们裹了起来，他说不上来。"},{"start":97.075,"end":103.987,"text":"可它们和它们那些精灵的声音一同隐没了；夜色又变回他先前走回家来时的模样。"},{"start":103.987,"end":108.362,"text":"斯克鲁奇关上窗子，又去查看那扇鬼魂进来的门。"},{"start":108.362,"end":114.35,"text":"它依旧上着双重锁，正如他亲手锁上的那样，门闩也丝毫没动过。"},{"start":114.35,"end":119.262,"text":"他想说一声\"胡——扯！\"可才吐出头一个字音就打住了。"},{"start":119.262,"end":135.8,"text":"也不知是因为方才那番惊吓，还是这一天的劳累，还是因为窥见了那看不见的世界，还是因为那鬼魂沉闷的谈话，再不然就是夜深了，总之他实在太需要歇息；便径直上床，衣服也没脱，转眼就睡着了。"}]},"en":{"text":"The apparition walked backward from him; and at every step it took, the window raised itself a little, so that when the spectre reached it, it was wide open.\nIt beckoned Scrooge to approach, which he did.\nWhen they were within two paces of each other, Marley's Ghost held up its hand, warning him to come no nearer.\nScrooge stopped.\nNot so much in obedience, as in surprise and fear: for on the raising of the hand, he became sensible of confused noises in the air; incoherent sounds of lamentation and regret; wailings inexpressibly sorrowful and self-accusatory.\nThe spectre, after listening for a moment, joined in the mournful dirge; and floated out upon the bleak, dark night.\nScrooge followed to the window: desperate in his curiosity.\nHe looked out.\nThe air was filled with phantoms, wandering hither and thither in restless haste, and moaning as they went.\nEvery one of them wore chains like Marley's Ghost; some few (they might be guilty governments) were linked together; none were free.\nMany had been personally known to Scrooge in their lives.\nHe had been quite familiar with one old ghost, in a white waistcoat, with a monstrous iron safe attached to its ancle, who cried piteously at being unable to assist a wretched woman with an infant, whom it saw below, upon a door-step.\nThe misery with them all was, clearly, that they sought to interfere, for good, in human matters, and had lost the power for ever.\nWhether these creatures faded into mist, or mist enshrouded them, he could not tell.\nBut they and their spirit voices faded together; and the night became as it had been when he walked home.\nScrooge closed the window, and examined the door by which the Ghost had entered.\nIt was double-locked, as he had locked it with his own hands, and the bolts were undisturbed.\nHe tried to say \"Hum-bug!\" but stopped at the first syllable.\nAnd being, from the emotion he had undergone, or the fatigues of the day, or his glimpse of the Invisible World, or the dull conversation of the Ghost, or the lateness of the hour, much in need of repose; went straight to bed, without undressing, and fell asleep upon the instant.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_I_小节20.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":9.475,"text":"The apparition walked backward from him; and at every step it took, the window raised itself a little, so that when the spectre reached it, it was wide open."},{"start":9.425,"end":12.937,"text":"It beckoned Scrooge to approach, which he did."},{"start":12.937,"end":19.45,"text":"When they were within two paces of each other, Marley's Ghost held up its hand, warning him to come no nearer."},{"start":19.45,"end":21.35,"text":"Scrooge stopped."},{"start":21.35,"end":35.975,"text":"Not so much in obedience, as in surprise and fear: for on the raising of the hand, he became sensible of confused noises in the air; incoherent sounds of lamentation and regret; wailings inexpressibly sorrowful and self-accusatory."},{"start":35.975,"end":43.362,"text":"The spectre, after listening for a moment, joined in the mournful dirge; and floated out upon the bleak, dark night."},{"start":43.362,"end":47.575,"text":"Scrooge followed to the window: desperate in his curiosity."},{"start":47.575,"end":49.3,"text":"He looked out."},{"start":49.3,"end":55.8,"text":"The air was filled with phantoms, wandering hither and thither in restless haste, and moaning as they went."},{"start":55.8,"end":64.175,"text":"Every one of them wore chains like Marley's Ghost; some few (they might be guilty governments) were linked together; none were free."},{"start":64.175,"end":67.875,"text":"Many had been personally known to Scrooge in their lives."},{"start":67.875,"end":81.7,"text":"He had been quite familiar with one old ghost, in a white waistcoat, with a monstrous iron safe attached to its ancle, who cried piteously at being unable to assist a wretched woman with an infant, whom it saw below, upon a door-step."},{"start":81.7,"end":90.612,"text":"The misery with them all was, clearly, that they sought to interfere, for good, in human matters, and had lost the power for ever."},{"start":90.612,"end":96.237,"text":"Whether these creatures faded into mist, or mist enshrouded them, he could not tell."},{"start":96.237,"end":102.187,"text":"But they and their spirit voices faded together; and the night became as it had been when he walked home."},{"start":102.187,"end":107.35,"text":"Scrooge closed the window, and examined the door by which the Ghost had entered."},{"start":107.35,"end":113.087,"text":"It was double-locked, as he had locked it with his own hands, and the bolts were undisturbed."},{"start":113.087,"end":117.625,"text":"He tried to say \"Hum-bug!\" but stopped at the first syllable."},{"start":117.625,"end":134.175,"text":"And being, from the emotion he had undergone, or the fatigues of the day, or his glimpse of the Invisible World, or the dull conversation of the Ghost, or the lateness of the hour, much in need of repose; went straight to bed, without undressing, and fell asleep upon the instant."}]}}]},{"id":"Stave_II","title":{"zh":"第二章","en":"STAVE II."},"sections":[{"id":"II_01","number":1,"zh":{"text":"第二章\n三个精灵中的第一个\n斯克鲁奇醒来时，天黑得厉害，他从床上往外望去，几乎分不清那透明的窗子和不透光的屋墙。\n他正用一双雪貂似的眼睛使劲去刺穿这黑暗，邻近一座教堂的排钟敲过了四个刻钟。\n于是他侧耳去听报时。\n叫他大为惊愕的是，那口沉钟从六点敲到七点，又从七点敲到八点，规规矩矩一路敲到十二点；这才停住。\n十二点！\n他上床时还是两点多呢。\n这钟出毛病了。\n准是有一根冰凌掉进机件里去了。\n十二点！\n他按了一下那只打簧表的弹簧，想纠正这只荒唐透顶的钟。\n那急促的小脉搏跳了十二下；停了。\n\"嗐，这不可能，\"斯克鲁奇说，\"我不可能睡过了整整一天，又睡进了另一个深夜里去。\n也不可能是太阳出了什么岔子，这会儿是正午十二点！\"\n这念头叫人惊慌，他连忙爬下床，摸索着挪到窗前。\n他不得不先用睡袍袖子把窗上的霜擦掉才看得见东西；可就算擦了也看不清多少。\n他所能辨出的，无非是外头依旧大雾弥漫、冷得出奇，没有人来来往往、闹腾喧嚷的声响——倘若当真是黑夜击退了白昼、占据了整个世界，那必定是会有这等动静的。\n这叫他大大松了口气，因为\"见票后三日付埃比尼泽·斯克鲁奇先生或其指定人\"云云的汇票，倘若没了日子可数，就成了一张空头的美国债券了。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_II_小节01.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":1.275,"text":"第二章"},{"start":1.225,"end":3.325,"text":"三个精灵中的第一个"},{"start":3.325,"end":11.7,"text":"斯克鲁奇醒来时，天黑得厉害，他从床上往外望去，几乎分不清那透明的窗子和不透光的屋墙。"},{"start":11.7,"end":19.2,"text":"他正用一双雪貂似的眼睛使劲去刺穿这黑暗，邻近一座教堂的排钟敲过了四个刻钟。"},{"start":19.2,"end":21.6,"text":"于是他侧耳去听报时。"},{"start":21.6,"end":31.4,"text":"叫他大为惊愕的是，那口沉钟从六点敲到七点，又从七点敲到八点，规规矩矩一路敲到十二点；这才停住。"},{"start":31.4,"end":32.575,"text":"十二点！"},{"start":32.575,"end":35.275,"text":"他上床时还是两点多呢。"},{"start":35.275,"end":37.012,"text":"这钟出毛病了。"},{"start":37.012,"end":40.025,"text":"准是有一根冰凌掉进机件里去了。"},{"start":40.025,"end":41.2,"text":"十二点！"},{"start":41.2,"end":46.625,"text":"他按了一下那只打簧表的弹簧，想纠正这只荒唐透顶的钟。"},{"start":46.625,"end":50.087,"text":"那急促的小脉搏跳了十二下；停了。"},{"start":50.087,"end":56.562,"text":"嗐，这不可能，\"斯克鲁奇说，\"我不可能睡过了整整一天，又睡进了另一个深夜里去。"},{"start":56.562,"end":61.187,"text":"也不可能是太阳出了什么岔子，这会儿是正午十二点！"},{"start":61.187,"end":66.1,"text":"这念头叫人惊慌，他连忙爬下床，摸索着挪到窗前。"},{"start":66.1,"end":73.675,"text":"他不得不先用睡袍袖子把窗上的霜擦掉才看得见东西；可就算擦了也看不清多少。"},{"start":73.675,"end":87.9,"text":"他所能辨出的，无非是外头依旧大雾弥漫、冷得出奇，没有人来来往往、闹腾喧嚷的声响——倘若当真是黑夜击退了白昼、占据了整个世界，那必定是会有这等动静的。"},{"start":87.9,"end":99.887,"text":"这叫他大大松了口气，因为\"见票后三日付埃比尼泽·斯克鲁奇先生或其指定人\"云云的汇票，倘若没了日子可数，就成了一张空头的美国债券了。"}]},"en":{"text":"STAVE II.\nTHE FIRST OF THE THREE SPIRITS.\nWhen Scrooge awoke, it was so dark, that looking out of bed, he could scarcely distinguish the transparent window from the opaque walls of his chamber.\nHe was endeavouring to pierce the darkness with his ferret eyes, when the chimes of a neighbouring church struck the four quarters.\nSo he listened for the hour.\nTo his great astonishment the heavy bell went on from six to seven, and from seven to eight, and regularly up to twelve; then stopped.\nTwelve!\nIt was past two when he went to bed.\nThe clock was wrong.\nAn icicle must have got into the works.\nTwelve!\nHe touched the spring of his repeater, to correct this most preposterous clock.\nIts rapid little pulse beat twelve; and stopped.\n\"Why, it isn't possible,\" said Scrooge, \"that I can have slept through a whole day and far into another night.\nIt isn't possible that anything has happened to the sun, and this is twelve at noon!\"\nThe idea being an alarming one, he scrambled out of bed, and groped his way to the window.\nHe was obliged to rub the frost off with the sleeve of his dressing-gown before he could see anything; and could see very little then.\nAll he could make out was, that it was still very foggy and extremely cold, and that there was no noise of people running to and fro, and making a great stir, as there unquestionably would have been if night had beaten off bright day, and taken possession of the world.\nThis was a great relief, because \"three days after sight of this First of Exchange pay to Mr. Ebenezer Scrooge or his order,\" and so forth, would have become a mere United States' security if there were no days to count by.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_II_小节01.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":1.887,"text":"STAVE II."},{"start":1.837,"end":4.425,"text":"THE FIRST OF THE THREE SPIRITS."},{"start":4.425,"end":13.4,"text":"When Scrooge awoke, it was so dark, that looking out of bed, he could scarcely distinguish the transparent window from the opaque walls of his chamber."},{"start":13.4,"end":20.487,"text":"He was endeavouring to pierce the darkness with his ferret eyes, when the chimes of a neighbouring church struck the four quarters."},{"start":20.487,"end":22.862,"text":"So he listened for the hour."},{"start":22.862,"end":31.487,"text":"To his great astonishment the heavy bell went on from six to seven, and from seven to eight, and regularly up to twelve; then stopped."},{"start":31.487,"end":32.925,"text":"Twelve!"},{"start":32.925,"end":35.712,"text":"It was past two when he went to bed."},{"start":35.712,"end":37.762,"text":"The clock was wrong."},{"start":37.762,"end":40.725,"text":"An icicle must have got into the works."},{"start":40.725,"end":42.162,"text":"Twelve!"},{"start":42.162,"end":47.15,"text":"He touched the spring of his repeater, to correct this most preposterous clock."},{"start":47.15,"end":50.85,"text":"Its rapid little pulse beat twelve; and stopped."},{"start":50.85,"end":57.837,"text":"Why, it isn't possible,\" said Scrooge, \"that I can have slept through a whole day and far into another night."},{"start":57.837,"end":63.025,"text":"It isn't possible that anything has happened to the sun, and this is twelve at noon!"},{"start":63.025,"end":68.987,"text":"The idea being an alarming one, he scrambled out of bed, and groped his way to the window."},{"start":68.987,"end":76.412,"text":"He was obliged to rub the frost off with the sleeve of his dressing-gown before he could see anything; and could see very little then."},{"start":76.412,"end":91.65,"text":"All he could make out was, that it was still very foggy and extremely cold, and that there was no noise of people running to and fro, and making a great stir, as there unquestionably would have been if night had beaten off bright day, and taken possession of the world."},{"start":91.65,"end":104.525,"text":"This was a great relief, because \"three days after sight of this First of Exchange pay to Mr. Ebenezer Scrooge or his order,\" and so forth, would have become a mere United States' security if there were no days to count by."}]}},{"id":"II_02","number":2,"zh":{"text":"斯克鲁奇又躺回床上，想了又想，想了又想，翻来覆去想了一遍又一遍，却怎么也想不出个所以然来。\n他越想越糊涂；越是想竭力不去想，反倒越想个不停。\n马利的鬼魂搅得他心烦意乱。\n每当他细细盘问一番，断定那不过是一场梦，他的心思便像松开的强力弹簧似的，啪地弹回原处，又把同一个难题重新摆到他面前，要他从头到尾再推敲一遍：\"那到底是不是一场梦？\"\n斯克鲁奇就这么躺着，直到排钟又敲过了三刻，他蓦地记起，那鬼魂警告过他，钟敲一点时会有一位访客造访。\n他打定主意要醒着熬过那个钟点；再说他这会儿要想睡着，简直比上天堂还难，所以这或许是他眼下所能拿定的最聪明的主意了。\n这一刻钟长得很，他不止一次确信自己准是不知不觉打了个盹，错过了报时的钟声。\n到末了，那钟声总算传进了他凝神倾听的耳朵。\n\"叮，咚！\"\n\"一点一刻了，\"斯克鲁奇数着说。\n\"叮，咚！\"\n\"一点半！\"斯克鲁奇说。\n\"叮，咚！\"\n\"差一刻就到点了，\"斯克鲁奇说。\n\"叮，咚！\"\n\"正点了，\"斯克鲁奇得意洋洋地说，\"就只到这儿了！\"\n他这话是赶在报点的钟声响起之前说的，那钟声这会儿响了，沉沉地、闷闷地、空空地、凄凄惨惨地敲了一记\"一点\"。\n霎时间屋里光芒一闪，他床上的帐子被拉开了。\n告诉你吧，他床上的帐子是被一只手拉到一边去的。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_II_小节02.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":8.512,"text":"斯克鲁奇又躺回床上，想了又想，想了又想，翻来覆去想了一遍又一遍，却怎么也想不出个所以然来。"},{"start":8.462,"end":13.562,"text":"他越想越糊涂；越是想竭力不去想，反倒越想个不停。"},{"start":13.562,"end":16.487,"text":"马利的鬼魂搅得他心烦意乱。"},{"start":16.487,"end":31.975,"text":"每当他细细盘问一番，断定那不过是一场梦，他的心思便像松开的强力弹簧似的，啪地弹回原处，又把同一个难题重新摆到他面前，要他从头到尾再推敲一遍：\"那到底是不是一场梦？"},{"start":31.975,"end":41.7,"text":"斯克鲁奇就这么躺着，直到排钟又敲过了三刻，他蓦地记起，那鬼魂警告过他，钟敲一点时会有一位访客造访。"},{"start":41.7,"end":53.15,"text":"他打定主意要醒着熬过那个钟点；再说他这会儿要想睡着，简直比上天堂还难，所以这或许是他眼下所能拿定的最聪明的主意了。"},{"start":53.15,"end":60.35,"text":"这一刻钟长得很，他不止一次确信自己准是不知不觉打了个盹，错过了报时的钟声。"},{"start":60.35,"end":64.875,"text":"到末了，那钟声总算传进了他凝神倾听的耳朵。"},{"start":64.875,"end":66.25,"text":"叮，咚！"},{"start":66.25,"end":69.025,"text":"一点一刻了，\"斯克鲁奇数着说。"},{"start":69.025,"end":70.4,"text":"叮，咚！"},{"start":70.4,"end":72.762,"text":"一点半！\"斯克鲁奇说。"},{"start":72.762,"end":74.137,"text":"叮，咚！"},{"start":74.137,"end":77,"text":"差一刻就到点了，\"斯克鲁奇说。"},{"start":77,"end":78.375,"text":"叮，咚！"},{"start":78.375,"end":82.537,"text":"正点了，\"斯克鲁奇得意洋洋地说，\"就只到这儿了！"},{"start":82.537,"end":92.762,"text":"他这话是赶在报点的钟声响起之前说的，那钟声这会儿响了，沉沉地、闷闷地、空空地、凄凄惨惨地敲了一记\"一点\"。"},{"start":92.762,"end":97,"text":"霎时间屋里光芒一闪，他床上的帐子被拉开了。"},{"start":97,"end":101.537,"text":"告诉你吧，他床上的帐子是被一只手拉到一边去的。"}]},"en":{"text":"Scrooge went to bed again, and thought, and thought, and thought it over and over and over, and could make nothing of it.\nThe more he thought, the more perplexed he was; and the more he endeavoured not to think, the more he thought.\nMarley's Ghost bothered him exceedingly.\nEvery time he resolved within himself, after mature inquiry, that it was all a dream, his mind flew back again like a strong spring released, to its first position, and presented the same problem to be worked all through, \"Was it a dream or not?\"\nScrooge lay in this state until the chimes had gone three quarters more, when he remembered, on a sudden, that the Ghost had warned him of a visitation when the bell tolled one.\nHe resolved to lie awake until the hour was past; and considering that he could no more go to sleep than go to Heaven, this was perhaps the wisest resolution in his power.\nThe quarter was so long, that he was more than once convinced he must have sunk into a doze unconsciously, and missed the clock.\nAt length it broke upon his listening ear.\n\"Ding, dong!\"\n\"A quarter past,\" said Scrooge, counting.\n\"Ding, dong!\"\n\"Half past!\" said Scrooge.\n\"Ding, dong!\"\n\"A quarter to it,\" said Scrooge.\n\"Ding, dong!\"\n\"The hour itself,\" said Scrooge, triumphantly, \"and nothing else!\"\nHe spoke before the hour bell sounded, which it now did with a deep, dull, hollow, melancholy ONE.\nLight flashed up in the room upon the instant, and the curtains of his bed were drawn.\nThe curtains of his bed were drawn aside, I tell you, by a hand.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_II_小节02.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":7.537,"text":"Scrooge went to bed again, and thought, and thought, and thought it over and over and over, and could make nothing of it."},{"start":7.487,"end":14.175,"text":"The more he thought, the more perplexed he was; and the more he endeavoured not to think, the more he thought."},{"start":14.175,"end":17.112,"text":"Marley's Ghost bothered him exceedingly."},{"start":17.112,"end":31.3,"text":"Every time he resolved within himself, after mature inquiry, that it was all a dream, his mind flew back again like a strong spring released, to its first position, and presented the same problem to be worked all through, \"Was it a dream or not?"},{"start":31.3,"end":41.075,"text":"Scrooge lay in this state until the chimes had gone three quarters more, when he remembered, on a sudden, that the Ghost had warned him of a visitation when the bell tolled one."},{"start":41.075,"end":50.912,"text":"He resolved to lie awake until the hour was past; and considering that he could no more go to sleep than go to Heaven, this was perhaps the wisest resolution in his power."},{"start":50.912,"end":58.687,"text":"The quarter was so long, that he was more than once convinced he must have sunk into a doze unconsciously, and missed the clock."},{"start":58.687,"end":61.7,"text":"At length it broke upon his listening ear."},{"start":61.7,"end":63.675,"text":"Ding, dong!"},{"start":63.675,"end":67.3,"text":"A quarter past,\" said Scrooge, counting."},{"start":67.3,"end":69.275,"text":"Ding, dong!"},{"start":69.275,"end":72.1,"text":"Half past!\" said Scrooge."},{"start":72.1,"end":74.075,"text":"Ding, dong!"},{"start":74.075,"end":76.912,"text":"A quarter to it,\" said Scrooge."},{"start":76.912,"end":78.887,"text":"Ding, dong!"},{"start":78.887,"end":84.075,"text":"The hour itself,\" said Scrooge, triumphantly, \"and nothing else!"},{"start":84.075,"end":90.912,"text":"He spoke before the hour bell sounded, which it now did with a deep, dull, hollow, melancholy ONE."},{"start":90.912,"end":96.075,"text":"Light flashed up in the room upon the instant, and the curtains of his bed were drawn."},{"start":96.075,"end":100.85,"text":"The curtains of his bed were drawn aside, I tell you, by a hand."}]}},{"id":"II_03","number":3,"zh":{"text":"不是他脚边的帐子，也不是他背后的帐子，而是正对着他脸的那一幅。\n他床上的帐子被拉到了一边；斯克鲁奇猛地撑起半坐的身子，发觉自己跟那位拉开帐子的非凡来客打了个照面：离它近得就像我此刻离你这么近，而我正以精灵之身站在你的胳膊肘边呢。\n那是个古怪的身形——像个孩子：可又不那么像孩子，倒更像个老人，仿佛隔着某种超凡的媒介望过去，叫他显得像是从眼前退远了，缩成了孩子的身量。\n它的头发披在脖颈上、垂到背后，白得像是上了年纪；可那张脸上却没有一道皱纹，皮肤上泛着最娇嫩的红润。\n它的胳膊很长，很有劲；那双手也一样，仿佛它一抓起来力气大得异乎寻常。\n它的腿和脚生得极其秀美，跟上身那些肢体一样，都赤裸着。\n它穿一件白得不能再白的束腰外衣；腰间系着一条光闪闪的带子，那光泽美极了。\n它手里擎着一枝青翠的冬青；而与这冬令的标志成了奇异的反衬，它的衣裳上却缀满了夏日的鲜花。\n可它身上最古怪的一点是：从它头顶上喷出一道明亮清澈的光柱，方才那一切都是借着这光才看得见的；它在意兴阑珊的时候，无疑就是用一顶大大的灭烛罩当帽子，这会儿正夹在腋下。\n不过，当斯克鲁奇越看越定睛时，便是这一点，也还不算它最古怪的地方。\n因为正如它那带子一会儿这处闪光、一会儿那处烁亮，这一刻是亮的、下一刻又暗了下去，那身形本身也时清时晰地变幻不定：一忽儿成了个独臂的东西，一忽儿独腿，一忽儿又长出二十条腿，一忽儿是一双没有脑袋的腿，一忽儿又是一个没有身子的脑袋：这些消融的部分，在它们隐没进去的那片浓重幽暗里，连个轮廓也瞧不见。\n而正当你看得诧异时，它又会复原如初；跟先前一样分明、一样清晰。\n\"先生，您就是那位预先告知要来见我的精灵吗？\"斯克鲁奇问。\n\"正是我！\"\n那声音柔和而温存。\n低得出奇，仿佛它并非就在他身旁这么近，而是在老远的地方。\n\"您是谁，又是什么？\"斯克鲁奇追问。\n\"我是往昔的圣诞之灵。\"\n\"很久很久以前的吗？\"斯克鲁奇问道，一面留意着它那侏儒般的身量。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_II_小节03.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":6.025,"text":"不是他脚边的帐子，也不是他背后的帐子，而是正对着他脸的那一幅。"},{"start":5.975,"end":21.275,"text":"他床上的帐子被拉到了一边；斯克鲁奇猛地撑起半坐的身子，发觉自己跟那位拉开帐子的非凡来客打了个照面：离它近得就像我此刻离你这么近，而我正以精灵之身站在你的胳膊肘边呢。"},{"start":21.275,"end":33.462,"text":"那是个古怪的身形——像个孩子：可又不那么像孩子，倒更像个老人，仿佛隔着某种超凡的媒介望过去，叫他显得像是从眼前退远了，缩成了孩子的身量。"},{"start":33.462,"end":43.187,"text":"它的头发披在脖颈上、垂到背后，白得像是上了年纪；可那张脸上却没有一道皱纹，皮肤上泛着最娇嫩的红润。"},{"start":43.187,"end":50.487,"text":"它的胳膊很长，很有劲；那双手也一样，仿佛它一抓起来力气大得异乎寻常。"},{"start":50.487,"end":56.162,"text":"它的腿和脚生得极其秀美，跟上身那些肢体一样，都赤裸着。"},{"start":56.162,"end":63.5,"text":"它穿一件白得不能再白的束腰外衣；腰间系着一条光闪闪的带子，那光泽美极了。"},{"start":63.5,"end":72.462,"text":"它手里擎着一枝青翠的冬青；而与这冬令的标志成了奇异的反衬，它的衣裳上却缀满了夏日的鲜花。"},{"start":72.462,"end":88.425,"text":"可它身上最古怪的一点是：从它头顶上喷出一道明亮清澈的光柱，方才那一切都是借着这光才看得见的；它在意兴阑珊的时候，无疑就是用一顶大大的灭烛罩当帽子，这会儿正夹在腋下。"},{"start":88.425,"end":94.75,"text":"不过，当斯克鲁奇越看越定睛时，便是这一点，也还不算它最古怪的地方。"},{"start":94.75,"end":121.325,"text":"因为正如它那带子一会儿这处闪光、一会儿那处烁亮，这一刻是亮的、下一刻又暗了下去，那身形本身也时清时晰地变幻不定：一忽儿成了个独臂的东西，一忽儿独腿，一忽儿又长出二十条腿，一忽儿是一双没有脑袋的腿，一忽儿又是一个没有身子的脑袋：这些消融的部分，在它们隐没进去的那片浓重幽暗里，连个轮廓也瞧不见。"},{"start":121.325,"end":127.6,"text":"而正当你看得诧异时，它又会复原如初；跟先前一样分明、一样清晰。"},{"start":127.6,"end":132.487,"text":"先生，您就是那位预先告知要来见我的精灵吗？\"斯克鲁奇问。"},{"start":132.487,"end":133.662,"text":"正是我！"},{"start":133.662,"end":135.962,"text":"那声音柔和而温存。"},{"start":135.962,"end":141.512,"text":"低得出奇，仿佛它并非就在他身旁这么近，而是在老远的地方。"},{"start":141.512,"end":144.612,"text":"您是谁，又是什么？\"斯克鲁奇追问。"},{"start":144.612,"end":146.925,"text":"我是往昔的圣诞之灵。"},{"start":146.925,"end":152.662,"text":"很久很久以前的吗？\"斯克鲁奇问道，一面留意着它那侏儒般的身量。"}]},"en":{"text":"Not the curtains at his feet, nor the curtains at his back, but those to which his face was addressed.\nThe curtains of his bed were drawn aside; and Scrooge, starting up into a half-recumbent attitude, found himself face to face with the unearthly visitor who drew them: as close to it as I am now to you, and I am standing in the spirit at your elbow.\nIt was a strange figure--like a child: yet not so like a child as like an old man, viewed through some supernatural medium, which gave him the appearance of having receded from the view, and being diminished to a child's proportions.\nIts hair, which hung about its neck and down its back, was white as if with age; and yet the face had not a wrinkle in it, and the tenderest bloom was on the skin.\nThe arms were very long and muscular; the hands the same, as if its hold were of uncommon strength.\nIts legs and feet, most delicately formed, were, like those upper members, bare.\nIt wore a tunic of the purest white; and round its waist was bound a lustrous belt, the sheen of which was beautiful.\nIt held a branch of fresh green holly in its hand; and, in singular contradiction of that wintry emblem, had its dress trimmed with summer flowers.\nBut the strangest thing about it was, that from the crown of its head there sprung a bright clear jet of light, by which all this was visible; and which was doubtless the occasion of its using, in its duller moments, a great extinguisher for a cap, which it now held under its arm.\nEven this, though, when Scrooge looked at it with increasing steadiness, was _not_ its strangest quality.\nFor as its belt sparkled and glittered now in one part and now in another, and what was light one instant, at another time was dark, so the figure itself fluctuated in its distinctness: being now a thing with one arm, now with one leg, now with twenty legs, now a pair of legs without a head, now a head without a body: of which dissolving parts, no outline would be visible in the dense gloom wherein they melted away.\nAnd in the very wonder of this, it would be itself again; distinct and clear as ever.\n\"Are you the Spirit, sir, whose coming was foretold to me?\" asked Scrooge.\n\"I am!\"\nThe voice was soft and gentle.\nSingularly low, as if instead of being so close beside him, it were at a distance.\n\"Who, and what are you?\" Scrooge demanded.\n\"I am the Ghost of Christmas Past.\"\n\"Long past?\" inquired Scrooge: observant of its dwarfish stature.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_II_小节03.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":6.387,"text":"Not the curtains at his feet, nor the curtains at his back, but those to which his face was addressed."},{"start":6.337,"end":20.862,"text":"The curtains of his bed were drawn aside; and Scrooge, starting up into a half-recumbent attitude, found himself face to face with the unearthly visitor who drew them: as close to it as I am now to you, and I am standing in the spirit at your elbow."},{"start":20.862,"end":33.925,"text":"It was a strange figure--like a child: yet not so like a child as like an old man, viewed through some supernatural medium, which gave him the appearance of having receded from the view, and being diminished to a child's proportions."},{"start":33.925,"end":43.2,"text":"Its hair, which hung about its neck and down its back, was white as if with age; and yet the face had not a wrinkle in it, and the tenderest bloom was on the skin."},{"start":43.2,"end":49.7,"text":"The arms were very long and muscular; the hands the same, as if its hold were of uncommon strength."},{"start":49.7,"end":55.837,"text":"Its legs and feet, most delicately formed, were, like those upper members, bare."},{"start":55.837,"end":62.975,"text":"It wore a tunic of the purest white; and round its waist was bound a lustrous belt, the sheen of which was beautiful."},{"start":62.975,"end":72.012,"text":"It held a branch of fresh green holly in its hand; and, in singular contradiction of that wintry emblem, had its dress trimmed with summer flowers."},{"start":72.012,"end":87.225,"text":"But the strangest thing about it was, that from the crown of its head there sprung a bright clear jet of light, by which all this was visible; and which was doubtless the occasion of its using, in its duller moments, a great extinguisher for a cap, which it now held under its arm."},{"start":87.225,"end":94.937,"text":"Even this, though, when Scrooge looked at it with increasing steadiness, was _not_ its strangest quality."},{"start":94.937,"end":119.65,"text":"For as its belt sparkled and glittered now in one part and now in another, and what was light one instant, at another time was dark, so the figure itself fluctuated in its distinctness: being now a thing with one arm, now with one leg, now with twenty legs, now a pair of legs without a head, now a head without a body: of which dissolving parts, no outline would be visible in the dense gloom wherein they melted away."},{"start":119.65,"end":125.237,"text":"And in the very wonder of this, it would be itself again; distinct and clear as ever."},{"start":125.237,"end":130.487,"text":"Are you the Spirit, sir, whose coming was foretold to me?\" asked Scrooge."},{"start":130.487,"end":132.062,"text":"I am!"},{"start":132.062,"end":134.687,"text":"The voice was soft and gentle."},{"start":134.687,"end":140.525,"text":"Singularly low, as if instead of being so close beside him, it were at a distance."},{"start":140.525,"end":142.737,"text":"Who, and what are you?"},{"start":142.737,"end":144.787,"text":"Scrooge demanded."},{"start":144.787,"end":147.55,"text":"I am the Ghost of Christmas Past."},{"start":147.55,"end":152.8,"text":"Long past?\" inquired Scrooge: observant of its dwarfish stature."}]}},{"id":"II_04","number":4,"zh":{"text":"\"不。是你的往昔。\"\n倘若有谁问起，斯克鲁奇大概也说不出个缘由来；可他偏偏特别想看看这精灵戴上帽子的样子；便求它把头罩上。\n\"什么！\"那鬼魂嚷道，\"你这就要用你那双俗手，把我放出的光给掐灭了吗？\n你正是那些人当中的一个，是你们的欲念造出了这顶帽子，逼着我一年又一年地把它低低压在眉头上——这还不够吗！\"\n斯克鲁奇恭恭敬敬地申明自己绝无冒犯之意，也不知道自己这辈子哪一刻曾故意给这精灵\"扣过帽子\"。\n随后他壮起胆子，问它到这儿来有何贵干。\n\"为你好！\"那鬼魂说。\n斯克鲁奇表示十分感激，可心里头不由得想：一整夜不受打扰的安睡，对这个\"好\"字怕是更有益些。\n那精灵想必听见了他的心思，因为它立时说道：\"那么，就为了把你挽救过来。\n当心了！\"\n它一面说，一面伸出那只有力的手，轻轻攥住了他的胳膊。\n\"起来！跟我走！\"\n斯克鲁奇就算要争辩说这天气、这钟点都不宜步行；说床上暖和，温度计早降到冰点老远以下；说他只穿着拖鞋、睡袍、睡帽，单薄得很；说他这会儿还正伤着风——也是白搭。\n那一握虽说柔得像女人的手，却由不得他抗拒。\n他起了身：可一发觉那精灵径直朝窗子走去，便一把抓住它的袍子哀求起来。\n\"我是个肉身凡胎，\"斯克鲁奇分辩道，\"是会摔下去的。\"\n\"只消让我的手在这儿碰你一下，\"那精灵说着，把手按在他心口上，\"凭这个，便是比眼下凶险得多的境地，你也撑得住！\"\n话音刚落，他俩便穿墙而过，立在了一条空旷的乡间大路上，两旁尽是田野。\n那座城市已经全然不见了踪影。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_II_小节04.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":0.937,"text":"不。"},{"start":0.887,"end":2.287,"text":"是你的往昔。"},{"start":2.287,"end":12,"text":"倘若有谁问起，斯克鲁奇大概也说不出个缘由来；可他偏偏特别想看看这精灵戴上帽子的样子；便求它把头罩上。"},{"start":12,"end":18.137,"text":"什么！\"那鬼魂嚷道，\"你这就要用你那双俗手，把我放出的光给掐灭了吗？"},{"start":18.137,"end":27.612,"text":"你正是那些人当中的一个，是你们的欲念造出了这顶帽子，逼着我一年又一年地把它低低压在眉头上——这还不够吗！"},{"start":27.612,"end":36.15,"text":"斯克鲁奇恭恭敬敬地申明自己绝无冒犯之意，也不知道自己这辈子哪一刻曾故意给这精灵\"扣过帽子\"。"},{"start":36.15,"end":40.137,"text":"随后他壮起胆子，问它到这儿来有何贵干。"},{"start":40.137,"end":42.262,"text":"为你好！\"那鬼魂说。"},{"start":42.262,"end":50.312,"text":"斯克鲁奇表示十分感激，可心里头不由得想：一整夜不受打扰的安睡，对这个\"好\"字怕是更有益些。"},{"start":50.312,"end":56.762,"text":"那精灵想必听见了他的心思，因为它立时说道：\"那么，就为了把你挽救过来。"},{"start":56.762,"end":57.962,"text":"当心了！"},{"start":57.962,"end":63.025,"text":"它一面说，一面伸出那只有力的手，轻轻攥住了他的胳膊。"},{"start":63.025,"end":64.062,"text":"起来！"},{"start":64.062,"end":65.237,"text":"跟我走！"},{"start":65.237,"end":81.775,"text":"斯克鲁奇就算要争辩说这天气、这钟点都不宜步行；说床上暖和，温度计早降到冰点老远以下；说他只穿着拖鞋、睡袍、睡帽，单薄得很；说他这会儿还正伤着风——也是白搭。"},{"start":81.775,"end":86.037,"text":"那一握虽说柔得像女人的手，却由不得他抗拒。"},{"start":86.037,"end":92.912,"text":"他起了身：可一发觉那精灵径直朝窗子走去，便一把抓住它的袍子哀求起来。"},{"start":92.912,"end":97.362,"text":"我是个肉身凡胎，\"斯克鲁奇分辩道，\"是会摔下去的。"},{"start":97.362,"end":106.85,"text":"只消让我的手在这儿碰你一下，\"那精灵说着，把手按在他心口上，\"凭这个，便是比眼下凶险得多的境地，你也撑得住！"},{"start":106.85,"end":113.887,"text":"话音刚落，他俩便穿墙而过，立在了一条空旷的乡间大路上，两旁尽是田野。"},{"start":113.887,"end":116.937,"text":"那座城市已经全然不见了踪影。"}]},"en":{"text":"\"No. Your past.\"\nPerhaps, Scrooge could not have told anybody why, if anybody could have asked him; but he had a special desire to see the Spirit in his cap; and begged him to be covered.\n\"What\" exclaimed the Ghost, \"would you so soon put out, with worldly hands, the light I give?\nIs it not enough that you are one of those whose passions made this cap, and force me through whole trains of years to wear it low upon my brow!\"\nScrooge reverently disclaimed all intention to offend, or any knowledge of having wilfully \"bonneted\" the Spirit at any period of his life.\nHe then made bold to inquire what business brought him there.\n\"Your welfare!\" said the Ghost.\nScrooge expressed himself much obliged, but could not help thinking that a night of unbroken rest would have been more conducive to that end.\nThe Spirit must have heard him thinking, for it said immediately: \"Your reclamation, then.\nTake heed!\"\nIt put out its strong hand as it spoke, and clasped him gently by the arm.\n\"Rise! and walk with me!\"\nIt would have been in vain for Scrooge to plead that the weather and the hour were not adapted to pedestrian purposes; that bed was warm, and the thermometer a long way below freezing; that he was clad but lightly in his slippers, dressing-gown, and nightcap; and that he had a cold upon him at that time.\nThe grasp, though gentle as a woman's hand, was not to be resisted.\nHe rose: but finding that the Spirit made towards the window, clasped its robe in supplication.\n\"I am a mortal,\" Scrooge remonstrated, \"and liable to fall.\"\n\"Bear but a touch of my hand _there_,\" said the Spirit, laying it upon his heart, \"and you shall be upheld in more than this!\"\nAs the words were spoken, they passed through the wall, and stood upon an open country road, with fields on either hand.\nThe city had entirely vanished.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_II_小节04.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":1.475,"text":"No."},{"start":1.425,"end":3.137,"text":"Your past."},{"start":3.137,"end":13.4,"text":"Perhaps, Scrooge could not have told anybody why, if anybody could have asked him; but he had a special desire to see the Spirit in his cap; and begged him to be covered."},{"start":13.4,"end":19.837,"text":"What\" exclaimed the Ghost, \"would you so soon put out, with worldly hands, the light I give?"},{"start":19.837,"end":27.825,"text":"Is it not enough that you are one of those whose passions made this cap, and force me through whole trains of years to wear it low upon my brow!"},{"start":27.825,"end":36.387,"text":"Scrooge reverently disclaimed all intention to offend, or any knowledge of having wilfully \"bonneted\" the Spirit at any period of his life."},{"start":36.387,"end":40.312,"text":"He then made bold to inquire what business brought him there."},{"start":40.312,"end":43.062,"text":"Your welfare!\" said the Ghost."},{"start":43.062,"end":50.787,"text":"Scrooge expressed himself much obliged, but could not help thinking that a night of unbroken rest would have been more conducive to that end."},{"start":50.787,"end":56.525,"text":"The Spirit must have heard him thinking, for it said immediately: \"Your reclamation, then."},{"start":56.525,"end":58.125,"text":"Take heed!"},{"start":58.125,"end":63.212,"text":"It put out its strong hand as it spoke, and clasped him gently by the arm."},{"start":63.212,"end":64.787,"text":"Rise!"},{"start":64.787,"end":66.637,"text":"and walk with me!"},{"start":66.637,"end":83.575,"text":"It would have been in vain for Scrooge to plead that the weather and the hour were not adapted to pedestrian purposes; that bed was warm, and the thermometer a long way below freezing; that he was clad but lightly in his slippers, dressing-gown, and nightcap; and that he had a cold upon him at that time."},{"start":83.575,"end":88.537,"text":"The grasp, though gentle as a woman's hand, was not to be resisted."},{"start":88.537,"end":94.925,"text":"He rose: but finding that the Spirit made towards the window, clasped its robe in supplication."},{"start":94.925,"end":99.562,"text":"I am a mortal,\" Scrooge remonstrated, \"and liable to fall."},{"start":99.562,"end":107.962,"text":"Bear but a touch of my hand _there_,\" said the Spirit, laying it upon his heart, \"and you shall be upheld in more than this!"},{"start":107.962,"end":115.262,"text":"As the words were spoken, they passed through the wall, and stood upon an open country road, with fields on either hand."},{"start":115.262,"end":118,"text":"The city had entirely vanished."}]}},{"id":"II_05","number":5,"zh":{"text":"连一星半点痕迹也瞧不见了。\n黑暗和雾气也随它一同消散了，因为这是个晴朗、寒冷的冬日，地上覆着雪。\n\"我的天哪！\"斯克鲁奇双手交握，一面四下张望，一面说道。\n\"我是在这地方长大的。\n我小时候就在这儿！\"\n那精灵温和地凝视着他。\n它那轻柔的一碰，虽说又轻又短暂，却仿佛仍留在这老人的触觉里。\n他觉出空中飘浮着千百种气味，每一种都连着千百样早已久久、久久被遗忘的念头、指望、欢乐和忧愁！\n\"你的嘴唇在发抖呢，\"那鬼魂说。\n\"你脸上那是什么？\"\n斯克鲁奇含含糊糊地说那是个小疙瘩，嗓子里头有种异样的哽咽；他求那鬼魂爱领他上哪儿就领他上哪儿。\n\"你还记得路吗？\"那精灵问道。\n\"记得它！\"斯克鲁奇热切地嚷道——\"蒙上眼睛我都走得了。\"\n\"奇怪，你竟把它忘了这么多年！\"那鬼魂说。\n\"咱们往前走吧。\"\n他们沿着大路往前走；斯克鲁奇认得出每一道门、每一根桩、每一棵树；直到远处现出一座小集镇，有它的桥、它的教堂，还有那蜿蜒的河。\n这会儿瞧见几匹毛蓬蓬的小马朝他们这边小跑过来，背上骑着孩子，他们朝着别的孩子吆喝，那些孩子坐在农夫赶着的乡间轻便马车和大车上。\n这些孩子一个个兴高采烈，彼此呼喊着，喊得那一片广阔的田野满是欢快的乐声，连那清冽的空气听了也笑了起来。\n\"这些不过是已逝事物的影子罢了，\"那鬼魂说。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_II_小节05.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":2.962,"text":"连一星半点痕迹也瞧不见了。"},{"start":2.912,"end":9.625,"text":"黑暗和雾气也随它一同消散了，因为这是个晴朗、寒冷的冬日，地上覆着雪。"},{"start":9.625,"end":14.762,"text":"我的天哪！\"斯克鲁奇双手交握，一面四下张望，一面说道。"},{"start":14.762,"end":16.85,"text":"我是在这地方长大的。"},{"start":16.85,"end":18.637,"text":"我小时候就在这儿！"},{"start":18.637,"end":21.037,"text":"那精灵温和地凝视着他。"},{"start":21.037,"end":26.987,"text":"它那轻柔的一碰，虽说又轻又短暂，却仿佛仍留在这老人的触觉里。"},{"start":26.987,"end":36.7,"text":"他觉出空中飘浮着千百种气味，每一种都连着千百样早已久久、久久被遗忘的念头、指望、欢乐和忧愁！"},{"start":36.7,"end":39.65,"text":"你的嘴唇在发抖呢，\"那鬼魂说。"},{"start":39.65,"end":41.4,"text":"你脸上那是什么？"},{"start":41.4,"end":50.437,"text":"斯克鲁奇含含糊糊地说那是个小疙瘩，嗓子里头有种异样的哽咽；他求那鬼魂爱领他上哪儿就领他上哪儿。"},{"start":50.437,"end":52.987,"text":"你还记得路吗？\"那精灵问道。"},{"start":52.987,"end":57.875,"text":"记得它！\"斯克鲁奇热切地嚷道——\"蒙上眼睛我都走得了。"},{"start":57.875,"end":61.775,"text":"奇怪，你竟把它忘了这么多年！\"那鬼魂说。"},{"start":61.775,"end":63.387,"text":"咱们往前走吧。"},{"start":63.387,"end":75.675,"text":"他们沿着大路往前走；斯克鲁奇认得出每一道门、每一根桩、每一棵树；直到远处现出一座小集镇，有它的桥、它的教堂，还有那蜿蜒的河。"},{"start":75.675,"end":87.75,"text":"这会儿瞧见几匹毛蓬蓬的小马朝他们这边小跑过来，背上骑着孩子，他们朝着别的孩子吆喝，那些孩子坐在农夫赶着的乡间轻便马车和大车上。"},{"start":87.75,"end":97.55,"text":"这些孩子一个个兴高采烈，彼此呼喊着，喊得那一片广阔的田野满是欢快的乐声，连那清冽的空气听了也笑了起来。"},{"start":97.55,"end":101.362,"text":"这些不过是已逝事物的影子罢了，\"那鬼魂说。"}]},"en":{"text":"Not a vestige of it was to be seen.\nThe darkness and the mist had vanished with it, for it was a clear, cold, winter day, with snow upon the ground.\n\"Good Heaven!\" said Scrooge, clasping his hands together, as he looked about him.\n\"I was bred in this place.\nI was a boy here!\"\nThe Spirit gazed upon him mildly.\nIts gentle touch, though it had been light and instantaneous, appeared still present to the old man's sense of feeling.\nHe was conscious of a thousand odours floating in the air, each one connected with a thousand thoughts, and hopes, and joys, and cares long, long, forgotten!\n\"Your lip is trembling,\" said the Ghost.\n\"And what is that upon your cheek?\"\nScrooge muttered, with an unusual catching in his voice, that it was a pimple; and begged the Ghost to lead him where he would.\n\"You recollect the way?\" inquired the Spirit.\n\"Remember it!\" cried Scrooge with fervour--\"I could walk it blindfold.\"\n\"Strange to have forgotten it for so many years!\" observed the Ghost.\n\"Let us go on.\"\nThey walked along the road; Scrooge recognising every gate, and post, and tree; until a little market-town appeared in the distance, with its bridge, its church, and winding river.\nSome shaggy ponies now were seen trotting towards them with boys upon their backs, who called to other boys in country gigs and carts, driven by farmers.\nAll these boys were in great spirits, and shouted to each other, until the broad fields were so full of merry music, that the crisp air laughed to hear it.\n\"These are but shadows of the things that have been,\" said the Ghost.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_II_小节05.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":2.9,"text":"Not a vestige of it was to be seen."},{"start":2.85,"end":10.212,"text":"The darkness and the mist had vanished with it, for it was a clear, cold, winter day, with snow upon the ground."},{"start":10.212,"end":15.712,"text":"Good Heaven!\" said Scrooge, clasping his hands together, as he looked about him."},{"start":15.712,"end":18.062,"text":"I was bred in this place."},{"start":18.062,"end":20.087,"text":"I was a boy here!"},{"start":20.087,"end":23,"text":"The Spirit gazed upon him mildly."},{"start":23,"end":30.05,"text":"Its gentle touch, though it had been light and instantaneous, appeared still present to the old man's sense of feeling."},{"start":30.05,"end":40.275,"text":"He was conscious of a thousand odours floating in the air, each one connected with a thousand thoughts, and hopes, and joys, and cares long, long, forgotten!"},{"start":40.275,"end":43.45,"text":"Your lip is trembling,\" said the Ghost."},{"start":43.45,"end":45.862,"text":"And what is that upon your cheek?"},{"start":45.862,"end":53.225,"text":"Scrooge muttered, with an unusual catching in his voice, that it was a pimple; and begged the Ghost to lead him where he would."},{"start":53.225,"end":56.625,"text":"You recollect the way?\" inquired the Spirit."},{"start":56.625,"end":61.3,"text":"Remember it!\" cried Scrooge with fervour--\"I could walk it blindfold."},{"start":61.3,"end":66.075,"text":"Strange to have forgotten it for so many years!\" observed the Ghost."},{"start":66.075,"end":67.875,"text":"Let us go on."},{"start":67.875,"end":79.462,"text":"They walked along the road; Scrooge recognising every gate, and post, and tree; until a little market-town appeared in the distance, with its bridge, its church, and winding river."},{"start":79.462,"end":88.662,"text":"Some shaggy ponies now were seen trotting towards them with boys upon their backs, who called to other boys in country gigs and carts, driven by farmers."},{"start":88.662,"end":97.887,"text":"All these boys were in great spirits, and shouted to each other, until the broad fields were so full of merry music, that the crisp air laughed to hear it."},{"start":97.887,"end":102.175,"text":"These are but shadows of the things that have been,\" said the Ghost."}]}},{"id":"II_06","number":6,"zh":{"text":"\"它们觉察不到咱们。\"\n那些欢天喜地的赶路人走了过来；他们一边走来，斯克鲁奇便一个个认了出来，叫出了名字。\n他瞧见他们，怎么会高兴得没了边！\n他们走过时，他那双冷眼怎么会发亮，他的心怎么会怦怦直跳！\n他听见他们在十字路口、在岔道上各自分手回家、彼此道一声圣诞快乐时，怎么会满心欢喜！\n圣诞快乐对斯克鲁奇算个什么？\n去他的圣诞快乐！\n它何曾给他带来过半点好处？\n\"那学堂还没全空，\"那鬼魂说。\n\"还剩着一个孤零零的孩子，被他的朋友们撇下，仍旧留在那儿。\"\n斯克鲁奇说他知道。\n说着便抽泣起来。\n他们离开大路，拐进一条记得清清楚楚的小巷，不一会儿就走近一幢暗红砖砌的宅子，屋顶上有个小小的圆顶亭，亭尖立着风向标，里头挂着一口钟。\n那是幢大宅，可家道已经败落；因为那些宽敞的厢房少有人用，墙壁又潮又长着青苔，窗子破了，大门也朽了。\n家禽在马厩里咯咯叫着、大摇大摆地踱来踱去；马车房和棚屋里野草疯长。\n里头也并不比外头更存得住几分昔日的气派；因为一进那阴森森的门厅，又透过好几间敞着门的屋子望去，他们见那些屋子都陈设寒酸，又冷又空旷。\n空气里有一股泥土的霉味，这地方透着一种冷清清的空荡，叫人不知怎的联想到天没亮就点着蜡烛起身、吃食却又少得可怜的光景。\n那鬼魂和斯克鲁奇穿过门厅，走到屋子后头的一扇门前。\n门在他们面前开了，露出一间长长的、空荡荡的、凄凉的屋子，一排排素净的杉木条凳和书桌，把它衬得越发空落了。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_II_小节06.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":2.112,"text":"它们觉察不到咱们。"},{"start":2.062,"end":9.625,"text":"那些欢天喜地的赶路人走了过来；他们一边走来，斯克鲁奇便一个个认了出来，叫出了名字。"},{"start":9.625,"end":12.75,"text":"他瞧见他们，怎么会高兴得没了边！"},{"start":12.75,"end":18.3,"text":"他们走过时，他那双冷眼怎么会发亮，他的心怎么会怦怦直跳！"},{"start":18.3,"end":26.387,"text":"他听见他们在十字路口、在岔道上各自分手回家、彼此道一声圣诞快乐时，怎么会满心欢喜！"},{"start":26.387,"end":29.325,"text":"圣诞快乐对斯克鲁奇算个什么？"},{"start":29.325,"end":31.175,"text":"去他的圣诞快乐！"},{"start":31.175,"end":34.037,"text":"它何曾给他带来过半点好处？"},{"start":34.037,"end":37.012,"text":"那学堂还没全空，\"那鬼魂说。"},{"start":37.012,"end":41.887,"text":"还剩着一个孤零零的孩子，被他的朋友们撇下，仍旧留在那儿。"},{"start":41.887,"end":44.025,"text":"斯克鲁奇说他知道。"},{"start":44.025,"end":46.112,"text":"说着便抽泣起来。"},{"start":46.112,"end":58.3,"text":"他们离开大路，拐进一条记得清清楚楚的小巷，不一会儿就走近一幢暗红砖砌的宅子，屋顶上有个小小的圆顶亭，亭尖立着风向标，里头挂着一口钟。"},{"start":58.3,"end":68.112,"text":"那是幢大宅，可家道已经败落；因为那些宽敞的厢房少有人用，墙壁又潮又长着青苔，窗子破了，大门也朽了。"},{"start":68.112,"end":75.075,"text":"家禽在马厩里咯咯叫着、大摇大摆地踱来踱去；马车房和棚屋里野草疯长。"},{"start":75.075,"end":87.962,"text":"里头也并不比外头更存得住几分昔日的气派；因为一进那阴森森的门厅，又透过好几间敞着门的屋子望去，他们见那些屋子都陈设寒酸，又冷又空旷。"},{"start":87.962,"end":99.8,"text":"空气里有一股泥土的霉味，这地方透着一种冷清清的空荡，叫人不知怎的联想到天没亮就点着蜡烛起身、吃食却又少得可怜的光景。"},{"start":99.8,"end":104.762,"text":"那鬼魂和斯克鲁奇穿过门厅，走到屋子后头的一扇门前。"},{"start":104.762,"end":114.687,"text":"门在他们面前开了，露出一间长长的、空荡荡的、凄凉的屋子，一排排素净的杉木条凳和书桌，把它衬得越发空落了。"}]},"en":{"text":"\"They have no consciousness of us.\"\nThe jocund travellers came on; and as they came, Scrooge knew and named them every one.\nWhy was he rejoiced beyond all bounds to see them!\nWhy did his cold eye glisten, and his heart leap up as they went past!\nWhy was he filled with gladness when he heard them give each other Merry Christmas, as they parted at cross-roads and bye-ways, for their several homes!\nWhat was merry Christmas to Scrooge?\nOut upon merry Christmas!\nWhat good had it ever done to him?\n\"The school is not quite deserted,\" said the Ghost.\n\"A solitary child, neglected by his friends, is left there still.\"\nScrooge said he knew it.\nAnd he sobbed.\nThey left the high-road, by a well remembered lane, and soon approached a mansion of dull red brick, with a little weathercock-surmounted cupola, on the roof, and a bell hanging in it.\nIt was a large house, but one of broken fortunes; for the spacious offices were little used, their walls were damp and mossy, their windows broken, and their gates decayed.\nFowls clucked and strutted in the stables; and the coach-houses and sheds were overrun with grass.\nNor was it more retentive of its ancient state, within; for entering the dreary hall, and glancing through the open doors of many rooms, they found them poorly furnished, cold, and vast.\nThere was an earthy savour in the air, a chilly bareness in the place, which associated itself somehow with too much getting up by candle-light, and not too much to eat.\nThey went, the Ghost and Scrooge, across the hall, to a door at the back of the house.\nIt opened before them, and disclosed a long, bare, melancholy room, made barer still by lines of plain deal forms and desks.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_II_小节06.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":2.75,"text":"They have no consciousness of us."},{"start":2.7,"end":8.762,"text":"The jocund travellers came on; and as they came, Scrooge knew and named them every one."},{"start":8.762,"end":12.5,"text":"Why was he rejoiced beyond all bounds to see them!"},{"start":12.5,"end":17.087,"text":"Why did his cold eye glisten, and his heart leap up as they went past!"},{"start":17.087,"end":25.9,"text":"Why was he filled with gladness when he heard them give each other Merry Christmas, as they parted at cross-roads and bye-ways, for their several homes!"},{"start":25.9,"end":28.625,"text":"What was merry Christmas to Scrooge?"},{"start":28.625,"end":31.137,"text":"Out upon merry Christmas!"},{"start":31.137,"end":33.65,"text":"What good had it ever done to him?"},{"start":33.65,"end":37.387,"text":"The school is not quite deserted,\" said the Ghost."},{"start":37.387,"end":42.475,"text":"A solitary child, neglected by his friends, is left there still."},{"start":42.475,"end":44.65,"text":"Scrooge said he knew it."},{"start":44.65,"end":46.425,"text":"And he sobbed."},{"start":46.425,"end":57.187,"text":"They left the high-road, by a well remembered lane, and soon approached a mansion of dull red brick, with a little weathercock-surmounted cupola, on the roof, and a bell hanging in it."},{"start":57.187,"end":68.087,"text":"It was a large house, but one of broken fortunes; for the spacious offices were little used, their walls were damp and mossy, their windows broken, and their gates decayed."},{"start":68.087,"end":74.287,"text":"Fowls clucked and strutted in the stables; and the coach-houses and sheds were overrun with grass."},{"start":74.287,"end":85.95,"text":"Nor was it more retentive of its ancient state, within; for entering the dreary hall, and glancing through the open doors of many rooms, they found them poorly furnished, cold, and vast."},{"start":85.95,"end":95.65,"text":"There was an earthy savour in the air, a chilly bareness in the place, which associated itself somehow with too much getting up by candle-light, and not too much to eat."},{"start":95.65,"end":101.65,"text":"They went, the Ghost and Scrooge, across the hall, to a door at the back of the house."},{"start":101.65,"end":110.3,"text":"It opened before them, and disclosed a long, bare, melancholy room, made barer still by lines of plain deal forms and desks."}]}},{"id":"II_07","number":7,"zh":{"text":"在其中一张桌旁，一个孤零零的男孩正凑着一炉微弱的火读书；斯克鲁奇在一条凳子上坐下，瞧见自己当年那个被人遗忘的可怜模样，不禁哭了起来。\n屋子里没有一丝潜藏的回声，护壁板后头老鼠的吱吱声和窜动声，后面那阴沉院子里半化的水管滴下的水珠，一棵颓丧的白杨那光秃秃的枝桠间的一声叹息，空仓房门无聊的晃荡，还有炉火里的一声噼啪——没有一样不落在斯克鲁奇心头，化作一股使他心软的力量，让他的泪水流得更畅快了。\n那精灵碰了碰他的胳膊，指了指他那个埋头读书的少年自己。\n忽然，一个身着异邦服色的男人——看上去逼真分明得出奇——立在了窗外，腰带里别着一柄斧子，手里牵着一头驮满木柴的驴。\n\"咦，那是阿里巴巴！\"斯克鲁奇欣喜若狂地嚷道。\n\"是亲爱的老实人阿里巴巴！\n是啊，是啊，我知道！\n有一年圣诞节，那边那个孤零零的孩子被独自撇在这儿，他头一回当真来过，就是那个样子。\n可怜的孩子！\n还有瓦伦丁，\"斯克鲁奇说，\"还有他那野性子的兄弟奥森；他们打那儿走过去啦！\n还有那个——叫什么名字来着——被人塞在裤子里、睡着了搁在大马士革城门口的；你没瞧见他吗！\n还有那个被神怪倒提起来的苏丹马夫；他正头朝下倒栽着呢！\n活该。\n我可乐意了。\n他凭什么娶了公主呀！\"\n听斯克鲁奇用一种又像笑又像哭的、再古怪不过的嗓音，把他天性里全副的热忱都倾注到这种话题上；再瞧瞧他那张涨红了、激动了的脸；这要叫他城里那些生意场上的朋友看见，当真会大吃一惊。\n\"那只鹦鹉在那儿呢！\"斯克鲁奇嚷道。\n\"绿身子黄尾巴，脑袋顶上还长着个生菜似的东西；它就在那儿！\n他绕岛航行回了家，管它叫'可怜的鲁滨孙·克鲁索'。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_II_小节07.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":12.562,"text":"在其中一张桌旁，一个孤零零的男孩正凑着一炉微弱的火读书；斯克鲁奇在一条凳子上坐下，瞧见自己当年那个被人遗忘的可怜模样，不禁哭了起来。"},{"start":12.512,"end":36.4,"text":"屋子里没有一丝潜藏的回声，护壁板后头老鼠的吱吱声和窜动声，后面那阴沉院子里半化的水管滴下的水珠，一棵颓丧的白杨那光秃秃的枝桠间的一声叹息，空仓房门无聊的晃荡，还有炉火里的一声噼啪——没有一样不落在斯克鲁奇心头，化作一股使他心软的力量，让他的泪水流得更畅快了。"},{"start":36.4,"end":41.7,"text":"那精灵碰了碰他的胳膊，指了指他那个埋头读书的少年自己。"},{"start":41.7,"end":52.625,"text":"忽然，一个身着异邦服色的男人——看上去逼真分明得出奇——立在了窗外，腰带里别着一柄斧子，手里牵着一头驮满木柴的驴。"},{"start":52.625,"end":56.9,"text":"咦，那是阿里巴巴！\"斯克鲁奇欣喜若狂地嚷道。"},{"start":56.9,"end":59.437,"text":"是亲爱的老实人阿里巴巴！"},{"start":59.437,"end":61.625,"text":"是啊，是啊，我知道！"},{"start":61.625,"end":69.025,"text":"有一年圣诞节，那边那个孤零零的孩子被独自撇在这儿，他头一回当真来过，就是那个样子。"},{"start":69.025,"end":70.487,"text":"可怜的孩子！"},{"start":70.487,"end":76.8,"text":"还有瓦伦丁，\"斯克鲁奇说，\"还有他那野性子的兄弟奥森；他们打那儿走过去啦！"},{"start":76.8,"end":84.5,"text":"还有那个——叫什么名字来着——被人塞在裤子里、睡着了搁在大马士革城门口的；你没瞧见他吗！"},{"start":84.5,"end":90.05,"text":"还有那个被神怪倒提起来的苏丹马夫；他正头朝下倒栽着呢！"},{"start":90.05,"end":91.175,"text":"活该。"},{"start":91.175,"end":92.562,"text":"我可乐意了。"},{"start":92.562,"end":94.6,"text":"他凭什么娶了公主呀！"},{"start":94.6,"end":111.175,"text":"听斯克鲁奇用一种又像笑又像哭的、再古怪不过的嗓音，把他天性里全副的热忱都倾注到这种话题上；再瞧瞧他那张涨红了、激动了的脸；这要叫他城里那些生意场上的朋友看见，当真会大吃一惊。"},{"start":111.175,"end":114.15,"text":"那只鹦鹉在那儿呢！\"斯克鲁奇嚷道。"},{"start":114.15,"end":119.525,"text":"绿身子黄尾巴，脑袋顶上还长着个生菜似的东西；它就在那儿！"},{"start":119.525,"end":123.962,"text":"他绕岛航行回了家，管它叫'可怜的鲁滨孙·克鲁索'。"}]},"en":{"text":"At one of these a lonely boy was reading near a feeble fire; and Scrooge sat down upon a form, and wept to see his poor forgotten self as he had used to be.\nNot a latent echo in the house, not a squeak and scuffle from the mice behind the panneling, not a drip from the half-thawed water-spout in the dull yard behind, not a sigh among the leafless boughs of one despondent poplar, not the idle swinging of an empty store-house door, no, not a clicking in the fire, but fell upon the heart of Scrooge with softening influence, and gave a freer passage to his tears.\nThe Spirit touched him on the arm, and pointed to his young self, intent upon his reading.\nSuddenly a man, in foreign garments: wonderfully real and distinct to look at: stood outside the window, with an axe stuck in his belt, and leading an ass laden with wood by the bridle.\n\"Why, it's Ali Baba!\" Scrooge exclaimed in ecstacy.\n\"It's dear old honest Ali Baba!\nYes, yes, I know!\nOne Christmas time, when yonder solitary child was left here all alone, he _did_ come, for the first time, just like that.\nPoor boy!\nAnd Valentine,\" said Scrooge, \"and his wild brother, Orson; there they go!\nAnd what's his name, who was put down in his drawers, asleep, at the Gate of Damascus; don't you see him!\nAnd the Sultan's Groom turned upside-down by the Genii; there he is upon his head!\nServe him right.\nI'm glad of it.\nWhat business had _he_ to be married to the Princess!\"\nTo hear Scrooge expending all the earnestness of his nature on such subjects, in a most extraordinary voice between laughing and crying; and to see his heightened and excited face; would have been a surprise to his business friends in the city, indeed.\n\"There's the Parrot!\" cried Scrooge.\n\"Green body and yellow tail, with a thing like a lettuce growing out of the top of his head; there he is!\nPoor Robin Crusoe, he called him, when he came home again after sailing round the island.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_II_小节07.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":9.287,"text":"At one of these a lonely boy was reading near a feeble fire; and Scrooge sat down upon a form, and wept to see his poor forgotten self as he had used to be."},{"start":9.237,"end":31.887,"text":"Not a latent echo in the house, not a squeak and scuffle from the mice behind the panneling, not a drip from the half-thawed water-spout in the dull yard behind, not a sigh among the leafless boughs of one despondent poplar, not the idle swinging of an empty store-house door, no, not a clicking in the fire, but fell upon the heart of Scrooge with softening influence, and gave a freer passage to his tears."},{"start":31.887,"end":37.712,"text":"The Spirit touched him on the arm, and pointed to his young self, intent upon his reading."},{"start":37.712,"end":49.037,"text":"Suddenly a man, in foreign garments: wonderfully real and distinct to look at: stood outside the window, with an axe stuck in his belt, and leading an ass laden with wood by the bridle."},{"start":49.037,"end":51.687,"text":"Why, it's Ali Baba!"},{"start":51.687,"end":54.425,"text":"Scrooge exclaimed in ecstacy."},{"start":54.425,"end":57.3,"text":"It's dear old honest Ali Baba!"},{"start":57.3,"end":60.075,"text":"Yes, yes, I know!"},{"start":60.075,"end":69.412,"text":"One Christmas time, when yonder solitary child was left here all alone, he _did_ come, for the first time, just like that."},{"start":69.412,"end":71.05,"text":"Poor boy!"},{"start":71.05,"end":76.875,"text":"And Valentine,\" said Scrooge, \"and his wild brother, Orson; there they go!"},{"start":76.875,"end":83.775,"text":"And what's his name, who was put down in his drawers, asleep, at the Gate of Damascus; don't you see him!"},{"start":83.775,"end":89.237,"text":"And the Sultan's Groom turned upside-down by the Genii; there he is upon his head!"},{"start":89.237,"end":91.05,"text":"Serve him right."},{"start":91.05,"end":92.825,"text":"I'm glad of it."},{"start":92.825,"end":97.362,"text":"What business had _he_ to be married to the Princess!"},{"start":97.362,"end":111.325,"text":"To hear Scrooge expending all the earnestness of his nature on such subjects, in a most extraordinary voice between laughing and crying; and to see his heightened and excited face; would have been a surprise to his business friends in the city, indeed."},{"start":111.325,"end":114.262,"text":"There's the Parrot!\" cried Scrooge."},{"start":114.262,"end":120.787,"text":"Green body and yellow tail, with a thing like a lettuce growing out of the top of his head; there he is!"},{"start":120.787,"end":126.637,"text":"Poor Robin Crusoe, he called him, when he came home again after sailing round the island."}]}},{"id":"II_08","number":8,"zh":{"text":"'可怜的鲁滨孙·克鲁索，你上哪儿去了呀，鲁滨孙·克鲁索？'那人只当自己在做梦，可他并没有。\n你要知道，那是那只鹦鹉在叫。\n'星期五'打那儿过去啦，没命地往那小河汊跑！\n喂！\n嗬！\n喂——！\"\n随后，他用一种很不合他平日脾性的、说变就变的劲头，怜惜起从前的自己来，说了声\"可怜的孩子！\"又哭了起来。\n\"我真希望，\"斯克鲁奇咕哝着，把手插进口袋，用袖口擦干眼睛后四下张望，\"可如今太迟了。\"\n\"怎么啦？\"那精灵问。\n\"没什么，\"斯克鲁奇说。\n\"没什么。\n昨儿晚上有个孩子在我门口唱圣诞颂歌。\n我真该给他点什么的：就这么回事。\"\n那鬼魂若有所思地一笑，挥了挥手：一面挥手一面说，\"咱们再看一个圣诞节吧！\"\n听了这话，斯克鲁奇那个从前的自己长大了些，屋子也变得暗了点、脏了点。\n护壁板缩了，窗子裂了；天花板上掉下几块灰泥，露出底下光秃秃的板条；可这一切是怎么变出来的，斯克鲁奇跟你一样摸不着头脑。\n他只知道这全然不错；知道事情正是这么发生的；知道当别的孩子都回家过那快活的假期时，他又是孤零零一个人留在那儿。\n这会儿他没在读书，而是绝望地踱来踱去。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_II_小节08.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":8.075,"text":"可怜的鲁滨孙·克鲁索，你上哪儿去了呀，鲁滨孙·克鲁索？'那人只当自己在做梦，可他并没有。"},{"start":8.025,"end":10.837,"text":"你要知道，那是那只鹦鹉在叫。"},{"start":10.837,"end":14.675,"text":"星期五'打那儿过去啦，没命地往那小河汊跑！"},{"start":14.675,"end":15.562,"text":"喂！"},{"start":15.562,"end":16.425,"text":"嗬！"},{"start":16.425,"end":17.312,"text":"喂——！"},{"start":17.312,"end":26.587,"text":"随后，他用一种很不合他平日脾性的、说变就变的劲头，怜惜起从前的自己来，说了声\"可怜的孩子！\"又哭了起来。"},{"start":26.587,"end":34.687,"text":"我真希望，\"斯克鲁奇咕哝着，把手插进口袋，用袖口擦干眼睛后四下张望，\"可如今太迟了。"},{"start":34.687,"end":36.7,"text":"怎么啦？\"那精灵问。"},{"start":36.7,"end":38.937,"text":"没什么，\"斯克鲁奇说。"},{"start":38.937,"end":40.075,"text":"没什么。"},{"start":40.075,"end":43.662,"text":"昨儿晚上有个孩子在我门口唱圣诞颂歌。"},{"start":43.662,"end":46.587,"text":"我真该给他点什么的：就这么回事。"},{"start":46.587,"end":53.15,"text":"那鬼魂若有所思地一笑，挥了挥手：一面挥手一面说，\"咱们再看一个圣诞节吧！"},{"start":53.15,"end":59.525,"text":"听了这话，斯克鲁奇那个从前的自己长大了些，屋子也变得暗了点、脏了点。"},{"start":59.525,"end":70.475,"text":"护壁板缩了，窗子裂了；天花板上掉下几块灰泥，露出底下光秃秃的板条；可这一切是怎么变出来的，斯克鲁奇跟你一样摸不着头脑。"},{"start":70.475,"end":80.4,"text":"他只知道这全然不错；知道事情正是这么发生的；知道当别的孩子都回家过那快活的假期时，他又是孤零零一个人留在那儿。"},{"start":80.4,"end":84.275,"text":"这会儿他没在读书，而是绝望地踱来踱去。"}]},"en":{"text":"'Poor Robin Crusoe, where have you been, Robin Crusoe?' The man thought he was dreaming, but he wasn't.\nIt was the Parrot, you know.\nThere goes Friday, running for his life to the little creek!\nHalloa!\nHoop!\nHalloo!\"\nThen, with a rapidity of transition very foreign to his usual character, he said, in pity for his former self, \"Poor boy!\" and cried again.\n\"I wish,\" Scrooge muttered, putting his hand in his pocket, and looking about him, after drying his eyes with his cuff: \"but it's too late now.\"\n\"What is the matter?\" asked the Spirit.\n\"Nothing,\" said Scrooge.\n\"Nothing.\nThere was a boy singing a Christmas Carol at my door last night.\nI should like to have given him something: that's all.\"\nThe Ghost smiled thoughtfully, and waved its hand: saying as it did so, \"Let us see another Christmas!\"\nScrooge's former self grew larger at the words, and the room became a little darker and more dirty.\nThe panels shrunk, the windows cracked; fragments of plaster fell out of the ceiling, and the naked laths were shown instead; but how all this was brought about, Scrooge knew no more than you do.\nHe only knew that it was quite correct; that everything had happened so; that there he was, alone again, when all the other boys had gone home for the jolly holidays.\nHe was not reading now, but walking up and down despairingly.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_II_小节08.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":4.137,"text":"Poor Robin Crusoe, where have you been, Robin Crusoe?"},{"start":4.087,"end":7.5,"text":"The man thought he was dreaming, but he wasn't."},{"start":7.5,"end":9.875,"text":"It was the Parrot, you know."},{"start":9.875,"end":13.762,"text":"There goes Friday, running for his life to the little creek!"},{"start":13.762,"end":15.237,"text":"Halloa!"},{"start":15.237,"end":16.525,"text":"Hoop!"},{"start":16.525,"end":17.975,"text":"Halloo!"},{"start":17.975,"end":27.537,"text":"Then, with a rapidity of transition very foreign to his usual character, he said, in pity for his former self, \"Poor boy!\" and cried again."},{"start":27.537,"end":36.375,"text":"I wish,\" Scrooge muttered, putting his hand in his pocket, and looking about him, after drying his eyes with his cuff: \"but it's too late now."},{"start":36.375,"end":39.287,"text":"What is the matter?\" asked the Spirit."},{"start":39.287,"end":41.837,"text":"Nothing,\" said Scrooge."},{"start":41.837,"end":43.275,"text":"Nothing."},{"start":43.275,"end":47.475,"text":"There was a boy singing a Christmas Carol at my door last night."},{"start":47.475,"end":50.875,"text":"I should like to have given him something: that's all."},{"start":50.875,"end":57.8,"text":"The Ghost smiled thoughtfully, and waved its hand: saying as it did so, \"Let us see another Christmas!"},{"start":57.8,"end":63.987,"text":"Scrooge's former self grew larger at the words, and the room became a little darker and more dirty."},{"start":63.987,"end":75.45,"text":"The panels shrunk, the windows cracked; fragments of plaster fell out of the ceiling, and the naked laths were shown instead; but how all this was brought about, Scrooge knew no more than you do."},{"start":75.45,"end":85.425,"text":"He only knew that it was quite correct; that everything had happened so; that there he was, alone again, when all the other boys had gone home for the jolly holidays."},{"start":85.425,"end":89.787,"text":"He was not reading now, but walking up and down despairingly."}]}},{"id":"II_09","number":9,"zh":{"text":"斯克鲁奇望着那鬼魂，悲伤地摇了摇头，又焦灼地朝门口瞥去。\n门开了；一个比那男孩小得多的小女孩飞奔进来，搂住他的脖子，一遍遍地亲他，唤他作她\"亲爱的，亲爱的哥哥\"。\n\"我来接你回家啦，亲爱的哥哥！\"那孩子拍着她那小小的手，弯下腰去笑着说。\n\"接你回家，回家，回家去！\"\n\"回家，小范？\"那男孩应道。\n\"对！\"那孩子满心欢喜地说。\n\"回家，从此再不走了。\n回家，永永远远。\n父亲比从前慈祥多了，家里头简直像天堂！\n有一个可亲的晚上，我正要上床睡觉，他跟我说话那样温和，我便壮起胆子又问了他一回，问你能不能回家来；他说，能，你该回来；还打发我坐马车来接你。\n你就要做个大人啦！\"那孩子睁大了眼睛说，\"再不用回这儿来了；可头一桩，咱们要一块儿过整整一个圣诞节，过全世界顶顶快活的日子。\"\n\"你都快成个大姑娘啦，小范！\"那男孩嚷道。\n她拍着手笑了起来，想去摸他的头；可她太矮了，够不着，便又笑了，踮起脚尖去搂他。\n随后她带着孩子气的急切，拖起他往门口走；他也巴不得走，便随她去了。\n门厅里一个可怕的声音喊道，\"把斯克鲁奇少爷的箱子搬下来，喂！\"门厅里随即出现了校长本人，他带着一种凶恶的屈尊神气瞪着斯克鲁奇少爷，又跟他握了握手，把他弄得心里头惶惶不安。\n接着他把他和他妹妹领进一间寒气逼人、活像一口老古井的上等客厅——那是从来没见过的；那墙上的地图、窗台上那两只天球仪和地球仪，都冻得像打了蜡似的。\n在这儿他取出一瓶轻得出奇的酒、一块沉得出奇的糕，把这些珍馐一份份分给这两个孩子；同时打发一个面黄肌瘦的仆人出去，给那马车夫递上一杯\"什么\"，马车夫回话说，多谢这位先生，可要还是他先前尝过的那一桶货，那他宁可不喝。\n这时候斯克鲁奇少爷的箱子已经捆在马车顶上了，两个孩子心甘情愿地向校长道了别；上了车，欢欢喜喜地顺着花园车道驶去；那飞转的车轮把白霜和雪从常青树深色的叶子上溅起，像迸出的水花。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_II_小节09.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":5.725,"text":"斯克鲁奇望着那鬼魂，悲伤地摇了摇头，又焦灼地朝门口瞥去。"},{"start":5.675,"end":15.137,"text":"门开了；一个比那男孩小得多的小女孩飞奔进来，搂住他的脖子，一遍遍地亲他，唤他作她\"亲爱的，亲爱的哥哥\"。"},{"start":15.137,"end":21.45,"text":"我来接你回家啦，亲爱的哥哥！\"那孩子拍着她那小小的手，弯下腰去笑着说。"},{"start":21.45,"end":24.162,"text":"接你回家，回家，回家去！"},{"start":24.162,"end":26.987,"text":"回家，小范？\"那男孩应道。"},{"start":26.987,"end":27.862,"text":"对！"},{"start":27.862,"end":30.075,"text":"那孩子满心欢喜地说。"},{"start":30.075,"end":32.525,"text":"回家，从此再不走了。"},{"start":32.525,"end":34.575,"text":"回家，永永远远。"},{"start":34.575,"end":38.637,"text":"父亲比从前慈祥多了，家里头简直像天堂！"},{"start":38.637,"end":52,"text":"有一个可亲的晚上，我正要上床睡觉，他跟我说话那样温和，我便壮起胆子又问了他一回，问你能不能回家来；他说，能，你该回来；还打发我坐马车来接你。"},{"start":52,"end":62.625,"text":"你就要做个大人啦！\"那孩子睁大了眼睛说，\"再不用回这儿来了；可头一桩，咱们要一块儿过整整一个圣诞节，过全世界顶顶快活的日子。"},{"start":62.625,"end":66.587,"text":"你都快成个大姑娘啦，小范！\"那男孩嚷道。"},{"start":66.587,"end":74.15,"text":"她拍着手笑了起来，想去摸他的头；可她太矮了，够不着，便又笑了，踮起脚尖去搂他。"},{"start":74.15,"end":80.862,"text":"随后她带着孩子气的急切，拖起他往门口走；他也巴不得走，便随她去了。"},{"start":80.862,"end":96.45,"text":"门厅里一个可怕的声音喊道，\"把斯克鲁奇少爷的箱子搬下来，喂！\"门厅里随即出现了校长本人，他带着一种凶恶的屈尊神气瞪着斯克鲁奇少爷，又跟他握了握手，把他弄得心里头惶惶不安。"},{"start":96.45,"end":111.262,"text":"接着他把他和他妹妹领进一间寒气逼人、活像一口老古井的上等客厅——那是从来没见过的；那墙上的地图、窗台上那两只天球仪和地球仪，都冻得像打了蜡似的。"},{"start":111.262,"end":130.137,"text":"在这儿他取出一瓶轻得出奇的酒、一块沉得出奇的糕，把这些珍馐一份份分给这两个孩子；同时打发一个面黄肌瘦的仆人出去，给那马车夫递上一杯\"什么\"，马车夫回话说，多谢这位先生，可要还是他先前尝过的那一桶货，那他宁可不喝。"},{"start":130.137,"end":147,"text":"这时候斯克鲁奇少爷的箱子已经捆在马车顶上了，两个孩子心甘情愿地向校长道了别；上了车，欢欢喜喜地顺着花园车道驶去；那飞转的车轮把白霜和雪从常青树深色的叶子上溅起，像迸出的水花。"}]},"en":{"text":"Scrooge looked at the Ghost, and with a mournful shaking of his head, glanced anxiously towards the door.\nIt opened; and a little girl, much younger than the boy, came darting in, and putting her arms about his neck, and often kissing him, addressed him as her \"Dear, dear brother.\"\n\"I have come to bring you home, dear brother!\" said the child, clapping her tiny hands, and bending down to laugh.\n\"To bring you home, home, home!\"\n\"Home, little Fan?\" returned the boy.\n\"Yes!\" said the child, brimful of glee.\n\"Home, for good and all.\nHome, for ever and ever.\nFather is so much kinder than he used to be, that home's like Heaven!\nHe spoke so gently to me one dear night when I was going to bed, that I was not afraid to ask him once more if you might come home; and he said Yes, you should; and sent me in a coach to bring you.\nAnd you're to be a man!\" said the child, opening her eyes, \"and are never to come back here; but first, we're to be together all the Christmas long, and have the merriest time in all the world.\"\n\"You are quite a woman, little Fan!\" exclaimed the boy.\nShe clapped her hands and laughed, and tried to touch his head; but being too little, laughed again, and stood on tiptoe to embrace him.\nThen she began to drag him, in her childish eagerness, towards the door; and he, nothing loth to go, accompanied her.\nA terrible voice in the hall cried, \"Bring down Master Scrooge's box, there!\" and in the hall appeared the schoolmaster himself, who glared on Master Scrooge with a ferocious condescension, and threw him into a dreadful state of mind by shaking hands with him.\nHe then conveyed him and his sister into the veriest old well of a shivering best-parlour that ever was seen, where the maps upon the wall, and the celestial and terrestrial globes in the windows, were waxy with cold.\nHere he produced a decanter of curiously light wine, and a block of curiously heavy cake, and administered instalments of those dainties to the young people: at the same time, sending out a meagre servant to offer a glass of \"something\" to the postboy, who answered that he thanked the gentleman, but if it was the same tap as he had tasted before, he had rather not.\nMaster Scrooge's trunk being by this time tied on to the top of the chaise, the children bade the schoolmaster good-bye right willingly; and getting into it, drove gaily down the garden-sweep; the quick wheels dashing the hoar-frost and snow from off the dark leaves of the evergreens like spray.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_II_小节09.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":6.6,"text":"Scrooge looked at the Ghost, and with a mournful shaking of his head, glanced anxiously towards the door."},{"start":6.55,"end":17.487,"text":"It opened; and a little girl, much younger than the boy, came darting in, and putting her arms about his neck, and often kissing him, addressed him as her \"Dear, dear brother."},{"start":17.487,"end":25.15,"text":"I have come to bring you home, dear brother!\" said the child, clapping her tiny hands, and bending down to laugh."},{"start":25.15,"end":28.225,"text":"To bring you home, home, home!"},{"start":28.225,"end":31.5,"text":"Home, little Fan?\" returned the boy."},{"start":31.5,"end":35.187,"text":"Yes!\" said the child, brimful of glee."},{"start":35.187,"end":37.812,"text":"Home, for good and all."},{"start":37.812,"end":40.5,"text":"Home, for ever and ever."},{"start":40.5,"end":45.237,"text":"Father is so much kinder than he used to be, that home's like Heaven!"},{"start":45.237,"end":56.387,"text":"He spoke so gently to me one dear night when I was going to bed, that I was not afraid to ask him once more if you might come home; and he said Yes, you should; and sent me in a coach to bring you."},{"start":56.387,"end":67.912,"text":"And you're to be a man!\" said the child, opening her eyes, \"and are never to come back here; but first, we're to be together all the Christmas long, and have the merriest time in all the world."},{"start":67.912,"end":72.012,"text":"You are quite a woman, little Fan!\" exclaimed the boy."},{"start":72.012,"end":80.212,"text":"She clapped her hands and laughed, and tried to touch his head; but being too little, laughed again, and stood on tiptoe to embrace him."},{"start":80.212,"end":88.325,"text":"Then she began to drag him, in her childish eagerness, towards the door; and he, nothing loth to go, accompanied her."},{"start":88.325,"end":103.125,"text":"A terrible voice in the hall cried, \"Bring down Master Scrooge's box, there!\" and in the hall appeared the schoolmaster himself, who glared on Master Scrooge with a ferocious condescension, and threw him into a dreadful state of mind by shaking hands with him."},{"start":103.125,"end":115.262,"text":"He then conveyed him and his sister into the veriest old well of a shivering best-parlour that ever was seen, where the maps upon the wall, and the celestial and terrestrial globes in the windows, were waxy with cold."},{"start":115.262,"end":135.387,"text":"Here he produced a decanter of curiously light wine, and a block of curiously heavy cake, and administered instalments of those dainties to the young people: at the same time, sending out a meagre servant to offer a glass of \"something\" to the postboy, who answered that he thanked the gentleman, but if it was the same tap as he had tasted before, he had rather not."},{"start":135.387,"end":151.65,"text":"Master Scrooge's trunk being by this time tied on to the top of the chaise, the children bade the schoolmaster good-bye right willingly; and getting into it, drove gaily down the garden-sweep; the quick wheels dashing the hoar-frost and snow from off the dark leaves of the evergreens like spray."}]}},{"id":"II_10","number":10,"zh":{"text":"\"一向是个娇弱的人儿，一口气仿佛就能把她吹蔫了，\"那鬼魂说。\n\"可她有一颗宽厚的心！\"\n\"她确实有，\"斯克鲁奇嚷道。\n\"你说得对。\n我决不否认这话，精灵。\n但愿上天保佑！\"\n\"她是长大成人后才去世的，\"那鬼魂说，\"依我看，还留下了孩子。\"\n\"一个孩子，\"斯克鲁奇应道。\n\"不错，\"那鬼魂说。\n\"是你的外甥！\"\n斯克鲁奇心里头似乎很不自在；只简短地答了一声，\"是的。\"\n他们虽说不过刚刚把那学堂抛在身后，这会儿却已置身于一座城市熙熙攘攘的大街上，影子似的行人来来往往；影子似的大车和马车争着抢道，真城市里那一切的纷扰喧嚷全在这儿了。\n单看那些店铺的装点，便清清楚楚地显出，这儿也又到了圣诞节；不过这会儿是傍晚，街上已经点起了灯。\n那鬼魂在一处货栈门口停下，问斯克鲁奇可认得这地方。\n\"认得它！\"斯克鲁奇说。\n\"我不就是在这儿当的学徒吗？\"\n他们走了进去。\n一瞧见一位戴着威尔士假发的老先生坐在那么高的一张写字台后头——他要是再高两英寸，脑袋准得撞着天花板——斯克鲁奇便万分激动地嚷道：\"咦，是老费齐威格！","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_II_小节10.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":5.312,"text":"一向是个娇弱的人儿，一口气仿佛就能把她吹蔫了，\"那鬼魂说。"},{"start":5.262,"end":7.462,"text":"可她有一颗宽厚的心！"},{"start":7.462,"end":10.05,"text":"她确实有，\"斯克鲁奇嚷道。"},{"start":10.05,"end":11.3,"text":"你说得对。"},{"start":11.3,"end":13.775,"text":"我决不否认这话，精灵。"},{"start":13.775,"end":15.512,"text":"但愿上天保佑！"},{"start":15.512,"end":21.2,"text":"她是长大成人后才去世的，\"那鬼魂说，\"依我看，还留下了孩子。"},{"start":21.2,"end":23.737,"text":"一个孩子，\"斯克鲁奇应道。"},{"start":23.737,"end":25.662,"text":"不错，\"那鬼魂说。"},{"start":25.662,"end":27.087,"text":"是你的外甥！"},{"start":27.087,"end":32.212,"text":"斯克鲁奇心里头似乎很不自在；只简短地答了一声，\"是的。"},{"start":32.212,"end":47.437,"text":"他们虽说不过刚刚把那学堂抛在身后，这会儿却已置身于一座城市熙熙攘攘的大街上，影子似的行人来来往往；影子似的大车和马车争着抢道，真城市里那一切的纷扰喧嚷全在这儿了。"},{"start":47.437,"end":55.975,"text":"单看那些店铺的装点，便清清楚楚地显出，这儿也又到了圣诞节；不过这会儿是傍晚，街上已经点起了灯。"},{"start":55.975,"end":61.312,"text":"那鬼魂在一处货栈门口停下，问斯克鲁奇可认得这地方。"},{"start":61.312,"end":63.587,"text":"认得它！\"斯克鲁奇说。"},{"start":63.587,"end":66.175,"text":"我不就是在这儿当的学徒吗？"},{"start":66.175,"end":67.812,"text":"他们走了进去。"},{"start":67.812,"end":81.575,"text":"一瞧见一位戴着威尔士假发的老先生坐在那么高的一张写字台后头——他要是再高两英寸，脑袋准得撞着天花板——斯克鲁奇便万分激动地嚷道：\"咦，是老费齐威格！"}]},"en":{"text":"\"Always a delicate creature, whom a breath might have withered,\" said the Ghost.\n\"But she had a large heart!\"\n\"So she had,\" cried Scrooge.\n\"You're right.\nI'll not gainsay it, Spirit.\nGod forbid!\"\n\"She died a woman,\" said the Ghost, \"and had, as I think, children.\"\n\"One child,\" Scrooge returned.\n\"True,\" said the Ghost.\n\"Your nephew!\"\nScrooge seemed uneasy in his mind; and answered briefly, \"Yes.\"\nAlthough they had but that moment left the school behind them, they were now in the busy thoroughfares of a city, where shadowy passengers passed and repassed; where shadowy carts and coaches battled for the way, and all the strife and tumult of a real city were.\nIt was made plain enough, by the dressing of the shops, that here too it was Christmas time again; but it was evening, and the streets were lighted up.\nThe Ghost stopped at a certain warehouse door, and asked Scrooge if he knew it.\n\"Know it!\" said Scrooge.\n\"Was I apprenticed here?\"\nThey went in.\nAt sight of an old gentleman in a Welch wig, sitting behind such a high desk, that if he had been two inches taller he must have knocked his head against the ceiling, Scrooge cried in great excitement: \"Why, it's old Fezziwig!","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_II_小节10.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":5.087,"text":"Always a delicate creature, whom a breath might have withered,\" said the Ghost."},{"start":5.037,"end":7.362,"text":"But she had a large heart!"},{"start":7.362,"end":10.362,"text":"So she had,\" cried Scrooge."},{"start":10.362,"end":11.925,"text":"You're right."},{"start":11.925,"end":14.762,"text":"I'll not gainsay it, Spirit."},{"start":14.762,"end":16.537,"text":"God forbid!"},{"start":16.537,"end":21.837,"text":"She died a woman,\" said the Ghost, \"and had, as I think, children."},{"start":21.837,"end":24.9,"text":"One child,\" Scrooge returned."},{"start":24.9,"end":27.325,"text":"True,\" said the Ghost."},{"start":27.325,"end":28.987,"text":"Your nephew!"},{"start":28.987,"end":34.062,"text":"Scrooge seemed uneasy in his mind; and answered briefly, \"Yes."},{"start":34.062,"end":48.475,"text":"Although they had but that moment left the school behind them, they were now in the busy thoroughfares of a city, where shadowy passengers passed and repassed; where shadowy carts and coaches battled for the way, and all the strife and tumult of a real city were."},{"start":48.475,"end":57.15,"text":"It was made plain enough, by the dressing of the shops, that here too it was Christmas time again; but it was evening, and the streets were lighted up."},{"start":57.15,"end":62.037,"text":"The Ghost stopped at a certain warehouse door, and asked Scrooge if he knew it."},{"start":62.037,"end":64.562,"text":"Know it!\" said Scrooge."},{"start":64.562,"end":66.687,"text":"Was I apprenticed here?"},{"start":66.687,"end":68.362,"text":"They went in."},{"start":68.362,"end":81.45,"text":"At sight of an old gentleman in a Welch wig, sitting behind such a high desk, that if he had been two inches taller he must have knocked his head against the ceiling, Scrooge cried in great excitement: \"Why, it's old Fezziwig!"}]}},{"id":"II_11","number":11,"zh":{"text":"天哪；是费齐威格又活过来啦！\"\n老费齐威格放下笔，抬头看了看钟，时针正指着七点。\n他搓了搓手；整了整那件宽大的背心；从鞋子一直笑到他那慈善之心，浑身上下都在笑；又用一种舒坦、油润、浑厚、丰沛、欢快的嗓音嚷道：\"喂——嗬，那边的！\n埃比尼泽！\n迪克！\"\n斯克鲁奇那个从前的自己，这会儿已长成个小伙子，伴着他的师兄弟轻快地走了进来。\n\"准是迪克·威尔金斯！\"斯克鲁奇对那鬼魂说。\n\"我的天，没错。\n他就在那儿。\n他可跟我要好啦，迪克这人。\n可怜的迪克！\n亲爱的，亲爱的！\"\n\"喂——嗬，孩子们！\"费齐威格说。\n\"今晚不干活啦。\n圣诞前夜呀，迪克。\n过圣诞节呢，埃比尼泽！\n咱们把窗板都装上吧，\"老费齐威格啪地一拍手嚷道，\"快得叫人来不及说一声'杰克·罗宾逊'！\"\n你简直不会相信那两个小伙子干起活来有多卖力！","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_II_小节11.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":3.225,"text":"天哪；是费齐威格又活过来啦！"},{"start":3.175,"end":8.3,"text":"老费齐威格放下笔，抬头看了看钟，时针正指着七点。"},{"start":8.3,"end":23.575,"text":"他搓了搓手；整了整那件宽大的背心；从鞋子一直笑到他那慈善之心，浑身上下都在笑；又用一种舒坦、油润、浑厚、丰沛、欢快的嗓音嚷道：\"喂——嗬，那边的！"},{"start":23.575,"end":24.862,"text":"埃比尼泽！"},{"start":24.862,"end":25.925,"text":"迪克！"},{"start":25.925,"end":32.937,"text":"斯克鲁奇那个从前的自己，这会儿已长成个小伙子，伴着他的师兄弟轻快地走了进来。"},{"start":32.937,"end":37.125,"text":"准是迪克·威尔金斯！\"斯克鲁奇对那鬼魂说。"},{"start":37.125,"end":38.85,"text":"我的天，没错。"},{"start":38.85,"end":40.175,"text":"他就在那儿。"},{"start":40.175,"end":42.662,"text":"他可跟我要好啦，迪克这人。"},{"start":42.662,"end":44.162,"text":"可怜的迪克！"},{"start":44.162,"end":45.987,"text":"亲爱的，亲爱的！"},{"start":45.987,"end":49.2,"text":"喂——嗬，孩子们！\"费齐威格说。"},{"start":49.2,"end":50.862,"text":"今晚不干活啦。"},{"start":50.862,"end":53.037,"text":"圣诞前夜呀，迪克。"},{"start":53.037,"end":55.425,"text":"过圣诞节呢，埃比尼泽！"},{"start":55.425,"end":63.137,"text":"咱们把窗板都装上吧，\"老费齐威格啪地一拍手嚷道，\"快得叫人来不及说一声'杰克·罗宾逊'！"},{"start":63.137,"end":67.675,"text":"你简直不会相信那两个小伙子干起活来有多卖力！"}]},"en":{"text":"Bless his heart; it's Fezziwig alive again!\"\nOld Fezziwig laid down his pen, and looked up at the clock, which pointed to the hour of seven.\nHe rubbed his hands; adjusted his capacious waistcoat; laughed all over himself, from his shoes to his organ of benevolence; and called out in a comfortable, oily, rich, fat, jovial voice: \"Yo ho, there!\nEbenezer!\nDick!\"\nScrooge's former self, now grown a young man, came briskly in, accompanied by his fellow-'prentice.\n\"Dick Wilkins, to be sure!\" said Scrooge to the Ghost.\n\"Bless me, yes.\nThere he is.\nHe was very much attached to me, was Dick.\nPoor Dick!\nDear, dear!\"\n\"Yo ho, my boys!\" said Fezziwig.\n\"No more work to-night.\nChristmas Eve, Dick.\nChristmas, Ebenezer!\nLet's have the shutters up,\" cried old Fezziwig, with a sharp clap of his hands, \"before a man can say, Jack Robinson!\"\nYou wouldn't believe how those two fellows went at it!","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_II_小节11.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":3.562,"text":"Bless his heart; it's Fezziwig alive again!"},{"start":3.512,"end":9.587,"text":"Old Fezziwig laid down his pen, and looked up at the clock, which pointed to the hour of seven."},{"start":9.587,"end":23.612,"text":"He rubbed his hands; adjusted his capacious waistcoat; laughed all over himself, from his shoes to his organ of benevolence; and called out in a comfortable, oily, rich, fat, jovial voice: \"Yo ho, there!"},{"start":23.612,"end":25.212,"text":"Ebenezer!"},{"start":25.212,"end":26.525,"text":"Dick!"},{"start":26.525,"end":33.462,"text":"Scrooge's former self, now grown a young man, came briskly in, accompanied by his fellow-'prentice."},{"start":33.462,"end":37.8,"text":"Dick Wilkins, to be sure!\" said Scrooge to the Ghost."},{"start":37.8,"end":40.025,"text":"Bless me, yes."},{"start":40.025,"end":41.862,"text":"There he is."},{"start":41.862,"end":45.2,"text":"He was very much attached to me, was Dick."},{"start":45.2,"end":46.762,"text":"Poor Dick!"},{"start":46.762,"end":48.837,"text":"Dear, dear!"},{"start":48.837,"end":52.412,"text":"Yo ho, my boys!\" said Fezziwig."},{"start":52.412,"end":54.6,"text":"No more work to-night."},{"start":54.6,"end":56.925,"text":"Christmas Eve, Dick."},{"start":56.925,"end":59.325,"text":"Christmas, Ebenezer!"},{"start":59.325,"end":67.4,"text":"Let's have the shutters up,\" cried old Fezziwig, with a sharp clap of his hands, \"before a man can say, Jack Robinson!"},{"start":67.4,"end":70.712,"text":"You wouldn't believe how those two fellows went at it!"}]}},{"id":"II_12","number":12,"zh":{"text":"他们抱着窗板冲到街上——一、二、三——把它们装上原位——四、五、六——上了闩、插了销——七、八、九——你还没数到十二，他们就回来了，喘得像两匹赛马。\n\"嗨——嗬！\"老费齐威格喊着，从那高写字台上一跃而下，敏捷得叫人称奇。\n\"都清开，小子们，让这儿腾出好大一片地方来！\n嗨——嗬，迪克！\n加把劲，埃比尼泽！\"\n清开！\n有老费齐威格在一旁瞧着，就没有什么是他们不肯清开、或是清不开的。\n一眨眼工夫就办妥了。\n凡是搬得动的家什全给收拾走了，仿佛要把它们从公众生活里永远撵出去似的；地板扫过、洒过水，灯芯剪好了，炉火上堆足了煤；那货栈便成了一间舒适、温暖、干爽、亮堂的舞厅，正是你冬夜里巴望看到的那种。\n进来一个提着乐谱本的提琴手，走到那高写字台跟前，把它当作了乐池，调起弦来，活像五十个人在闹肚子疼。\n进来了费齐威格太太，浑身上下一团又敦实又畅快的笑。\n进来了费齐威格家三位小姐，笑盈盈的，惹人怜爱。\n进来了那六个被她们勾断了心的年轻追求者。\n进来了店里所有受雇的年轻男女。\n进来了女佣，带着她那做面包师的表哥。\n进来了厨娘，带着她哥哥的好友——那个送奶的。\n进来了对门那个小子，人都疑心他东家没管够他的饭食；他想躲到隔壁第二家那姑娘身后，那姑娘可是有凭有据地让女主人揪过耳朵的。\n他们一个接一个全进来了；有的腼腆，有的大方，有的雅致，有的笨拙，有的连推，有的带拽；横竖各式各样，全都进来了。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_II_小节12.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":15.037,"text":"他们抱着窗板冲到街上——一、二、三——把它们装上原位——四、五、六——上了闩、插了销——七、八、九——你还没数到十二，他们就回来了，喘得像两匹赛马。"},{"start":14.987,"end":21.5,"text":"嗨——嗬！\"老费齐威格喊着，从那高写字台上一跃而下，敏捷得叫人称奇。"},{"start":21.5,"end":25.65,"text":"都清开，小子们，让这儿腾出好大一片地方来！"},{"start":25.65,"end":27.612,"text":"嗨——嗬，迪克！"},{"start":27.612,"end":29.75,"text":"加把劲，埃比尼泽！"},{"start":29.75,"end":30.85,"text":"清开！"},{"start":30.85,"end":36.8,"text":"有老费齐威格在一旁瞧着，就没有什么是他们不肯清开、或是清不开的。"},{"start":36.8,"end":39.087,"text":"一眨眼工夫就办妥了。"},{"start":39.087,"end":57.875,"text":"凡是搬得动的家什全给收拾走了，仿佛要把它们从公众生活里永远撵出去似的；地板扫过、洒过水，灯芯剪好了，炉火上堆足了煤；那货栈便成了一间舒适、温暖、干爽、亮堂的舞厅，正是你冬夜里巴望看到的那种。"},{"start":57.875,"end":67.162,"text":"进来一个提着乐谱本的提琴手，走到那高写字台跟前，把它当作了乐池，调起弦来，活像五十个人在闹肚子疼。"},{"start":67.162,"end":72.35,"text":"进来了费齐威格太太，浑身上下一团又敦实又畅快的笑。"},{"start":72.35,"end":76.9,"text":"进来了费齐威格家三位小姐，笑盈盈的，惹人怜爱。"},{"start":76.9,"end":81.1,"text":"进来了那六个被她们勾断了心的年轻追求者。"},{"start":81.1,"end":84.075,"text":"进来了店里所有受雇的年轻男女。"},{"start":84.075,"end":87.7,"text":"进来了女佣，带着她那做面包师的表哥。"},{"start":87.7,"end":91.787,"text":"进来了厨娘，带着她哥哥的好友——那个送奶的。"},{"start":91.787,"end":103.3,"text":"进来了对门那个小子，人都疑心他东家没管够他的饭食；他想躲到隔壁第二家那姑娘身后，那姑娘可是有凭有据地让女主人揪过耳朵的。"},{"start":103.3,"end":114.075,"text":"他们一个接一个全进来了；有的腼腆，有的大方，有的雅致，有的笨拙，有的连推，有的带拽；横竖各式各样，全都进来了。"}]},"en":{"text":"They charged into the street with the shutters--one, two, three--had 'em up in their places--four, five, six--barred 'em and pinned 'em--seven, eight, nine--and came back before you could have got to twelve, panting like race-horses.\n\"Hilli-ho!\" cried old Fezziwig, skipping down from the high desk, with wonderful agility.\n\"Clear away, my lads, and let's have lots of room here!\nHilli-ho, Dick!\nChirrup, Ebenezer!\"\nClear away!\nThere was nothing they wouldn't have cleared away, or couldn't have cleared away, with old Fezziwig looking on.\nIt was done in a minute.\nEvery movable was packed off, as if it were dismissed from public life for ever-more; the floor was swept and watered, the lamps were trimmed, fuel was heaped upon the fire; and the warehouse was as snug, and warm, and dry, and bright a ball-room, as you would desire to see upon a winter's night.\nIn came a fiddler with a music-book, and went up to the lofty desk, and made an orchestra of it, and tuned like fifty stomach-aches.\nIn came Mrs. Fezziwig, one vast substantial smile.\nIn came the three Miss Fezziwigs, beaming and loveable.\nIn came the six young followers whose hearts they broke.\nIn came all the young men and women employed in the business.\nIn came the housemaid, with her cousin, the baker.\nIn came the cook, with her brother's particular friend, the milkman.\nIn came the boy from over the way, who was suspected of not having board enough from his master; trying to hide himself behind the girl from next door but one, who was proved to have had her ears pulled by her Mistress.\nIn they all came, one after another; some shyly, some boldly, some gracefully, some awkwardly, some pushing, some pulling; in they all came, anyhow and everyhow.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_II_小节12.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":14.062,"text":"They charged into the street with the shutters--one, two, three--had 'em up in their places--four, five, six--barred 'em and pinned 'em--seven, eight, nine--and came back before you could have got to twelve, panting like race-horses."},{"start":14.012,"end":20.125,"text":"Hilli-ho!\" cried old Fezziwig, skipping down from the high desk, with wonderful agility."},{"start":20.125,"end":24.425,"text":"Clear away, my lads, and let's have lots of room here!"},{"start":24.425,"end":26.512,"text":"Hilli-ho, Dick!"},{"start":26.512,"end":28.762,"text":"Chirrup, Ebenezer!"},{"start":28.762,"end":30.437,"text":"Clear away!"},{"start":30.437,"end":36.65,"text":"There was nothing they wouldn't have cleared away, or couldn't have cleared away, with old Fezziwig looking on."},{"start":36.65,"end":38.675,"text":"It was done in a minute."},{"start":38.675,"end":56.012,"text":"Every movable was packed off, as if it were dismissed from public life for ever-more; the floor was swept and watered, the lamps were trimmed, fuel was heaped upon the fire; and the warehouse was as snug, and warm, and dry, and bright a ball-room, as you would desire to see upon a winter's night."},{"start":56.012,"end":64.175,"text":"In came a fiddler with a music-book, and went up to the lofty desk, and made an orchestra of it, and tuned like fifty stomach-aches."},{"start":64.175,"end":68.425,"text":"In came Mrs. Fezziwig, one vast substantial smile."},{"start":68.425,"end":72.412,"text":"In came the three Miss Fezziwigs, beaming and loveable."},{"start":72.412,"end":76.162,"text":"In came the six young followers whose hearts they broke."},{"start":76.162,"end":80.025,"text":"In came all the young men and women employed in the business."},{"start":80.025,"end":83.887,"text":"In came the housemaid, with her cousin, the baker."},{"start":83.887,"end":88.45,"text":"In came the cook, with her brother's particular friend, the milkman."},{"start":88.45,"end":100.275,"text":"In came the boy from over the way, who was suspected of not having board enough from his master; trying to hide himself behind the girl from next door but one, who was proved to have had her ears pulled by her Mistress."},{"start":100.275,"end":112.35,"text":"In they all came, one after another; some shyly, some boldly, some gracefully, some awkwardly, some pushing, some pulling; in they all came, anyhow and everyhow."}]}},{"id":"II_13","number":13,"zh":{"text":"他们全跳起舞来，二十对一齐上场，手拉手转半圈再反方向转回来；从中间穿下去再绕上来；变着花样亲亲热热地围成一圈又一圈；那对老领舞总在不该出现的地方冒出来；新领舞刚转到头，又重新起步；到末了人人都成了领舞，连一对压尾的也没剩下，没人帮衬他们了。\n弄到这般地步，老费齐威格啪地拍手叫停了舞，嚷道，\"跳得好！\"那提琴手便把发烫的脸往一壶黑啤里一扎，那啤酒是专为这用处备下的。\n可他一冒头，便不屑歇息，立时又拉了起来，虽说这会儿还没人跳舞，仿佛那另一个提琴手已累瘫了被人用窗板抬回家去、而他是个生龙活虎的新手，铁了心要把对方比下去、不然就拼了命。\n又跳了好几场舞，还玩了罚物游戏，又跳了好几场舞，有糕点，有香料酒，有一大块冷烤肉，有一大块冷煮肉，有肉馅饼，还有的是啤酒。\n可这一晚最精彩的，是在冷烤肉、冷煮肉之后来的，那时提琴手（记住，这是条狡猾的老手！\n是那种比你我能教他的还更精通自家本行的人）奏起了《罗杰·德·考夫利爵士》。这时老费齐威格站出来，要跟费齐威格太太跳。\n也是那对领舞；给他们排下的可是一桩硬碰硬的活儿；二十三四对舞伴；都是些惹不得的角色；都是些铁了心要跳、压根没打算斯斯文文走两步的人。\n可就算他们再多一倍：啊，多三倍：老费齐威格也照样应付得来，费齐威格太太也一样。\n要说她，无论从哪个意义上讲，都配得上做他的舞伴。\n这要不算高的夸奖，你倒说个更高的来，我准用上。\n费齐威格的小腿肚子，简直像是发出了实实在在的光。\n它们在舞步的每一个段落里都像月亮似的发亮。\n你随便在哪一刻都料不准它们下一步会变出什么花样来。\n等老费齐威格和费齐威格太太把整套舞跳了个遍；进步、退步，跟舞伴手拉手；鞠躬、行屈膝礼；像开瓶塞似的旋转；穿针引线般地绕来绕去，再回到原位；费齐威格来了个\"跳腿击踝\"——跳得那样利落，仿佛他是用两条腿在眨眼，落地时又稳稳当当，一点没踉跄。\n钟敲十一点时，这场家庭舞会散了。\n费齐威格夫妇各守一边，一人站在门的一侧，每有男女宾客走出，便一一同他握手，祝他或她圣诞快乐。\n等众人都散尽、只剩那两个学徒时，他们也照样同他俩握手道贺；于是那一片欢声笑语渐渐消歇，两个小伙子各自回去睡觉；他们的床就铺在后店一张柜台底下。\n这一段时间里，斯克鲁奇始终像个失了魂的人。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_II_小节13.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":23.537,"text":"他们全跳起舞来，二十对一齐上场，手拉手转半圈再反方向转回来；从中间穿下去再绕上来；变着花样亲亲热热地围成一圈又一圈；那对老领舞总在不该出现的地方冒出来；新领舞刚转到头，又重新起步；到末了人人都成了领舞，连一对压尾的也没剩下，没人帮衬他们了。"},{"start":23.537,"end":35.387,"text":"弄到这般地步，老费齐威格啪地拍手叫停了舞，嚷道，\"跳得好！\"那提琴手便把发烫的脸往一壶黑啤里一扎，那啤酒是专为这用处备下的。"},{"start":35.387,"end":50.737,"text":"可他一冒头，便不屑歇息，立时又拉了起来，虽说这会儿还没人跳舞，仿佛那另一个提琴手已累瘫了被人用窗板抬回家去、而他是个生龙活虎的新手，铁了心要把对方比下去、不然就拼了命。"},{"start":50.737,"end":62.5,"text":"又跳了好几场舞，还玩了罚物游戏，又跳了好几场舞，有糕点，有香料酒，有一大块冷烤肉，有一大块冷煮肉，有肉馅饼，还有的是啤酒。"},{"start":62.5,"end":70.287,"text":"可这一晚最精彩的，是在冷烤肉、冷煮肉之后来的，那时提琴手（记住，这是条狡猾的老手！"},{"start":70.287,"end":77.025,"text":"是那种比你我能教他的还更精通自家本行的人）奏起了《罗杰·德·考夫利爵士》。"},{"start":77.025,"end":81.375,"text":"这时老费齐威格站出来，要跟费齐威格太太跳。"},{"start":81.375,"end":93.975,"text":"也是那对领舞；给他们排下的可是一桩硬碰硬的活儿；二十三四对舞伴；都是些惹不得的角色；都是些铁了心要跳、压根没打算斯斯文文走两步的人。"},{"start":93.975,"end":101.462,"text":"可就算他们再多一倍：啊，多三倍：老费齐威格也照样应付得来，费齐威格太太也一样。"},{"start":101.462,"end":106.087,"text":"要说她，无论从哪个意义上讲，都配得上做他的舞伴。"},{"start":106.087,"end":110.575,"text":"这要不算高的夸奖，你倒说个更高的来，我准用上。"},{"start":110.575,"end":115.625,"text":"费齐威格的小腿肚子，简直像是发出了实实在在的光。"},{"start":115.625,"end":119.6,"text":"它们在舞步的每一个段落里都像月亮似的发亮。"},{"start":119.6,"end":124.337,"text":"你随便在哪一刻都料不准它们下一步会变出什么花样来。"},{"start":124.337,"end":147.562,"text":"等老费齐威格和费齐威格太太把整套舞跳了个遍；进步、退步，跟舞伴手拉手；鞠躬、行屈膝礼；像开瓶塞似的旋转；穿针引线般地绕来绕去，再回到原位；费齐威格来了个\"跳腿击踝\"——跳得那样利落，仿佛他是用两条腿在眨眼，落地时又稳稳当当，一点没踉跄。"},{"start":147.562,"end":150.912,"text":"钟敲十一点时，这场家庭舞会散了。"},{"start":150.912,"end":160.1,"text":"费齐威格夫妇各守一边，一人站在门的一侧，每有男女宾客走出，便一一同他握手，祝他或她圣诞快乐。"},{"start":160.1,"end":174.512,"text":"等众人都散尽、只剩那两个学徒时，他们也照样同他俩握手道贺；于是那一片欢声笑语渐渐消歇，两个小伙子各自回去睡觉；他们的床就铺在后店一张柜台底下。"},{"start":174.512,"end":178.775,"text":"这一段时间里，斯克鲁奇始终像个失了魂的人。"}]},"en":{"text":"Away they all went, twenty couple at once, hands half round and back again the other way; down the middle and up again; round and round in various stages of affectionate grouping; old top couple always turning up in the wrong place; new top couple starting off again, as soon as they got there; all top couples at last, and not a bottom one to help them.\nWhen this result was brought about, old Fezziwig, clapping his hands to stop the dance, cried out, \"Well down!\" and the fiddler plunged his hot face into a pot of porter, especially provided for that purpose.\nBut scorning rest upon his reappearance, he instantly began again, though there were no dancers yet, as if the other fiddler had been carried home, exhausted, on a shutter; and he were a bran-new man resolved to beat him out of sight, or perish.\nThere were more dances, and there were forfeits, and more dances, and there was cake, and there was negus, and there was a great piece of Cold Roast, and there was a great piece of Cold Boiled, and there were mince-pies, and plenty of beer.\nBut the great effect of the evening came after the Roast and Boiled, when the fiddler (an artful dog, mind!\nThe sort of man who knew his business better than you or I could have told it him!) struck up \"Sir Roger de Coverley.\" Then old Fezziwig stood out to dance with Mrs. Fezziwig.\nTop couple too; with a good stiff piece of work cut out for them; three or four and twenty pair of partners; people who were not to be trifled with; people who _would_ dance, and had no notion of walking.\nBut if they had been twice as many: ah, four times: old Fezziwig would have been a match for them, and so would Mrs. Fezziwig.\nAs to _her_, she was worthy to be his partner in every sense of the term.\nIf that's not high praise, tell me higher, and I'll use it.\nA positive light appeared to issue from Fezziwig's calves.\nThey shone in every part of the dance like moons.\nYou couldn't have predicted, at any given time, what would become of 'em next.\nAnd when old Fezziwig and Mrs. Fezziwig had gone all through the dance; advance and retire, hold hands with your partner; bow and curtsey; corkscrew; thread-the-needle, and back again to your place; Fezziwig \"cut\"--cut so deftly, that he appeared to wink with his legs, and came upon his feet again without a stagger.\nWhen the clock struck eleven, this domestic ball broke up.\nMr. and Mrs. Fezziwig took their stations, one on either side the door, and shaking hands with every person individually as he or she went out, wished him or her a Merry Christmas.\nWhen everybody had retired but the two 'prentices, they did the same to them; and thus the cheerful voices died away, and the lads were left to their beds; which were under a counter in the back-shop.\nDuring the whole of this time, Scrooge had acted like a man out of his wits.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_II_小节13.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":20.45,"text":"Away they all went, twenty couple at once, hands half round and back again the other way; down the middle and up again; round and round in various stages of affectionate grouping; old top couple always turning up in the wrong place; new top couple starting off again, as soon as they got there; all top couples at last, and not a bottom one to help them."},{"start":20.4,"end":33.062,"text":"When this result was brought about, old Fezziwig, clapping his hands to stop the dance, cried out, \"Well down!\" and the fiddler plunged his hot face into a pot of porter, especially provided for that purpose."},{"start":33.062,"end":47.412,"text":"But scorning rest upon his reappearance, he instantly began again, though there were no dancers yet, as if the other fiddler had been carried home, exhausted, on a shutter; and he were a bran-new man resolved to beat him out of sight, or perish."},{"start":47.412,"end":61.175,"text":"There were more dances, and there were forfeits, and more dances, and there was cake, and there was negus, and there was a great piece of Cold Roast, and there was a great piece of Cold Boiled, and there were mince-pies, and plenty of beer."},{"start":61.175,"end":68.137,"text":"But the great effect of the evening came after the Roast and Boiled, when the fiddler (an artful dog, mind!"},{"start":68.137,"end":74.987,"text":"The sort of man who knew his business better than you or I could have told it him!) struck up \"Sir Roger de Coverley."},{"start":74.987,"end":78.962,"text":"Then old Fezziwig stood out to dance with Mrs. Fezziwig."},{"start":78.962,"end":91.925,"text":"Top couple too; with a good stiff piece of work cut out for them; three or four and twenty pair of partners; people who were not to be trifled with; people who _would_ dance, and had no notion of walking."},{"start":91.925,"end":100.137,"text":"But if they had been twice as many: ah, four times: old Fezziwig would have been a match for them, and so would Mrs. Fezziwig."},{"start":100.137,"end":105.8,"text":"As to _her_, she was worthy to be his partner in every sense of the term."},{"start":105.8,"end":110.087,"text":"If that's not high praise, tell me higher, and I'll use it."},{"start":110.087,"end":114.137,"text":"A positive light appeared to issue from Fezziwig's calves."},{"start":114.137,"end":117.7,"text":"They shone in every part of the dance like moons."},{"start":117.7,"end":122.85,"text":"You couldn't have predicted, at any given time, what would become of 'em next."},{"start":122.85,"end":141.787,"text":"And when old Fezziwig and Mrs. Fezziwig had gone all through the dance; advance and retire, hold hands with your partner; bow and curtsey; corkscrew; thread-the-needle, and back again to your place; Fezziwig \"cut\"--cut so deftly, that he appeared to wink with his legs, and came upon his feet again without a stagger."},{"start":141.787,"end":145.862,"text":"When the clock struck eleven, this domestic ball broke up."},{"start":145.862,"end":156.737,"text":"Mr. and Mrs. Fezziwig took their stations, one on either side the door, and shaking hands with every person individually as he or she went out, wished him or her a Merry Christmas."},{"start":156.737,"end":167.987,"text":"When everybody had retired but the two 'prentices, they did the same to them; and thus the cheerful voices died away, and the lads were left to their beds; which were under a counter in the back-shop."},{"start":167.987,"end":172.862,"text":"During the whole of this time, Scrooge had acted like a man out of his wits."}]}},{"id":"II_14","number":14,"zh":{"text":"他的整个心魂都扑在这情景上，扑在他从前的自己身上。\n他印证着每一桩事，记得起每一桩事，享受着每一桩事，心里头掀起最古怪的激荡。\n直到这会儿，等他从前的自己和迪克那两张神采焕发的脸转开去，他才记起那鬼魂，才觉出它正定睛望着他，它头上那光烧得格外清亮。\n\"一桩小事，\"那鬼魂说，\"就叫这些傻里傻气的人感激成这样。\"\n\"小事！\"斯克鲁奇应声重复道。\n那精灵示意他去听那两个学徒说话，他俩正掏心掏肺地夸赞费齐威格；等他听完了，那精灵说，\"怎么！\n难道不是吗？\n他不过花了你们凡人的几个钱：兴许三四镑罢了。\n难道这就多得值当人家这么夸赞他吗？\"\n\"不是为这个，\"斯克鲁奇让这话说得激动起来，不知不觉竟用起他从前、而非后来那个自己的口吻说话。\n\"不是为这个，精灵。\n他有那份能耐，能叫我们快活或不快活；能叫我们干起活来轻松或是吃力；是桩乐事，还是桩苦差。\n就说他那能耐全在三言两语、举手投足之间吧；全在那些细微琐碎、根本没法加起来一笔笔细数的事情上：那又怎么样呢？\n他给的那份快活，分量跟花了一大笔钱换来的一样大。\"\n他觉出那精灵的目光，便打住了。\n\"怎么啦？\"那鬼魂问。\n\"没什么要紧的，\"斯克鲁奇说。\n\"我看是有点什么吧？\"那鬼魂追问道。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_II_小节14.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":5.325,"text":"他的整个心魂都扑在这情景上，扑在他从前的自己身上。"},{"start":5.275,"end":12.6,"text":"他印证着每一桩事，记得起每一桩事，享受着每一桩事，心里头掀起最古怪的激荡。"},{"start":12.6,"end":25.012,"text":"直到这会儿，等他从前的自己和迪克那两张神采焕发的脸转开去，他才记起那鬼魂，才觉出它正定睛望着他，它头上那光烧得格外清亮。"},{"start":25.012,"end":30.262,"text":"一桩小事，\"那鬼魂说，\"就叫这些傻里傻气的人感激成这样。"},{"start":30.262,"end":33.287,"text":"小事！\"斯克鲁奇应声重复道。"},{"start":33.287,"end":42.037,"text":"那精灵示意他去听那两个学徒说话，他俩正掏心掏肺地夸赞费齐威格；等他听完了，那精灵说，\"怎么！"},{"start":42.037,"end":43.537,"text":"难道不是吗？"},{"start":43.537,"end":47.5,"text":"他不过花了你们凡人的几个钱：兴许三四镑罢了。"},{"start":47.5,"end":50.85,"text":"难道这就多得值当人家这么夸赞他吗？"},{"start":50.85,"end":59.462,"text":"不是为这个，\"斯克鲁奇让这话说得激动起来，不知不觉竟用起他从前、而非后来那个自己的口吻说话。"},{"start":59.462,"end":61.425,"text":"不是为这个，精灵。"},{"start":61.425,"end":70.325,"text":"他有那份能耐，能叫我们快活或不快活；能叫我们干起活来轻松或是吃力；是桩乐事，还是桩苦差。"},{"start":70.325,"end":80.712,"text":"就说他那能耐全在三言两语、举手投足之间吧；全在那些细微琐碎、根本没法加起来一笔笔细数的事情上：那又怎么样呢？"},{"start":80.712,"end":85.075,"text":"他给的那份快活，分量跟花了一大笔钱换来的一样大。"},{"start":85.075,"end":88.25,"text":"他觉出那精灵的目光，便打住了。"},{"start":88.25,"end":90.262,"text":"怎么啦？\"那鬼魂问。"},{"start":90.262,"end":92.862,"text":"没什么要紧的，\"斯克鲁奇说。"},{"start":92.862,"end":96.112,"text":"我看是有点什么吧？\"那鬼魂追问道。"}]},"en":{"text":"His heart and soul were in the scene, and with his former self.\nHe corroborated everything, remembered everything, enjoyed everything, and underwent the strangest agitation.\nIt was not until now, when the bright faces of his former self and Dick were turned from them, that he remembered the Ghost, and became conscious that it was looking full upon him, while the light upon its head burnt very clear.\n\"A small matter,\" said the Ghost, \"to make these silly folks so full of gratitude.\"\n\"Small!\" echoed Scrooge.\nThe Spirit signed to him to listen to the two apprentices, who were pouring out their hearts in praise of Fezziwig: and when he had done so, said, \"Why!\nIs it not?\nHe has spent but a few pounds of your mortal money: three or four, perhaps.\nIs that so much that he deserves this praise?\"\n\"It isn't that,\" said Scrooge, heated by the remark, and speaking unconsciously like his former, not his latter, self.\n\"It isn't that, Spirit.\nHe has the power to render us happy or unhappy; to make our service light or burdensome; a pleasure or a toil.\nSay that his power lies in words and looks; in things so slight and insignificant that it is impossible to add and count 'em up: what then?\nThe happiness he gives, is quite as great as if it cost a fortune.\"\nHe felt the Spirit's glance, and stopped.\n\"What is the matter?\" asked the Ghost.\n\"Nothing particular,\" said Scrooge.\n\"Something, I think?\" the Ghost insisted.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_II_小节14.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":4.325,"text":"His heart and soul were in the scene, and with his former self."},{"start":4.275,"end":11.587,"text":"He corroborated everything, remembered everything, enjoyed everything, and underwent the strangest agitation."},{"start":11.587,"end":23.8,"text":"It was not until now, when the bright faces of his former self and Dick were turned from them, that he remembered the Ghost, and became conscious that it was looking full upon him, while the light upon its head burnt very clear."},{"start":23.8,"end":29.412,"text":"A small matter,\" said the Ghost, \"to make these silly folks so full of gratitude."},{"start":29.412,"end":32.075,"text":"Small!\" echoed Scrooge."},{"start":32.075,"end":41.187,"text":"The Spirit signed to him to listen to the two apprentices, who were pouring out their hearts in praise of Fezziwig: and when he had done so, said, \"Why!"},{"start":41.187,"end":42.762,"text":"Is it not?"},{"start":42.762,"end":48.012,"text":"He has spent but a few pounds of your mortal money: three or four, perhaps."},{"start":48.012,"end":51.3,"text":"Is that so much that he deserves this praise?"},{"start":51.3,"end":59.362,"text":"It isn't that,\" said Scrooge, heated by the remark, and speaking unconsciously like his former, not his latter, self."},{"start":59.362,"end":61.812,"text":"It isn't that, Spirit."},{"start":61.812,"end":69.35,"text":"He has the power to render us happy or unhappy; to make our service light or burdensome; a pleasure or a toil."},{"start":69.35,"end":78.162,"text":"Say that his power lies in words and looks; in things so slight and insignificant that it is impossible to add and count 'em up: what then?"},{"start":78.162,"end":82.775,"text":"The happiness he gives, is quite as great as if it cost a fortune."},{"start":82.775,"end":86.1,"text":"He felt the Spirit's glance, and stopped."},{"start":86.1,"end":89,"text":"What is the matter?\" asked the Ghost."},{"start":89,"end":92.012,"text":"Nothing particular,\" said Scrooge."},{"start":92.012,"end":95.425,"text":"Something, I think?\" the Ghost insisted."}]}},{"id":"II_15","number":15,"zh":{"text":"\"没有，\"斯克鲁奇说，\"没有。我只是这会儿想跟我那伙计说上一两句话！\n就这么回事。\"\n他从前的自己一边把灯捻暗，他一边吐出这个心愿；斯克鲁奇和那鬼魂便又并肩立在了露天里。\n\"我的时辰不多了，\"那精灵说道。\n\"快！\"\n这话不是冲斯克鲁奇说的，也不是冲他看得见的什么人说的，可它立时见了效。\n因为斯克鲁奇又看见了他自己。\n这会儿他年纪大些了；是个壮年的男人。\n他脸上还没有后来岁月里那种又生硬又刻板的纹路；可已经开始显出忧虑和贪婪的痕迹。\n那眼睛里有一种急切、贪婪、不安的神情，显出已经扎了根的那股欲念，也显出那株渐渐长大的树，影子将要落在何处。\n他并不是独自一人，而是坐在一个穿丧服的标致姑娘身旁：她眼里含着泪，在往昔圣诞之灵射出的光里闪着晶莹。\n\"这没多大关系，\"她轻声说。\n\"对你，关系很小很小。\n另一个偶像把我顶替了；倘若它将来能像我本想做的那样，给你带来欢欣和慰藉，那我也没有正当的理由去伤心。\"\n\"是什么偶像把你顶替了？\"他应道。\n\"一个金子的偶像。\"\n\"这就是这世道公平无私的处事之道！\"他说。\n\"世上没有什么比贫穷更叫它狠下心来对待的了；可也没有什么比追逐财富更叫它声称要严加谴责的了！\"","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_II_小节15.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":2.725,"text":"没有，\"斯克鲁奇说，\"没有。"},{"start":2.675,"end":6.325,"text":"我只是这会儿想跟我那伙计说上一两句话！"},{"start":6.325,"end":7.8,"text":"就这么回事。"},{"start":7.8,"end":16.2,"text":"他从前的自己一边把灯捻暗，他一边吐出这个心愿；斯克鲁奇和那鬼魂便又并肩立在了露天里。"},{"start":16.2,"end":18.975,"text":"我的时辰不多了，\"那精灵说道。"},{"start":18.975,"end":19.925,"text":"快！"},{"start":19.925,"end":26.287,"text":"这话不是冲斯克鲁奇说的，也不是冲他看得见的什么人说的，可它立时见了效。"},{"start":26.287,"end":29.262,"text":"因为斯克鲁奇又看见了他自己。"},{"start":29.262,"end":32.787,"text":"这会儿他年纪大些了；是个壮年的男人。"},{"start":32.787,"end":40.262,"text":"他脸上还没有后来岁月里那种又生硬又刻板的纹路；可已经开始显出忧虑和贪婪的痕迹。"},{"start":40.262,"end":51.075,"text":"那眼睛里有一种急切、贪婪、不安的神情，显出已经扎了根的那股欲念，也显出那株渐渐长大的树，影子将要落在何处。"},{"start":51.075,"end":60.712,"text":"他并不是独自一人，而是坐在一个穿丧服的标致姑娘身旁：她眼里含着泪，在往昔圣诞之灵射出的光里闪着晶莹。"},{"start":60.712,"end":63.425,"text":"这没多大关系，\"她轻声说。"},{"start":63.425,"end":65.687,"text":"对你，关系很小很小。"},{"start":65.687,"end":74.637,"text":"另一个偶像把我顶替了；倘若它将来能像我本想做的那样，给你带来欢欣和慰藉，那我也没有正当的理由去伤心。"},{"start":74.637,"end":77.612,"text":"是什么偶像把你顶替了？\"他应道。"},{"start":77.612,"end":79.35,"text":"一个金子的偶像。"},{"start":79.35,"end":83.237,"text":"这就是这世道公平无私的处事之道！\"他说。"},{"start":83.237,"end":92.025,"text":"世上没有什么比贫穷更叫它狠下心来对待的了；可也没有什么比追逐财富更叫它声称要严加谴责的了！"}]},"en":{"text":"\"No,\" said Scrooge, \"No. I should like to be able to say a word or two to my clerk just now!\nThat's all.\"\nHis former self turned down the lamps as he gave utterance to the wish; and Scrooge and the Ghost again stood side by side in the open air.\n\"My time grows short,\" observed the Spirit.\n\"Quick!\"\nThis was not addressed to Scrooge, or to any one whom he could see, but it produced an immediate effect.\nFor again Scrooge saw himself.\nHe was older now; a man in the prime of life.\nHis face had not the harsh and rigid lines of later years; but it had begun to wear the signs of care and avarice.\nThere was an eager, greedy, restless motion in the eye, which showed the passion that had taken root, and where the shadow of the growing tree would fall.\nHe was not alone, but sat by the side of a fair young girl in a mourning-dress: in whose eyes there were tears, which sparkled in the light that shone out of the Ghost of Christmas Past.\n\"It matters little,\" she said, softly.\n\"To you, very little.\nAnother idol has displaced me; and if it can cheer and comfort you in time to come, as I would have tried to do, I have no just cause to grieve.\"\n\"What Idol has displaced you?\" he rejoined.\n\"A golden one.\"\n\"This is the even-handed dealing of the world!\" he said.\n\"There is nothing on which it is so hard as poverty; and there is nothing it professes to condemn with such severity as the pursuit of wealth!\"","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_II_小节15.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":3.05,"text":"No,\" said Scrooge, \"No."},{"start":3,"end":7.287,"text":"I should like to be able to say a word or two to my clerk just now!"},{"start":7.287,"end":8.787,"text":"That's all."},{"start":8.787,"end":16.937,"text":"His former self turned down the lamps as he gave utterance to the wish; and Scrooge and the Ghost again stood side by side in the open air."},{"start":16.937,"end":20.35,"text":"My time grows short,\" observed the Spirit."},{"start":20.35,"end":21.712,"text":"Quick!"},{"start":21.712,"end":28.1,"text":"This was not addressed to Scrooge, or to any one whom he could see, but it produced an immediate effect."},{"start":28.1,"end":30.925,"text":"For again Scrooge saw himself."},{"start":30.925,"end":34.612,"text":"He was older now; a man in the prime of life."},{"start":34.612,"end":41.675,"text":"His face had not the harsh and rigid lines of later years; but it had begun to wear the signs of care and avarice."},{"start":41.675,"end":50.4,"text":"There was an eager, greedy, restless motion in the eye, which showed the passion that had taken root, and where the shadow of the growing tree would fall."},{"start":50.4,"end":61.087,"text":"He was not alone, but sat by the side of a fair young girl in a mourning-dress: in whose eyes there were tears, which sparkled in the light that shone out of the Ghost of Christmas Past."},{"start":61.087,"end":64.55,"text":"It matters little,\" she said, softly."},{"start":64.55,"end":66.812,"text":"To you, very little."},{"start":66.812,"end":75.637,"text":"Another idol has displaced me; and if it can cheer and comfort you in time to come, as I would have tried to do, I have no just cause to grieve."},{"start":75.637,"end":79.025,"text":"What Idol has displaced you?\" he rejoined."},{"start":79.025,"end":80.825,"text":"A golden one."},{"start":80.825,"end":84.537,"text":"This is the even-handed dealing of the world!\" he said."},{"start":84.537,"end":92.512,"text":"There is nothing on which it is so hard as poverty; and there is nothing it professes to condemn with such severity as the pursuit of wealth!"}]}},{"id":"II_16","number":16,"zh":{"text":"\"你太怕这世道了，\"她温柔地答道。\n\"你别的指望统统并进了一个指望里，就是想躲开它那卑劣的责难。\n我眼看着你那些更高尚的志向一个接一个地脱落，直到'获利'这个主宰一切的欲念把你整个攫住。\n我说得不对吗？\"\n\"那又怎么样？\"他反唇相讥。\n\"就算我变得精明了这许多，那又怎么样？\n我待你可没有变。\"\n她摇了摇头。\n\"我变了吗？\"\n\"咱们的婚约是早就订下的。\n那是在咱俩都还穷、又都甘于安贫的时候订的，只盼着有朝一日凭咱们耐心的勤勉，能改善尘世的境遇。\n你是变了。\n订婚约的时候，你是另外一个人。\"\n\"那时我是个毛头小子，\"他不耐烦地说。\n\"你自己的感觉会告诉你，你已经不是当年那个你了，\"她答道。\n\"我还是我。\n当咱俩同心一意时本许下幸福的，如今咱俩成了两条心，便满含着苦楚了。\n这事我想过多少回、想得多么痛切，我就不说了。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_II_小节16.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":3.1,"text":"你太怕这世道了，\"她温柔地答道。"},{"start":3.05,"end":8.737,"text":"你别的指望统统并进了一个指望里，就是想躲开它那卑劣的责难。"},{"start":8.737,"end":16.637,"text":"我眼看着你那些更高尚的志向一个接一个地脱落，直到'获利'这个主宰一切的欲念把你整个攫住。"},{"start":16.637,"end":18.225,"text":"我说得不对吗？"},{"start":18.225,"end":20.875,"text":"那又怎么样？\"他反唇相讥。"},{"start":20.875,"end":24.15,"text":"就算我变得精明了这许多，那又怎么样？"},{"start":24.15,"end":25.875,"text":"我待你可没有变。"},{"start":25.875,"end":27.425,"text":"她摇了摇头。"},{"start":27.425,"end":28.75,"text":"我变了吗？"},{"start":28.75,"end":31.35,"text":"咱们的婚约是早就订下的。"},{"start":31.35,"end":40.025,"text":"那是在咱俩都还穷、又都甘于安贫的时候订的，只盼着有朝一日凭咱们耐心的勤勉，能改善尘世的境遇。"},{"start":40.025,"end":41.362,"text":"你是变了。"},{"start":41.362,"end":44.025,"text":"订婚约的时候，你是另外一个人。"},{"start":44.025,"end":47.437,"text":"那时我是个毛头小子，\"他不耐烦地说。"},{"start":47.437,"end":52.325,"text":"你自己的感觉会告诉你，你已经不是当年那个你了，\"她答道。"},{"start":52.325,"end":53.637,"text":"我还是我。"},{"start":53.637,"end":60.575,"text":"当咱俩同心一意时本许下幸福的，如今咱俩成了两条心，便满含着苦楚了。"},{"start":60.575,"end":64.825,"text":"这事我想过多少回、想得多么痛切，我就不说了。"}]},"en":{"text":"\"You fear the world too much,\" she answered, gently.\n\"All your other hopes have merged into the hope of being beyond the chance of its sordid reproach.\nI have seen your nobler aspirations fall off one by one, until the master-passion, Gain, engrosses you.\nHave I not?\"\n\"What then?\" he retorted.\n\"Even if I have grown so much wiser, what then?\nI am not changed towards you.\"\nShe shook her head.\n\"Am I?\"\n\"Our contract is an old one.\nIt was made when we were both poor and content to be so, until, in good season, we could improve our worldly fortune by our patient industry.\nYou _are_ changed.\nWhen it was made, you were another man.\"\n\"I was a boy,\" he said impatiently.\n\"Your own feeling tells you that you were not what you are,\" she returned.\n\"I am.\nThat which promised happiness when we were one in heart, is fraught with misery now that we are two.\nHow often and how keenly I have thought of this, I will not say.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_II_小节16.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":4.225,"text":"You fear the world too much,\" she answered, gently."},{"start":4.175,"end":9.587,"text":"All your other hopes have merged into the hope of being beyond the chance of its sordid reproach."},{"start":9.587,"end":16.962,"text":"I have seen your nobler aspirations fall off one by one, until the master-passion, Gain, engrosses you."},{"start":16.962,"end":18.537,"text":"Have I not?"},{"start":18.537,"end":20.975,"text":"What then?\" he retorted."},{"start":20.975,"end":24.487,"text":"Even if I have grown so much wiser, what then?"},{"start":24.487,"end":27.125,"text":"I am not changed towards you."},{"start":27.125,"end":29.05,"text":"She shook her head."},{"start":29.05,"end":30.412,"text":"Am I?"},{"start":30.412,"end":32.925,"text":"Our contract is an old one."},{"start":32.925,"end":41.887,"text":"It was made when we were both poor and content to be so, until, in good season, we could improve our worldly fortune by our patient industry."},{"start":41.887,"end":44.887,"text":"You _are_ changed."},{"start":44.887,"end":47.862,"text":"When it was made, you were another man."},{"start":47.862,"end":50.912,"text":"I was a boy,\" he said impatiently."},{"start":50.912,"end":55.437,"text":"Your own feeling tells you that you were not what you are,\" she returned."},{"start":55.437,"end":56.95,"text":"I am."},{"start":56.95,"end":62.912,"text":"That which promised happiness when we were one in heart, is fraught with misery now that we are two."},{"start":62.912,"end":67.325,"text":"How often and how keenly I have thought of this, I will not say."}]}},{"id":"II_17","number":17,"zh":{"text":"只消知道我确曾想过它，能把你放开，也就够了。\"\n\"我可曾求过解约吗？\"\n\"嘴上没有。\n没有。从来没有。\"\n\"那从哪儿看出来呢？\"\n\"从一种变了的天性；从一颗变了的心；从另一种生活的气息；从作为你人生大目标的另一个指望。\n从那一切曾使我的爱在你眼里有几分分量、几分价值的东西上。\n倘若咱俩之间从不曾有过这桩婚约，\"那姑娘温和却又坚定地望着他说，\"你倒告诉我，你这会儿还会去寻我、想方设法来赢得我吗？\n唉，不会的！\"\n他仿佛不由自主地屈服于这个推断的公道。\n可他还是挣扎着说，\"你以为不会。\"\n\"我要是能，倒情愿往别处想呢，\"她答道，\"老天作证！\n当我也悟出这样一条道理，我便晓得它必定何等真切、何等不容抗拒。\n可即便你今天、明天、昨天身子是自由的，便是我，又能信你会去挑一个没有嫁妆的姑娘吗——你这么个人，便是跟她推心置腹时，也凡事都拿'获利'去掂量：或者，就算你挑了她，就算你有那么一刻竟背离了你那唯一的处世准则、当真这么做了，难道我会不知道，你的懊悔和遗憾必定随之而来？\n我知道；所以我把你放开。\n满心诚意地放开你，看在你从前那个人的份上。\"\n他正要开口；可她把头扭开去，又接着说道。\n\"你也许会——往事的记忆叫我隐隐指望你会——为这事感到几分痛楚。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_II_小节17.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":4.662,"text":"只消知道我确曾想过它，能把你放开，也就够了。"},{"start":4.612,"end":6.687,"text":"我可曾求过解约吗？"},{"start":6.687,"end":8.062,"text":"嘴上没有。"},{"start":8.062,"end":9.087,"text":"没有。"},{"start":9.087,"end":10.487,"text":"从来没有。"},{"start":10.487,"end":12.262,"text":"那从哪儿看出来呢？"},{"start":12.262,"end":20.675,"text":"从一种变了的天性；从一颗变了的心；从另一种生活的气息；从作为你人生大目标的另一个指望。"},{"start":20.675,"end":26.05,"text":"从那一切曾使我的爱在你眼里有几分分量、几分价值的东西上。"},{"start":26.05,"end":36.475,"text":"倘若咱俩之间从不曾有过这桩婚约，\"那姑娘温和却又坚定地望着他说，\"你倒告诉我，你这会儿还会去寻我、想方设法来赢得我吗？"},{"start":36.475,"end":38.012,"text":"唉，不会的！"},{"start":38.012,"end":41.862,"text":"他仿佛不由自主地屈服于这个推断的公道。"},{"start":41.862,"end":44.95,"text":"可他还是挣扎着说，\"你以为不会。"},{"start":44.95,"end":49.437,"text":"我要是能，倒情愿往别处想呢，\"她答道，\"老天作证！"},{"start":49.437,"end":55.437,"text":"当我也悟出这样一条道理，我便晓得它必定何等真切、何等不容抗拒。"},{"start":55.437,"end":79.137,"text":"可即便你今天、明天、昨天身子是自由的，便是我，又能信你会去挑一个没有嫁妆的姑娘吗——你这么个人，便是跟她推心置腹时，也凡事都拿'获利'去掂量：或者，就算你挑了她，就算你有那么一刻竟背离了你那唯一的处世准则、当真这么做了，难道我会不知道，你的懊悔和遗憾必定随之而来？"},{"start":79.137,"end":81.5,"text":"我知道；所以我把你放开。"},{"start":81.5,"end":85.362,"text":"满心诚意地放开你，看在你从前那个人的份上。"},{"start":85.362,"end":89.487,"text":"他正要开口；可她把头扭开去，又接着说道。"},{"start":89.487,"end":94.975,"text":"你也许会——往事的记忆叫我隐隐指望你会——为这事感到几分痛楚。"}]},"en":{"text":"It is enough that I _have_ thought of it, and can release you.\"\n\"Have I ever sought release?\"\n\"In words.\nNo. Never.\"\n\"In what, then?\"\n\"In a changed nature; in an altered spirit; in another atmosphere of life; another Hope as its great end.\nIn everything that made my love of any worth or value in your sight.\nIf this had never been between us,\" said the girl, looking mildly, but with steadiness, upon him; \"tell me, would you seek me out and try to win me now?\nAh, no!\"\nHe seemed to yield to the justice of this supposition, in spite of himself.\nBut he said, with a struggle, \"You think not.\"\n\"I would gladly think otherwise if I could,\" she answered, \"Heaven knows!\nWhen _I_ have learned a Truth like this, I know how strong and irresistible it must be.\nBut if you were free to-day, to-morrow, yesterday, can even I believe that you would choose a dowerless girl--you who, in your very confidence with her, weigh everything by Gain: or, choosing her, if for a moment you were false enough to your one guiding principle to do so, do I not know that your repentance and regret would surely follow?\nI do; and I release you.\nWith a full heart, for the love of him you once were.\"\nHe was about to speak; but with her head turned from him, she resumed.\n\"You may--the memory of what is past half makes me hope you will--have pain in this.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_II_小节17.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":4.875,"text":"It is enough that I _have_ thought of it, and can release you."},{"start":4.825,"end":7.125,"text":"Have I ever sought release?"},{"start":7.125,"end":8.812,"text":"In words."},{"start":8.812,"end":10.187,"text":"No."},{"start":10.187,"end":11.587,"text":"Never."},{"start":11.587,"end":13.537,"text":"In what, then?"},{"start":13.537,"end":20.812,"text":"In a changed nature; in an altered spirit; in another atmosphere of life; another Hope as its great end."},{"start":20.812,"end":25.112,"text":"In everything that made my love of any worth or value in your sight."},{"start":25.112,"end":34.587,"text":"If this had never been between us,\" said the girl, looking mildly, but with steadiness, upon him; \"tell me, would you seek me out and try to win me now?"},{"start":34.587,"end":36.575,"text":"Ah, no!"},{"start":36.575,"end":41.45,"text":"He seemed to yield to the justice of this supposition, in spite of himself."},{"start":41.45,"end":44.975,"text":"But he said, with a struggle, \"You think not."},{"start":44.975,"end":50.05,"text":"I would gladly think otherwise if I could,\" she answered, \"Heaven knows!"},{"start":50.05,"end":56.762,"text":"When _I_ have learned a Truth like this, I know how strong and irresistible it must be."},{"start":56.762,"end":74.975,"text":"But if you were free to-day, to-morrow, yesterday, can even I believe that you would choose a dowerless girl--you who, in your very confidence with her, weigh everything by Gain: or, choosing her, if for a moment you were false enough to your one guiding principle to do so, do I not know that your repentance and regret would surely follow?"},{"start":74.975,"end":77.7,"text":"I do; and I release you."},{"start":77.7,"end":81.387,"text":"With a full heart, for the love of him you once were."},{"start":81.387,"end":86.3,"text":"He was about to speak; but with her head turned from him, she resumed."},{"start":86.3,"end":91.075,"text":"You may--the memory of what is past half makes me hope you will--have pain in this."}]}},{"id":"II_18","number":18,"zh":{"text":"可只消极短极短一段工夫，你便会欣然把这记忆当作一场无益的梦撇开，幸而你及时从梦里醒了过来。\n愿你在自己选定的生活里得享幸福！\"\n她离开了他；他俩就此分手了。\n\"精灵！\"斯克鲁奇说，\"别再让我看了！\n领我回家去。\n你为什么以折磨我为乐？\"\n\"再看一个影子！\"那鬼魂嚷道。\n\"别再看了！\"斯克鲁奇喊道。\n\"别再看了。\n我不愿意看。\n别再让我看了！\"\n可那狠心的鬼魂用两条胳膊把他箍住，逼他去看接下来发生的事。\n他们置身于另一处情景、另一个地方：一个房间，不算很大或很气派，却满是温馨。\n冬日的炉火旁坐着一个美丽的姑娘，跟方才那一个像极了，斯克鲁奇还当是同一个人，直到他瞧见了她——如今已是个标致的主妇，坐在女儿对面。\n这屋里的吵闹简直闹翻了天，因为这儿的孩子多得，斯克鲁奇心绪那样纷乱，怎么也数不清；而且，跟那首诗里有名的羊群不同，他们可不是四十个孩子像一个似的，而是每一个孩子都闹得像四十个。\n那后果喧闹得叫人没法相信；可没有一个人像是在意；恰恰相反，那做母亲的和做女儿的纵情大笑，乐在其中；那女儿不一会儿便也搀和到嬉闹里去，被那帮小强盗劫掠得最是无情。\n要是能做他们当中的一个，我还有什么舍不得给的呢！\n不过我可决不会那么粗野，不，不会！","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_II_小节18.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":9.225,"text":"可只消极短极短一段工夫，你便会欣然把这记忆当作一场无益的梦撇开，幸而你及时从梦里醒了过来。"},{"start":9.175,"end":12.462,"text":"愿你在自己选定的生活里得享幸福！"},{"start":12.462,"end":15.487,"text":"她离开了他；他俩就此分手了。"},{"start":15.487,"end":18.562,"text":"精灵！\"斯克鲁奇说，\"别再让我看了！"},{"start":18.562,"end":20.025,"text":"领我回家去。"},{"start":20.025,"end":22.287,"text":"你为什么以折磨我为乐？"},{"start":22.287,"end":25.125,"text":"再看一个影子！\"那鬼魂嚷道。"},{"start":25.125,"end":27.712,"text":"别再看了！\"斯克鲁奇喊道。"},{"start":27.712,"end":29.062,"text":"别再看了。"},{"start":29.062,"end":30.487,"text":"我不愿意看。"},{"start":30.487,"end":32.062,"text":"别再让我看了！"},{"start":32.062,"end":37.625,"text":"可那狠心的鬼魂用两条胳膊把他箍住，逼他去看接下来发生的事。"},{"start":37.625,"end":44.5,"text":"他们置身于另一处情景、另一个地方：一个房间，不算很大或很气派，却满是温馨。"},{"start":44.5,"end":56.475,"text":"冬日的炉火旁坐着一个美丽的姑娘，跟方才那一个像极了，斯克鲁奇还当是同一个人，直到他瞧见了她——如今已是个标致的主妇，坐在女儿对面。"},{"start":56.475,"end":72.85,"text":"这屋里的吵闹简直闹翻了天，因为这儿的孩子多得，斯克鲁奇心绪那样纷乱，怎么也数不清；而且，跟那首诗里有名的羊群不同，他们可不是四十个孩子像一个似的，而是每一个孩子都闹得像四十个。"},{"start":72.85,"end":88.687,"text":"那后果喧闹得叫人没法相信；可没有一个人像是在意；恰恰相反，那做母亲的和做女儿的纵情大笑，乐在其中；那女儿不一会儿便也搀和到嬉闹里去，被那帮小强盗劫掠得最是无情。"},{"start":88.687,"end":92.65,"text":"要是能做他们当中的一个，我还有什么舍不得给的呢！"},{"start":92.65,"end":96.212,"text":"不过我可决不会那么粗野，不，不会！"}]},"en":{"text":"A very, very brief time, and you will dismiss the recollection of it, gladly, as an unprofitable dream, from which it happened well that you awoke.\nMay you be happy in the life you have chosen!\"\nShe left him; and they parted.\n\"Spirit!\" said Scrooge, \"show me no more!\nConduct me home.\nWhy do you delight to torture me?\"\n\"One shadow more!\" exclaimed the Ghost.\n\"No more!\" cried Scrooge.\n\"No more.\nI don't wish to see it.\nShow me no more!\"\nBut the relentless Ghost pinioned him in both his arms, and forced him to observe what happened next.\nThey were in another scene and place: a room, not very large or handsome, but full of comfort.\nNear to the winter fire sat a beautiful young girl, so like the last that Scrooge believed it was the same, until he saw _her_, now a comely matron, sitting opposite her daughter.\nThe noise in this room was perfectly tumultuous, for there were more children there, than Scrooge in his agitated state of mind could count; and, unlike the celebrated herd in the poem, they were not forty children conducting themselves like one, but every child was conducting itself like forty.\nThe consequences were uproarious beyond belief; but no one seemed to care; on the contrary, the mother and daughter laughed heartily, and enjoyed it very much; and the latter, soon beginning to mingle in the sports, got pillaged by the young brigands most ruthlessly.\nWhat would I not have given to be one of them!\nThough I never could have been so rude, no, no!","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_II_小节18.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":9.412,"text":"A very, very brief time, and you will dismiss the recollection of it, gladly, as an unprofitable dream, from which it happened well that you awoke."},{"start":9.362,"end":12.45,"text":"May you be happy in the life you have chosen!"},{"start":12.45,"end":15.137,"text":"She left him; and they parted."},{"start":15.137,"end":19.05,"text":"Spirit!\" said Scrooge, \"show me no more!"},{"start":19.05,"end":20.975,"text":"Conduct me home."},{"start":20.975,"end":23.375,"text":"Why do you delight to torture me?"},{"start":23.375,"end":26.762,"text":"One shadow more!\" exclaimed the Ghost."},{"start":26.762,"end":29.5,"text":"No more!\" cried Scrooge."},{"start":29.5,"end":31.1,"text":"No more."},{"start":31.1,"end":33.175,"text":"I don't wish to see it."},{"start":33.175,"end":35.25,"text":"Show me no more!"},{"start":35.25,"end":41.425,"text":"But the relentless Ghost pinioned him in both his arms, and forced him to observe what happened next."},{"start":41.425,"end":47.8,"text":"They were in another scene and place: a room, not very large or handsome, but full of comfort."},{"start":47.8,"end":59.362,"text":"Near to the winter fire sat a beautiful young girl, so like the last that Scrooge believed it was the same, until he saw _her_, now a comely matron, sitting opposite her daughter."},{"start":59.362,"end":76.062,"text":"The noise in this room was perfectly tumultuous, for there were more children there, than Scrooge in his agitated state of mind could count; and, unlike the celebrated herd in the poem, they were not forty children conducting themselves like one, but every child was conducting itself like forty."},{"start":76.062,"end":91.825,"text":"The consequences were uproarious beyond belief; but no one seemed to care; on the contrary, the mother and daughter laughed heartily, and enjoyed it very much; and the latter, soon beginning to mingle in the sports, got pillaged by the young brigands most ruthlessly."},{"start":91.825,"end":94.65,"text":"What would I not have given to be one of them!"},{"start":94.65,"end":98.637,"text":"Though I never could have been so rude, no, no!"}]}},{"id":"II_19","number":19,"zh":{"text":"便是把全世界的财富给我，我也不忍把那编好的发辫揉乱、扯散；至于那只珍贵的小鞋，便是要我的命，我也不忍把它从脚上褪下来，上帝保佑我的灵魂！\n至于像他们那样闹着玩去量她的腰身，那帮胆大包天的小崽子，我可干不出来；我准料定我的胳膊会因此遭报应，从此长得弯弯地绕着她、再也直不回来。\n不过老实说，我倒着实渴望能碰一碰她的嘴唇；能问她句话，好叫她把唇启开；能瞧一瞧她那低垂的眼睫，又惹不起她半点羞红；能放开她那一绺绺的秀发，哪怕一英寸都是无价的纪念：总而言之，我承认，我巴望能有孩童那一丁点最轻的放肆，却又有成人那份心思，懂得这份放肆的可贵。\n可这会儿听见敲门声，门口随即一阵蜂拥，她那张笑盈盈的脸、那身被劫掠过的衣裳，便被簇拥在一群涨红了脸、闹哄哄的人当中，朝门口涌去，恰好赶上迎接那做父亲的；他回家来了，身后跟着个人，驮着满满的圣诞玩具和礼物。\n随即便是那一阵叫嚷、扭打，朝那毫无招架之力的脚夫发起的猛攻！\n拿椅子当梯子往他身上爬，去掏他的口袋，把他那些牛皮纸包夺下来，死死揪住他的领巾，搂住他的脖子，捶他的背，又踢他的腿，那股按捺不住的亲热劲儿！\n每拆开一个包裹时，迎来的那一片惊奇又欢喜的喊声！\n还有那骇人的通报：说有人逮着那小娃娃正把一只玩具煎锅往嘴里塞，而且大有把一只粘在木盘上的假火鸡吞下去的嫌疑！\n等发觉这是虚惊一场时那莫大的宽慰！\n那欢乐，那感激，那狂喜！\n这些一概没法形容。\n只消知道这一点也就够了：孩子们连同他们那些情绪，渐渐挪出了客厅，一级楼梯一级楼梯地，上到屋子顶层；在那儿他们上床睡觉，于是平息了下来。\n这会儿斯克鲁奇看得比先前任何时候都专注，那当家的让女儿亲昵地偎在身上，跟她、跟她母亲一同在自家炉火边坐下；当他想到，本来也可能有这么个一样优雅、一样满怀前程的人儿唤他作父亲，做他那憔悴的人生寒冬里的一片春光，他的眼睛便着实模糊得很了。\n\"贝儿，\"那做丈夫的含笑转向妻子说，\"今儿下午我碰见你一位老朋友。\"\n\"是谁呀？\"\n\"猜猜看！\"\n\"我哪儿猜得着？\n得，我还能不知道，\"她紧跟着添了一句，随他一同笑了起来。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_II_小节19.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":13.2,"text":"便是把全世界的财富给我，我也不忍把那编好的发辫揉乱、扯散；至于那只珍贵的小鞋，便是要我的命，我也不忍把它从脚上褪下来，上帝保佑我的灵魂！"},{"start":13.15,"end":25.475,"text":"至于像他们那样闹着玩去量她的腰身，那帮胆大包天的小崽子，我可干不出来；我准料定我的胳膊会因此遭报应，从此长得弯弯地绕着她、再也直不回来。"},{"start":25.475,"end":49.125,"text":"不过老实说，我倒着实渴望能碰一碰她的嘴唇；能问她句话，好叫她把唇启开；能瞧一瞧她那低垂的眼睫，又惹不起她半点羞红；能放开她那一绺绺的秀发，哪怕一英寸都是无价的纪念：总而言之，我承认，我巴望能有孩童那一丁点最轻的放肆，却又有成人那份心思，懂得这份放肆的可贵。"},{"start":49.125,"end":68.3,"text":"可这会儿听见敲门声，门口随即一阵蜂拥，她那张笑盈盈的脸、那身被劫掠过的衣裳，便被簇拥在一群涨红了脸、闹哄哄的人当中，朝门口涌去，恰好赶上迎接那做父亲的；他回家来了，身后跟着个人，驮着满满的圣诞玩具和礼物。"},{"start":68.3,"end":74.737,"text":"随即便是那一阵叫嚷、扭打，朝那毫无招架之力的脚夫发起的猛攻！"},{"start":74.737,"end":87.687,"text":"拿椅子当梯子往他身上爬，去掏他的口袋，把他那些牛皮纸包夺下来，死死揪住他的领巾，搂住他的脖子，捶他的背，又踢他的腿，那股按捺不住的亲热劲儿！"},{"start":87.687,"end":92.387,"text":"每拆开一个包裹时，迎来的那一片惊奇又欢喜的喊声！"},{"start":92.387,"end":102.3,"text":"还有那骇人的通报：说有人逮着那小娃娃正把一只玩具煎锅往嘴里塞，而且大有把一只粘在木盘上的假火鸡吞下去的嫌疑！"},{"start":102.3,"end":106.025,"text":"等发觉这是虚惊一场时那莫大的宽慰！"},{"start":106.025,"end":108.9,"text":"那欢乐，那感激，那狂喜！"},{"start":108.9,"end":111.112,"text":"这些一概没法形容。"},{"start":111.112,"end":123.687,"text":"只消知道这一点也就够了：孩子们连同他们那些情绪，渐渐挪出了客厅，一级楼梯一级楼梯地，上到屋子顶层；在那儿他们上床睡觉，于是平息了下来。"},{"start":123.687,"end":146.062,"text":"这会儿斯克鲁奇看得比先前任何时候都专注，那当家的让女儿亲昵地偎在身上，跟她、跟她母亲一同在自家炉火边坐下；当他想到，本来也可能有这么个一样优雅、一样满怀前程的人儿唤他作父亲，做他那憔悴的人生寒冬里的一片春光，他的眼睛便着实模糊得很了。"},{"start":146.062,"end":151.575,"text":"贝儿，\"那做丈夫的含笑转向妻子说，\"今儿下午我碰见你一位老朋友。"},{"start":151.575,"end":152.812,"text":"是谁呀？"},{"start":152.812,"end":153.987,"text":"猜猜看！"},{"start":153.987,"end":155.5,"text":"我哪儿猜得着？"},{"start":155.5,"end":160.425,"text":"得，我还能不知道，\"她紧跟着添了一句，随他一同笑了起来。"}]},"en":{"text":"I wouldn't for the wealth of all the world have crushed that braided hair, and torn it down; and for the precious little shoe, I wouldn't have plucked it off, God bless my soul! to save my life.\nAs to measuring her waist in sport, as they did, bold young brood, I couldn't have done it; I should have expected my arm to have grown round it for a punishment, and never come straight again.\nAnd yet I should have dearly liked, I own, to have touched her lips; to have questioned her, that she might have opened them; to have looked upon the lashes of her downcast eyes, and never raised a blush; to have let loose waves of hair, an inch of which would be a keepsake beyond price: in short, I should have liked, I do confess, to have had the lightest license of a child, and yet been man enough to know its value.\nBut now a knocking at the door was heard, and such a rush immediately ensued that she with laughing face and plundered dress was borne towards it the centre of a flushed and boisterous group, just in time to greet the father, who, came home attended by a man laden with Christmas toys and presents.\nThen the shouting and the struggling, and the onslaught that was made on the defenceless porter!\nThe scaling him, with chairs for ladders, to dive into his pockets, despoil him of brown-paper parcels, hold on tight by his cravat, hug him round the neck, pommel his back, and kick his legs in irrepressible affection!\nThe shouts of wonder and delight with which the development of every package was received!\nThe terrible announcement that the baby had been taken in the act of putting a doll's frying-pan into his mouth, and was more than suspected of having swallowed a fictitious turkey, glued on a wooden platter!\nThe immense relief of finding this a false alarm!\nThe joy, and gratitude, and ecstacy!\nThey are all indescribable alike.\nIt is enough that by degrees the children and their emotions got out of the parlour and by one stair at a time, up to the top of the house; where they went to bed, and so subsided.\nAnd now Scrooge looked on more attentively than ever, when the master of the house, having his daughter leaning fondly on him, sat down with her and her mother at his own fireside; and when he thought that such another creature, quite as graceful and as full of promise, might have called him father, and been a spring-time in the haggard winter of his life, his sight grew very dim indeed.\n\"Belle,\" said the husband, turning to his wife with a smile, \"I saw an old friend of yours this afternoon.\"\n\"Who was it?\"\n\"Guess!\"\n\"How can I?\nTut, don't I know,\" she added in the same breath, laughing as he laughed.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_II_小节19.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":10.037,"text":"I wouldn't for the wealth of all the world have crushed that braided hair, and torn it down; and for the precious little shoe, I wouldn't have plucked it off, God bless my soul!"},{"start":9.987,"end":12.037,"text":"to save my life."},{"start":12.037,"end":22.887,"text":"As to measuring her waist in sport, as they did, bold young brood, I couldn't have done it; I should have expected my arm to have grown round it for a punishment, and never come straight again."},{"start":22.887,"end":46.987,"text":"And yet I should have dearly liked, I own, to have touched her lips; to have questioned her, that she might have opened them; to have looked upon the lashes of her downcast eyes, and never raised a blush; to have let loose waves of hair, an inch of which would be a keepsake beyond price: in short, I should have liked, I do confess, to have had the lightest license of a child, and yet been man enough to know its value."},{"start":46.987,"end":62.95,"text":"But now a knocking at the door was heard, and such a rush immediately ensued that she with laughing face and plundered dress was borne towards it the centre of a flushed and boisterous group, just in time to greet the father, who, came home attended by a man laden with Christmas toys and presents."},{"start":62.95,"end":68.2,"text":"Then the shouting and the struggling, and the onslaught that was made on the defenceless porter!"},{"start":68.2,"end":81.925,"text":"The scaling him, with chairs for ladders, to dive into his pockets, despoil him of brown-paper parcels, hold on tight by his cravat, hug him round the neck, pommel his back, and kick his legs in irrepressible affection!"},{"start":81.925,"end":87.125,"text":"The shouts of wonder and delight with which the development of every package was received!"},{"start":87.125,"end":97.975,"text":"The terrible announcement that the baby had been taken in the act of putting a doll's frying-pan into his mouth, and was more than suspected of having swallowed a fictitious turkey, glued on a wooden platter!"},{"start":97.975,"end":101.475,"text":"The immense relief of finding this a false alarm!"},{"start":101.475,"end":105.15,"text":"The joy, and gratitude, and ecstacy!"},{"start":105.15,"end":107.962,"text":"They are all indescribable alike."},{"start":107.962,"end":118.137,"text":"It is enough that by degrees the children and their emotions got out of the parlour and by one stair at a time, up to the top of the house; where they went to bed, and so subsided."},{"start":118.137,"end":139.212,"text":"And now Scrooge looked on more attentively than ever, when the master of the house, having his daughter leaning fondly on him, sat down with her and her mother at his own fireside; and when he thought that such another creature, quite as graceful and as full of promise, might have called him father, and been a spring-time in the haggard winter of his life, his sight grew very dim indeed."},{"start":139.212,"end":145.787,"text":"Belle,\" said the husband, turning to his wife with a smile, \"I saw an old friend of yours this afternoon."},{"start":145.787,"end":147.325,"text":"Who was it?"},{"start":147.325,"end":148.775,"text":"Guess!"},{"start":148.775,"end":150.337,"text":"How can I?"},{"start":150.337,"end":155.625,"text":"Tut, don't I know,\" she added in the same breath, laughing as he laughed."}]}},{"id":"II_20","number":20,"zh":{"text":"\"是斯克鲁奇先生。\"\n\"正是斯克鲁奇先生。\n我打他账房窗前经过；窗子没关，里头点着一支蜡烛，我想不瞧见他也难。\n我听说，他那合伙人快要咽气了；他就一个人坐在那儿。\n我当真相信，他在这世上孤零零的，一个人也没有。\"\n\"精灵！\"斯克鲁奇用哽咽的嗓音说，\"带我离开这地方。\"\n\"我告诉过你，这些都是已逝事物的影子，\"那鬼魂说。\n\"它们是这副模样，可别怪我！\"\n\"带我走！\"斯克鲁奇嚷道。\n\"我受不了啦！\"\n他猛地转向那鬼魂，瞧见它正望着他，那张脸上不知怎么古怪地凑着它先前给他看过的所有那些脸的片断，便跟它扭打起来。\n\"放开我！\n带我回去。\n别再缠着我了！\"\n在这场扭打里——倘若这也算得上扭打的话，那鬼魂自己并没显出半点抵抗，对手再怎么使劲也撼它不动——斯克鲁奇瞧见它那光烧得又高又亮；他隐隐把这光跟它对自己的那股魔力联系到一处，便一把抓起那灭烛罩似的帽子，猛地往它头上按下去。\n那精灵在帽子底下矮了下去，弄得灭烛罩把它整个身形都罩住了；可斯克鲁奇虽使出浑身力气往下按，却遮不住那光：那光从罩子底下泻出来，源源不断地铺在地上。\n他觉出自己精疲力竭，被一阵不可抗拒的睡意压倒了；再者，又觉出自己正待在自己的卧室里。\n他临了又把那帽子捏了一把，手便松了下来；刚来得及踉踉跄跄扑到床上，就沉沉睡了过去。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_II_小节20.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":2,"text":"是斯克鲁奇先生。"},{"start":1.95,"end":4.075,"text":"正是斯克鲁奇先生。"},{"start":4.075,"end":10.812,"text":"我打他账房窗前经过；窗子没关，里头点着一支蜡烛，我想不瞧见他也难。"},{"start":10.812,"end":15.487,"text":"我听说，他那合伙人快要咽气了；他就一个人坐在那儿。"},{"start":15.487,"end":19.812,"text":"我当真相信，他在这世上孤零零的，一个人也没有。"},{"start":19.812,"end":24.412,"text":"精灵！\"斯克鲁奇用哽咽的嗓音说，\"带我离开这地方。"},{"start":24.412,"end":28.825,"text":"我告诉过你，这些都是已逝事物的影子，\"那鬼魂说。"},{"start":28.825,"end":31.55,"text":"它们是这副模样，可别怪我！"},{"start":31.55,"end":33.962,"text":"带我走！\"斯克鲁奇嚷道。"},{"start":33.962,"end":35.462,"text":"我受不了啦！"},{"start":35.462,"end":45.925,"text":"他猛地转向那鬼魂，瞧见它正望着他，那张脸上不知怎么古怪地凑着它先前给他看过的所有那些脸的片断，便跟它扭打起来。"},{"start":45.925,"end":47.212,"text":"放开我！"},{"start":47.212,"end":48.512,"text":"带我回去。"},{"start":48.512,"end":50.212,"text":"别再缠着我了！"},{"start":50.212,"end":70.837,"text":"在这场扭打里——倘若这也算得上扭打的话，那鬼魂自己并没显出半点抵抗，对手再怎么使劲也撼它不动——斯克鲁奇瞧见它那光烧得又高又亮；他隐隐把这光跟它对自己的那股魔力联系到一处，便一把抓起那灭烛罩似的帽子，猛地往它头上按下去。"},{"start":70.837,"end":84.912,"text":"那精灵在帽子底下矮了下去，弄得灭烛罩把它整个身形都罩住了；可斯克鲁奇虽使出浑身力气往下按，却遮不住那光：那光从罩子底下泻出来，源源不断地铺在地上。"},{"start":84.912,"end":93.162,"text":"他觉出自己精疲力竭，被一阵不可抗拒的睡意压倒了；再者，又觉出自己正待在自己的卧室里。"},{"start":93.162,"end":101.425,"text":"他临了又把那帽子捏了一把，手便松了下来；刚来得及踉踉跄跄扑到床上，就沉沉睡了过去。"}]},"en":{"text":"\"Mr. Scrooge.\"\n\"Mr. Scrooge it was.\nI passed his office window; and as it was not shut up, and he had a candle inside, I could scarcely help seeing him.\nHis partner lies upon the point of death, I hear; and there he sat alone.\nQuite alone in the world, I do believe.\"\n\"Spirit!\" said Scrooge in a broken voice, \"remove me from this place.\"\n\"I told you these were shadows of the things that have been,\" said the Ghost.\n\"That they are what they are, do not blame me!\"\n\"Remove me!\" Scrooge exclaimed.\n\"I cannot bear it!\"\nHe turned upon the Ghost, and seeing that it looked upon him with a face, in which in some strange way there were fragments of all the faces it had shown him, wrestled with it.\n\"Leave me!\nTake me back.\nHaunt me no longer!\"\nIn the struggle, if that can be called a struggle in which the Ghost with no visible resistance on its own part was undisturbed by any effort of its adversary, Scrooge observed that its light was burning high and bright; and dimly connecting that with its influence over him, he seized the extinguisher-cap, and by a sudden action pressed it down upon its head.\nThe Spirit dropped beneath it, so that the extinguisher covered its whole form; but though Scrooge pressed it down with all his force, he could not hide the light: which streamed from under it, in an unbroken flood upon the ground.\nHe was conscious of being exhausted, and overcome by an irresistible drowsiness; and, further, of being in his own bedroom.\nHe gave the cap a parting squeeze, in which his hand relaxed; and had barely time to reel to bed, before he sank into a heavy sleep.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_II_小节20.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":2,"text":"Mr. Scrooge."},{"start":1.95,"end":4.225,"text":"Mr. Scrooge it was."},{"start":4.225,"end":11.8,"text":"I passed his office window; and as it was not shut up, and he had a candle inside, I could scarcely help seeing him."},{"start":11.8,"end":16.962,"text":"His partner lies upon the point of death, I hear; and there he sat alone."},{"start":16.962,"end":20.175,"text":"Quite alone in the world, I do believe."},{"start":20.175,"end":25.275,"text":"Spirit!\" said Scrooge in a broken voice, \"remove me from this place."},{"start":25.275,"end":29.862,"text":"I told you these were shadows of the things that have been,\" said the Ghost."},{"start":29.862,"end":33.137,"text":"That they are what they are, do not blame me!"},{"start":33.137,"end":34.8,"text":"Remove me!"},{"start":34.8,"end":36.925,"text":"Scrooge exclaimed."},{"start":36.925,"end":38.875,"text":"I cannot bear it!"},{"start":38.875,"end":48.45,"text":"He turned upon the Ghost, and seeing that it looked upon him with a face, in which in some strange way there were fragments of all the faces it had shown him, wrestled with it."},{"start":48.45,"end":50.037,"text":"Leave me!"},{"start":50.037,"end":51.837,"text":"Take me back."},{"start":51.837,"end":53.85,"text":"Haunt me no longer!"},{"start":53.85,"end":72.975,"text":"In the struggle, if that can be called a struggle in which the Ghost with no visible resistance on its own part was undisturbed by any effort of its adversary, Scrooge observed that its light was burning high and bright; and dimly connecting that with its influence over him, he seized the extinguisher-cap, and by a sudden action pressed it down upon its head."},{"start":72.975,"end":85.75,"text":"The Spirit dropped beneath it, so that the extinguisher covered its whole form; but though Scrooge pressed it down with all his force, he could not hide the light: which streamed from under it, in an unbroken flood upon the ground."},{"start":85.75,"end":94.237,"text":"He was conscious of being exhausted, and overcome by an irresistible drowsiness; and, further, of being in his own bedroom."},{"start":94.237,"end":102.875,"text":"He gave the cap a parting squeeze, in which his hand relaxed; and had barely time to reel to bed, before he sank into a heavy sleep."}]}}]},{"id":"Stave_III","title":{"zh":"第三章","en":"STAVE III."},"sections":[{"id":"III_01","number":1,"zh":{"text":"第三章\n三个精灵中的第二个\n斯克鲁奇在一记格外响亮的鼾声当中醒了过来，从床上坐起身来理一理思绪，用不着谁来告诉他，那钟又快敲一点了。\n他觉着自己恰恰是在这要紧的当口恢复了知觉，专为着同那第二位经雅各布·马利从中斡旋、派到他这儿来的使者会上一面。\n可他刚一琢磨起这新幽灵会拉开他哪一幅床帐，便浑身不自在地发起冷来，于是干脆亲手把每一幅都撇到了一边；又重新躺下，把床的四周都严严实实地盯紧了。\n因为他打算趁那精灵一现身就向它发问，不愿被冷不丁吓着、弄得心慌意乱。\n有那么些随随便便的先生，自诩通晓一两手门道、平日里也总应付得了局面，便夸口说自己从掷钱赌博到杀人越货，样样都来得，以此显示他们冒险胆量的广博无边；而在这两个极端之间，无疑横着相当宽广、相当周全的一大片名目。\n我不敢替斯克鲁奇把话说得这么硬气，可我满可以请你相信：他对名目繁多的各色怪象都已有了准备，从一个婴儿到一头犀牛，中间无论冒出什么来，都吓不着他多少。\n眼下，他对几乎什么都有了准备，却唯独对\"什么都没有\"全无防备；因此，当那钟敲过一点、却不见有什么形象现身时，他猛地一阵剧烈的哆嗦。\n五分钟，十分钟，一刻钟过去了，却什么也没来。\n这一向，他都躺在床上，正是那一片红光的核心与中央，钟报时的时候，那光便倾泻到床上来；它既然只是光，便比一打鬼魂还叫人惊慌，因为他全然弄不明白它是什么意思、要做什么；他有时还提心吊胆，只怕自己此时此刻正是一桩有趣的自燃案例，却连知道这一点的那点安慰都得不着。\n可到末了，他到底想了起来——换了你我，起初就会这么想了；因为身在局外的人总归知道局中该怎么办，而且毫无疑问也必定会那么办——我是说，他到末了想到，这鬼火的源头和秘密兴许在隔壁房间里：再往下追究，那光仿佛正是从那儿照过来的。\n这念头把他的心思整个占住了，他便轻手轻脚起了身，趿拉着拖鞋蹭到门口。\n斯克鲁奇的手刚一搭上门闩，一个古怪的声音便唤起他的名字，叫他进去。\n他依言进了去。\n那是他自己的房间。\n这一点毫无疑问。\n可它已经经历了一场叫人吃惊的大变样。\n墙壁和天花板上挂满了生气盎然的绿叶，看上去活像一片不折不扣的树林，处处都有亮晶晶的浆果在闪光。\n冬青、槲寄生和常春藤那爽脆的叶子把光反射回来，仿佛那儿撒满了无数面小镜子；烟囱里腾腾地烧着那么旺的一炉火，是那块死沉沉、石头似的炉膛在斯克鲁奇的年月里、马利的年月里、在过去许多许多个冬令时节里都不曾领略过的。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_III_小节01.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":1.312,"text":"第三章"},{"start":1.262,"end":3.4,"text":"三个精灵中的第二个"},{"start":3.4,"end":13.362,"text":"斯克鲁奇在一记格外响亮的鼾声当中醒了过来，从床上坐起身来理一理思绪，用不着谁来告诉他，那钟又快敲一点了。"},{"start":13.362,"end":24.55,"text":"他觉着自己恰恰是在这要紧的当口恢复了知觉，专为着同那第二位经雅各布·马利从中斡旋、派到他这儿来的使者会上一面。"},{"start":24.55,"end":38.862,"text":"可他刚一琢磨起这新幽灵会拉开他哪一幅床帐，便浑身不自在地发起冷来，于是干脆亲手把每一幅都撇到了一边；又重新躺下，把床的四周都严严实实地盯紧了。"},{"start":38.862,"end":45.35,"text":"因为他打算趁那精灵一现身就向它发问，不愿被冷不丁吓着、弄得心慌意乱。"},{"start":45.35,"end":65.062,"text":"有那么些随随便便的先生，自诩通晓一两手门道、平日里也总应付得了局面，便夸口说自己从掷钱赌博到杀人越货，样样都来得，以此显示他们冒险胆量的广博无边；而在这两个极端之间，无疑横着相当宽广、相当周全的一大片名目。"},{"start":65.062,"end":79.112,"text":"我不敢替斯克鲁奇把话说得这么硬气，可我满可以请你相信：他对名目繁多的各色怪象都已有了准备，从一个婴儿到一头犀牛，中间无论冒出什么来，都吓不着他多少。"},{"start":79.112,"end":91.887,"text":"眼下，他对几乎什么都有了准备，却唯独对\"什么都没有\"全无防备；因此，当那钟敲过一点、却不见有什么形象现身时，他猛地一阵剧烈的哆嗦。"},{"start":91.887,"end":96.275,"text":"五分钟，十分钟，一刻钟过去了，却什么也没来。"},{"start":96.275,"end":121.212,"text":"这一向，他都躺在床上，正是那一片红光的核心与中央，钟报时的时候，那光便倾泻到床上来；它既然只是光，便比一打鬼魂还叫人惊慌，因为他全然弄不明白它是什么意思、要做什么；他有时还提心吊胆，只怕自己此时此刻正是一桩有趣的自燃案例，却连知道这一点的那点安慰都得不着。"},{"start":121.212,"end":141.612,"text":"可到末了，他到底想了起来——换了你我，起初就会这么想了；因为身在局外的人总归知道局中该怎么办，而且毫无疑问也必定会那么办——我是说，他到末了想到，这鬼火的源头和秘密兴许在隔壁房间里：再往下追究，那光仿佛正是从那儿照过来的。"},{"start":141.612,"end":148.5,"text":"这念头把他的心思整个占住了，他便轻手轻脚起了身，趿拉着拖鞋蹭到门口。"},{"start":148.5,"end":154.925,"text":"斯克鲁奇的手刚一搭上门闩，一个古怪的声音便唤起他的名字，叫他进去。"},{"start":154.925,"end":156.612,"text":"他依言进了去。"},{"start":156.612,"end":158.675,"text":"那是他自己的房间。"},{"start":158.675,"end":160.5,"text":"这一点毫无疑问。"},{"start":160.5,"end":164.187,"text":"可它已经经历了一场叫人吃惊的大变样。"},{"start":164.187,"end":173.462,"text":"墙壁和天花板上挂满了生气盎然的绿叶，看上去活像一片不折不扣的树林，处处都有亮晶晶的浆果在闪光。"},{"start":173.462,"end":193.562,"text":"冬青、槲寄生和常春藤那爽脆的叶子把光反射回来，仿佛那儿撒满了无数面小镜子；烟囱里腾腾地烧着那么旺的一炉火，是那块死沉沉、石头似的炉膛在斯克鲁奇的年月里、马利的年月里、在过去许多许多个冬令时节里都不曾领略过的。"}]},"en":{"text":"STAVE III.\nTHE SECOND OF THE THREE SPIRITS.\nAwaking in the middle of a prodigiously tough snore, and sitting up in bed to get his thoughts together, Scrooge had no occasion to be told that the bell was again upon the stroke of One.\nHe felt that he was restored to consciousness in the right nick of time, for the especial purpose of holding a conference with the second messenger despatched to him through Jacob Marley's intervention.\nBut finding that he turned uncomfortably cold when he began to wonder which of his curtains this new spectre would draw back, he put them every one aside with his own hands; and lying down again, established a sharp look-out all round the bed.\nFor he wished to challenge the Spirit on the moment of its appearance, and did not wish to be taken by surprise and made nervous.\nGentlemen of the free-and-easy sort, who plume themselves on being acquainted with a move or two, and being usually equal to the time-of-day, express the wide range of their capacity for adventure by observing that they are good for anything from pitch-and-toss to manslaughter; between which opposite extremes, no doubt, there lies a tolerably wide and comprehensive range of subjects.\nWithout venturing for Scrooge quite as hardily as this, I don't mind calling on you to believe that he was ready for a good broad field of strange appearances, and that nothing between a baby and a rhinoceros would have astonished him very much.\nNow, being prepared for almost anything, he was not by any means prepared for nothing; and, consequently, when the Bell struck One, and no shape appeared, he was taken with a violent fit of trembling.\nFive minutes, ten minutes, a quarter of an hour went by, yet nothing came.\nAll this time, he lay upon his bed, the very core and centre of a blaze of ruddy light, which streamed upon it when the clock proclaimed the hour; and which being only light, was more alarming than a dozen ghosts, as he was powerless to make out what it meant, or would be at; and was sometimes apprehensive that he might be at that very moment an interesting case of spontaneous combustion, without having the consolation of knowing it.\nAt last, however, he began to think--as you or I would have thought at first; for it is always the person not in the predicament who knows what ought to have been done in it, and would unquestionably have done it too--at last, I say, he began to think that the source and secret of this ghostly light might be in the adjoining room: from whence, on further tracing it, it seemed to shine.\nThis idea taking full possession of his mind, he got up softly and shuffled in his slippers to the door.\nThe moment Scrooge's hand was on the lock, a strange voice called him by his name, and bade him enter.\nHe obeyed.\nIt was his own room.\nThere was no doubt about that.\nBut it had undergone a surprising transformation.\nThe walls and ceiling were so hung with living green, that it looked a perfect grove, from every part of which, bright gleaming berries glistened.\nThe crisp leaves of holly, mistletoe, and ivy reflected back the light, as if so many little mirrors had been scattered there; and such a mighty blaze went roaring up the chimney, as that dull petrifaction of a hearth had never known in Scrooge's time, or Marley's, or for many and many a winter season gone.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_III_小节01.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":1.962,"text":"STAVE III."},{"start":1.912,"end":4.575,"text":"THE SECOND OF THE THREE SPIRITS."},{"start":4.575,"end":14.45,"text":"Awaking in the middle of a prodigiously tough snore, and sitting up in bed to get his thoughts together, Scrooge had no occasion to be told that the bell was again upon the stroke of One."},{"start":14.45,"end":24.6,"text":"He felt that he was restored to consciousness in the right nick of time, for the especial purpose of holding a conference with the second messenger despatched to him through Jacob Marley's intervention."},{"start":24.6,"end":37.95,"text":"But finding that he turned uncomfortably cold when he began to wonder which of his curtains this new spectre would draw back, he put them every one aside with his own hands; and lying down again, established a sharp look-out all round the bed."},{"start":37.95,"end":45.337,"text":"For he wished to challenge the Spirit on the moment of its appearance, and did not wish to be taken by surprise and made nervous."},{"start":45.337,"end":66.387,"text":"Gentlemen of the free-and-easy sort, who plume themselves on being acquainted with a move or two, and being usually equal to the time-of-day, express the wide range of their capacity for adventure by observing that they are good for anything from pitch-and-toss to manslaughter; between which opposite extremes, no doubt, there lies a tolerably wide and comprehensive range of subjects."},{"start":66.387,"end":79.487,"text":"Without venturing for Scrooge quite as hardily as this, I don't mind calling on you to believe that he was ready for a good broad field of strange appearances, and that nothing between a baby and a rhinoceros would have astonished him very much."},{"start":79.487,"end":91.987,"text":"Now, being prepared for almost anything, he was not by any means prepared for nothing; and, consequently, when the Bell struck One, and no shape appeared, he was taken with a violent fit of trembling."},{"start":91.987,"end":97.662,"text":"Five minutes, ten minutes, a quarter of an hour went by, yet nothing came."},{"start":97.662,"end":121.362,"text":"All this time, he lay upon his bed, the very core and centre of a blaze of ruddy light, which streamed upon it when the clock proclaimed the hour; and which being only light, was more alarming than a dozen ghosts, as he was powerless to make out what it meant, or would be at; and was sometimes apprehensive that he might be at that very moment an interesting case of spontaneous combustion, without having the consolation of knowing it."},{"start":121.362,"end":141.737,"text":"At last, however, he began to think--as you or I would have thought at first; for it is always the person not in the predicament who knows what ought to have been done in it, and would unquestionably have done it too--at last, I say, he began to think that the source and secret of this ghostly light might be in the adjoining room: from whence, on further tracing it, it seemed to shine."},{"start":141.737,"end":148.3,"text":"This idea taking full possession of his mind, he got up softly and shuffled in his slippers to the door."},{"start":148.3,"end":154.712,"text":"The moment Scrooge's hand was on the lock, a strange voice called him by his name, and bade him enter."},{"start":154.712,"end":156.337,"text":"He obeyed."},{"start":156.337,"end":158.4,"text":"It was his own room."},{"start":158.4,"end":160.762,"text":"There was no doubt about that."},{"start":160.762,"end":164.137,"text":"But it had undergone a surprising transformation."},{"start":164.137,"end":172.987,"text":"The walls and ceiling were so hung with living green, that it looked a perfect grove, from every part of which, bright gleaming berries glistened."},{"start":172.987,"end":190.85,"text":"The crisp leaves of holly, mistletoe, and ivy reflected back the light, as if so many little mirrors had been scattered there; and such a mighty blaze went roaring up the chimney, as that dull petrifaction of a hearth had never known in Scrooge's time, or Marley's, or for many and many a winter season gone."}]}},{"id":"III_02","number":2,"zh":{"text":"地板上堆得高高的，垒成了一座宝座似的：有火鸡、鹅、野味、家禽，有冻肉，有大块大块的肉，有乳猪，有一长串一长串的香肠，有肉馅饼，有葡萄干布丁，有一桶桶牡蛎，有滚烫的栗子，有红如樱桃脸蛋的苹果，有汁水淋漓的橙子，有甘美的梨子，有大得吓人的主显节蛋糕，还有一钵钵沸腾的潘趣酒，那喷香的热气把屋子都熏得朦朦胧胧了。\n在这卧榻上安然自在地坐着一位欢乐的巨人，看着教人赞叹；他擎着一支熊熊燃烧的火炬，形状跟丰饶角不无相似，高高地举着，好把光洒到斯克鲁奇身上——斯克鲁奇正探头探脑地绕着门往里瞧呢。\n\"进来！\"那鬼魂嚷道。\n\"进来！来跟我多亲近亲近，老兄！\"\n斯克鲁奇怯生生地走了进去，在这精灵面前垂下了头。\n他不再是从前那个执拗的斯克鲁奇了；那精灵的眼睛虽说清亮又和善，他却不大乐意去迎它们的目光。\n\"我是当下的圣诞之灵，\"那精灵说。\n\"瞧瞧我吧！\"\n斯克鲁奇恭恭敬敬地照办了。\n它身上只裹着一件素净的深绿色长袍，或者说斗篷，镶着白色的毛皮边。\n这件衣裳松松垮垮地披在身上，把它那宽阔的胸膛敞露在外，仿佛不屑用什么巧饰去遮护、去掩藏。\n它那双脚露在衣裳宽大的褶子底下，也赤裸着；头上除了一顶冬青花环之外别无遮盖，那花环上这儿那儿地点缀着亮晶晶的冰凌。\n它那深棕色的鬈发又长又散：散漫得跟它那张和蔼的脸、那双闪亮的眼睛、那只摊开的手、那爽朗的嗓音、那无拘无束的举止、那喜气洋洋的神情一样。\n腰间束着一只古旧的剑鞘；可里头并没有剑，那古老的鞘子已让锈给蚀光了。\n\"你从前从没见过我这样的吧！\"那精灵嚷道。\n\"从没有，\"斯克鲁奇答它道。\n\"也从没跟我家里那些年轻些的成员一道出来走动过吧——我是说（因为我很年轻）我那些近些年才出世的兄长？\"那幽灵接着说。\n\"我想我没有过，\"斯克鲁奇说。\n\"我怕是没有过。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_III_小节02.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":29.837,"text":"地板上堆得高高的，垒成了一座宝座似的：有火鸡、鹅、野味、家禽，有冻肉，有大块大块的肉，有乳猪，有一长串一长串的香肠，有肉馅饼，有葡萄干布丁，有一桶桶牡蛎，有滚烫的栗子，有红如樱桃脸蛋的苹果，有汁水淋漓的橙子，有甘美的梨子，有大得吓人的主显节蛋糕，还有一钵钵沸腾的潘趣酒，那喷香的热气把屋子都熏得朦朦胧胧了。"},{"start":29.837,"end":46.75,"text":"在这卧榻上安然自在地坐着一位欢乐的巨人，看着教人赞叹；他擎着一支熊熊燃烧的火炬，形状跟丰饶角不无相似，高高地举着，好把光洒到斯克鲁奇身上——斯克鲁奇正探头探脑地绕着门往里瞧呢。"},{"start":46.75,"end":49.062,"text":"进来！\"那鬼魂嚷道。"},{"start":49.062,"end":50.125,"text":"进来！"},{"start":50.125,"end":52.725,"text":"来跟我多亲近亲近，老兄！"},{"start":52.725,"end":57.387,"text":"斯克鲁奇怯生生地走了进去，在这精灵面前垂下了头。"},{"start":57.387,"end":66.2,"text":"他不再是从前那个执拗的斯克鲁奇了；那精灵的眼睛虽说清亮又和善，他却不大乐意去迎它们的目光。"},{"start":66.2,"end":69.4,"text":"我是当下的圣诞之灵，\"那精灵说。"},{"start":69.4,"end":70.762,"text":"瞧瞧我吧！"},{"start":70.762,"end":73.462,"text":"斯克鲁奇恭恭敬敬地照办了。"},{"start":73.462,"end":79.812,"text":"它身上只裹着一件素净的深绿色长袍，或者说斗篷，镶着白色的毛皮边。"},{"start":79.812,"end":88.387,"text":"这件衣裳松松垮垮地披在身上，把它那宽阔的胸膛敞露在外，仿佛不屑用什么巧饰去遮护、去掩藏。"},{"start":88.387,"end":99.837,"text":"它那双脚露在衣裳宽大的褶子底下，也赤裸着；头上除了一顶冬青花环之外别无遮盖，那花环上这儿那儿地点缀着亮晶晶的冰凌。"},{"start":99.837,"end":113.137,"text":"它那深棕色的鬈发又长又散：散漫得跟它那张和蔼的脸、那双闪亮的眼睛、那只摊开的手、那爽朗的嗓音、那无拘无束的举止、那喜气洋洋的神情一样。"},{"start":113.137,"end":120.05,"text":"腰间束着一只古旧的剑鞘；可里头并没有剑，那古老的鞘子已让锈给蚀光了。"},{"start":120.05,"end":123.6,"text":"你从前从没见过我这样的吧！\"那精灵嚷道。"},{"start":123.6,"end":126.125,"text":"从没有，\"斯克鲁奇答它道。"},{"start":126.125,"end":136.362,"text":"也从没跟我家里那些年轻些的成员一道出来走动过吧——我是说（因为我很年轻）我那些近些年才出世的兄长？\"那幽灵接着说。"},{"start":136.362,"end":139.037,"text":"我想我没有过，\"斯克鲁奇说。"},{"start":139.037,"end":140.762,"text":"我怕是没有过。"}]},"en":{"text":"Heaped up upon the floor, to form a kind of throne, were turkeys, geese, game, poultry, brawn, great joints of meat, sucking-pigs, long wreaths of sausages, mince-pies, plum-puddings, barrels of oysters, red-hot chestnuts, cherry-cheeked apples, juicy oranges, luscious pears, immense twelfth-cakes, and seething bowls of punch, that made the chamber dim with their delicious steam.\nIn easy state upon this couch, there sat a jolly Giant, glorious to see; who bore a glowing torch, in shape not unlike Plenty's horn, and held it up, high up, to shed its light on Scrooge, as he came peeping round the door.\n\"Come in!\" exclaimed the Ghost.\n\"Come in! and know me better, man!\"\nScrooge entered timidly, and hung his head before this Spirit.\nHe was not the dogged Scrooge he had been; and though its eyes were clear and kind, he did not like to meet them.\n\"I am the Ghost of Christmas Present,\" said the Spirit.\n\"Look upon me!\"\nScrooge reverently did so.\nIt was clothed in one simple deep green robe, or mantle, bordered with white fur.\nThis garment hung so loosely on the figure, that its capacious breast was bare, as if disdaining to be warded or concealed by any artifice.\nIts feet, observable beneath the ample folds of the garment, were also bare; and on its head it wore no other covering than a holly wreath set here and there with shining icicles.\nIts dark brown curls were long and free: free as its genial face, its sparkling eye, its open hand, its cheery voice, its unconstrained demeanour, and its joyful air.\nGirded round its middle was an antique scabbard; but no sword was in it, and the ancient sheath was eaten up with rust.\n\"You have never seen the like of me before!\" exclaimed the Spirit.\n\"Never,\" Scrooge made answer to it.\n\"Have never walked forth with the younger members of my family; meaning (for I am very young) my elder brothers born in these later years?\" pursued the Phantom.\n\"I don't think I have,\" said Scrooge.\n\"I am afraid I have not.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_III_小节02.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":25.662,"text":"Heaped up upon the floor, to form a kind of throne, were turkeys, geese, game, poultry, brawn, great joints of meat, sucking-pigs, long wreaths of sausages, mince-pies, plum-puddings, barrels of oysters, red-hot chestnuts, cherry-cheeked apples, juicy oranges, luscious pears, immense twelfth-cakes, and seething bowls of punch, that made the chamber dim with their delicious steam."},{"start":25.612,"end":40.25,"text":"In easy state upon this couch, there sat a jolly Giant, glorious to see; who bore a glowing torch, in shape not unlike Plenty's horn, and held it up, high up, to shed its light on Scrooge, as he came peeping round the door."},{"start":40.25,"end":42.987,"text":"Come in!\" exclaimed the Ghost."},{"start":42.987,"end":44.412,"text":"Come in!"},{"start":44.412,"end":46.925,"text":"and know me better, man!"},{"start":46.925,"end":51.375,"text":"Scrooge entered timidly, and hung his head before this Spirit."},{"start":51.375,"end":57.975,"text":"He was not the dogged Scrooge he had been; and though its eyes were clear and kind, he did not like to meet them."},{"start":57.975,"end":61.637,"text":"I am the Ghost of Christmas Present,\" said the Spirit."},{"start":61.637,"end":63.45,"text":"Look upon me!"},{"start":63.45,"end":65.975,"text":"Scrooge reverently did so."},{"start":65.975,"end":71.675,"text":"It was clothed in one simple deep green robe, or mantle, bordered with white fur."},{"start":71.675,"end":80.45,"text":"This garment hung so loosely on the figure, that its capacious breast was bare, as if disdaining to be warded or concealed by any artifice."},{"start":80.45,"end":90.825,"text":"Its feet, observable beneath the ample folds of the garment, were also bare; and on its head it wore no other covering than a holly wreath set here and there with shining icicles."},{"start":90.825,"end":102.45,"text":"Its dark brown curls were long and free: free as its genial face, its sparkling eye, its open hand, its cheery voice, its unconstrained demeanour, and its joyful air."},{"start":102.45,"end":109.637,"text":"Girded round its middle was an antique scabbard; but no sword was in it, and the ancient sheath was eaten up with rust."},{"start":109.637,"end":113.962,"text":"You have never seen the like of me before!\" exclaimed the Spirit."},{"start":113.962,"end":117,"text":"Never,\" Scrooge made answer to it."},{"start":117,"end":126.637,"text":"Have never walked forth with the younger members of my family; meaning (for I am very young) my elder brothers born in these later years?\" pursued the Phantom."},{"start":126.637,"end":129.762,"text":"I don't think I have,\" said Scrooge."},{"start":129.762,"end":132.087,"text":"I am afraid I have not."}]}},{"id":"III_03","number":3,"zh":{"text":"你有过许多兄弟吗，精灵？\"\n\"一千八百多个呢，\"那鬼魂说。\n\"好大一家子要养活呀！\"斯克鲁奇咕哝道。\n当下的圣诞之灵站起身来。\n\"精灵，\"斯克鲁奇恭顺地说，\"你爱领我上哪儿就上哪儿吧。\n昨儿夜里我是被逼着出去的，可我领受了一番教训，这会儿正在起作用呢。\n今晚，倘若你有什么要教导我的，就让我从中得益吧。\"\n\"碰一碰我的袍子！\"\n斯克鲁奇依言而行，紧紧攥住了它。\n冬青、槲寄生、红浆果、常春藤、火鸡、鹅、野味、家禽、冻肉、肉、乳猪、香肠、牡蛎、馅饼、布丁、果子和潘趣酒，霎时间全都不见了。\n那房间、那炉火、那红光、那夜里的时辰，也一并消失了，他们立在了圣诞早晨城里的街道上，这儿（因为天气严寒）人们从自家门前的人行道上、从自家屋顶上铲雪，弄出一种粗粝、却又轻快、不算难听的乐声：那雪从屋顶扑簌簌落进底下的马路里、迸成一阵阵人造的小雪暴，看在孩子们眼里真是说不出的痛快。\n那一排排房屋的门脸够黑的了，窗子更黑，跟屋顶上那平滑的白雪、跟地上那肮脏些的雪一比，越发显得黑；地上那层积雪，已让大车、货车沉重的轮子犁出了一道道深沟；在大街分岔的地方，这些沟横一道竖一道地交错了千百回，在那厚厚的黄泥和冰水里冲出一条条曲折难辨的水道。\n天色阴沉，那些最短的街巷都让一团昏黄的雾给堵住了，那雾半化半冻，较重的颗粒像一阵烟灰似的微尘纷纷落下，仿佛全大不列颠的烟囱不约而同地着了火，正烧得称心如意、痛快淋漓。\n这天气也好，这市镇也好，本没有什么十分令人欢欣的，可外头却洋溢着一种欢欣的气象，便是最清朗的夏日空气、最明媚的夏日骄阳，想要播散开来，怕也是枉然。\n因为那些在屋顶上铲雪的人个个兴高采烈、满心欢喜；隔着矮墙彼此呼喊，时不时还逗趣地互掷一个雪球——这玩意儿做的飞弹，可比许多耍嘴皮子的俏皮话脾气好多了——掷中了便纵情大笑，掷歪了也照样笑个痛快。\n家禽铺子还半开着，水果铺更是辉煌得满堂生光。\n有一大筐一大筐又圆又鼓、活像欢乐老绅士背心的栗子，懒洋洋地靠在门口，又脑溢血似的胀鼓鼓地往街上滚出来。\n有红润润、棕脸膛、腰身宽阔的西班牙洋葱，长得肥头大耳，亮闪闪的活像西班牙修士；它们从架子上挤眉弄眼，放浪而狡黠地朝走过的姑娘们使着眼色，又一本正经地瞟一瞟那挂着的槲寄生。\n有梨子和苹果，高高地簇成一座座绚烂的金字塔；有一串串葡萄，托店主的好心，特意挂在显眼的钩子上，好叫过路人不花钱也能馋得直流口水；有一堆堆毛茸茸、棕褐色的榛子，那香气勾起人对昔日林间漫步的回忆，勾起在没膝的枯叶里愉快地趟来趟去的光景；有诺福克苹果，又矮又黑，把橙子和柠檬的金黄衬托得越发分明，它们那汁水饱满的身子敦敦实实，迫不及待地央求、恳求着要被装进纸袋带回家去、饭后享用。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_III_小节03.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":2.675,"text":"你有过许多兄弟吗，精灵？"},{"start":2.625,"end":5.45,"text":"一千八百多个呢，\"那鬼魂说。"},{"start":5.45,"end":9.062,"text":"好大一家子要养活呀！\"斯克鲁奇咕哝道。"},{"start":9.062,"end":11.862,"text":"当下的圣诞之灵站起身来。"},{"start":11.862,"end":16.237,"text":"精灵，\"斯克鲁奇恭顺地说，\"你爱领我上哪儿就上哪儿吧。"},{"start":16.237,"end":22.062,"text":"昨儿夜里我是被逼着出去的，可我领受了一番教训，这会儿正在起作用呢。"},{"start":22.062,"end":26.4,"text":"今晚，倘若你有什么要教导我的，就让我从中得益吧。"},{"start":26.4,"end":28.125,"text":"碰一碰我的袍子！"},{"start":28.125,"end":31.5,"text":"斯克鲁奇依言而行，紧紧攥住了它。"},{"start":31.5,"end":46.487,"text":"冬青、槲寄生、红浆果、常春藤、火鸡、鹅、野味、家禽、冻肉、肉、乳猪、香肠、牡蛎、馅饼、布丁、果子和潘趣酒，霎时间全都不见了。"},{"start":46.487,"end":72.762,"text":"那房间、那炉火、那红光、那夜里的时辰，也一并消失了，他们立在了圣诞早晨城里的街道上，这儿（因为天气严寒）人们从自家门前的人行道上、从自家屋顶上铲雪，弄出一种粗粝、却又轻快、不算难听的乐声：那雪从屋顶扑簌簌落进底下的马路里、迸成一阵阵人造的小雪暴，看在孩子们眼里真是说不出的痛快。"},{"start":72.762,"end":97.087,"text":"那一排排房屋的门脸够黑的了，窗子更黑，跟屋顶上那平滑的白雪、跟地上那肮脏些的雪一比，越发显得黑；地上那层积雪，已让大车、货车沉重的轮子犁出了一道道深沟；在大街分岔的地方，这些沟横一道竖一道地交错了千百回，在那厚厚的黄泥和冰水里冲出一条条曲折难辨的水道。"},{"start":97.087,"end":113.462,"text":"天色阴沉，那些最短的街巷都让一团昏黄的雾给堵住了，那雾半化半冻，较重的颗粒像一阵烟灰似的微尘纷纷落下，仿佛全大不列颠的烟囱不约而同地着了火，正烧得称心如意、痛快淋漓。"},{"start":113.462,"end":127.25,"text":"这天气也好，这市镇也好，本没有什么十分令人欢欣的，可外头却洋溢着一种欢欣的气象，便是最清朗的夏日空气、最明媚的夏日骄阳，想要播散开来，怕也是枉然。"},{"start":127.25,"end":145.037,"text":"因为那些在屋顶上铲雪的人个个兴高采烈、满心欢喜；隔着矮墙彼此呼喊，时不时还逗趣地互掷一个雪球——这玩意儿做的飞弹，可比许多耍嘴皮子的俏皮话脾气好多了——掷中了便纵情大笑，掷歪了也照样笑个痛快。"},{"start":145.037,"end":149.875,"text":"家禽铺子还半开着，水果铺更是辉煌得满堂生光。"},{"start":149.875,"end":160.125,"text":"有一大筐一大筐又圆又鼓、活像欢乐老绅士背心的栗子，懒洋洋地靠在门口，又脑溢血似的胀鼓鼓地往街上滚出来。"},{"start":160.125,"end":177.25,"text":"有红润润、棕脸膛、腰身宽阔的西班牙洋葱，长得肥头大耳，亮闪闪的活像西班牙修士；它们从架子上挤眉弄眼，放浪而狡黠地朝走过的姑娘们使着眼色，又一本正经地瞟一瞟那挂着的槲寄生。"},{"start":177.25,"end":214.112,"text":"有梨子和苹果，高高地簇成一座座绚烂的金字塔；有一串串葡萄，托店主的好心，特意挂在显眼的钩子上，好叫过路人不花钱也能馋得直流口水；有一堆堆毛茸茸、棕褐色的榛子，那香气勾起人对昔日林间漫步的回忆，勾起在没膝的枯叶里愉快地趟来趟去的光景；有诺福克苹果，又矮又黑，把橙子和柠檬的金黄衬托得越发分明，它们那汁水饱满的身子敦敦实实，迫不及待地央求、恳求着要被装进纸袋带回家去、饭后享用。"}]},"en":{"text":"Have you had many brothers, Spirit?\"\n\"More than eighteen hundred,\" said the Ghost.\n\"A tremendous family to provide for!\" muttered Scrooge.\nThe Ghost of Christmas Present rose.\n\"Spirit,\" said Scrooge submissively, \"conduct me where you will.\nI went forth last night on compulsion, and I learnt a lesson which is working now.\nTo-night, if you have aught to teach me, let me profit by it.\"\n\"Touch my robe!\"\nScrooge did as he was told, and held it fast.\nHolly, mistletoe, red berries, ivy, turkeys, geese, game, poultry, brawn, meat, pigs, sausages, oysters, pies, puddings, fruit, and punch, all vanished instantly.\nSo did the room, the fire, the ruddy glow, the hour of night, and they stood in the city streets on Christmas morning, where (for the weather was severe) the people made a rough, but brisk and not unpleasant kind of music, in scraping the snow from the pavement in front of their dwellings, and from the tops of their houses: whence it was mad delight to the boys to see it come plumping down into the road below, and splitting into artificial little snowstorms.\nThe house fronts looked black enough, and the windows blacker, contrasting with the smooth white sheet of snow upon the roofs, and with the dirtier snow upon the ground; which last deposit had been ploughed up in deep furrows by the heavy wheels of carts and waggons; furrows that crossed and recrossed each other hundreds of times where the great streets branched off, and made intricate channels, hard to trace, in the thick yellow mud and icy water.\nThe sky was gloomy, and the shortest streets were choked up with a dingy mist, half thawed half frozen, whose heavier particles descended in a shower of sooty atoms, as if all the chimneys in Great Britain had, by one consent, caught fire, and were blazing away to their dear hearts' content.\nThere was nothing very cheerful in the climate or the town, and yet was there an air of cheerfulness abroad that the clearest summer air and brightest summer sun might have endeavoured to diffuse in vain.\nFor the people who were shovelling away on the house-tops were jovial and full of glee; calling out to one another from the parapets, and now and then exchanging a facetious snowball--better-natured missile far than many a wordy jest--laughing heartily if it went right, and not less heartily if it went wrong.\nThe poulterers' shops were still half open, and the fruiterers' were radiant in their glory.\nThere were great, round, pot-bellied baskets of chestnuts, shaped like the waistcoats of jolly old gentlemen, lolling at the doors, and tumbling out into the street in their apoplectic opulence.\nThere were ruddy, brown-faced, broad-girthed Spanish Onions, shining in the fatness of their growth like Spanish Friars; and winking from their shelves in wanton slyness at the girls as they went by, and glanced demurely at the hung-up mistletoe.\nThere were pears and apples, clustered high in blooming pyramids; there were bunches of grapes, made, in the shopkeepers' benevolence, to dangle from conspicuous hooks, that people's mouths might water gratis as they passed; there were piles of filberts, mossy and brown, recalling, in their fragrance, ancient walks among the woods, and pleasant shufflings ankle deep through withered leaves; there were Norfolk Biffins, squab and swarthy, setting off the yellow of the oranges and lemons, and, in the great compactness of their juicy persons, urgently entreating and beseeching to be carried home in paper bags and eaten after dinner.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_III_小节03.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":2.887,"text":"Have you had many brothers, Spirit?"},{"start":2.837,"end":6.062,"text":"More than eighteen hundred,\" said the Ghost."},{"start":6.062,"end":10.262,"text":"A tremendous family to provide for!\" muttered Scrooge."},{"start":10.262,"end":13.1,"text":"The Ghost of Christmas Present rose."},{"start":13.1,"end":17.625,"text":"Spirit,\" said Scrooge submissively, \"conduct me where you will."},{"start":17.625,"end":22.8,"text":"I went forth last night on compulsion, and I learnt a lesson which is working now."},{"start":22.8,"end":27.037,"text":"To-night, if you have aught to teach me, let me profit by it."},{"start":27.037,"end":28.875,"text":"Touch my robe!"},{"start":28.875,"end":32.675,"text":"Scrooge did as he was told, and held it fast."},{"start":32.675,"end":47.575,"text":"Holly, mistletoe, red berries, ivy, turkeys, geese, game, poultry, brawn, meat, pigs, sausages, oysters, pies, puddings, fruit, and punch, all vanished instantly."},{"start":47.575,"end":73.475,"text":"So did the room, the fire, the ruddy glow, the hour of night, and they stood in the city streets on Christmas morning, where (for the weather was severe) the people made a rough, but brisk and not unpleasant kind of music, in scraping the snow from the pavement in front of their dwellings, and from the tops of their houses: whence it was mad delight to the boys to see it come plumping down into the road below, and splitting into artificial little snowstorms."},{"start":73.475,"end":97.587,"text":"The house fronts looked black enough, and the windows blacker, contrasting with the smooth white sheet of snow upon the roofs, and with the dirtier snow upon the ground; which last deposit had been ploughed up in deep furrows by the heavy wheels of carts and waggons; furrows that crossed and recrossed each other hundreds of times where the great streets branched off, and made intricate channels, hard to trace, in the thick yellow mud and icy water."},{"start":97.587,"end":114.425,"text":"The sky was gloomy, and the shortest streets were choked up with a dingy mist, half thawed half frozen, whose heavier particles descended in a shower of sooty atoms, as if all the chimneys in Great Britain had, by one consent, caught fire, and were blazing away to their dear hearts' content."},{"start":114.425,"end":124.75,"text":"There was nothing very cheerful in the climate or the town, and yet was there an air of cheerfulness abroad that the clearest summer air and brightest summer sun might have endeavoured to diffuse in vain."},{"start":124.75,"end":140.537,"text":"For the people who were shovelling away on the house-tops were jovial and full of glee; calling out to one another from the parapets, and now and then exchanging a facetious snowball--better-natured missile far than many a wordy jest--laughing heartily if it went right, and not less heartily if it went wrong."},{"start":140.537,"end":145.937,"text":"The poulterers' shops were still half open, and the fruiterers' were radiant in their glory."},{"start":145.937,"end":157.525,"text":"There were great, round, pot-bellied baskets of chestnuts, shaped like the waistcoats of jolly old gentlemen, lolling at the doors, and tumbling out into the street in their apoplectic opulence."},{"start":157.525,"end":171.725,"text":"There were ruddy, brown-faced, broad-girthed Spanish Onions, shining in the fatness of their growth like Spanish Friars; and winking from their shelves in wanton slyness at the girls as they went by, and glanced demurely at the hung-up mistletoe."},{"start":171.725,"end":201.987,"text":"There were pears and apples, clustered high in blooming pyramids; there were bunches of grapes, made, in the shopkeepers' benevolence, to dangle from conspicuous hooks, that people's mouths might water gratis as they passed; there were piles of filberts, mossy and brown, recalling, in their fragrance, ancient walks among the woods, and pleasant shufflings ankle deep through withered leaves; there were Norfolk Biffins, squab and swarthy, setting off the yellow of the oranges and lemons, and, in"},{"start":201.987,"end":209.862,"text":"the great compactness of their juicy persons, urgently entreating and beseeching to be carried home in paper bags and eaten after dinner."}]}},{"id":"III_04","number":4,"zh":{"text":"便是那些摆在这些精选果子当中、盛在一只钵子里的金鱼银鱼，虽说属于一个迟钝、血脉不活的族类，也仿佛知道出了什么事；它们一条不剩地绕着自己那小小的天地，缓慢而不动声色地兴奋着，一圈又一圈地游个不停。\n那些杂货铺！哦那些杂货铺！差不多都关了，兴许卸下了两扇窗板，或是一扇；可就从那些缝里头，瞧见的是何等景象！\n不单是那秤盘落在柜台上发出的欢快声响，不单是那线绳和卷轴麻利地分了家，不单是那些罐子像变戏法似的上下叮当作响，甚而不单是那茶香与咖啡香交融在一处、那样沁人鼻息，甚而不单是那葡萄干又多又稀罕、那杏仁白得出奇、那一根根肉桂又长又直、那别的香料鲜美无比、那蜜饯结着糖霜又斑斑点点地沾着熔化的糖、看得最冷心肠的旁观者都觉着头晕、随后又泛起恶心来。\n也不单是那无花果又润又多肉，不单是那法国李子从装点得花哨的盒子里透出几分腼腆的酸意而泛着红晕，也不单是样样东西都好吃、都穿上了圣诞的盛装：而是那些主顾全都那样匆忙、那样急切，怀着这佳节满含指望的允诺，一个个在门口撞作一团，把柳条篮子胡乱磕碰，把买下的东西撂在柜台上，又跑回来取，兴致再好不过地犯下千百桩这类糊涂错；那杂货店主和他的伙计们又是那样坦率、那样精神，扎在他们围裙背后那两颗擦得锃亮的心，简直像是他们自个儿的心挂在外头任人评看、随便哪只圣诞寒鸦高兴啄就由它去啄似的。\n可不一会儿，那些尖塔便召唤所有的善男信女上礼拜堂、小教堂去，于是他们都来了，穿着最好的衣裳、带着最快活的脸，成群结队地从街上拥过。\n与此同时，从几十条小街、小巷和不知名的拐角里，涌出数不清的人来，端着自家的饭食往面包铺去。\n这些穷苦的欢度佳节者的情景，仿佛叫那精灵大感兴味，因为他带着斯克鲁奇站在一家面包铺的门口，每逢端饭的人走过，便把盖子揭开，从他的火炬上往他们的饭食上洒下香霭。\n那还是一支极不寻常的火炬，因为有那么一两回，几个端饭的人彼此挤撞起来、说了几句气话，他便从火炬上往他们身上洒下几滴水，他们的好脾气登时就回来了。\n因为他们说，圣诞节这天吵架可太不像话。\n可不是嘛！\n上帝保佑这个日子，可不就是这样嘛！\n钟声到时候歇了，面包铺也关了门；可是每家面包炉子上头那块化了冻的潮湿斑痕里，仍旧温温和和地透出这一切饭食和它们烹煮进度的影子；那儿连人行道都冒着热气，仿佛连石头也在烹煮似的。\n\"你从火炬上洒下的东西，有一种特别的味道吗？\"斯克鲁奇问。\n\"有的。\n是我自己的味道。\"\n\"今天这日子，它对哪一种饭食都管用吗？\"斯克鲁奇问。\n\"凡是出于善心给的，都管用。\n对一份寒酸的饭食最管用。\"\n\"为什么对寒酸的最管用呢？\"斯克鲁奇问。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_III_小节04.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":18.05,"text":"便是那些摆在这些精选果子当中、盛在一只钵子里的金鱼银鱼，虽说属于一个迟钝、血脉不活的族类，也仿佛知道出了什么事；它们一条不剩地绕着自己那小小的天地，缓慢而不动声色地兴奋着，一圈又一圈地游个不停。"},{"start":18.05,"end":19.662,"text":"那些杂货铺！"},{"start":19.662,"end":21.362,"text":"哦那些杂货铺！"},{"start":21.362,"end":29.175,"text":"差不多都关了，兴许卸下了两扇窗板，或是一扇；可就从那些缝里头，瞧见的是何等景象！"},{"start":29.175,"end":61.987,"text":"不单是那秤盘落在柜台上发出的欢快声响，不单是那线绳和卷轴麻利地分了家，不单是那些罐子像变戏法似的上下叮当作响，甚而不单是那茶香与咖啡香交融在一处、那样沁人鼻息，甚而不单是那葡萄干又多又稀罕、那杏仁白得出奇、那一根根肉桂又长又直、那别的香料鲜美无比、那蜜饯结着糖霜又斑斑点点地沾着熔化的糖、看得最冷心肠的旁观者都觉着头晕、随后又泛起恶心来。"},{"start":61.987,"end":107.15,"text":"也不单是那无花果又润又多肉，不单是那法国李子从装点得花哨的盒子里透出几分腼腆的酸意而泛着红晕，也不单是样样东西都好吃、都穿上了圣诞的盛装：而是那些主顾全都那样匆忙、那样急切，怀着这佳节满含指望的允诺，一个个在门口撞作一团，把柳条篮子胡乱磕碰，把买下的东西撂在柜台上，又跑回来取，兴致再好不过地犯下千百桩这类糊涂错；那杂货店主和他的伙计们又是那样坦率、那样精神，扎在他们围裙背后那两颗擦得锃亮的心，简直像是他们自个儿的心挂在外头任人评看、随便哪只圣诞寒鸦高兴啄就由它去啄似的。"},{"start":107.15,"end":119.75,"text":"可不一会儿，那些尖塔便召唤所有的善男信女上礼拜堂、小教堂去，于是他们都来了，穿着最好的衣裳、带着最快活的脸，成群结队地从街上拥过。"},{"start":119.75,"end":128.937,"text":"与此同时，从几十条小街、小巷和不知名的拐角里，涌出数不清的人来，端着自家的饭食往面包铺去。"},{"start":128.937,"end":144.087,"text":"这些穷苦的欢度佳节者的情景，仿佛叫那精灵大感兴味，因为他带着斯克鲁奇站在一家面包铺的门口，每逢端饭的人走过，便把盖子揭开，从他的火炬上往他们的饭食上洒下香霭。"},{"start":144.087,"end":157.425,"text":"那还是一支极不寻常的火炬，因为有那么一两回，几个端饭的人彼此挤撞起来、说了几句气话，他便从火炬上往他们身上洒下几滴水，他们的好脾气登时就回来了。"},{"start":157.425,"end":161.337,"text":"因为他们说，圣诞节这天吵架可太不像话。"},{"start":161.337,"end":162.712,"text":"可不是嘛！"},{"start":162.712,"end":165.925,"text":"上帝保佑这个日子，可不就是这样嘛！"},{"start":165.925,"end":182.287,"text":"钟声到时候歇了，面包铺也关了门；可是每家面包炉子上头那块化了冻的潮湿斑痕里，仍旧温温和和地透出这一切饭食和它们烹煮进度的影子；那儿连人行道都冒着热气，仿佛连石头也在烹煮似的。"},{"start":182.287,"end":187.112,"text":"你从火炬上洒下的东西，有一种特别的味道吗？\"斯克鲁奇问。"},{"start":187.112,"end":188.137,"text":"有的。"},{"start":188.137,"end":189.875,"text":"是我自己的味道。"},{"start":189.875,"end":194.312,"text":"今天这日子，它对哪一种饭食都管用吗？\"斯克鲁奇问。"},{"start":194.312,"end":197.112,"text":"凡是出于善心给的，都管用。"},{"start":197.112,"end":199.675,"text":"对一份寒酸的饭食最管用。"},{"start":199.675,"end":203.3,"text":"为什么对寒酸的最管用呢？\"斯克鲁奇问。"}]},"en":{"text":"The very gold and silver fish, set forth among these choice fruits in a bowl, though members of a dull and stagnant-blooded race, appeared to know that there was something going on; and, to a fish, went grasping round and round their little world in slow and passionless excitement.\nThe Grocers'! oh the Grocers'! nearly closed, with perhaps two shutters down, or one; but through those gaps such glimpses!\nIt was not alone that the scales descending on the counter made a merry sound, or that the twine and roller parted company so briskly, or that the canisters were rattled up and down like juggling tricks, or even that the blended scents of tea and coffee were so grateful to the nose, or even that the raisins were so plentiful and rare, the almonds so extremely white, the sticks of cinnamon so long and straight, the other spices so delicious, the candied fruits so caked and spotted with molten sugar as to make the coldest lookers-on feel faint and subsequently bilious.\nNor was it that the figs were moist and pulpy, or that the French plums blushed in modest tartness from their highly-decorated boxes, or that everything was good to eat and in its Christmas dress: but the customers were all so hurried and so eager in the hopeful promise of the day, that they tumbled up against each other at the door, clashing their wicker baskets wildly, and left their purchases upon the counter, and came running back to fetch them, and committed hundreds of the like mistakes in the best humour possible; while the Grocer and his people were so frank and fresh that the polished hearts with which they fastened their aprons behind might have been their own, worn outside for general inspection, and for Christmas daws to peck at if they chose.\nBut soon the steeples called good people all, to church and chapel, and away they came, flocking through the streets in their best clothes, and with their gayest faces.\nAnd at the same time there emerged from scores of bye streets, lanes, and nameless turnings, innumerable people, carrying their dinners to the bakers' shops.\nThe sight of these poor revellers appeared to interest the Spirit very much, for he stood with Scrooge beside him in a baker's doorway, and taking off the covers as their bearers passed, sprinkled incense on their dinners from his torch.\nAnd it was a very uncommon kind of torch, for once or twice when there were angry words between some dinner-carriers who had jostled with each other, he shed a few drops of water on them from it, and their good humour was restored directly.\nFor they said, it was a shame to quarrel upon Christmas Day.\nAnd so it was!\nGod love it, so it was!\nIn time the bells ceased, and the bakers' were shut up; and yet there was a genial shadowing forth of all these dinners and the progress of their cooking, in the thawed blotch of wet above each baker's oven; where the pavement smoked as if its stones were cooking too.\n\"Is there a peculiar flavour in what you sprinkle from your torch?\" asked Scrooge.\n\"There is.\nMy own.\"\n\"Would it apply to any kind of dinner on this day?\" asked Scrooge.\n\"To any kindly given.\nTo a poor one most.\"\n\"Why to a poor one most?\" asked Scrooge.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_III_小节04.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":15.937,"text":"The very gold and silver fish, set forth among these choice fruits in a bowl, though members of a dull and stagnant-blooded race, appeared to know that there was something going on; and, to a fish, went grasping round and round their little world in slow and passionless excitement."},{"start":15.887,"end":17.662,"text":"The Grocers'!"},{"start":17.662,"end":19.637,"text":"oh the Grocers'!"},{"start":19.637,"end":26.287,"text":"nearly closed, with perhaps two shutters down, or one; but through those gaps such glimpses!"},{"start":26.287,"end":53.9,"text":"It was not alone that the scales descending on the counter made a merry sound, or that the twine and roller parted company so briskly, or that the canisters were rattled up and down like juggling tricks, or even that the blended scents of tea and coffee were so grateful to the nose, or even that the raisins were so plentiful and rare, the almonds so extremely white, the sticks of cinnamon so long and straight, the other spices so delicious, the candied fruits so caked and spotted with molten"},{"start":53.9,"end":58.962,"text":"sugar as to make the coldest lookers-on feel faint and subsequently bilious."},{"start":58.962,"end":85.4,"text":"Nor was it that the figs were moist and pulpy, or that the French plums blushed in modest tartness from their highly-decorated boxes, or that everything was good to eat and in its Christmas dress: but the customers were all so hurried and so eager in the hopeful promise of the day, that they tumbled up against each other at the door, clashing their wicker baskets wildly, and left their purchases upon the counter, and came running back to fetch them, and committed hundreds of the like mistakes"},{"start":85.4,"end":99.075,"text":"in the best humour possible; while the Grocer and his people were so frank and fresh that the polished hearts with which they fastened their aprons behind might have been their own, worn outside for general inspection, and for Christmas daws to peck at if they chose."},{"start":99.075,"end":109.137,"text":"But soon the steeples called good people all, to church and chapel, and away they came, flocking through the streets in their best clothes, and with their gayest faces."},{"start":109.137,"end":118.925,"text":"And at the same time there emerged from scores of bye streets, lanes, and nameless turnings, innumerable people, carrying their dinners to the bakers' shops."},{"start":118.925,"end":131.762,"text":"The sight of these poor revellers appeared to interest the Spirit very much, for he stood with Scrooge beside him in a baker's doorway, and taking off the covers as their bearers passed, sprinkled incense on their dinners from his torch."},{"start":131.762,"end":144.775,"text":"And it was a very uncommon kind of torch, for once or twice when there were angry words between some dinner-carriers who had jostled with each other, he shed a few drops of water on them from it, and their good humour was restored directly."},{"start":144.775,"end":149.05,"text":"For they said, it was a shame to quarrel upon Christmas Day."},{"start":149.05,"end":151.15,"text":"And so it was!"},{"start":151.15,"end":153.925,"text":"God love it, so it was!"},{"start":153.925,"end":168.15,"text":"In time the bells ceased, and the bakers' were shut up; and yet there was a genial shadowing forth of all these dinners and the progress of their cooking, in the thawed blotch of wet above each baker's oven; where the pavement smoked as if its stones were cooking too."},{"start":168.15,"end":173.125,"text":"Is there a peculiar flavour in what you sprinkle from your torch?\" asked Scrooge."},{"start":173.125,"end":174.7,"text":"There is."},{"start":174.7,"end":176.262,"text":"My own."},{"start":176.262,"end":180.6,"text":"Would it apply to any kind of dinner on this day?\" asked Scrooge."},{"start":180.6,"end":182.812,"text":"To any kindly given."},{"start":182.812,"end":185.05,"text":"To a poor one most."},{"start":185.05,"end":188.65,"text":"Why to a poor one most?\" asked Scrooge."}]}},{"id":"III_05","number":5,"zh":{"text":"\"因为它最需要。\"\n\"精灵，\"斯克鲁奇想了想说，\"我真纳闷，在咱们周遭这许多世界里的一切生灵当中，怎么偏偏是你，倒想去掐断这些人享受这点清白乐趣的机会呢。\"\n\"我！\"那精灵嚷道。\n\"你要剥夺他们每逢第七日吃顿饭的法子——而那往往是他们唯一称得上吃顿饭的日子，\"斯克鲁奇说。\n\"难道不是吗？\"\n\"我！\"那精灵嚷道。\n\"你不是想方设法要在第七日把这些地方关掉吗？\"斯克鲁奇说。\n\"反正归根到底是一回事。\"\n\"是我想方设法！\"那精灵嚷道。\n\"我若说错了，还请你原谅。\n这事是借着你的名义干的，至少也是借着你那一族的名义，\"斯克鲁奇说。\n\"在你们这个尘世上，\"那精灵回道，\"有那么些人，自称跟我们相熟，却借着我们的名义去干那些出于私欲、傲慢、恶意、仇恨、嫉妒、偏执和自私的勾当；这些人跟我们、跟我们所有的亲眷都生分得很，简直像是压根没活过一般。\n记住这一点，把他们干的事算到他们自己头上去，别算在我们身上。\"\n斯克鲁奇答应了；他们便又像先前一样，隐着身往这市镇的近郊走去。\n这鬼魂有一桩了不起的本事（斯克鲁奇在面包铺那儿就已经留意到了）：尽管他身材魁伟，却能轻而易举地把自己安顿在任何地方；他立在一处低矮的屋顶底下，照样那么优雅，那么有一副超凡脱俗的派头，仿佛立在任何巍峨的大厅里也不过如此。\n也许是这善良的精灵乐意卖弄一下自己这本事，再不然就是出于他自己那慈祥、慷慨、热忱的天性，出于他对一切穷苦人的体恤，他径直把斯克鲁奇领到了斯克鲁奇那伙计的家里；他就是上那儿去了，还拽着抓住他袍子的斯克鲁奇一同去；在门槛上，那精灵微微一笑，停下脚步，用他火炬洒下的甘霖为鲍勃·克拉奇特的住处祝福。\n想想看吧！\n鲍勃自己一礼拜才挣十五个\"鲍勃\"（先令）；每逢礼拜六他装进口袋里的，不过是他教名的十五个翻版罢了；然而当下圣诞之灵竟为他这四间房的小屋祝起福来！\n随后克拉奇特太太——克拉奇特的妻子——站起身来，身上穿得寒酸，是件翻改过两道的旧袍子，可缎带却扎得挺神气，那玩意儿便宜，花上六便士就很能撑撑场面；她铺起了桌布，二女儿贝琳达·克拉奇特在一旁帮衬，也一样神气地扎着缎带；彼得·克拉奇特少爷把一把叉子戳进那锅煮土豆里，又把他那硕大无比的衬衫领角（那是鲍勃的私房宝贝，为庆贺这日子赏给了他这位儿子兼继承人）的尖儿衔进嘴里，发觉自己穿戴得这般气派，乐不可支，巴不得能上时髦的公园里去显摆显摆他这身细布行头。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_III_小节05.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":1.825,"text":"因为它最需要。"},{"start":1.775,"end":13.612,"text":"精灵，\"斯克鲁奇想了想说，\"我真纳闷，在咱们周遭这许多世界里的一切生灵当中，怎么偏偏是你，倒想去掐断这些人享受这点清白乐趣的机会呢。"},{"start":13.612,"end":14.562,"text":"我！"},{"start":14.562,"end":16.25,"text":"那精灵嚷道。"},{"start":16.25,"end":24.175,"text":"你要剥夺他们每逢第七日吃顿饭的法子——而那往往是他们唯一称得上吃顿饭的日子，\"斯克鲁奇说。"},{"start":24.175,"end":25.675,"text":"难道不是吗？"},{"start":25.675,"end":26.625,"text":"我！"},{"start":26.625,"end":28.312,"text":"那精灵嚷道。"},{"start":28.312,"end":33.375,"text":"你不是想方设法要在第七日把这些地方关掉吗？\"斯克鲁奇说。"},{"start":33.375,"end":35.775,"text":"反正归根到底是一回事。"},{"start":35.775,"end":38.687,"text":"是我想方设法！\"那精灵嚷道。"},{"start":38.687,"end":41.325,"text":"我若说错了，还请你原谅。"},{"start":41.325,"end":47.037,"text":"这事是借着你的名义干的，至少也是借着你那一族的名义，\"斯克鲁奇说。"},{"start":47.037,"end":66.75,"text":"在你们这个尘世上，\"那精灵回道，\"有那么些人，自称跟我们相熟，却借着我们的名义去干那些出于私欲、傲慢、恶意、仇恨、嫉妒、偏执和自私的勾当；这些人跟我们、跟我们所有的亲眷都生分得很，简直像是压根没活过一般。"},{"start":66.75,"end":72.062,"text":"记住这一点，把他们干的事算到他们自己头上去，别算在我们身上。"},{"start":72.062,"end":78.362,"text":"斯克鲁奇答应了；他们便又像先前一样，隐着身往这市镇的近郊走去。"},{"start":78.362,"end":98.4,"text":"这鬼魂有一桩了不起的本事（斯克鲁奇在面包铺那儿就已经留意到了）：尽管他身材魁伟，却能轻而易举地把自己安顿在任何地方；他立在一处低矮的屋顶底下，照样那么优雅，那么有一副超凡脱俗的派头，仿佛立在任何巍峨的大厅里也不过如此。"},{"start":98.4,"end":126.275,"text":"也许是这善良的精灵乐意卖弄一下自己这本事，再不然就是出于他自己那慈祥、慷慨、热忱的天性，出于他对一切穷苦人的体恤，他径直把斯克鲁奇领到了斯克鲁奇那伙计的家里；他就是上那儿去了，还拽着抓住他袍子的斯克鲁奇一同去；在门槛上，那精灵微微一笑，停下脚步，用他火炬洒下的甘霖为鲍勃·克拉奇特的住处祝福。"},{"start":126.275,"end":127.687,"text":"想想看吧！"},{"start":127.687,"end":141.525,"text":"鲍勃自己一礼拜才挣十五个\"鲍勃\"（先令）；每逢礼拜六他装进口袋里的，不过是他教名的十五个翻版罢了；然而当下圣诞之灵竟为他这四间房的小屋祝起福来！"},{"start":141.525,"end":183.137,"text":"随后克拉奇特太太——克拉奇特的妻子——站起身来，身上穿得寒酸，是件翻改过两道的旧袍子，可缎带却扎得挺神气，那玩意儿便宜，花上六便士就很能撑撑场面；她铺起了桌布，二女儿贝琳达·克拉奇特在一旁帮衬，也一样神气地扎着缎带；彼得·克拉奇特少爷把一把叉子戳进那锅煮土豆里，又把他那硕大无比的衬衫领角（那是鲍勃的私房宝贝，为庆贺这日子赏给了他这位儿子兼继承人）的尖儿衔进嘴里，发觉自己穿戴得这般气派，乐不可支，巴不得能上时髦的公园里去显摆显摆他这身细布行头。"}]},"en":{"text":"\"Because it needs it most.\"\n\"Spirit,\" said Scrooge, after a moment's thought, \"I wonder you, of all the beings in the many worlds about us, should desire to cramp these people's opportunities of innocent enjoyment.\"\n\"I!\" cried the Spirit.\n\"You would deprive them of their means of dining every seventh day, often the only day on which they can be said to dine at all,\" said Scrooge.\n\"Wouldn't you?\"\n\"I!\" cried the Spirit.\n\"You seek to close these places on the Seventh Day?\" said Scrooge.\n\"And it comes to the same thing.\"\n\"_I_ seek!\" exclaimed the Spirit.\n\"Forgive me if I am wrong.\nIt has been done in your name, or at least in that of your family,\" said Scrooge.\n\"There are some upon this earth of yours,\" returned the Spirit, \"who lay claim to know us, and who do their deeds of passion, pride, ill-will, hatred, envy, bigotry, and selfishness in our name; who are as strange to us and all our kith and kin, as if they had never lived.\nRemember that, and charge their doings on themselves, not us.\"\nScrooge promised that he would; and they went on, invisible, as they had been before, into the suburbs of the town.\nIt was a remarkable quality of the Ghost (which Scrooge had observed at the baker's) that notwithstanding his gigantic size, he could accommodate himself to any place with ease; and that he stood beneath a low roof quite as gracefully and like a supernatural creature, as it was possible he could have done in any lofty hall.\nAnd perhaps it was the pleasure the good Spirit had in showing off this power of his, or else it was his own kind, generous, hearty nature, and his sympathy with all poor men, that led him straight to Scrooge's clerk's; for there he went, and took Scrooge with him, holding to his robe; and on the threshold of the door the Spirit smiled, and stopped to bless Bob Cratchit's dwelling with the sprinklings of his torch.\nThink of that!\nBob had but fifteen \"Bob\" a-week himself; he pocketed on Saturdays but fifteen copies of his Christian name; and yet the Ghost of Christmas Present blessed his four-roomed house!\nThen up rose Mrs. Cratchit, Cratchit's wife, dressed out but poorly in a twice-turned gown, but brave in ribbons, which are cheap and make a goodly show for sixpence; and she laid the cloth, assisted by Belinda Cratchit, second of her daughters, also brave in ribbons; while Master Peter Cratchit plunged a fork into the saucepan of potatoes, and getting the corners of his monstrous shirt-collar (Bob's private property, conferred upon his son and heir in honour of the day) into his mouth, rejoiced to find himself so gallantly attired, and yearned to show his linen in the fashionable Parks.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_III_小节05.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":2.35,"text":"Because it needs it most."},{"start":2.3,"end":13.312,"text":"Spirit,\" said Scrooge, after a moment's thought, \"I wonder you, of all the beings in the many worlds about us, should desire to cramp these people's opportunities of innocent enjoyment."},{"start":13.312,"end":15.825,"text":"I!\" cried the Spirit."},{"start":15.825,"end":24.025,"text":"You would deprive them of their means of dining every seventh day, often the only day on which they can be said to dine at all,\" said Scrooge."},{"start":24.025,"end":25.45,"text":"Wouldn't you?"},{"start":25.45,"end":27.962,"text":"I!\" cried the Spirit."},{"start":27.962,"end":32.487,"text":"You seek to close these places on the Seventh Day?\" said Scrooge."},{"start":32.487,"end":34.862,"text":"And it comes to the same thing."},{"start":34.862,"end":38.925,"text":"_I_ seek!\" exclaimed the Spirit."},{"start":38.925,"end":41.275,"text":"Forgive me if I am wrong."},{"start":41.275,"end":46.287,"text":"It has been done in your name, or at least in that of your family,\" said Scrooge."},{"start":46.287,"end":63.55,"text":"There are some upon this earth of yours,\" returned the Spirit, \"who lay claim to know us, and who do their deeds of passion, pride, ill-will, hatred, envy, bigotry, and selfishness in our name; who are as strange to us and all our kith and kin, as if they had never lived."},{"start":63.55,"end":68.15,"text":"Remember that, and charge their doings on themselves, not us."},{"start":68.15,"end":75.837,"text":"Scrooge promised that he would; and they went on, invisible, as they had been before, into the suburbs of the town."},{"start":75.837,"end":93.675,"text":"It was a remarkable quality of the Ghost (which Scrooge had observed at the baker's) that notwithstanding his gigantic size, he could accommodate himself to any place with ease; and that he stood beneath a low roof quite as gracefully and like a supernatural creature, as it was possible he could have done in any lofty hall."},{"start":93.675,"end":116.637,"text":"And perhaps it was the pleasure the good Spirit had in showing off this power of his, or else it was his own kind, generous, hearty nature, and his sympathy with all poor men, that led him straight to Scrooge's clerk's; for there he went, and took Scrooge with him, holding to his robe; and on the threshold of the door the Spirit smiled, and stopped to bless Bob Cratchit's dwelling with the sprinklings of his torch."},{"start":116.637,"end":118.275,"text":"Think of that!"},{"start":118.275,"end":129.1,"text":"Bob had but fifteen \"Bob\" a-week himself; he pocketed on Saturdays but fifteen copies of his Christian name; and yet the Ghost of Christmas Present blessed his four-roomed house!"},{"start":129.1,"end":157.837,"text":"Then up rose Mrs. Cratchit, Cratchit's wife, dressed out but poorly in a twice-turned gown, but brave in ribbons, which are cheap and make a goodly show for sixpence; and she laid the cloth, assisted by Belinda Cratchit, second of her daughters, also brave in ribbons; while Master Peter Cratchit plunged a fork into the saucepan of potatoes, and getting the corners of his monstrous shirt-collar (Bob's private property, conferred upon his son and heir in honour of the day) into his mouth,"},{"start":157.837,"end":164.275,"text":"rejoiced to find himself so gallantly attired, and yearned to show his linen in the fashionable Parks."}]}},{"id":"III_06","number":6,"zh":{"text":"这会儿又有两个小些的克拉奇特——一男一女——飞奔进来，嚷嚷说他们在面包铺外头闻到了那只鹅的香味，一闻就认出是自家的；这两个小克拉奇特心里头美滋滋地想着鼠尾草拌洋葱的填料，绕着桌子手舞足蹈，把彼得·克拉奇特少爷捧到了天上，而彼得呢（他倒不骄傲，尽管那领子勒得他差点透不过气来）只顾吹着火，直吹到那些慢吞吞的土豆咕嘟咕嘟冒起泡来，砰砰地直敲锅盖，吵着要放它们出来削皮。\n\"你们那宝贝爹这是又上哪儿去了呢，\"克拉奇特太太说。\n\"还有你们的弟弟小蒂姆；玛莎去年圣诞节也没迟这半个钟头哪！\"\n\"玛莎来啦，妈！\"一个姑娘说着便现了身。\n\"玛莎来啦，妈！\"那两个小克拉奇特一齐嚷道。\n\"好哇！\n有那么大一只鹅呢，玛莎！\"\n\"哎呀，我的乖乖，可把你盼来了，怎么这么晚呀！\"克拉奇特太太说着，亲了她十几下，又献殷勤似的麻利地替她脱下披肩、摘下帽子。\n\"昨儿夜里有好大一摊活儿要赶完，\"那姑娘答道，\"今儿早上还得收拾收拾，妈！\"\n\"得！\n只要你来了就好，别管那些个，\"克拉奇特太太说。\n\"到火跟前坐下，我的乖乖，暖和暖和，上帝保佑你！\"\n\"别别！\n爹回来啦，\"那两个小克拉奇特嚷道，他们简直一下子无处不在。\n\"快把玛莎藏起来，藏起来！\"\n于是玛莎藏了起来，小个子鲍勃——那做父亲的——走了进来，胸前耷拉着至少三英尺长的围巾，流苏还不算在内；他那身磨得快透了的衣裳缝补熨刷过，好显出几分应景的样子；小蒂姆骑在他肩头。\n可怜的小蒂姆呀，他拄着一根小拐杖，四肢全靠一副铁架子撑着！\n\"咦，咱们的玛莎呢？\"鲍勃·克拉奇特四下张望着嚷道。\n\"不来了，\"克拉奇特太太说。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_III_小节06.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":33.887,"text":"这会儿又有两个小些的克拉奇特——一男一女——飞奔进来，嚷嚷说他们在面包铺外头闻到了那只鹅的香味，一闻就认出是自家的；这两个小克拉奇特心里头美滋滋地想着鼠尾草拌洋葱的填料，绕着桌子手舞足蹈，把彼得·克拉奇特少爷捧到了天上，而彼得呢（他倒不骄傲，尽管那领子勒得他差点透不过气来）只顾吹着火，直吹到那些慢吞吞的土豆咕嘟咕嘟冒起泡来，砰砰地直敲锅盖，吵着要放它们出来削皮。"},{"start":33.887,"end":38.112,"text":"你们那宝贝爹这是又上哪儿去了呢，\"克拉奇特太太说。"},{"start":38.112,"end":43.612,"text":"还有你们的弟弟小蒂姆；玛莎去年圣诞节也没迟这半个钟头哪！"},{"start":43.612,"end":47.587,"text":"玛莎来啦，妈！\"一个姑娘说着便现了身。"},{"start":47.587,"end":51.712,"text":"玛莎来啦，妈！\"那两个小克拉奇特一齐嚷道。"},{"start":51.712,"end":52.725,"text":"好哇！"},{"start":52.725,"end":55.325,"text":"有那么大一只鹅呢，玛莎！"},{"start":55.325,"end":66.275,"text":"哎呀，我的乖乖，可把你盼来了，怎么这么晚呀！\"克拉奇特太太说着，亲了她十几下，又献殷勤似的麻利地替她脱下披肩、摘下帽子。"},{"start":66.275,"end":72.4,"text":"昨儿夜里有好大一摊活儿要赶完，\"那姑娘答道，\"今儿早上还得收拾收拾，妈！"},{"start":72.4,"end":73.312,"text":"得！"},{"start":73.312,"end":77.362,"text":"只要你来了就好，别管那些个，\"克拉奇特太太说。"},{"start":77.362,"end":81.887,"text":"到火跟前坐下，我的乖乖，暖和暖和，上帝保佑你！"},{"start":81.887,"end":82.962,"text":"别别！"},{"start":82.962,"end":88.275,"text":"爹回来啦，\"那两个小克拉奇特嚷道，他们简直一下子无处不在。"},{"start":88.275,"end":90.825,"text":"快把玛莎藏起来，藏起来！"},{"start":90.825,"end":107.5,"text":"于是玛莎藏了起来，小个子鲍勃——那做父亲的——走了进来，胸前耷拉着至少三英尺长的围巾，流苏还不算在内；他那身磨得快透了的衣裳缝补熨刷过，好显出几分应景的样子；小蒂姆骑在他肩头。"},{"start":107.5,"end":113.487,"text":"可怜的小蒂姆呀，他拄着一根小拐杖，四肢全靠一副铁架子撑着！"},{"start":113.487,"end":118.487,"text":"咦，咱们的玛莎呢？\"鲍勃·克拉奇特四下张望着嚷道。"},{"start":118.487,"end":120.937,"text":"不来了，\"克拉奇特太太说。"}]},"en":{"text":"And now two smaller Cratchits, boy and girl, came tearing in, screaming that outside the baker's they had smelt the goose, and known it for their own; and basking in luxurious thoughts of sage-and-onion, these young Cratchits danced about the table, and exalted Master Peter Cratchit to the skies, while he (not proud, although his collars nearly choked him) blew the fire, until the slow potatoes bubbling up, knocked loudly at the saucepan-lid to be let out and peeled.\n\"What has ever got your precious father then,\" said Mrs. Cratchit.\n\"And your brother, Tiny Tim; and Martha warn't as late last Christmas Day by half-an-hour!\"\n\"Here's Martha, mother!\" said a girl, appearing as she spoke.\n\"Here's Martha, mother!\" cried the two young Cratchits.\n\"Hurrah!\nThere's _such_ a goose, Martha!\"\n\"Why, bless your heart alive, my dear, how late you are!\" said Mrs. Cratchit, kissing her a dozen times, and taking off her shawl and bonnet for her, with officious zeal.\n\"We'd a deal of work to finish up last night,\" replied the girl, \"and had to clear away this morning, mother!\"\n\"Well!\nNever mind so long as you are come,\" said Mrs. Cratchit.\n\"Sit ye down before the fire, my dear, and have a warm, Lord bless ye!\"\n\"No no!\nThere's father coming,\" cried the two young Cratchits, who were everywhere at once.\n\"Hide Martha, hide!\"\nSo Martha hid herself, and in came little Bob, the father, with at least three feet of comforter exclusive of the fringe, hanging down before him; and his thread-bare clothes darned up and brushed, to look seasonable; and Tiny Tim upon his shoulder.\nAlas for Tiny Tim, he bore a little crutch, and had his limbs supported by an iron frame!\n\"Why, where's our Martha?\" cried Bob Cratchit looking around.\n\"Not coming,\" said Mrs. Cratchit.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_III_小节06.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":27.912,"text":"And now two smaller Cratchits, boy and girl, came tearing in, screaming that outside the baker's they had smelt the goose, and known it for their own; and basking in luxurious thoughts of sage-and-onion, these young Cratchits danced about the table, and exalted Master Peter Cratchit to the skies, while he (not proud, although his collars nearly choked him) blew the fire, until the slow potatoes bubbling up, knocked loudly at the saucepan-lid to be let out and peeled."},{"start":27.912,"end":32.15,"text":"What has ever got your precious father then,\" said Mrs. Cratchit."},{"start":32.15,"end":38.212,"text":"And your brother, Tiny Tim; and Martha warn't as late last Christmas Day by half-an-hour!"},{"start":38.212,"end":42.65,"text":"Here's Martha, mother!\" said a girl, appearing as she spoke."},{"start":42.65,"end":46.6,"text":"Here's Martha, mother!\" cried the two young Cratchits."},{"start":46.6,"end":48.025,"text":"Hurrah!"},{"start":48.025,"end":51.775,"text":"There's _such_ a goose, Martha!"},{"start":51.775,"end":63.187,"text":"Why, bless your heart alive, my dear, how late you are!\" said Mrs. Cratchit, kissing her a dozen times, and taking off her shawl and bonnet for her, with officious zeal."},{"start":63.187,"end":69.812,"text":"We'd a deal of work to finish up last night,\" replied the girl, \"and had to clear away this morning, mother!"},{"start":69.812,"end":71.125,"text":"Well!"},{"start":71.125,"end":75.312,"text":"Never mind so long as you are come,\" said Mrs. Cratchit."},{"start":75.312,"end":80.787,"text":"Sit ye down before the fire, my dear, and have a warm, Lord bless ye!"},{"start":80.787,"end":82.4,"text":"No no!"},{"start":82.4,"end":87.687,"text":"There's father coming,\" cried the two young Cratchits, who were everywhere at once."},{"start":87.687,"end":90.225,"text":"Hide Martha, hide!"},{"start":90.225,"end":104.762,"text":"So Martha hid herself, and in came little Bob, the father, with at least three feet of comforter exclusive of the fringe, hanging down before him; and his thread-bare clothes darned up and brushed, to look seasonable; and Tiny Tim upon his shoulder."},{"start":104.762,"end":111.087,"text":"Alas for Tiny Tim, he bore a little crutch, and had his limbs supported by an iron frame!"},{"start":111.087,"end":115.562,"text":"Why, where's our Martha?\" cried Bob Cratchit looking around."},{"start":115.562,"end":118.55,"text":"Not coming,\" said Mrs. Cratchit."}]}},{"id":"III_07","number":7,"zh":{"text":"\"不来了！\"鲍勃说，方才那一腔高兴劲儿陡地矮了下去；因为他这一路从教堂回来，一直当着小蒂姆的\"赛马\"，到家时还正撒着欢儿呢。\n\"圣诞节这天竟不来！\"\n玛莎不忍心见他失望，哪怕只是句玩笑话；于是她从壁橱门后头提前露了面，扑进了他怀里，那两个小克拉奇特则连推带拥地把小蒂姆架走，带进洗衣房，好让他听一听那布丁在铜锅里咝咝歌唱。\n\"咱们的小蒂姆乖不乖呀？\"等克拉奇特太太把鲍勃这般轻信取笑了一通、鲍勃也把女儿搂了个够，她才问道。\n\"乖得像金子，\"鲍勃说，\"还更乖呢。\n不知怎的，他老一个人坐着，便变得爱琢磨了，想出的尽是些你从没听过的稀奇念头。\n回家路上他跟我说，他盼着教堂里的人都瞧见他，因为他是个跛子，叫他们在圣诞节这天想一想那位曾使瘸腿的乞丐能走、瞎子能见光的主，兴许是件叫人快慰的事。\"\n鲍勃跟他们说这话时嗓音直发颤，说到小蒂姆正一天天硬朗结实起来时，颤得更厉害了。\n他那根灵便的小拐杖在地板上敲响了，还没等再说一个字，小蒂姆便由哥哥姐姐护着回来了，被送到火炉旁他那张小凳上；鲍勃卷起袖口——这可怜人，仿佛那袖口还能弄得更寒酸似的——往一只罐子里掺上杜松子酒和柠檬，调成一种热乎乎的饮料，搅了又搅，搁到炉架上去煨着；彼得少爷和那两个无处不在的小克拉奇特去端那只鹅，不一会儿便浩浩荡荡地端了回来。\n随即一阵忙乱，你简直会当那鹅是天底下最稀罕的鸟儿；是一桩长着羽毛的奇观，比起它来，黑天鹅都算不得什么稀奇了：说实话，在那户人家，它还真就差不多是这么个稀罕物。\n克拉奇特太太把肉汁（早预备在一只小锅里了）烧得咝咝滚烫；彼得少爷使出难以置信的力气捣着土豆；贝琳达小姐把苹果酱调甜；玛莎擦着烫手的盘子；鲍勃把小蒂姆拉到身边、桌角一个小小的旮旯里坐下；那两个小克拉奇特给每个人摆好椅子，也没忘了自己，然后守在各自的岗位上，把调羹塞进嘴里，免得还没轮到分给他们，就先嚷着要吃鹅。\n菜终于上齐了，做了饭前祷告。\n接着是一阵屏息的停顿，克拉奇特太太顺着那把切肉刀慢慢看过去，准备往鹅胸脯上扎下去；可等她真扎了下去，等那盼了好久的填料一涌而出，满桌子顿时响起一片欣喜的低语，连小蒂姆也让那两个小克拉奇特撩拨得兴奋起来，用刀柄敲着桌子，有气无力地喊了一声\"好哇！\"\n从没有过这样一只鹅。\n鲍勃说他简直不信世上烧过这样一只鹅。\n它的鲜嫩、它的香味、它的个头、它的便宜，成了人人交口称赞的话题。\n有苹果酱和土豆泥添补着，这一只鹅就足够全家人吃一顿了；可不是嘛，正如克拉奇特太太喜不自胜地说的（一面端详着盘子上那一小丁点儿骨头），他们到末了竟没把它吃光！\n可人人都吃了个饱，尤其是那两个最小的克拉奇特，从眉毛到脚都浸透了鼠尾草和洋葱味儿！\n这会儿，贝琳达小姐换过盘子，克拉奇特太太独自离了屋——她紧张得受不了有人在旁看着——去把那布丁端起来、端进屋里。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_III_小节07.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":10.712,"text":"不来了！\"鲍勃说，方才那一腔高兴劲儿陡地矮了下去；因为他这一路从教堂回来，一直当着小蒂姆的\"赛马\"，到家时还正撒着欢儿呢。"},{"start":10.662,"end":12.775,"text":"圣诞节这天竟不来！"},{"start":12.775,"end":29.625,"text":"玛莎不忍心见他失望，哪怕只是句玩笑话；于是她从壁橱门后头提前露了面，扑进了他怀里，那两个小克拉奇特则连推带拥地把小蒂姆架走，带进洗衣房，好让他听一听那布丁在铜锅里咝咝歌唱。"},{"start":29.625,"end":38.387,"text":"咱们的小蒂姆乖不乖呀？\"等克拉奇特太太把鲍勃这般轻信取笑了一通、鲍勃也把女儿搂了个够，她才问道。"},{"start":38.387,"end":41.7,"text":"乖得像金子，\"鲍勃说，\"还更乖呢。"},{"start":41.7,"end":48.875,"text":"不知怎的，他老一个人坐着，便变得爱琢磨了，想出的尽是些你从没听过的稀奇念头。"},{"start":48.875,"end":62.662,"text":"回家路上他跟我说，他盼着教堂里的人都瞧见他，因为他是个跛子，叫他们在圣诞节这天想一想那位曾使瘸腿的乞丐能走、瞎子能见光的主，兴许是件叫人快慰的事。"},{"start":62.662,"end":70.637,"text":"鲍勃跟他们说这话时嗓音直发颤，说到小蒂姆正一天天硬朗结实起来时，颤得更厉害了。"},{"start":70.637,"end":99.987,"text":"他那根灵便的小拐杖在地板上敲响了，还没等再说一个字，小蒂姆便由哥哥姐姐护着回来了，被送到火炉旁他那张小凳上；鲍勃卷起袖口——这可怜人，仿佛那袖口还能弄得更寒酸似的——往一只罐子里掺上杜松子酒和柠檬，调成一种热乎乎的饮料，搅了又搅，搁到炉架上去煨着；彼得少爷和那两个无处不在的小克拉奇特去端那只鹅，不一会儿便浩浩荡荡地端了回来。"},{"start":99.987,"end":114.637,"text":"随即一阵忙乱，你简直会当那鹅是天底下最稀罕的鸟儿；是一桩长着羽毛的奇观，比起它来，黑天鹅都算不得什么稀奇了：说实话，在那户人家，它还真就差不多是这么个稀罕物。"},{"start":114.637,"end":143.662,"text":"克拉奇特太太把肉汁（早预备在一只小锅里了）烧得咝咝滚烫；彼得少爷使出难以置信的力气捣着土豆；贝琳达小姐把苹果酱调甜；玛莎擦着烫手的盘子；鲍勃把小蒂姆拉到身边、桌角一个小小的旮旯里坐下；那两个小克拉奇特给每个人摆好椅子，也没忘了自己，然后守在各自的岗位上，把调羹塞进嘴里，免得还没轮到分给他们，就先嚷着要吃鹅。"},{"start":143.662,"end":146.65,"text":"菜终于上齐了，做了饭前祷告。"},{"start":146.65,"end":169.062,"text":"接着是一阵屏息的停顿，克拉奇特太太顺着那把切肉刀慢慢看过去，准备往鹅胸脯上扎下去；可等她真扎了下去，等那盼了好久的填料一涌而出，满桌子顿时响起一片欣喜的低语，连小蒂姆也让那两个小克拉奇特撩拨得兴奋起来，用刀柄敲着桌子，有气无力地喊了一声\"好哇！"},{"start":169.062,"end":171.2,"text":"从没有过这样一只鹅。"},{"start":171.2,"end":174.862,"text":"鲍勃说他简直不信世上烧过这样一只鹅。"},{"start":174.862,"end":181.212,"text":"它的鲜嫩、它的香味、它的个头、它的便宜，成了人人交口称赞的话题。"},{"start":181.212,"end":195.65,"text":"有苹果酱和土豆泥添补着，这一只鹅就足够全家人吃一顿了；可不是嘛，正如克拉奇特太太喜不自胜地说的（一面端详着盘子上那一小丁点儿骨头），他们到末了竟没把它吃光！"},{"start":195.65,"end":203.762,"text":"可人人都吃了个饱，尤其是那两个最小的克拉奇特，从眉毛到脚都浸透了鼠尾草和洋葱味儿！"},{"start":203.762,"end":213.75,"text":"这会儿，贝琳达小姐换过盘子，克拉奇特太太独自离了屋——她紧张得受不了有人在旁看着——去把那布丁端起来、端进屋里。"}]},"en":{"text":"\"Not coming!\" said Bob, with a sudden declension in his high spirits; for he had been Tim's blood horse all the way from church, and had come home rampant.\n\"Not coming upon Christmas Day!\"\nMartha didn't like to see him disappointed, if it were only in joke; so she came out prematurely from behind the closet door, and ran into his arms, while the two young Cratchits hustled Tiny Tim, and bore him off into the wash-house, that he might hear the pudding singing in the copper.\n\"And how did little Tim behave?\" asked Mrs. Cratchit, when she had rallied Bob on his credulity and Bob had hugged his daughter to his heart's content.\n\"As good as gold,\" said Bob, \"and better.\nSomehow he gets thoughtful sitting by himself so much, and thinks the strangest things you ever heard.\nHe told me, coming home, that he hoped the people saw him in the church, because he was a cripple, and it might be pleasant to them to remember upon Christmas Day, who made lame beggars walk and blind men see.\"\nBob's voice was tremulous when he told them this, and trembled more when he said that Tiny Tim was growing strong and hearty.\nHis active little crutch was heard upon the floor, and back came Tiny Tim before another word was spoken, escorted by his brother and sister to his stool beside the fire; and while Bob, turning up his cuffs--as if, poor fellow, they were capable of being made more shabby--compounded some hot mixture in a jug with gin and lemons, and stirred it round and round and put it on the hob to simmer; Master Peter and the two ubiquitous young Cratchits went to fetch the goose, with which they soon returned in high procession.\nSuch a bustle ensued that you might have thought a goose the rarest of all birds; a feathered phenomenon, to which a black swan was a matter of course: and in truth it was something very like it in that house.\nMrs. Cratchit made the gravy (ready beforehand in a little saucepan) hissing hot; Master Peter mashed the potatoes with incredible vigour; Miss Belinda sweetened up the apple-sauce; Martha dusted the hot plates; Bob took Tiny Tim beside him in a tiny corner at the table; the two young Cratchits set chairs for everybody, not forgetting themselves, and mounting guard upon their posts, crammed spoons into their mouths, lest they should shriek for goose before their turn came to be helped.\nAt last the dishes were set on, and grace was said.\nIt was succeeded by a breathless pause, as Mrs. Cratchit, looking slowly all along the carving-knife, prepared to plunge it in the breast; but when she did, and when the long expected gush of stuffing issued forth, one murmur of delight arose all round the board, and even Tiny Tim, excited by the two young Cratchits, beat on the table with the handle of his knife, and feebly cried Hurrah!\nThere never was such a goose.\nBob said he didn't believe there ever was such a goose cooked.\nIts tenderness and flavour, size and cheapness, were the themes of universal admiration.\nEked out by the apple-sauce and mashed potatoes, it was a sufficient dinner for the whole family; indeed, as Mrs. Cratchit said with a great delight (surveying one small atom of a bone upon the dish), they hadn't ate it all at last!\nYet every one had had enough, and the youngest Cratchits in particular, were steeped in sage and onion to the eyebrows!\nBut now, the plates being changed by Miss Belinda, Mrs. Cratchit left the room alone--too nervous to bear witnesses--to take the pudding up, and bring it in.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_III_小节07.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":9.55,"text":"Not coming!\" said Bob, with a sudden declension in his high spirits; for he had been Tim's blood horse all the way from church, and had come home rampant."},{"start":9.5,"end":12.237,"text":"Not coming upon Christmas Day!"},{"start":12.237,"end":28.237,"text":"Martha didn't like to see him disappointed, if it were only in joke; so she came out prematurely from behind the closet door, and ran into his arms, while the two young Cratchits hustled Tiny Tim, and bore him off into the wash-house, that he might hear the pudding singing in the copper."},{"start":28.237,"end":36.837,"text":"And how did little Tim behave?\" asked Mrs. Cratchit, when she had rallied Bob on his credulity and Bob had hugged his daughter to his heart's content."},{"start":36.837,"end":40.387,"text":"As good as gold,\" said Bob, \"and better."},{"start":40.387,"end":46.55,"text":"Somehow he gets thoughtful sitting by himself so much, and thinks the strangest things you ever heard."},{"start":46.55,"end":58.575,"text":"He told me, coming home, that he hoped the people saw him in the church, because he was a cripple, and it might be pleasant to them to remember upon Christmas Day, who made lame beggars walk and blind men see."},{"start":58.575,"end":66.012,"text":"Bob's voice was tremulous when he told them this, and trembled more when he said that Tiny Tim was growing strong and hearty."},{"start":66.012,"end":93.3,"text":"His active little crutch was heard upon the floor, and back came Tiny Tim before another word was spoken, escorted by his brother and sister to his stool beside the fire; and while Bob, turning up his cuffs--as if, poor fellow, they were capable of being made more shabby--compounded some hot mixture in a jug with gin and lemons, and stirred it round and round and put it on the hob to simmer; Master Peter and the two ubiquitous young Cratchits went to fetch the goose, with which they soon"},{"start":93.3,"end":95.65,"text":"returned in high procession."},{"start":95.65,"end":107.162,"text":"Such a bustle ensued that you might have thought a goose the rarest of all birds; a feathered phenomenon, to which a black swan was a matter of course: and in truth it was something very like it in that house."},{"start":107.162,"end":135.3,"text":"Mrs. Cratchit made the gravy (ready beforehand in a little saucepan) hissing hot; Master Peter mashed the potatoes with incredible vigour; Miss Belinda sweetened up the apple-sauce; Martha dusted the hot plates; Bob took Tiny Tim beside him in a tiny corner at the table; the two young Cratchits set chairs for everybody, not forgetting themselves, and mounting guard upon their posts, crammed spoons into their mouths, lest they should shriek for goose before their turn came to be helped."},{"start":135.3,"end":139.262,"text":"At last the dishes were set on, and grace was said."},{"start":139.262,"end":162.212,"text":"It was succeeded by a breathless pause, as Mrs. Cratchit, looking slowly all along the carving-knife, prepared to plunge it in the breast; but when she did, and when the long expected gush of stuffing issued forth, one murmur of delight arose all round the board, and even Tiny Tim, excited by the two young Cratchits, beat on the table with the handle of his knife, and feebly cried Hurrah!"},{"start":162.212,"end":164.687,"text":"There never was such a goose."},{"start":164.687,"end":168.562,"text":"Bob said he didn't believe there ever was such a goose cooked."},{"start":168.562,"end":174.75,"text":"Its tenderness and flavour, size and cheapness, were the themes of universal admiration."},{"start":174.75,"end":188.875,"text":"Eked out by the apple-sauce and mashed potatoes, it was a sufficient dinner for the whole family; indeed, as Mrs. Cratchit said with a great delight (surveying one small atom of a bone upon the dish), they hadn't ate it all at last!"},{"start":188.875,"end":196.225,"text":"Yet every one had had enough, and the youngest Cratchits in particular, were steeped in sage and onion to the eyebrows!"},{"start":196.225,"end":205.475,"text":"But now, the plates being changed by Miss Belinda, Mrs. Cratchit left the room alone--too nervous to bear witnesses--to take the pudding up, and bring it in."}]}},{"id":"III_08","number":8,"zh":{"text":"万一它没熟透可怎么好！\n万一倒出来时散了架可怎么好！\n万一趁他们吃鹅吃得高兴时，有谁翻过后院的墙、把它偷走了可怎么好：一想到这个，那两个小克拉奇特的脸都吓得发青了！\n各式各样的可怕念头都设想了个遍。\n喂！\n好大一团蒸汽！\n布丁出锅了。\n一股洗衣日似的气味！\n那是裹布的味儿。\n一股气味，像是一家饭馆和一家糕饼铺紧挨在一处，旁边又紧挨着一家洗衣作坊！\n那就是布丁的味儿。\n不出半分钟，克拉奇特太太进来了：脸涨得通红，却得意地微笑着：捧着那布丁，像一颗带斑点的炮弹，又硬又结实，烧着小半个及耳量的白兰地，蓝幽幽地燃着，顶上还插着圣诞冬青作装点。\n哦，好一个了不起的布丁！\n鲍勃·克拉奇特说——而且说得平心静气——他认为这是克拉奇特太太成亲以来取得的最大成就。\n克拉奇特太太说，这会儿心头一块石头落了地，她要招认，她原先对面粉的分量是有过疑虑的。\n人人都对它有一番说道，可没有一个人说、也没有一个人想这布丁对一大家子人来说嫌小了点。\n谁要那么说，简直就是赤裸裸的异端邪说。\n随便哪个克拉奇特，只要稍稍露出这么个意思，都会臊得满脸通红。\n这顿饭终于全吃完了，桌布撤了，炉床扫了，炉火也添旺了。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_III_小节08.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":2.65,"text":"万一它没熟透可怎么好！"},{"start":2.6,"end":5.525,"text":"万一倒出来时散了架可怎么好！"},{"start":5.525,"end":15.7,"text":"万一趁他们吃鹅吃得高兴时，有谁翻过后院的墙、把它偷走了可怎么好：一想到这个，那两个小克拉奇特的脸都吓得发青了！"},{"start":15.7,"end":18.812,"text":"各式各样的可怕念头都设想了个遍。"},{"start":18.812,"end":19.7,"text":"喂！"},{"start":19.7,"end":21.412,"text":"好大一团蒸汽！"},{"start":21.412,"end":22.912,"text":"布丁出锅了。"},{"start":22.912,"end":25.037,"text":"一股洗衣日似的气味！"},{"start":25.037,"end":26.687,"text":"那是裹布的味儿。"},{"start":26.687,"end":33.962,"text":"一股气味，像是一家饭馆和一家糕饼铺紧挨在一处，旁边又紧挨着一家洗衣作坊！"},{"start":33.962,"end":35.787,"text":"那就是布丁的味儿。"},{"start":35.787,"end":52.137,"text":"不出半分钟，克拉奇特太太进来了：脸涨得通红，却得意地微笑着：捧着那布丁，像一颗带斑点的炮弹，又硬又结实，烧着小半个及耳量的白兰地，蓝幽幽地燃着，顶上还插着圣诞冬青作装点。"},{"start":52.137,"end":54.612,"text":"哦，好一个了不起的布丁！"},{"start":54.612,"end":63.012,"text":"鲍勃·克拉奇特说——而且说得平心静气——他认为这是克拉奇特太太成亲以来取得的最大成就。"},{"start":63.012,"end":71.15,"text":"克拉奇特太太说，这会儿心头一块石头落了地，她要招认，她原先对面粉的分量是有过疑虑的。"},{"start":71.15,"end":78.812,"text":"人人都对它有一番说道，可没有一个人说、也没有一个人想这布丁对一大家子人来说嫌小了点。"},{"start":78.812,"end":82.662,"text":"谁要那么说，简直就是赤裸裸的异端邪说。"},{"start":82.662,"end":88.162,"text":"随便哪个克拉奇特，只要稍稍露出这么个意思，都会臊得满脸通红。"},{"start":88.162,"end":93.375,"text":"这顿饭终于全吃完了，桌布撤了，炉床扫了，炉火也添旺了。"}]},"en":{"text":"Suppose it should not be done enough!\nSuppose it should break in turning out!\nSuppose somebody should have got over the wall of the back-yard, and stolen it, while they were merry with the goose: a supposition at which the two young Cratchits became livid!\nAll sorts of horrors were supposed.\nHallo!\nA great deal of steam!\nThe pudding was out of the copper.\nA smell like a washing-day!\nThat was the cloth.\nA smell like an eating-house, and a pastry cook's next door to each other, with a laundress's next door to that!\nThat was the pudding.\nIn half a minute Mrs. Cratchit entered: flushed, but smiling proudly: with the pudding, like a speckled cannon-ball, so hard and firm, blazing in half of half-a-quartern of ignited brandy, and bedight with Christmas holly stuck into the top.\nOh, a wonderful pudding!\nBob Cratchit said, and calmly too, that he regarded it as the greatest success achieved by Mrs. Cratchit since their marriage.\nMrs. Cratchit said that now the weight was off her mind, she would confess she had had her doubts about the quantity of flour.\nEverybody had something to say about it, but nobody said or thought it was at all a small pudding for a large family.\nIt would have been flat heresy to do so.\nAny Cratchit would have blushed to hint at such a thing.\nAt last the dinner was all done, the cloth was cleared, the hearth swept, and the fire made up.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_III_小节08.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":2.85,"text":"Suppose it should not be done enough!"},{"start":2.8,"end":5.675,"text":"Suppose it should break in turning out!"},{"start":5.675,"end":15.512,"text":"Suppose somebody should have got over the wall of the back-yard, and stolen it, while they were merry with the goose: a supposition at which the two young Cratchits became livid!"},{"start":15.512,"end":18.475,"text":"All sorts of horrors were supposed."},{"start":18.475,"end":19.95,"text":"Hallo!"},{"start":19.95,"end":22.312,"text":"A great deal of steam!"},{"start":22.312,"end":24.712,"text":"The pudding was out of the copper."},{"start":24.712,"end":27.212,"text":"A smell like a washing-day!"},{"start":27.212,"end":29.187,"text":"That was the cloth."},{"start":29.187,"end":35.95,"text":"A smell like an eating-house, and a pastry cook's next door to each other, with a laundress's next door to that!"},{"start":35.95,"end":37.8,"text":"That was the pudding."},{"start":37.8,"end":52.037,"text":"In half a minute Mrs. Cratchit entered: flushed, but smiling proudly: with the pudding, like a speckled cannon-ball, so hard and firm, blazing in half of half-a-quartern of ignited brandy, and bedight with Christmas holly stuck into the top."},{"start":52.037,"end":54.575,"text":"Oh, a wonderful pudding!"},{"start":54.575,"end":62.65,"text":"Bob Cratchit said, and calmly too, that he regarded it as the greatest success achieved by Mrs. Cratchit since their marriage."},{"start":62.65,"end":69.787,"text":"Mrs. Cratchit said that now the weight was off her mind, she would confess she had had her doubts about the quantity of flour."},{"start":69.787,"end":76.512,"text":"Everybody had something to say about it, but nobody said or thought it was at all a small pudding for a large family."},{"start":76.512,"end":79.525,"text":"It would have been flat heresy to do so."},{"start":79.525,"end":83.037,"text":"Any Cratchit would have blushed to hint at such a thing."},{"start":83.037,"end":89.45,"text":"At last the dinner was all done, the cloth was cleared, the hearth swept, and the fire made up."}]}},{"id":"III_09","number":9,"zh":{"text":"罐子里调好的饮料尝过了，公认是再好不过，便把苹果和橙子摆上桌，又往火里添了一铲栗子。\n随后全家克拉奇特围着炉床坐下，照鲍勃·克拉奇特的说法是围成一\"圈\"，其实不过半圈罢了；鲍勃·克拉奇特胳膊肘边摆着这家子全部的玻璃器皿：两只平底杯，外加一只没把儿的奶蛋盅。\n不过，这几样盛起罐子里那热饮来，倒跟金酒杯一样使得；鲍勃满面春风地一一斟着，火里的栗子噼噼啪啪炸得正欢。\n随后鲍勃举杯祝道：\"祝咱们大家圣诞快乐，我亲爱的们。\n上帝保佑咱们！\"\n全家人也都跟着应和了一遍。\n\"上帝保佑咱们每一个人！\"小蒂姆末了一个说道。\n他紧挨着父亲身边，坐在他那张小凳上。\n鲍勃把他那只枯瘦的小手攥在自己手里，仿佛深爱着这孩子，盼着把他留在身边，又生怕他会从自己身边被夺走。\n\"精灵，\"斯克鲁奇怀着一种他从未有过的关切说，\"告诉我，小蒂姆能不能活下来。\"\n\"我看见一个空座位，\"那鬼魂答道，\"在那贫寒的炉角里；还有一根没了主人的拐杖，被小心地保存着。\n倘若这些影子不被未来改变，这孩子就会死。\"\n\"不，不，\"斯克鲁奇说。\n\"哦不，善良的精灵！说他会得救吧。\"\n\"倘若这些影子不被未来改变，那么我那一族里再没有别的，\"那鬼魂回道，\"会在这儿见着他了。\n那又怎么样呢？\n他既然要死，就不如早死，也好减一减这过剩的人口。\"\n斯克鲁奇听那精灵引用自己的话，垂下了头，悔恨和悲伤一齐涌上心头。\n\"人哪，\"那鬼魂说，\"你心里头若当真是个人、而非铁石，就别再说那恶毒的滥调了，除非你已弄清那'过剩'是什么、又在哪里。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_III_小节09.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":8.087,"text":"罐子里调好的饮料尝过了，公认是再好不过，便把苹果和橙子摆上桌，又往火里添了一铲栗子。"},{"start":8.037,"end":24.487,"text":"随后全家克拉奇特围着炉床坐下，照鲍勃·克拉奇特的说法是围成一\"圈\"，其实不过半圈罢了；鲍勃·克拉奇特胳膊肘边摆着这家子全部的玻璃器皿：两只平底杯，外加一只没把儿的奶蛋盅。"},{"start":24.487,"end":34.975,"text":"不过，这几样盛起罐子里那热饮来，倒跟金酒杯一样使得；鲍勃满面春风地一一斟着，火里的栗子噼噼啪啪炸得正欢。"},{"start":34.975,"end":39.75,"text":"随后鲍勃举杯祝道：\"祝咱们大家圣诞快乐，我亲爱的们。"},{"start":39.75,"end":41.45,"text":"上帝保佑咱们！"},{"start":41.45,"end":44.1,"text":"全家人也都跟着应和了一遍。"},{"start":44.1,"end":48.075,"text":"上帝保佑咱们每一个人！\"小蒂姆末了一个说道。"},{"start":48.075,"end":51.687,"text":"他紧挨着父亲身边，坐在他那张小凳上。"},{"start":51.687,"end":61.375,"text":"鲍勃把他那只枯瘦的小手攥在自己手里，仿佛深爱着这孩子，盼着把他留在身边，又生怕他会从自己身边被夺走。"},{"start":61.375,"end":68.125,"text":"精灵，\"斯克鲁奇怀着一种他从未有过的关切说，\"告诉我，小蒂姆能不能活下来。"},{"start":68.125,"end":76.087,"text":"我看见一个空座位，\"那鬼魂答道，\"在那贫寒的炉角里；还有一根没了主人的拐杖，被小心地保存着。"},{"start":76.087,"end":80.037,"text":"倘若这些影子不被未来改变，这孩子就会死。"},{"start":80.037,"end":82.437,"text":"不，不，\"斯克鲁奇说。"},{"start":82.437,"end":84.537,"text":"哦不，善良的精灵！"},{"start":84.537,"end":86.35,"text":"说他会得救吧。"},{"start":86.35,"end":93.837,"text":"倘若这些影子不被未来改变，那么我那一族里再没有别的，\"那鬼魂回道，\"会在这儿见着他了。"},{"start":93.837,"end":95.312,"text":"那又怎么样呢？"},{"start":95.312,"end":100.362,"text":"他既然要死，就不如早死，也好减一减这过剩的人口。"},{"start":100.362,"end":106.887,"text":"斯克鲁奇听那精灵引用自己的话，垂下了头，悔恨和悲伤一齐涌上心头。"},{"start":106.887,"end":117.837,"text":"人哪，\"那鬼魂说，\"你心里头若当真是个人、而非铁石，就别再说那恶毒的滥调了，除非你已弄清那'过剩'是什么、又在哪里。"}]},"en":{"text":"The compound in the jug being tasted and considered perfect, apples and oranges were put upon the table, and a shovel-full of chesnuts on the fire.\nThen all the Cratchit family drew round the hearth, in what Bob Cratchit called a circle, meaning half a one; and at Bob Cratchit's elbow stood the family display of glass; two tumblers, and a custard-cup without a handle.\nThese held the hot stuff from the jug, however, as well as golden goblets would have done; and Bob served it out with beaming looks, while the chesnuts on the fire sputtered and crackled noisily.\nThen Bob proposed: \"A Merry Christmas to us all, my dears.\nGod bless us!\"\nWhich all the family re-echoed.\n\"God bless us every one!\" said Tiny Tim, the last of all.\nHe sat very close to his father's side, upon his little stool.\nBob held his withered little hand in his, as if he loved the child, and wished to keep him by his side, and dreaded that he might be taken from him.\n\"Spirit,\" said Scrooge, with an interest he had never felt before, \"tell me if Tiny Tim will live.\"\n\"I see a vacant seat,\" replied the Ghost, \"in the poor chimney corner, and a crutch without an owner, carefully preserved.\nIf these shadows remain unaltered by the Future, the child will die.\"\n\"No, no,\" said Scrooge.\n\"Oh no, kind Spirit! say he will be spared.\"\n\"If these shadows remain unaltered by the Future, none other of my race,\" returned the Ghost, \"will find him here.\nWhat then?\nIf he be like to die, he had better do it, and decrease the surplus population.\"\nScrooge hung his head to hear his own words quoted by the Spirit, and was overcome with penitence and grief.\n\"Man,\" said the Ghost, \"if man you be in heart, not adamant, forbear that wicked cant until you have discovered What the surplus is, and Where it is.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_III_小节09.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":8.637,"text":"The compound in the jug being tasted and considered perfect, apples and oranges were put upon the table, and a shovel-full of chesnuts on the fire."},{"start":8.587,"end":22.037,"text":"Then all the Cratchit family drew round the hearth, in what Bob Cratchit called a circle, meaning half a one; and at Bob Cratchit's elbow stood the family display of glass; two tumblers, and a custard-cup without a handle."},{"start":22.037,"end":33.162,"text":"These held the hot stuff from the jug, however, as well as golden goblets would have done; and Bob served it out with beaming looks, while the chesnuts on the fire sputtered and crackled noisily."},{"start":33.162,"end":38,"text":"Then Bob proposed: \"A Merry Christmas to us all, my dears."},{"start":38,"end":39.962,"text":"God bless us!"},{"start":39.962,"end":42.525,"text":"Which all the family re-echoed."},{"start":42.525,"end":47.212,"text":"God bless us every one!\" said Tiny Tim, the last of all."},{"start":47.212,"end":51.687,"text":"He sat very close to his father's side, upon his little stool."},{"start":51.687,"end":60.412,"text":"Bob held his withered little hand in his, as if he loved the child, and wished to keep him by his side, and dreaded that he might be taken from him."},{"start":60.412,"end":66.95,"text":"Spirit,\" said Scrooge, with an interest he had never felt before, \"tell me if Tiny Tim will live."},{"start":66.95,"end":74.837,"text":"I see a vacant seat,\" replied the Ghost, \"in the poor chimney corner, and a crutch without an owner, carefully preserved."},{"start":74.837,"end":79.562,"text":"If these shadows remain unaltered by the Future, the child will die."},{"start":79.562,"end":82.537,"text":"No, no,\" said Scrooge."},{"start":82.537,"end":85.162,"text":"Oh no, kind Spirit!"},{"start":85.162,"end":87.487,"text":"say he will be spared."},{"start":87.487,"end":94.762,"text":"If these shadows remain unaltered by the Future, none other of my race,\" returned the Ghost, \"will find him here."},{"start":94.762,"end":96.187,"text":"What then?"},{"start":96.187,"end":101.637,"text":"If he be like to die, he had better do it, and decrease the surplus population."},{"start":101.637,"end":108.25,"text":"Scrooge hung his head to hear his own words quoted by the Spirit, and was overcome with penitence and grief."},{"start":108.25,"end":117.712,"text":"Man,\" said the Ghost, \"if man you be in heart, not adamant, forbear that wicked cant until you have discovered What the surplus is, and Where it is."}]}},{"id":"III_10","number":10,"zh":{"text":"难道由你来决定哪些人该活、哪些人该死吗？\n说不定在上天眼里，比起千千万万像这穷人孩子一样的人来，你才更没价值、更不配活着呢。\n哦天哪！竟听见叶子上的虫豸，对着尘土里它那些挨饿的弟兄，妄论起谁的命太多余来了！\"\n斯克鲁奇在那鬼魂的斥责下低下了头，哆嗦着把眼睛投向地面。\n可他一听见自己的名字，便飞快地抬起了眼。\n\"斯克鲁奇先生！\"鲍勃说，\"我来给大家敬斯克鲁奇先生，这盛宴的奠基人！\"\n\"亏他还是这盛宴的奠基人呢！\"克拉奇特太太涨红了脸嚷道。\n\"我真希望他这会儿就在这儿。\n我准把心里头的话全端出来给他享用，但愿他胃口好，受用得了。\"\n\"我亲爱的，\"鲍勃说，\"孩子们呢；今儿是圣诞节啊。\"\n\"那敢情是圣诞节喽，\"她说，\"不然谁会去给斯克鲁奇先生这么个可憎、吝啬、铁石、冷酷的人祝健康呢。\n你心里清楚他就是这号人，罗伯特！\n没人比你更清楚了，可怜的人哪！\"\n\"我亲爱的，\"鲍勃温和地答道，\"今儿是圣诞节啊。\"\n\"看在你和这日子的份上，我就给他祝个健康吧，\"克拉奇特太太说，\"可不是看在他的份上。\n祝他长命百岁！\n圣诞快乐，新年快乐！——他准会快快活活、高高兴兴的，这我毫不怀疑！\"\n孩子们跟在她后头干了这杯。\n这是他们今晚头一桩做得没半点真心实意的事。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_III_小节10.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":4.3,"text":"难道由你来决定哪些人该活、哪些人该死吗？"},{"start":4.25,"end":11.7,"text":"说不定在上天眼里，比起千千万万像这穷人孩子一样的人来，你才更没价值、更不配活着呢。"},{"start":11.7,"end":13.012,"text":"哦天哪！"},{"start":13.012,"end":20.175,"text":"竟听见叶子上的虫豸，对着尘土里它那些挨饿的弟兄，妄论起谁的命太多余来了！"},{"start":20.175,"end":25.962,"text":"斯克鲁奇在那鬼魂的斥责下低下了头，哆嗦着把眼睛投向地面。"},{"start":25.962,"end":29.85,"text":"可他一听见自己的名字，便飞快地抬起了眼。"},{"start":29.85,"end":35.825,"text":"斯克鲁奇先生！\"鲍勃说，\"我来给大家敬斯克鲁奇先生，这盛宴的奠基人！"},{"start":35.825,"end":41.025,"text":"亏他还是这盛宴的奠基人呢！\"克拉奇特太太涨红了脸嚷道。"},{"start":41.025,"end":43.362,"text":"我真希望他这会儿就在这儿。"},{"start":43.362,"end":48.775,"text":"我准把心里头的话全端出来给他享用，但愿他胃口好，受用得了。"},{"start":48.775,"end":53.05,"text":"我亲爱的，\"鲍勃说，\"孩子们呢；今儿是圣诞节啊。"},{"start":53.05,"end":62.537,"text":"那敢情是圣诞节喽，\"她说，\"不然谁会去给斯克鲁奇先生这么个可憎、吝啬、铁石、冷酷的人祝健康呢。"},{"start":62.537,"end":65.85,"text":"你心里清楚他就是这号人，罗伯特！"},{"start":65.85,"end":68.862,"text":"没人比你更清楚了，可怜的人哪！"},{"start":68.862,"end":72.85,"text":"我亲爱的，\"鲍勃温和地答道，\"今儿是圣诞节啊。"},{"start":72.85,"end":80.037,"text":"看在你和这日子的份上，我就给他祝个健康吧，\"克拉奇特太太说，\"可不是看在他的份上。"},{"start":80.037,"end":81.9,"text":"祝他长命百岁！"},{"start":81.9,"end":84.162,"text":"圣诞快乐，新年快乐！"},{"start":84.162,"end":88.387,"text":"他准会快快活活、高高兴兴的，这我毫不怀疑！"},{"start":88.387,"end":91.125,"text":"孩子们跟在她后头干了这杯。"},{"start":91.125,"end":95.475,"text":"这是他们今晚头一桩做得没半点真心实意的事。"}]},"en":{"text":"Will you decide what men shall live, what men shall die?\nIt may be, that in the sight of Heaven, you are more worthless and less fit to live than millions like this poor man's child.\nOh God! to hear the Insect on the leaf pronouncing on the too much life among his hungry brothers in the dust!\"\nScrooge bent before the Ghost's rebuke, and trembling cast his eyes upon the ground.\nBut he raised them speedily, on hearing his own name.\n\"Mr. Scrooge!\" said Bob; \"I'll give you Mr. Scrooge, the Founder of the Feast!\"\n\"The Founder of the Feast indeed!\" cried Mrs. Cratchit, reddening.\n\"I wish I had him here.\nI'd give him a piece of my mind to feast upon, and I hope he'd have a good appetite for it.\"\n\"My dear,\" said Bob, \"the children; Christmas Day.\"\n\"It should be Christmas Day, I am sure,\" said she, \"on which one drinks the health of such an odious, stingy, hard, unfeeling man as Mr. Scrooge.\nYou know he is, Robert!\nNobody knows it better than you do, poor fellow!\"\n\"My dear,\" was Bob's mild answer, \"Christmas Day.\"\n\"I'll drink his health for your sake and the Day's,\" said Mrs. Cratchit, \"not for his.\nLong life to him!\nA Merry Christmas and a happy new year!--he'll be very merry and very happy, I have no doubt!\"\nThe children drank the toast after her.\nIt was the first of their proceedings which had no heartiness in it.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_III_小节10.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":4.187,"text":"Will you decide what men shall live, what men shall die?"},{"start":4.137,"end":11.737,"text":"It may be, that in the sight of Heaven, you are more worthless and less fit to live than millions like this poor man's child."},{"start":11.737,"end":13.375,"text":"Oh God!"},{"start":13.375,"end":19.175,"text":"to hear the Insect on the leaf pronouncing on the too much life among his hungry brothers in the dust!"},{"start":19.175,"end":24.75,"text":"Scrooge bent before the Ghost's rebuke, and trembling cast his eyes upon the ground."},{"start":24.75,"end":28.6,"text":"But he raised them speedily, on hearing his own name."},{"start":28.6,"end":34.337,"text":"Mr. Scrooge!\" said Bob; \"I'll give you Mr. Scrooge, the Founder of the Feast!"},{"start":34.337,"end":39.112,"text":"The Founder of the Feast indeed!\" cried Mrs. Cratchit, reddening."},{"start":39.112,"end":41.225,"text":"I wish I had him here."},{"start":41.225,"end":46.687,"text":"I'd give him a piece of my mind to feast upon, and I hope he'd have a good appetite for it."},{"start":46.687,"end":50.975,"text":"My dear,\" said Bob, \"the children; Christmas Day."},{"start":50.975,"end":61.137,"text":"It should be Christmas Day, I am sure,\" said she, \"on which one drinks the health of such an odious, stingy, hard, unfeeling man as Mr. Scrooge."},{"start":61.137,"end":63.75,"text":"You know he is, Robert!"},{"start":63.75,"end":67.45,"text":"Nobody knows it better than you do, poor fellow!"},{"start":67.45,"end":71.712,"text":"My dear,\" was Bob's mild answer, \"Christmas Day."},{"start":71.712,"end":77.15,"text":"I'll drink his health for your sake and the Day's,\" said Mrs. Cratchit, \"not for his."},{"start":77.15,"end":79.137,"text":"Long life to him!"},{"start":79.137,"end":85.45,"text":"A Merry Christmas and a happy new year!--he'll be very merry and very happy, I have no doubt!"},{"start":85.45,"end":88.287,"text":"The children drank the toast after her."},{"start":88.287,"end":92.237,"text":"It was the first of their proceedings which had no heartiness in it."}]}},{"id":"III_11","number":11,"zh":{"text":"小蒂姆末了一个干了杯，可他压根没把这敬酒放在心上。\n斯克鲁奇是这一家子眼里的吃人妖魔。\n一提起他的名字，便给这聚会投下一道阴影，足足五分钟也驱散不开。\n等这阴影过去了，他们反倒比先前快活了十倍，单单因为可算把那扫兴的斯克鲁奇打发过去了。\n鲍勃·克拉奇特告诉他们，他替彼得少爷物色了一个差事，要是能弄到手，一礼拜足足能挣五先令六便士。\n那两个小克拉奇特一想到彼得要做生意人，便笑得前仰后合；彼得自己呢，从两片领子中间若有所思地望着炉火，仿佛在盘算着，等他领上那笔叫人眼花缭乱的薪水，该挑哪几样买卖去投。\n玛莎在一家女帽店当个可怜的学徒，这会儿便告诉他们她得干些什么活、一气要干上多少钟头、她打算明儿早上怎样赖在床上好好歇个够；因为明天是个假日，她要在家里过。\n她还说前些日子怎样见着了一位伯爵夫人和一位勋爵，那勋爵\"个头差不多跟彼得一般高\"；彼得听了把领子拉得老高，你便是在场，也瞧不见他的脑袋了。\n这一向，栗子和酒罐传来传去；不一会儿小蒂姆给他们唱了一支歌，唱的是一个迷路的孩子在雪地里走着；他嗓音又细又凄婉，唱得着实很好。\n这里头并没有什么了不得的。\n他们不是个标致的人家；他们穿得不体面；他们的鞋子离不漏水还差得远；他们的衣裳单薄；彼得多半，而且十有八九，是进过当铺、识得里头光景的。\n可他们快活、感恩、彼此投缘、安于眼前的时光；当他们渐渐隐去、在那精灵临别时火炬洒下的明亮甘霖里显得越发快活时，斯克鲁奇一直盯着他们，尤其盯着小蒂姆，直到最后。\n这工夫天渐渐黑了，雪也下得相当大了；斯克鲁奇和那精灵沿街走着，厨房、客厅以及各式各样房间里那熊熊炉火的明亮，真叫人称奇。\n这边，那摇曳的火光映出一桌温馨晚餐的张罗，热乎乎的盘子在火前烘得透透的，深红的帷幔预备好了要拉上，把寒冷和黑暗都关在外头。\n那边，全家的孩子都奔进雪地里去迎接出了嫁的姐姐、成了家的哥哥，迎接堂表兄弟姐妹、叔伯姑姨，争着头一个上前问好。\n这边，又见窗帘上映着宾客聚拢的影子；那边一群标致姑娘，个个戴着风帽、穿着毛皮靴，叽叽喳喳地一齐说着话，轻盈地碎步走向附近某家邻舍；可怜哪个单身汉瞧见她们走进门去——这些个狡黠的小妖精，她们心里头门儿清——一个个红光满面！\n可你若单凭那些赶赴友人聚会的人数去估量，倒会以为他们到了地方竟没人在家迎接他们呢，殊不知家家户户都盼着客来，把炉火堆得半截烟囱那么高。\n天保佑它，那鬼魂多么欢欣鼓舞啊！\n它怎样袒开它那宽阔的胸膛，摊开它那宽大的手掌，一路飘着，慷慨地伸出手来，把它那明亮无害的欢乐倾洒到所及的一切之上！","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_III_小节11.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":4.925,"text":"小蒂姆末了一个干了杯，可他压根没把这敬酒放在心上。"},{"start":4.875,"end":8.362,"text":"斯克鲁奇是这一家子眼里的吃人妖魔。"},{"start":8.362,"end":14.775,"text":"一提起他的名字，便给这聚会投下一道阴影，足足五分钟也驱散不开。"},{"start":14.775,"end":22.437,"text":"等这阴影过去了，他们反倒比先前快活了十倍，单单因为可算把那扫兴的斯克鲁奇打发过去了。"},{"start":22.437,"end":31.3,"text":"鲍勃·克拉奇特告诉他们，他替彼得少爷物色了一个差事，要是能弄到手，一礼拜足足能挣五先令六便士。"},{"start":31.3,"end":46.8,"text":"那两个小克拉奇特一想到彼得要做生意人，便笑得前仰后合；彼得自己呢，从两片领子中间若有所思地望着炉火，仿佛在盘算着，等他领上那笔叫人眼花缭乱的薪水，该挑哪几样买卖去投。"},{"start":46.8,"end":61.162,"text":"玛莎在一家女帽店当个可怜的学徒，这会儿便告诉他们她得干些什么活、一气要干上多少钟头、她打算明儿早上怎样赖在床上好好歇个够；因为明天是个假日，她要在家里过。"},{"start":61.162,"end":73.937,"text":"她还说前些日子怎样见着了一位伯爵夫人和一位勋爵，那勋爵\"个头差不多跟彼得一般高\"；彼得听了把领子拉得老高，你便是在场，也瞧不见他的脑袋了。"},{"start":73.937,"end":86.7,"text":"这一向，栗子和酒罐传来传去；不一会儿小蒂姆给他们唱了一支歌，唱的是一个迷路的孩子在雪地里走着；他嗓音又细又凄婉，唱得着实很好。"},{"start":86.7,"end":89.05,"text":"这里头并没有什么了不得的。"},{"start":89.05,"end":102.137,"text":"他们不是个标致的人家；他们穿得不体面；他们的鞋子离不漏水还差得远；他们的衣裳单薄；彼得多半，而且十有八九，是进过当铺、识得里头光景的。"},{"start":102.137,"end":117.9,"text":"可他们快活、感恩、彼此投缘、安于眼前的时光；当他们渐渐隐去、在那精灵临别时火炬洒下的明亮甘霖里显得越发快活时，斯克鲁奇一直盯着他们，尤其盯着小蒂姆，直到最后。"},{"start":117.9,"end":130.212,"text":"这工夫天渐渐黑了，雪也下得相当大了；斯克鲁奇和那精灵沿街走着，厨房、客厅以及各式各样房间里那熊熊炉火的明亮，真叫人称奇。"},{"start":130.212,"end":141.937,"text":"这边，那摇曳的火光映出一桌温馨晚餐的张罗，热乎乎的盘子在火前烘得透透的，深红的帷幔预备好了要拉上，把寒冷和黑暗都关在外头。"},{"start":141.937,"end":152.525,"text":"那边，全家的孩子都奔进雪地里去迎接出了嫁的姐姐、成了家的哥哥，迎接堂表兄弟姐妹、叔伯姑姨，争着头一个上前问好。"},{"start":152.525,"end":172.675,"text":"这边，又见窗帘上映着宾客聚拢的影子；那边一群标致姑娘，个个戴着风帽、穿着毛皮靴，叽叽喳喳地一齐说着话，轻盈地碎步走向附近某家邻舍；可怜哪个单身汉瞧见她们走进门去——这些个狡黠的小妖精，她们心里头门儿清——一个个红光满面！"},{"start":172.675,"end":185.725,"text":"可你若单凭那些赶赴友人聚会的人数去估量，倒会以为他们到了地方竟没人在家迎接他们呢，殊不知家家户户都盼着客来，把炉火堆得半截烟囱那么高。"},{"start":185.725,"end":189.062,"text":"天保佑它，那鬼魂多么欢欣鼓舞啊！"},{"start":189.062,"end":200.5,"text":"它怎样袒开它那宽阔的胸膛，摊开它那宽大的手掌，一路飘着，慷慨地伸出手来，把它那明亮无害的欢乐倾洒到所及的一切之上！"}]},"en":{"text":"Tiny Tim drank it last of all, but he didn't care twopence for it.\nScrooge was the Ogre of the family.\nThe mention of his name cast a dark shadow on the party, which was not dispelled for full five minutes.\nAfter it had passed away, they were ten times merrier than before, from the mere relief of Scrooge the Baleful being done with.\nBob Cratchit told them how he had a situation in his eye for Master Peter, which would bring in, if obtained, full five-and-sixpence weekly.\nThe two young Cratchits laughed tremendously at the idea of Peter's being a man of business; and Peter himself looked thoughtfully at the fire from between his collars, as if he were deliberating what particular investments he should favour when he came into the receipt of that bewildering income.\nMartha, who was a poor apprentice at a milliner's, then told them what kind of work she had to do, and how many hours she worked at a stretch, and how she meant to lie a-bed to-morrow morning for a good long rest; to-morrow being a holiday she passed at home.\nAlso how she had seen a countess and a lord some days before, and how the lord \"was much about as tall as Peter;\" at which Peter pulled up his collars so high that you couldn't have seen his head if you had been there.\nAll this time the chesnuts and the jug went round and round; and bye and bye they had a song, about a lost child travelling in the snow, from Tiny Tim; who had a plaintive little voice, and sang it very well indeed.\nThere was nothing of high mark in this.\nThey were not a handsome family; they were not well dressed; their shoes were far from being waterproof; their clothes were scanty; and Peter might have known, and very likely did, the inside of a pawnbroker's.\nBut they were happy, grateful, pleased with one another, and contented with the time; and when they faded, and looked happier yet in the bright sprinklings of the Spirit's torch at parting, Scrooge had his eye upon them, and especially on Tiny Tim, until the last.\nBy this time it was getting dark, and snowing pretty heavily; and as Scrooge and the Spirit went along the streets, the brightness of the roaring fires in kitchens, parlours, and all sorts of rooms, was wonderful.\nHere, the flickering of the blaze showed preparations for a cosy dinner, with hot plates baking through and through before the fire, and deep red curtains, ready to be drawn, to shut out cold and darkness.\nThere, all the children of the house were running out into the snow to meet their married sisters, brothers, cousins, uncles, aunts, and be the first to greet them.\nHere, again, were shadows on the window-blind of guests assembling; and there a group of handsome girls, all hooded and fur-booted, and all chattering at once, tripped lightly off to some near neighbour's house; where, wo upon the single man who saw them enter--artful witches: well they knew it--in a glow!\nBut if you had judged from the numbers of people on their way to friendly gatherings, you might have thought that no one was at home to give them welcome when they got there, instead of every house expecting company, and piling up its fires half-chimney high.\nBlessings on it, how the Ghost exulted!\nHow it bared its breadth of breast, and opened its capacious palm, and floated on, outpouring, with a generous hand, its bright and harmless mirth on everything within its reach!","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_III_小节11.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":4.537,"text":"Tiny Tim drank it last of all, but he didn't care twopence for it."},{"start":4.487,"end":7.262,"text":"Scrooge was the Ogre of the family."},{"start":7.262,"end":13.562,"text":"The mention of his name cast a dark shadow on the party, which was not dispelled for full five minutes."},{"start":13.562,"end":21.012,"text":"After it had passed away, they were ten times merrier than before, from the mere relief of Scrooge the Baleful being done with."},{"start":21.012,"end":29.762,"text":"Bob Cratchit told them how he had a situation in his eye for Master Peter, which would bring in, if obtained, full five-and-sixpence weekly."},{"start":29.762,"end":44.737,"text":"The two young Cratchits laughed tremendously at the idea of Peter's being a man of business; and Peter himself looked thoughtfully at the fire from between his collars, as if he were deliberating what particular investments he should favour when he came into the receipt of that bewildering income."},{"start":44.737,"end":59.562,"text":"Martha, who was a poor apprentice at a milliner's, then told them what kind of work she had to do, and how many hours she worked at a stretch, and how she meant to lie a-bed to-morrow morning for a good long rest; to-morrow being a holiday she passed at home."},{"start":59.562,"end":71.2,"text":"Also how she had seen a countess and a lord some days before, and how the lord \"was much about as tall as Peter;\" at which Peter pulled up his collars so high that you couldn't have seen his head if you had been there."},{"start":71.2,"end":84.487,"text":"All this time the chesnuts and the jug went round and round; and bye and bye they had a song, about a lost child travelling in the snow, from Tiny Tim; who had a plaintive little voice, and sang it very well indeed."},{"start":84.487,"end":87.287,"text":"There was nothing of high mark in this."},{"start":87.287,"end":100.037,"text":"They were not a handsome family; they were not well dressed; their shoes were far from being waterproof; their clothes were scanty; and Peter might have known, and very likely did, the inside of a pawnbroker's."},{"start":100.037,"end":114.775,"text":"But they were happy, grateful, pleased with one another, and contented with the time; and when they faded, and looked happier yet in the bright sprinklings of the Spirit's torch at parting, Scrooge had his eye upon them, and especially on Tiny Tim, until the last."},{"start":114.775,"end":127.475,"text":"By this time it was getting dark, and snowing pretty heavily; and as Scrooge and the Spirit went along the streets, the brightness of the roaring fires in kitchens, parlours, and all sorts of rooms, was wonderful."},{"start":127.475,"end":139.737,"text":"Here, the flickering of the blaze showed preparations for a cosy dinner, with hot plates baking through and through before the fire, and deep red curtains, ready to be drawn, to shut out cold and darkness."},{"start":139.737,"end":149.5,"text":"There, all the children of the house were running out into the snow to meet their married sisters, brothers, cousins, uncles, aunts, and be the first to greet them."},{"start":149.5,"end":167.15,"text":"Here, again, were shadows on the window-blind of guests assembling; and there a group of handsome girls, all hooded and fur-booted, and all chattering at once, tripped lightly off to some near neighbour's house; where, wo upon the single man who saw them enter--artful witches: well they knew it--in a glow!"},{"start":167.15,"end":180.087,"text":"But if you had judged from the numbers of people on their way to friendly gatherings, you might have thought that no one was at home to give them welcome when they got there, instead of every house expecting company, and piling up its fires half-chimney high."},{"start":180.087,"end":183.312,"text":"Blessings on it, how the Ghost exulted!"},{"start":183.312,"end":194.2,"text":"How it bared its breadth of breast, and opened its capacious palm, and floated on, outpouring, with a generous hand, its bright and harmless mirth on everything within its reach!"}]}},{"id":"III_12","number":12,"zh":{"text":"便是那点灯人——他在前头跑着，把昏暗的街道点上一星一点的光，又打扮停当要上哪儿去消磨这一晚——在那精灵走过时也放声大笑了起来：尽管这点灯人压根不晓得，除了圣诞节，还有谁在他身边作伴！\n这会儿，那鬼魂连半句招呼也没打，他们便立在了一片荒凉的旷野上，那儿乱抛着一堆堆狰狞的粗石，仿佛是巨人的葬身之地；水想往哪儿淌就往哪儿淌——本该如此，要不是寒霜把它囚住了的话；那儿除了青苔、荆豆和粗粝丛生的野草，什么也不长。\n西边天底下，落日留下一道火红的余痕，刹那间像一只阴郁的眼睛瞪着这片荒凉，随即越皱越低、越低、越低，终于隐没进那最深的黑夜浓重的幽暗里。\n\"这是什么地方？\"斯克鲁奇问。\n\"是矿工住的地方，他们在大地的肚腹里劳作，\"那精灵答道。\n\"可他们认得我。\n你瞧！\"\n一间小屋的窗子里透出一点灯光，他们便迅速朝它走去。\n穿过那泥石砌的墙，他们瞧见一伙快活的人围着一炉旺火聚在一处。\n一对老得不能再老的老夫妻，带着他们的儿女、儿女的儿女，再往下还有一辈，个个喜气洋洋地穿着节日的盛装。\n那老头儿用一种难得高过这荒原上呼啸风声的嗓音，给他们唱着一支圣诞歌；在他还是个孩子的时候，这就已经是支很老很老的歌了；他们时不时一齐加进副歌里去。\n他们一放开嗓子，那老头儿便十分欢快、声音也响亮起来；他们一停下，他的劲头便又低落下去。\n那精灵没在这儿耽搁，只叫斯克鲁奇抓住他的袍子，越过那旷野往前飞去，飞往何处？\n不会是海上吧？\n正是海上。\n叫斯克鲁奇骇然的是，回头一望，他瞧见陆地的尽头，一道可怕的礁岩，落在他们身后；他的耳朵被那雷鸣般的水声震得发聋，那水翻滚着、咆哮着、在它冲蚀出的一个个可怖洞窟间狂怒地奔突，凶猛地要把大地的根基掏空。\n在离岸约莫一里格的一片阴森的暗礁上——一年到头任凭浪涛在那上头冲刷、拍击——孤零零地立着一座灯塔。\n大堆大堆的海藻攀附在它的塔基上，那些暴风鸟——你大可以说它们是风所生，正如海藻是水所生——绕着它一起一落，像它们掠过的波浪一样。\n可就连在这儿，两个守灯塔的人也生起了一炉火，那火光透过厚石墙上的射孔，向那可怖的大海投出一道明亮。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_III_小节12.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":16.275,"text":"便是那点灯人——他在前头跑着，把昏暗的街道点上一星一点的光，又打扮停当要上哪儿去消磨这一晚——在那精灵走过时也放声大笑了起来：尽管这点灯人压根不晓得，除了圣诞节，还有谁在他身边作伴！"},{"start":16.275,"end":37.1,"text":"这会儿，那鬼魂连半句招呼也没打，他们便立在了一片荒凉的旷野上，那儿乱抛着一堆堆狰狞的粗石，仿佛是巨人的葬身之地；水想往哪儿淌就往哪儿淌——本该如此，要不是寒霜把它囚住了的话；那儿除了青苔、荆豆和粗粝丛生的野草，什么也不长。"},{"start":37.1,"end":51.05,"text":"西边天底下，落日留下一道火红的余痕，刹那间像一只阴郁的眼睛瞪着这片荒凉，随即越皱越低、越低、越低，终于隐没进那最深的黑夜浓重的幽暗里。"},{"start":51.05,"end":53.662,"text":"这是什么地方？\"斯克鲁奇问。"},{"start":53.662,"end":58.625,"text":"是矿工住的地方，他们在大地的肚腹里劳作，\"那精灵答道。"},{"start":58.625,"end":60.287,"text":"可他们认得我。"},{"start":60.287,"end":61.362,"text":"你瞧！"},{"start":61.362,"end":66.487,"text":"一间小屋的窗子里透出一点灯光，他们便迅速朝它走去。"},{"start":66.487,"end":72.425,"text":"穿过那泥石砌的墙，他们瞧见一伙快活的人围着一炉旺火聚在一处。"},{"start":72.425,"end":81.875,"text":"一对老得不能再老的老夫妻，带着他们的儿女、儿女的儿女，再往下还有一辈，个个喜气洋洋地穿着节日的盛装。"},{"start":81.875,"end":95.5,"text":"那老头儿用一种难得高过这荒原上呼啸风声的嗓音，给他们唱着一支圣诞歌；在他还是个孩子的时候，这就已经是支很老很老的歌了；他们时不时一齐加进副歌里去。"},{"start":95.5,"end":103.837,"text":"他们一放开嗓子，那老头儿便十分欢快、声音也响亮起来；他们一停下，他的劲头便又低落下去。"},{"start":103.837,"end":111.112,"text":"那精灵没在这儿耽搁，只叫斯克鲁奇抓住他的袍子，越过那旷野往前飞去，飞往何处？"},{"start":111.112,"end":112.687,"text":"不会是海上吧？"},{"start":112.687,"end":114.112,"text":"正是海上。"},{"start":114.112,"end":133.525,"text":"叫斯克鲁奇骇然的是，回头一望，他瞧见陆地的尽头，一道可怕的礁岩，落在他们身后；他的耳朵被那雷鸣般的水声震得发聋，那水翻滚着、咆哮着、在它冲蚀出的一个个可怖洞窟间狂怒地奔突，凶猛地要把大地的根基掏空。"},{"start":133.525,"end":142.962,"text":"在离岸约莫一里格的一片阴森的暗礁上——一年到头任凭浪涛在那上头冲刷、拍击——孤零零地立着一座灯塔。"},{"start":142.962,"end":155.012,"text":"大堆大堆的海藻攀附在它的塔基上，那些暴风鸟——你大可以说它们是风所生，正如海藻是水所生——绕着它一起一落，像它们掠过的波浪一样。"},{"start":155.012,"end":164.225,"text":"可就连在这儿，两个守灯塔的人也生起了一炉火，那火光透过厚石墙上的射孔，向那可怖的大海投出一道明亮。"}]},"en":{"text":"The very lamplighter, who ran on before dotting the dusky street with specks of light, and who was dressed to spend the evening somewhere, laughed out loudly as the Spirit passed: though little kenned the lamplighter that he had any company but Christmas!\nAnd now, without a word of warning from the Ghost, they stood upon a bleak and desert moor, where monstrous masses of rude stone were cast about, as though it were the burial-place of giants; and water spread itself wheresoever it listed--or would have done so, but for the frost that held it prisoner; and nothing grew but moss and furze, and coarse, rank grass.\nDown in the west the setting sun had left a streak of fiery red, which glared upon the desolation for an instant, like a sullen eye, and frowning lower, lower, lower yet, was lost in the thick gloom of darkest night.\n\"What place is this?\" asked Scrooge.\n\"A place where Miners live, who labour in the bowels of the earth,\" returned the Spirit.\n\"But they know me.\nSee!\"\nA light shone from the window of a hut, and swiftly they advanced towards it.\nPassing through the wall of mud and stone, they found a cheerful company assembled round a glowing fire.\nAn old, old man and woman, with their children and their children's children, and another generation beyond that, all decked out gaily in their holiday attire.\nThe old man, in a voice that seldom rose above the howling of the wind upon the barren waste, was singing them a Christmas song; it had been a very old song when he was a boy; and from time to time they all joined in the chorus.\nSo surely as they raised their voices, the old man got quite blithe and loud; and so surely as they stopped, his vigour sank again.\nThe Spirit did not tarry here, but bade Scrooge hold his robe, and passing on above the moor, sped whither?\nNot to sea?\nTo sea.\nTo Scrooge's horror, looking back, he saw the last of the land, a frightful range of rocks, behind them; and his ears were deafened by the thundering of water, as it rolled, and roared, and raged among the dreadful caverns it had worn, and fiercely tried to undermine the earth.\nBuilt upon a dismal reef of sunken rocks, some league or so from shore, on which the waters chafed and dashed, the wild year through, there stood a solitary lighthouse.\nGreat heaps of sea-weed clung to its base, and storm-birds--born of the wind one might suppose, as sea-weed of the water--rose and fell about it, like the waves they skimmed.\nBut even here, two men who watched the light had made a fire, that through the loophole in the thick stone wall shed out a ray of brightness on the awful sea.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_III_小节12.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":13.525,"text":"The very lamplighter, who ran on before dotting the dusky street with specks of light, and who was dressed to spend the evening somewhere, laughed out loudly as the Spirit passed: though little kenned the lamplighter that he had any company but Christmas!"},{"start":13.475,"end":34.262,"text":"And now, without a word of warning from the Ghost, they stood upon a bleak and desert moor, where monstrous masses of rude stone were cast about, as though it were the burial-place of giants; and water spread itself wheresoever it listed--or would have done so, but for the frost that held it prisoner; and nothing grew but moss and furze, and coarse, rank grass."},{"start":34.262,"end":47.237,"text":"Down in the west the setting sun had left a streak of fiery red, which glared upon the desolation for an instant, like a sullen eye, and frowning lower, lower, lower yet, was lost in the thick gloom of darkest night."},{"start":47.237,"end":50.375,"text":"What place is this?\" asked Scrooge."},{"start":50.375,"end":55.975,"text":"A place where Miners live, who labour in the bowels of the earth,\" returned the Spirit."},{"start":55.975,"end":57.75,"text":"But they know me."},{"start":57.75,"end":59.225,"text":"See!"},{"start":59.225,"end":64.175,"text":"A light shone from the window of a hut, and swiftly they advanced towards it."},{"start":64.175,"end":70.475,"text":"Passing through the wall of mud and stone, they found a cheerful company assembled round a glowing fire."},{"start":70.475,"end":79.675,"text":"An old, old man and woman, with their children and their children's children, and another generation beyond that, all decked out gaily in their holiday attire."},{"start":79.675,"end":92.562,"text":"The old man, in a voice that seldom rose above the howling of the wind upon the barren waste, was singing them a Christmas song; it had been a very old song when he was a boy; and from time to time they all joined in the chorus."},{"start":92.562,"end":101.337,"text":"So surely as they raised their voices, the old man got quite blithe and loud; and so surely as they stopped, his vigour sank again."},{"start":101.337,"end":108.437,"text":"The Spirit did not tarry here, but bade Scrooge hold his robe, and passing on above the moor, sped whither?"},{"start":108.437,"end":110.037,"text":"Not to sea?"},{"start":110.037,"end":111.5,"text":"To sea."},{"start":111.5,"end":127.925,"text":"To Scrooge's horror, looking back, he saw the last of the land, a frightful range of rocks, behind them; and his ears were deafened by the thundering of water, as it rolled, and roared, and raged among the dreadful caverns it had worn, and fiercely tried to undermine the earth."},{"start":127.925,"end":138.9,"text":"Built upon a dismal reef of sunken rocks, some league or so from shore, on which the waters chafed and dashed, the wild year through, there stood a solitary lighthouse."},{"start":138.9,"end":149.187,"text":"Great heaps of sea-weed clung to its base, and storm-birds--born of the wind one might suppose, as sea-weed of the water--rose and fell about it, like the waves they skimmed."},{"start":149.187,"end":158.05,"text":"But even here, two men who watched the light had made a fire, that through the loophole in the thick stone wall shed out a ray of brightness on the awful sea."}]}},{"id":"III_13","number":13,"zh":{"text":"他们隔着身前那张粗糙的桌子，把长满老茧的手握到一处，举起各自的格罗格酒罐，彼此道一声圣诞快乐；其中一个：还是那年长的，一张脸让恶劣的天气糟蹋得伤痕累累，活像一艘旧船的船头雕像：唱起一支雄浑的歌，那歌本身就像一场狂风。\n那鬼魂又往前飞去，越过那黑沉沉、起伏翻涌的大海——往前，往前——直到（照他对斯克鲁奇说的）远离了任何海岸，他们落在了一艘船上。\n他们立在掌着舵轮的舵手身旁，立在船头瞭望的人身旁，立在当值的高级船员身旁；一个个在各自的岗位上像幽暗的鬼影；可他们当中每一个人都哼着一支圣诞曲调，或是怀着一桩圣诞的心事，或是压低了嗓子跟同伴说起某个逝去的圣诞节、说起那节日里思乡的指望。\n船上每一个人，无论醒着睡着、是好是歹，这一天对旁人说的话都比一年里任何一天来得和气些；都多少分享了这节日的欢庆；都惦记着远方他所牵挂的人，也知道那些人正乐于惦记着他。\n斯克鲁奇一面听着风的呜咽，一面想着：在这无人的黑暗里，越过一道深不可测、其幽深犹如死亡般神秘的无底深渊往前行进，是何等庄严的一桩事；正当他这么想着，竟听见一阵爽朗的大笑，这叫斯克鲁奇大吃一惊。\n更叫斯克鲁奇吃惊的是，他认出那是他自己外甥的笑声，又发觉自己置身于一间明亮、干爽、亮堂的屋子里，那精灵含笑立在他身旁，正带着赞许的和悦神情望着那同一个外甥！\n\"哈，哈！\"斯克鲁奇的外甥笑道。\n\"哈，哈，哈！\"\n你倘若碰巧——纵然这机会渺茫得很——认得一个笑起来比斯克鲁奇外甥更有福气的人，我只能说，我也很想认识认识他。\n把他引见给我吧，我准乐意结交他。\n这世上有一桩公平、无私、高尚的安排：疾病和悲伤固然传染，可天底下却没有什么比欢笑和好脾气更不可抗拒地能传染开来的了。\n斯克鲁奇的外甥就这么笑着：捧着两肋，晃着脑袋，把脸扭成最荒唐的怪相：斯克鲁奇那娶进门的外甥媳妇也笑得跟他一样畅快。\n聚在那儿的朋友们也丝毫不甘落后，放声大笑起来。\n\"哈，哈！\n哈，哈，哈，哈！\"\n\"他说圣诞节是胡扯，我敢拿性命担保！\"斯克鲁奇的外甥嚷道。\n\"而且他还当真这么信！\"\n\"他这就更该羞了，弗雷德！\"斯克鲁奇的外甥媳妇愤愤地说。\n天保佑这些女人；她们做什么事从不肯只做一半。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_III_小节13.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":20.8,"text":"他们隔着身前那张粗糙的桌子，把长满老茧的手握到一处，举起各自的格罗格酒罐，彼此道一声圣诞快乐；其中一个：还是那年长的，一张脸让恶劣的天气糟蹋得伤痕累累，活像一艘旧船的船头雕像：唱起一支雄浑的歌，那歌本身就像一场狂风。"},{"start":20.8,"end":32.887,"text":"那鬼魂又往前飞去，越过那黑沉沉、起伏翻涌的大海——往前，往前——直到（照他对斯克鲁奇说的）远离了任何海岸，他们落在了一艘船上。"},{"start":32.887,"end":55.725,"text":"他们立在掌着舵轮的舵手身旁，立在船头瞭望的人身旁，立在当值的高级船员身旁；一个个在各自的岗位上像幽暗的鬼影；可他们当中每一个人都哼着一支圣诞曲调，或是怀着一桩圣诞的心事，或是压低了嗓子跟同伴说起某个逝去的圣诞节、说起那节日里思乡的指望。"},{"start":55.725,"end":71.825,"text":"船上每一个人，无论醒着睡着、是好是歹，这一天对旁人说的话都比一年里任何一天来得和气些；都多少分享了这节日的欢庆；都惦记着远方他所牵挂的人，也知道那些人正乐于惦记着他。"},{"start":71.825,"end":90.112,"text":"斯克鲁奇一面听着风的呜咽，一面想着：在这无人的黑暗里，越过一道深不可测、其幽深犹如死亡般神秘的无底深渊往前行进，是何等庄严的一桩事；正当他这么想着，竟听见一阵爽朗的大笑，这叫斯克鲁奇大吃一惊。"},{"start":90.112,"end":106.137,"text":"更叫斯克鲁奇吃惊的是，他认出那是他自己外甥的笑声，又发觉自己置身于一间明亮、干爽、亮堂的屋子里，那精灵含笑立在他身旁，正带着赞许的和悦神情望着那同一个外甥！"},{"start":106.137,"end":108.987,"text":"哈，哈！\"斯克鲁奇的外甥笑道。"},{"start":108.987,"end":110.675,"text":"哈，哈，哈！"},{"start":110.675,"end":120.137,"text":"你倘若碰巧——纵然这机会渺茫得很——认得一个笑起来比斯克鲁奇外甥更有福气的人，我只能说，我也很想认识认识他。"},{"start":120.137,"end":123.437,"text":"把他引见给我吧，我准乐意结交他。"},{"start":123.437,"end":135.15,"text":"这世上有一桩公平、无私、高尚的安排：疾病和悲伤固然传染，可天底下却没有什么比欢笑和好脾气更不可抗拒地能传染开来的了。"},{"start":135.15,"end":146.15,"text":"斯克鲁奇的外甥就这么笑着：捧着两肋，晃着脑袋，把脸扭成最荒唐的怪相：斯克鲁奇那娶进门的外甥媳妇也笑得跟他一样畅快。"},{"start":146.15,"end":150.287,"text":"聚在那儿的朋友们也丝毫不甘落后，放声大笑起来。"},{"start":150.287,"end":151.562,"text":"哈，哈！"},{"start":151.562,"end":153.75,"text":"哈，哈，哈，哈！"},{"start":153.75,"end":158.887,"text":"他说圣诞节是胡扯，我敢拿性命担保！\"斯克鲁奇的外甥嚷道。"},{"start":158.887,"end":161.237,"text":"而且他还当真这么信！"},{"start":161.237,"end":166.45,"text":"他这就更该羞了，弗雷德！\"斯克鲁奇的外甥媳妇愤愤地说。"},{"start":166.45,"end":171.175,"text":"天保佑这些女人；她们做什么事从不肯只做一半。"}]},"en":{"text":"Joining their horny hands over the rough table at which they sat, they wished each other Merry Christmas in their can of grog; and one of them: the elder, too, with his face all damaged and scarred with hard weather, as the figure-head of an old ship might be: struck up a sturdy song that was like a Gale in itself.\nAgain the Ghost sped on, above the black and heaving sea--on, on--until, being far away, as he told Scrooge, from any shore, they lighted on a ship.\nThey stood beside the helmsman at the wheel, the look-out in the bow, the officers who had the watch; dark, ghostly figures in their several stations; but every man among them hummed a Christmas tune, or had a Christmas thought, or spoke below his breath to his companion of some bygone Christmas Day, with homeward hopes belonging to it.\nAnd every man on board, waking or sleeping, good or bad, had had a kinder word for another on that day than on any day in the year; and had shared to some extent in its festivities; and had remembered those he cared for at a distance, and had known that they delighted to remember him.\nIt was a great surprise to Scrooge, while listening to the moaning of the wind, and thinking what a solemn thing it was to move on through the lonely darkness over an unknown abyss, whose depths were secrets as profound as Death: it was a great surprise to Scrooge, while thus engaged, to hear a hearty laugh.\nIt was a much greater surprise to Scrooge to recognise it as his own nephew's, and to find himself in a bright, dry, gleaming room, with the Spirit standing smiling by his side, and looking at that same nephew with approving affability!\n\"Ha, ha!\" laughed Scrooge's nephew.\n\"Ha, ha, ha!\"\nIf you should happen, by any unlikely chance, to know a man more blest in a laugh than Scrooge's nephew, all I can say is, I should like to know him too.\nIntroduce him to me, and I'll cultivate his acquaintance.\nIt is a fair, even-handed, noble adjustment of things, that while there is infection in disease and sorrow, there is nothing in the world so irresistibly contagious as laughter and good-humour.\nWhen Scrooge's nephew laughed in this way: holding his sides, rolling his head, and twisting his face into the most extravagant contortions: Scrooge's niece, by marriage, laughed as heartily as he.\nAnd their assembled friends being not a bit behindhand, roared out, lustily.\n\"Ha, ha!\nHa, ha, ha, ha!\"\n\"He said that Christmas was a humbug, as I live!\" cried Scrooge's nephew.\n\"He believed it too!\"\n\"More shame for him, Fred!\" said Scrooge's niece, indignantly.\nBless those women; they never do anything by halves.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_III_小节13.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":17.537,"text":"Joining their horny hands over the rough table at which they sat, they wished each other Merry Christmas in their can of grog; and one of them: the elder, too, with his face all damaged and scarred with hard weather, as the figure-head of an old ship might be: struck up a sturdy song that was like a Gale in itself."},{"start":17.487,"end":27.787,"text":"Again the Ghost sped on, above the black and heaving sea--on, on--until, being far away, as he told Scrooge, from any shore, they lighted on a ship."},{"start":27.787,"end":46.687,"text":"They stood beside the helmsman at the wheel, the look-out in the bow, the officers who had the watch; dark, ghostly figures in their several stations; but every man among them hummed a Christmas tune, or had a Christmas thought, or spoke below his breath to his companion of some bygone Christmas Day, with homeward hopes belonging to it."},{"start":46.687,"end":62.437,"text":"And every man on board, waking or sleeping, good or bad, had had a kinder word for another on that day than on any day in the year; and had shared to some extent in its festivities; and had remembered those he cared for at a distance, and had known that they delighted to remember him."},{"start":62.437,"end":79.362,"text":"It was a great surprise to Scrooge, while listening to the moaning of the wind, and thinking what a solemn thing it was to move on through the lonely darkness over an unknown abyss, whose depths were secrets as profound as Death: it was a great surprise to Scrooge, while thus engaged, to hear a hearty laugh."},{"start":79.362,"end":93.237,"text":"It was a much greater surprise to Scrooge to recognise it as his own nephew's, and to find himself in a bright, dry, gleaming room, with the Spirit standing smiling by his side, and looking at that same nephew with approving affability!"},{"start":93.237,"end":96.55,"text":"Ha, ha!\" laughed Scrooge's nephew."},{"start":96.55,"end":99.025,"text":"Ha, ha, ha!"},{"start":99.025,"end":108.6,"text":"If you should happen, by any unlikely chance, to know a man more blest in a laugh than Scrooge's nephew, all I can say is, I should like to know him too."},{"start":108.6,"end":112.537,"text":"Introduce him to me, and I'll cultivate his acquaintance."},{"start":112.537,"end":123.737,"text":"It is a fair, even-handed, noble adjustment of things, that while there is infection in disease and sorrow, there is nothing in the world so irresistibly contagious as laughter and good-humour."},{"start":123.737,"end":135.85,"text":"When Scrooge's nephew laughed in this way: holding his sides, rolling his head, and twisting his face into the most extravagant contortions: Scrooge's niece, by marriage, laughed as heartily as he."},{"start":135.85,"end":141.25,"text":"And their assembled friends being not a bit behindhand, roared out, lustily."},{"start":141.25,"end":143.1,"text":"Ha, ha!"},{"start":143.1,"end":146.2,"text":"Ha, ha, ha, ha!"},{"start":146.2,"end":151.5,"text":"He said that Christmas was a humbug, as I live!\" cried Scrooge's nephew."},{"start":151.5,"end":153.512,"text":"He believed it too!"},{"start":153.512,"end":158.475,"text":"More shame for him, Fred!\" said Scrooge's niece, indignantly."},{"start":158.475,"end":162.425,"text":"Bless those women; they never do anything by halves."}]}},{"id":"III_14","number":14,"zh":{"text":"她们总是一片真心。\n她很标致：标致得出奇。\n一张俏脸蛋上有酒窝，常带着一副惊讶的神情；一张红润的小嘴，仿佛生来就是要让人亲的——无疑也确实让人亲过；下巴上有各式各样可爱的小窝儿，一笑起来便彼此融成一片；还有你在任何小人儿头上都不曾见过的、最明媚的一双眼睛。\n总而言之，她就是那种你会说叫人心痒的人，你懂的；可又叫人称心。\n哦，称心极了！\n\"他是个滑稽的老头儿，\"斯克鲁奇的外甥说，\"这是实话；也不像他本可以做到的那么招人喜欢。\n不过呢，他的过错自有它们的报应，我对他没什么可说的。\"\n\"我敢说他可有钱啦，弗雷德，\"斯克鲁奇的外甥媳妇暗示道。\n\"至少你总是这么跟我说的。\"\n\"那又怎么样呢，我亲爱的！\"斯克鲁奇的外甥说。\n\"他那财富对他毫无用处。\n他不拿它做半点好事。\n他不拿它让自己过得舒坦些。\n他也没有那份快慰去想一想——哈，哈，哈！——他将来会拿它给咱们什么好处。\"\n\"我对他可一点耐心也没有，\"斯克鲁奇的外甥媳妇说道。\n斯克鲁奇外甥媳妇的姐妹们，还有别的太太小姐们，都说了同样的话。\n\"哦，我可有耐心！\"斯克鲁奇的外甥说。\n\"我为他难过；我就是想生他的气也生不起来。\n他那些坏脾气坑了谁呢？","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_III_小节14.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":2.1,"text":"她们总是一片真心。"},{"start":2.05,"end":4.512,"text":"她很标致：标致得出奇。"},{"start":4.512,"end":24.412,"text":"一张俏脸蛋上有酒窝，常带着一副惊讶的神情；一张红润的小嘴，仿佛生来就是要让人亲的——无疑也确实让人亲过；下巴上有各式各样可爱的小窝儿，一笑起来便彼此融成一片；还有你在任何小人儿头上都不曾见过的、最明媚的一双眼睛。"},{"start":24.412,"end":30.325,"text":"总而言之，她就是那种你会说叫人心痒的人，你懂的；可又叫人称心。"},{"start":30.325,"end":32.287,"text":"哦，称心极了！"},{"start":32.287,"end":39.65,"text":"他是个滑稽的老头儿，\"斯克鲁奇的外甥说，\"这是实话；也不像他本可以做到的那么招人喜欢。"},{"start":39.65,"end":44.312,"text":"不过呢，他的过错自有它们的报应，我对他没什么可说的。"},{"start":44.312,"end":49.262,"text":"我敢说他可有钱啦，弗雷德，\"斯克鲁奇的外甥媳妇暗示道。"},{"start":49.262,"end":51.587,"text":"至少你总是这么跟我说的。"},{"start":51.587,"end":55.287,"text":"那又怎么样呢，我亲爱的！\"斯克鲁奇的外甥说。"},{"start":55.287,"end":57.862,"text":"他那财富对他毫无用处。"},{"start":57.862,"end":60.1,"text":"他不拿它做半点好事。"},{"start":60.1,"end":63,"text":"他不拿它让自己过得舒坦些。"},{"start":63,"end":66.712,"text":"他也没有那份快慰去想一想——哈，哈，哈！"},{"start":66.712,"end":69.462,"text":"他将来会拿它给咱们什么好处。"},{"start":69.462,"end":73.862,"text":"我对他可一点耐心也没有，\"斯克鲁奇的外甥媳妇说道。"},{"start":73.862,"end":79.325,"text":"斯克鲁奇外甥媳妇的姐妹们，还有别的太太小姐们，都说了同样的话。"},{"start":79.325,"end":82.775,"text":"哦，我可有耐心！\"斯克鲁奇的外甥说。"},{"start":82.775,"end":86.987,"text":"我为他难过；我就是想生他的气也生不起来。"},{"start":86.987,"end":89.487,"text":"他那些坏脾气坑了谁呢？"}]},"en":{"text":"They are always in earnest.\nShe was very pretty: exceedingly pretty.\nWith a dimpled, surprised-looking, capital face; a ripe little mouth, that seemed made to be kissed--as no doubt it was; all kinds of good little dots about her chin, that melted into one another when she laughed; and the sunniest pair of eyes you ever saw in any little creature's head.\nAltogether she was what you would have called provoking, you know; but satisfactory, too.\nOh, perfectly satisfactory!\n\"He's a comical old fellow,\" said Scrooge's nephew, \"that's the truth; and not so pleasant as he might be.\nHowever, his offences carry their own punishment, and I have nothing to say against him.\"\n\"I am sure he is very rich, Fred,\" hinted Scrooge's niece.\n\"At least you always tell _me_ so.\"\n\"What of that, my dear!\" said Scrooge's nephew.\n\"His wealth is of no use to him.\nHe don't do any good with it.\nHe don't make himself comfortable with it.\nHe hasn't the satisfaction of thinking--ha, ha, ha!--that he is ever going to benefit us with it.\"\n\"I have no patience with him,\" observed Scrooge's niece.\nScrooge's niece's sisters, and all the other ladies, expressed the same opinion.\n\"Oh, I have!\" said Scrooge's nephew.\n\"I am sorry for him; I couldn't be angry with him if I tried.\nWho suffers by his ill whims?","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_III_小节14.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":2.412,"text":"They are always in earnest."},{"start":2.362,"end":5.737,"text":"She was very pretty: exceedingly pretty."},{"start":5.737,"end":22.575,"text":"With a dimpled, surprised-looking, capital face; a ripe little mouth, that seemed made to be kissed--as no doubt it was; all kinds of good little dots about her chin, that melted into one another when she laughed; and the sunniest pair of eyes you ever saw in any little creature's head."},{"start":22.575,"end":28.3,"text":"Altogether she was what you would have called provoking, you know; but satisfactory, too."},{"start":28.3,"end":31.15,"text":"Oh, perfectly satisfactory!"},{"start":31.15,"end":38.087,"text":"He's a comical old fellow,\" said Scrooge's nephew, \"that's the truth; and not so pleasant as he might be."},{"start":38.087,"end":43.7,"text":"However, his offences carry their own punishment, and I have nothing to say against him."},{"start":43.7,"end":48.375,"text":"I am sure he is very rich, Fred,\" hinted Scrooge's niece."},{"start":48.375,"end":52.15,"text":"At least you always tell _me_ so."},{"start":52.15,"end":56.075,"text":"What of that, my dear!\" said Scrooge's nephew."},{"start":56.075,"end":58.712,"text":"His wealth is of no use to him."},{"start":58.712,"end":60.962,"text":"He don't do any good with it."},{"start":60.962,"end":63.7,"text":"He don't make himself comfortable with it."},{"start":63.7,"end":69.937,"text":"He hasn't the satisfaction of thinking--ha, ha, ha!--that he is ever going to benefit us with it."},{"start":69.937,"end":73.975,"text":"I have no patience with him,\" observed Scrooge's niece."},{"start":73.975,"end":79.462,"text":"Scrooge's niece's sisters, and all the other ladies, expressed the same opinion."},{"start":79.462,"end":82.925,"text":"Oh, I have!\" said Scrooge's nephew."},{"start":82.925,"end":86.987,"text":"I am sorry for him; I couldn't be angry with him if I tried."},{"start":86.987,"end":89.562,"text":"Who suffers by his ill whims?"}]}},{"id":"III_15","number":15,"zh":{"text":"坑的总是他自己。\n就说这会儿吧，他心血来潮不待见咱们，便不肯来跟咱们吃饭。\n结果怎么样？\n他也没少吃多少一顿好饭。\"\n\"说实话，我看他可是错过了一顿顶好的饭呢，\"斯克鲁奇的外甥媳妇插嘴道。\n旁人也都这么说，而且总得承认他们是够格的评判者，因为他们方才刚吃过饭；这会儿桌上摆着甜点，借着灯光围在炉火旁。\n\"得！\n听你们这么说我可太高兴了，\"斯克鲁奇的外甥说，\"因为我对这些个年轻媳妇的持家本事，实在没多大信心。\n你说呢，托珀？\"\n托珀分明早把眼睛盯在斯克鲁奇外甥媳妇的一个姐妹身上了，因为他答道，单身汉是个可怜的弃儿，没资格对这个话题发表意见。\n听了这话，斯克鲁奇外甥媳妇的那个姐妹——就是戴蕾丝领、丰满的那个，不是别着玫瑰的那个——脸红了。\n\"接着说呀，弗雷德，\"斯克鲁奇的外甥媳妇拍着手说。\n\"他一开口的话就从没说完过！\n真是个叫人发笑的家伙！\"\n斯克鲁奇的外甥又纵情大笑了一场，那笑既然没法不传染开去；尽管那丰满的姐妹使劲拿芳香醋去抵挡；众人还是一致跟着他笑了。\n\"我方才不过是想说，\"斯克鲁奇的外甥说，\"依我看，他不待见咱们、不肯跟咱们一道快活，这后果便是他错过了一些愉快的时光，而这些时光本对他没半点害处。\n我敢说，无论是在他那霉烂的老账房里，还是在他那满是灰尘的住所里，他从自己那些念头里寻得的伙伴，都不如他错过的这些来得可亲。\n我打算每年都给他这同一个机会，不管他乐意不乐意，因为我可怜他。\n他尽可以咒骂圣诞节，咒到死为止，可他到底没法不对它高看几分——我谅他做不到——倘若他瞧见我年复一年地、好脾气地上他那儿去，说一声：斯克鲁奇舅舅，您好哇？","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_III_小节15.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":2.137,"text":"坑的总是他自己。"},{"start":2.087,"end":7.35,"text":"就说这会儿吧，他心血来潮不待见咱们，便不肯来跟咱们吃饭。"},{"start":7.35,"end":8.75,"text":"结果怎么样？"},{"start":8.75,"end":11.312,"text":"他也没少吃多少一顿好饭。"},{"start":11.312,"end":17.537,"text":"说实话，我看他可是错过了一顿顶好的饭呢，\"斯克鲁奇的外甥媳妇插嘴道。"},{"start":17.537,"end":28.312,"text":"旁人也都这么说，而且总得承认他们是够格的评判者，因为他们方才刚吃过饭；这会儿桌上摆着甜点，借着灯光围在炉火旁。"},{"start":28.312,"end":29.225,"text":"得！"},{"start":29.225,"end":37.35,"text":"听你们这么说我可太高兴了，\"斯克鲁奇的外甥说，\"因为我对这些个年轻媳妇的持家本事，实在没多大信心。"},{"start":37.35,"end":39.1,"text":"你说呢，托珀？"},{"start":39.1,"end":49.475,"text":"托珀分明早把眼睛盯在斯克鲁奇外甥媳妇的一个姐妹身上了，因为他答道，单身汉是个可怜的弃儿，没资格对这个话题发表意见。"},{"start":49.475,"end":57.9,"text":"听了这话，斯克鲁奇外甥媳妇的那个姐妹——就是戴蕾丝领、丰满的那个，不是别着玫瑰的那个——脸红了。"},{"start":57.9,"end":62.437,"text":"接着说呀，弗雷德，\"斯克鲁奇的外甥媳妇拍着手说。"},{"start":62.437,"end":65.35,"text":"他一开口的话就从没说完过！"},{"start":65.35,"end":67.687,"text":"真是个叫人发笑的家伙！"},{"start":67.687,"end":79.45,"text":"斯克鲁奇的外甥又纵情大笑了一场，那笑既然没法不传染开去；尽管那丰满的姐妹使劲拿芳香醋去抵挡；众人还是一致跟着他笑了。"},{"start":79.45,"end":93,"text":"我方才不过是想说，\"斯克鲁奇的外甥说，\"依我看，他不待见咱们、不肯跟咱们一道快活，这后果便是他错过了一些愉快的时光，而这些时光本对他没半点害处。"},{"start":93,"end":104.725,"text":"我敢说，无论是在他那霉烂的老账房里，还是在他那满是灰尘的住所里，他从自己那些念头里寻得的伙伴，都不如他错过的这些来得可亲。"},{"start":104.725,"end":110.875,"text":"我打算每年都给他这同一个机会，不管他乐意不乐意，因为我可怜他。"},{"start":110.875,"end":124.35,"text":"他尽可以咒骂圣诞节，咒到死为止，可他到底没法不对它高看几分——我谅他做不到——倘若他瞧见我年复一年地、好脾气地上他那儿去，说一声：斯克鲁奇舅舅，您好哇？"}]},"en":{"text":"Himself, always.\nHere, he takes it into his head to dislike us, and he won't come and dine with us.\nWhat's the consequence?\nHe don't lose much of a dinner.\"\n\"Indeed, I think he loses a very good dinner,\" interrupted Scrooge's niece.\nEverybody else said the same, and they must be allowed to have been competent judges, because they had just had dinner; and, with the dessert upon the table, were clustered round the fire, by lamplight.\n\"Well!\nI am very glad to hear it,\" said Scrooge's nephew, \"because I haven't any great faith in these young housekeepers.\nWhat do _you_ say, Topper?\"\nTopper had clearly got his eye upon one of Scrooge's niece's sisters, for he answered that a bachelor was a wretched outcast, who had no right to express an opinion on the subject.\nWhereat Scrooge's niece's sister--the plump one with the lace tucker: not the one with the roses--blushed.\n\"Do go on, Fred,\" said Scrooge's niece, clapping her hands.\n\"He never finishes what he begins to say!\nHe is such a ridiculous fellow!\"\nScrooge's nephew revelled in another laugh, and as it was impossible to keep the infection off; though the plump sister tried hard to do it with aromatic vinegar; his example was unanimously followed.\n\"I was only going to say,\" said Scrooge's nephew, \"that the consequence of his taking a dislike to us, and not making merry with us, is, as I think, that he loses some pleasant moments, which could do him no harm.\nI am sure he loses pleasanter companions than he can find in his own thoughts, either in his mouldy old office, or his dusty chambers.\nI mean to give him the same chance every year, whether he likes it or not, for I pity him.\nHe may rail at Christmas till he dies, but he can't help thinking better of it--I defy him--if he finds me going there, in good temper, year after year, and saying Uncle Scrooge, how are you?","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_III_小节15.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":2.512,"text":"Himself, always."},{"start":2.462,"end":7.937,"text":"Here, he takes it into his head to dislike us, and he won't come and dine with us."},{"start":7.937,"end":10.05,"text":"What's the consequence?"},{"start":10.05,"end":12.487,"text":"He don't lose much of a dinner."},{"start":12.487,"end":17.812,"text":"Indeed, I think he loses a very good dinner,\" interrupted Scrooge's niece."},{"start":17.812,"end":29.012,"text":"Everybody else said the same, and they must be allowed to have been competent judges, because they had just had dinner; and, with the dessert upon the table, were clustered round the fire, by lamplight."},{"start":29.012,"end":30.325,"text":"Well!"},{"start":30.325,"end":37.425,"text":"I am very glad to hear it,\" said Scrooge's nephew, \"because I haven't any great faith in these young housekeepers."},{"start":37.425,"end":40.85,"text":"What do _you_ say, Topper?"},{"start":40.85,"end":51.15,"text":"Topper had clearly got his eye upon one of Scrooge's niece's sisters, for he answered that a bachelor was a wretched outcast, who had no right to express an opinion on the subject."},{"start":51.15,"end":57.362,"text":"Whereat Scrooge's niece's sister--the plump one with the lace tucker: not the one with the roses--blushed."},{"start":57.362,"end":62.337,"text":"Do go on, Fred,\" said Scrooge's niece, clapping her hands."},{"start":62.337,"end":65.512,"text":"He never finishes what he begins to say!"},{"start":65.512,"end":68.225,"text":"He is such a ridiculous fellow!"},{"start":68.225,"end":79.862,"text":"Scrooge's nephew revelled in another laugh, and as it was impossible to keep the infection off; though the plump sister tried hard to do it with aromatic vinegar; his example was unanimously followed."},{"start":79.862,"end":92.9,"text":"I was only going to say,\" said Scrooge's nephew, \"that the consequence of his taking a dislike to us, and not making merry with us, is, as I think, that he loses some pleasant moments, which could do him no harm."},{"start":92.9,"end":100.8,"text":"I am sure he loses pleasanter companions than he can find in his own thoughts, either in his mouldy old office, or his dusty chambers."},{"start":100.8,"end":106.487,"text":"I mean to give him the same chance every year, whether he likes it or not, for I pity him."},{"start":106.487,"end":117.725,"text":"He may rail at Christmas till he dies, but he can't help thinking better of it--I defy him--if he finds me going there, in good temper, year after year, and saying Uncle Scrooge, how are you?"}]}},{"id":"III_16","number":16,"zh":{"text":"哪怕这只叫他动了个心思，留给他那可怜的伙计五十镑，那也就值了；我看昨儿我可把他说动了几分。\"\n这会儿轮到他们笑了，笑他竟想把斯克鲁奇说动。\n可他这人脾气再好不过，也不大计较他们笑的是什么，只要他们笑得开心就行，便撺掇着他们尽情乐呵，喜气洋洋地把酒瓶传了下去。\n喝过茶，他们奏了一阵音乐。\n因为他们是个爱音乐的人家，我向你担保，他们唱起合唱曲或轮唱曲来，那是行家里手：尤其是托珀，他能像模像样地在低声部里嗡嗡到底，从不把额上那几根大青筋憋得鼓起来，也不把脸涨得通红。\n斯克鲁奇的外甥媳妇琴弹得很好；她弹的曲子里有一支简单的小调（简直算不得什么：你两分钟就能学会吹它），正是那个把斯克鲁奇从寄宿学堂接走的孩子所熟悉的——往昔圣诞之灵方才唤起过他这段记忆。\n这支曲调一响起，那精灵给他看过的一切便都涌上了他的心头；他越来越心软；他想，倘若多年以前他能常常听一听它，也许早就亲手培养起种种人生的善意、为自己赢得幸福了，用不着求助于那把埋葬雅各布·马利的教堂司事的铁锹。\n不过他们也没把整个晚上都耗在音乐上。\n过了一会儿，他们玩起了罚物游戏；因为人有时做做孩子是桩好事，而再没有比圣诞节更好的时候了，因为它那伟大的奠基者本身就曾是个孩子。\n慢着！\n头一桩是玩捉迷藏。\n那是自然。\n我才不信托珀当真蒙住了眼，正如我不信他靴子里头长着眼睛。\n依我看，这是他跟斯克鲁奇外甥串通好了的；而且当下的圣诞之灵也心知肚明。\n他追那个戴蕾丝领的丰满姐妹的那副架势，简直是对人类轻信本性的一种侮辱。\n撞翻了火钳火铲，绊倒在椅子上，撞上了钢琴，把自己闷在帷幔里，她走到哪儿，他就追到哪儿。\n他总知道那丰满姐妹在哪儿。\n他偏偏不肯逮别人。\n你若像他们当中有些人那样撞到他身上、又站着不动；他便会装出一副要来抓你的样子，那分明是对你智力的侮辱；随即立刻又侧着身往那丰满姐妹的方向溜去。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_III_小节16.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":8.137,"text":"哪怕这只叫他动了个心思，留给他那可怜的伙计五十镑，那也就值了；我看昨儿我可把他说动了几分。"},{"start":8.087,"end":12.312,"text":"这会儿轮到他们笑了，笑他竟想把斯克鲁奇说动。"},{"start":12.312,"end":23,"text":"可他这人脾气再好不过，也不大计较他们笑的是什么，只要他们笑得开心就行，便撺掇着他们尽情乐呵，喜气洋洋地把酒瓶传了下去。"},{"start":23,"end":25.687,"text":"喝过茶，他们奏了一阵音乐。"},{"start":25.687,"end":42.45,"text":"因为他们是个爱音乐的人家，我向你担保，他们唱起合唱曲或轮唱曲来，那是行家里手：尤其是托珀，他能像模像样地在低声部里嗡嗡到底，从不把额上那几根大青筋憋得鼓起来，也不把脸涨得通红。"},{"start":42.45,"end":59.112,"text":"斯克鲁奇的外甥媳妇琴弹得很好；她弹的曲子里有一支简单的小调（简直算不得什么：你两分钟就能学会吹它），正是那个把斯克鲁奇从寄宿学堂接走的孩子所熟悉的——往昔圣诞之灵方才唤起过他这段记忆。"},{"start":59.112,"end":78.937,"text":"这支曲调一响起，那精灵给他看过的一切便都涌上了他的心头；他越来越心软；他想，倘若多年以前他能常常听一听它，也许早就亲手培养起种种人生的善意、为自己赢得幸福了，用不着求助于那把埋葬雅各布·马利的教堂司事的铁锹。"},{"start":78.937,"end":82.65,"text":"不过他们也没把整个晚上都耗在音乐上。"},{"start":82.65,"end":94.25,"text":"过了一会儿，他们玩起了罚物游戏；因为人有时做做孩子是桩好事，而再没有比圣诞节更好的时候了，因为它那伟大的奠基者本身就曾是个孩子。"},{"start":94.25,"end":95.325,"text":"慢着！"},{"start":95.325,"end":97.5,"text":"头一桩是玩捉迷藏。"},{"start":97.5,"end":98.95,"text":"那是自然。"},{"start":98.95,"end":104.425,"text":"我才不信托珀当真蒙住了眼，正如我不信他靴子里头长着眼睛。"},{"start":104.425,"end":111.375,"text":"依我看，这是他跟斯克鲁奇外甥串通好了的；而且当下的圣诞之灵也心知肚明。"},{"start":111.375,"end":118.175,"text":"他追那个戴蕾丝领的丰满姐妹的那副架势，简直是对人类轻信本性的一种侮辱。"},{"start":118.175,"end":126.275,"text":"撞翻了火钳火铲，绊倒在椅子上，撞上了钢琴，把自己闷在帷幔里，她走到哪儿，他就追到哪儿。"},{"start":126.275,"end":129.112,"text":"他总知道那丰满姐妹在哪儿。"},{"start":129.112,"end":131.15,"text":"他偏偏不肯逮别人。"},{"start":131.15,"end":145.15,"text":"你若像他们当中有些人那样撞到他身上、又站着不动；他便会装出一副要来抓你的样子，那分明是对你智力的侮辱；随即立刻又侧着身往那丰满姐妹的方向溜去。"}]},"en":{"text":"If it only puts him in the vein to leave his poor clerk fifty pounds, _that's_ something; and I think I shook him, yesterday.\"\nIt was their turn to laugh now, at the notion of his shaking Scrooge.\nBut being thoroughly good-natured, and not much caring what they laughed at, so that they laughed at any rate, he encouraged them in their merriment, and passed the bottle, joyously.\nAfter tea, they had some music.\nFor they were a musical family, and knew what they were about, when they sung a Glee or Catch, I can assure you: especially Topper, who could growl away in the bass like a good one, and never swell the large veins in his forehead, or get red in the face over it.\nScrooge's niece played well upon the harp; and played among other tunes a simple little air (a mere nothing: you might learn to whistle it in two minutes), which had been familiar to the child who fetched Scrooge from the boarding-school, as he had been reminded by the Ghost of Christmas Past.\nWhen this strain of music sounded, all the things that Ghost had shown him, came upon his mind; he softened more and more; and thought that if he could have listened to it often, years ago, he might have cultivated the kindnesses of life for his own happiness with his own hands, without resorting to the sexton's spade that buried Jacob Marley.\nBut they didn't devote the whole evening to music.\nAfter a while they played at forfeits; for it is good to be children sometimes, and never better than at Christmas, when its mighty Founder was a child himself.\nStop!\nThere was first a game at blindman's buff.\nOf course there was.\nAnd I no more believe Topper was really blind than I believe he had eyes in his boots.\nMy opinion is, that it was a done thing between him and Scrooge's nephew; and that the Ghost of Christmas Present knew it.\nThe way he went after that plump sister in the lace tucker, was an outrage on the credulity of human nature.\nKnocking down the fire-irons, tumbling over the chairs, bumping up against the piano, smothering himself among the curtains, wherever she went, there went he.\nHe always knew where the plump sister was.\nHe wouldn't catch anybody else.\nIf you had fallen up against him, as some of them did, and stood there; he would have made a feint of endeavouring to seize you, which would have been an affront to your understanding; and would instantly have sidled off in the direction of the plump sister.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_III_小节16.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":8.375,"text":"If it only puts him in the vein to leave his poor clerk fifty pounds, _that's_ something; and I think I shook him, yesterday."},{"start":8.325,"end":12.875,"text":"It was their turn to laugh now, at the notion of his shaking Scrooge."},{"start":12.875,"end":23.325,"text":"But being thoroughly good-natured, and not much caring what they laughed at, so that they laughed at any rate, he encouraged them in their merriment, and passed the bottle, joyously."},{"start":23.325,"end":26.275,"text":"After tea, they had some music."},{"start":26.275,"end":41.162,"text":"For they were a musical family, and knew what they were about, when they sung a Glee or Catch, I can assure you: especially Topper, who could growl away in the bass like a good one, and never swell the large veins in his forehead, or get red in the face over it."},{"start":41.162,"end":56.437,"text":"Scrooge's niece played well upon the harp; and played among other tunes a simple little air (a mere nothing: you might learn to whistle it in two minutes), which had been familiar to the child who fetched Scrooge from the boarding-school, as he had been reminded by the Ghost of Christmas Past."},{"start":56.437,"end":75.012,"text":"When this strain of music sounded, all the things that Ghost had shown him, came upon his mind; he softened more and more; and thought that if he could have listened to it often, years ago, he might have cultivated the kindnesses of life for his own happiness with his own hands, without resorting to the sexton's spade that buried Jacob Marley."},{"start":75.012,"end":78.262,"text":"But they didn't devote the whole evening to music."},{"start":78.262,"end":87.55,"text":"After a while they played at forfeits; for it is good to be children sometimes, and never better than at Christmas, when its mighty Founder was a child himself."},{"start":87.55,"end":89.062,"text":"Stop!"},{"start":89.062,"end":92.225,"text":"There was first a game at blindman's buff."},{"start":92.225,"end":94.312,"text":"Of course there was."},{"start":94.312,"end":99.687,"text":"And I no more believe Topper was really blind than I believe he had eyes in his boots."},{"start":99.687,"end":106.75,"text":"My opinion is, that it was a done thing between him and Scrooge's nephew; and that the Ghost of Christmas Present knew it."},{"start":106.75,"end":113.012,"text":"The way he went after that plump sister in the lace tucker, was an outrage on the credulity of human nature."},{"start":113.012,"end":122.975,"text":"Knocking down the fire-irons, tumbling over the chairs, bumping up against the piano, smothering himself among the curtains, wherever she went, there went he."},{"start":122.975,"end":126.125,"text":"He always knew where the plump sister was."},{"start":126.125,"end":128.65,"text":"He wouldn't catch anybody else."},{"start":128.65,"end":141.575,"text":"If you had fallen up against him, as some of them did, and stood there; he would have made a feint of endeavouring to seize you, which would have been an affront to your understanding; and would instantly have sidled off in the direction of the plump sister."}]}},{"id":"III_17","number":17,"zh":{"text":"她一遍遍嚷着这不公平；这可真是不公平。\n可到末了，他到底逮住了她；尽管她绸衣窸窣作响、从他身边一闪而过，他还是把她逼进了一个无处可逃的墙角；这时他的举动便最是叫人不齿了。\n因为他假装认不出她；假装非得摸一摸她的头饰，还要按一按她手指上某一只戒指、脖子上某一条项链，才能进一步确认她的身份；这真是卑鄙，岂有此理！\n等换了另一个人蒙眼当差、他俩在帷幔后头亲亲热热咬耳朵时，她无疑把她对这事的看法都告诉他了。\n斯克鲁奇的外甥媳妇没参加捉迷藏，而是被安顿在一个舒适的角落里，一张大椅子加一个脚凳，舒舒服服地坐着，鬼魂和斯克鲁奇就紧挨在她身后。\n不过她加进了罚物游戏，把她的心上人用整套字母从头到尾爱了个遍，叫人叹服。\n玩\"怎样、何时、何地\"那游戏时，她也大显身手，叫斯克鲁奇的外甥暗自得意，把她的姐妹们远远比了下去：尽管那几个姐妹也都是机灵姑娘，这一点托珀准能告诉你。\n那儿大概有二十来个人，有老有少，可他们全玩了起来，斯克鲁奇也玩了；因为他对眼前的事兴味盎然，全然忘了自己的嗓音在他们耳朵里发不出声，便时不时相当响亮地说出他的猜测，而且十有八九还猜对了；因为便是最尖的针、上等的怀特查佩尔货、保管不会扎进眼睛的，也不比斯克鲁奇更尖：尽管他打定主意要做个迟钝的人。\n那鬼魂瞧见他这副心境，大为欢喜，望着他那样满含嘉许，他便像个孩子似的央求，要它允他留到宾客散去。\n可那精灵说这办不到。\n\"这儿有个新游戏，\"斯克鲁奇说。\n\"半个钟头，精灵，就半个钟头！\"\n那是个叫作\"是与否\"的游戏，斯克鲁奇的外甥得想好一样东西，其余人须得猜出是什么；他只就着情形回答他们是或不是。\n人家朝他放出的那一连串噼里啪啦的盘问，从他嘴里逼出来：他想的是一只动物，一只活的动物，一只相当讨人嫌的动物，一只凶野的动物，一只有时咆哮、有时哼哼、有时又说话的动物，住在伦敦，在街上走动，不供人观看，没人牵着，不住在动物园里，从不在市场上被宰杀，既不是马、不是驴、不是母牛、不是公牛、不是老虎、不是狗、不是猪、不是猫，也不是熊。\n人家每抛给他一个新问题，这外甥便爆出一阵新的大笑；笑得无法形容地痛快，不得不从沙发上站起来直跺脚。\n末了那丰满姐妹也笑成了一团，嚷道：\"我猜着啦！\n我知道是什么了，弗雷德！\n我知道是什么了！\"\n\"是什么？\"弗雷德嚷道。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_III_小节17.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":4.387,"text":"她一遍遍嚷着这不公平；这可真是不公平。"},{"start":4.337,"end":17.612,"text":"可到末了，他到底逮住了她；尽管她绸衣窸窣作响、从他身边一闪而过，他还是把她逼进了一个无处可逃的墙角；这时他的举动便最是叫人不齿了。"},{"start":17.612,"end":30.737,"text":"因为他假装认不出她；假装非得摸一摸她的头饰，还要按一按她手指上某一只戒指、脖子上某一条项链，才能进一步确认她的身份；这真是卑鄙，岂有此理！"},{"start":30.737,"end":39.25,"text":"等换了另一个人蒙眼当差、他俩在帷幔后头亲亲热热咬耳朵时，她无疑把她对这事的看法都告诉他了。"},{"start":39.25,"end":51.762,"text":"斯克鲁奇的外甥媳妇没参加捉迷藏，而是被安顿在一个舒适的角落里，一张大椅子加一个脚凳，舒舒服服地坐着，鬼魂和斯克鲁奇就紧挨在她身后。"},{"start":51.762,"end":59.387,"text":"不过她加进了罚物游戏，把她的心上人用整套字母从头到尾爱了个遍，叫人叹服。"},{"start":59.387,"end":73.65,"text":"玩\"怎样、何时、何地\"那游戏时，她也大显身手，叫斯克鲁奇的外甥暗自得意，把她的姐妹们远远比了下去：尽管那几个姐妹也都是机灵姑娘，这一点托珀准能告诉你。"},{"start":73.65,"end":99.8,"text":"那儿大概有二十来个人，有老有少，可他们全玩了起来，斯克鲁奇也玩了；因为他对眼前的事兴味盎然，全然忘了自己的嗓音在他们耳朵里发不出声，便时不时相当响亮地说出他的猜测，而且十有八九还猜对了；因为便是最尖的针、上等的怀特查佩尔货、保管不会扎进眼睛的，也不比斯克鲁奇更尖：尽管他打定主意要做个迟钝的人。"},{"start":99.8,"end":109.375,"text":"那鬼魂瞧见他这副心境，大为欢喜，望着他那样满含嘉许，他便像个孩子似的央求，要它允他留到宾客散去。"},{"start":109.375,"end":111.762,"text":"可那精灵说这办不到。"},{"start":111.762,"end":114.562,"text":"这儿有个新游戏，\"斯克鲁奇说。"},{"start":114.562,"end":117.712,"text":"半个钟头，精灵，就半个钟头！"},{"start":117.712,"end":127.925,"text":"那是个叫作\"是与否\"的游戏，斯克鲁奇的外甥得想好一样东西，其余人须得猜出是什么；他只就着情形回答他们是或不是。"},{"start":127.925,"end":158.187,"text":"人家朝他放出的那一连串噼里啪啦的盘问，从他嘴里逼出来：他想的是一只动物，一只活的动物，一只相当讨人嫌的动物，一只凶野的动物，一只有时咆哮、有时哼哼、有时又说话的动物，住在伦敦，在街上走动，不供人观看，没人牵着，不住在动物园里，从不在市场上被宰杀，既不是马、不是驴、不是母牛、不是公牛、不是老虎、不是狗、不是猪、不是猫，也不是熊。"},{"start":158.187,"end":167.4,"text":"人家每抛给他一个新问题，这外甥便爆出一阵新的大笑；笑得无法形容地痛快，不得不从沙发上站起来直跺脚。"},{"start":167.4,"end":171.875,"text":"末了那丰满姐妹也笑成了一团，嚷道：\"我猜着啦！"},{"start":171.875,"end":174.275,"text":"我知道是什么了，弗雷德！"},{"start":174.275,"end":175.975,"text":"我知道是什么了！"},{"start":175.975,"end":178.212,"text":"是什么？\"弗雷德嚷道。"}]},"en":{"text":"She often cried out that it wasn't fair; and it really was not.\nBut when at last, he caught her; when, in spite of all her silken rustlings, and her rapid flutterings past him, he got her into a corner whence there was no escape; then his conduct was the most execrable.\nFor his pretending not to know her; his pretending that it was necessary to touch her head-dress, and further to assure himself of her identity by pressing a certain ring upon her finger, and a certain chain about her neck; was vile, monstrous!\nNo doubt she told him her opinion of it, when, another blind-man being in office, they were so very confidential together, behind the curtains.\nScrooge's niece was not one of the blind-man's buff party, but was made comfortable with a large chair and a footstool, in a snug corner, where the Ghost and Scrooge were close behind her.\nBut she joined in the forfeits, and loved her love to admiration with all the letters of the alphabet.\nLikewise at the game of How, When, and Where, she was very great, and to the secret joy of Scrooge's nephew, beat her sisters hollow: though they were sharp girls too, as Topper could have told you.\nThere might have been twenty people there, young and old, but they all played, and so did Scrooge; for, wholly forgetting in the interest he had in what was going on, that his voice made no sound in their ears, he sometimes came out with his guess quite loud, and very often guessed right, too; for the sharpest needle, best Whitechapel, warranted not to cut in the eye, was not sharper than Scrooge: blunt as he took it in his head to be.\nThe Ghost was greatly pleased to find him in this mood, and looked upon him with such favour that he begged like a boy to be allowed to stay until the guests departed.\nBut this the Spirit said could not be done.\n\"Here's a new game,\" said Scrooge.\n\"One half hour, Spirit, only one!\"\nIt was a Game called Yes and No, where Scrooge's nephew had to think of something, and the rest must find out what; he only answering to their questions yes or no as the case was.\nThe brisk fire of questioning to which he was exposed, elicited from him that he was thinking of an animal, a live animal, rather a disagreeable animal, a savage animal, an animal that growled and grunted sometimes, and talked sometimes, and lived in London, and walked about the streets, and wasn't made a show of, and wasn't led by anybody, and didn't live in a menagerie, and was never killed in a market, and was not a horse, or an ass, or a cow, or a bull, or a tiger, or a dog, or a pig, or a cat, or a bear.\nAt every fresh question that was put to him, this nephew burst into a fresh roar of laughter; and was so inexpressibly tickled, that he was obliged to get up off the sofa and stamp.\nAt last the plump sister, falling into a similar state, cried out: \"I have found it out!\nI know what it is, Fred!\nI know what it is!\"\n\"What is it?\" cried Fred.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_III_小节17.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":4.487,"text":"She often cried out that it wasn't fair; and it really was not."},{"start":4.437,"end":17.012,"text":"But when at last, he caught her; when, in spite of all her silken rustlings, and her rapid flutterings past him, he got her into a corner whence there was no escape; then his conduct was the most execrable."},{"start":17.012,"end":30.837,"text":"For his pretending not to know her; his pretending that it was necessary to touch her head-dress, and further to assure himself of her identity by pressing a certain ring upon her finger, and a certain chain about her neck; was vile, monstrous!"},{"start":30.837,"end":39.762,"text":"No doubt she told him her opinion of it, when, another blind-man being in office, they were so very confidential together, behind the curtains."},{"start":39.762,"end":50.35,"text":"Scrooge's niece was not one of the blind-man's buff party, but was made comfortable with a large chair and a footstool, in a snug corner, where the Ghost and Scrooge were close behind her."},{"start":50.35,"end":56.375,"text":"But she joined in the forfeits, and loved her love to admiration with all the letters of the alphabet."},{"start":56.375,"end":68.675,"text":"Likewise at the game of How, When, and Where, she was very great, and to the secret joy of Scrooge's nephew, beat her sisters hollow: though they were sharp girls too, as Topper could have told you."},{"start":68.675,"end":93.287,"text":"There might have been twenty people there, young and old, but they all played, and so did Scrooge; for, wholly forgetting in the interest he had in what was going on, that his voice made no sound in their ears, he sometimes came out with his guess quite loud, and very often guessed right, too; for the sharpest needle, best Whitechapel, warranted not to cut in the eye, was not sharper than Scrooge: blunt as he took it in his head to be."},{"start":93.287,"end":102.15,"text":"The Ghost was greatly pleased to find him in this mood, and looked upon him with such favour that he begged like a boy to be allowed to stay until the guests departed."},{"start":102.15,"end":105.3,"text":"But this the Spirit said could not be done."},{"start":105.3,"end":108.225,"text":"Here's a new game,\" said Scrooge."},{"start":108.225,"end":111.725,"text":"One half hour, Spirit, only one!"},{"start":111.725,"end":122.15,"text":"It was a Game called Yes and No, where Scrooge's nephew had to think of something, and the rest must find out what; he only answering to their questions yes or no as the case was."},{"start":122.15,"end":152.887,"text":"The brisk fire of questioning to which he was exposed, elicited from him that he was thinking of an animal, a live animal, rather a disagreeable animal, a savage animal, an animal that growled and grunted sometimes, and talked sometimes, and lived in London, and walked about the streets, and wasn't made a show of, and wasn't led by anybody, and didn't live in a menagerie, and was never killed in a market, and was not a horse, or an ass, or a cow, or a bull, or a tiger, or a dog, or a pig, or a"},{"start":152.887,"end":155.062,"text":"cat, or a bear."},{"start":155.062,"end":165.85,"text":"At every fresh question that was put to him, this nephew burst into a fresh roar of laughter; and was so inexpressibly tickled, that he was obliged to get up off the sofa and stamp."},{"start":165.85,"end":172.062,"text":"At last the plump sister, falling into a similar state, cried out: \"I have found it out!"},{"start":172.062,"end":174.687,"text":"I know what it is, Fred!"},{"start":174.687,"end":176.737,"text":"I know what it is!"},{"start":176.737,"end":179.287,"text":"What is it?\" cried Fred."}]}},{"id":"III_18","number":18,"zh":{"text":"\"是你那位斯克鲁——奇——奇——奇舅舅！\"\n那可不正是嘛。\n人人都赞叹不已，不过有几个抗议说，问到\"是不是熊？\"那时本该答\"是\"才对；因为一个否定的回答，就足够把他们的心思从斯克鲁奇先生身上引开了——假如他们当真有过往那上头想的苗头的话。\n\"我敢说，他可给咱们带来了不少欢乐，\"弗雷德说，\"咱们不给他祝个健康，未免太不知好歹。\n这会儿手边正好有一杯热葡萄酒；我说一声'斯克鲁奇舅舅'！\"\n\"好！\n斯克鲁奇舅舅！\"他们嚷道。\n\"祝这老头儿圣诞快乐、新年快乐，不管他是个什么样的人！\"斯克鲁奇的外甥说。\n\"他是不肯领我的情的，可愿他到底得着这份祝福。\n斯克鲁奇舅舅！\"\n斯克鲁奇舅舅不知不觉间变得这般欢欣、心头这般轻快，倘若那鬼魂给他工夫，他真会回敬这浑然不觉的一伙人、用一篇听不见的祝词来谢他们。\n可整个情景随着他外甥说出最后一个字的那口气消散了；他和那精灵又踏上了游历的路。\n他们看了许多，走了很远，访了许多人家，可结局总是欢喜的。\n那精灵立在病榻旁，病榻便有了生气；立在异邦，异邦便恍如近在家乡；立在苦苦挣扎的人身旁，他们便在更大的指望里变得有了耐心；立在贫穷身旁，贫穷便也富足了。\n在济贫院、在医院、在监狱，在苦难的每一处栖身之所，凡是渺小的人凭着他那短暂卑微的权柄没能把门闩死、没把那精灵关在外头的地方，他都留下了他的祝福，又把他的箴言教给斯克鲁奇。\n这是一个漫长的夜，倘若这当真只是一夜的话；可斯克鲁奇对此却有几分疑惑，因为那整个圣诞假期仿佛都浓缩进了他们一同度过的这段时光里。\n还有桩怪事，就是斯克鲁奇外表始终没变，那鬼魂却老了，分明地老了。\n斯克鲁奇早留意到这变化，却始终没作声，直到他们离开一场孩子们的主显节晚会，他俩一同立在一处空地上，他望着那精灵，注意到它的头发已经灰白了。\n\"精灵的寿命就这么短吗？\"斯克鲁奇问。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_III_小节18.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":3.6,"text":"是你那位斯克鲁——奇——奇——奇舅舅！"},{"start":3.55,"end":5.262,"text":"那可不正是嘛。"},{"start":5.262,"end":21.375,"text":"人人都赞叹不已，不过有几个抗议说，问到\"是不是熊？\"那时本该答\"是\"才对；因为一个否定的回答，就足够把他们的心思从斯克鲁奇先生身上引开了——假如他们当真有过往那上头想的苗头的话。"},{"start":21.375,"end":28.8,"text":"我敢说，他可给咱们带来了不少欢乐，\"弗雷德说，\"咱们不给他祝个健康，未免太不知好歹。"},{"start":28.8,"end":34.075,"text":"这会儿手边正好有一杯热葡萄酒；我说一声'斯克鲁奇舅舅'！"},{"start":34.075,"end":35.012,"text":"好！"},{"start":35.012,"end":37.537,"text":"斯克鲁奇舅舅！\"他们嚷道。"},{"start":37.537,"end":43.6,"text":"祝这老头儿圣诞快乐、新年快乐，不管他是个什么样的人！\"斯克鲁奇的外甥说。"},{"start":43.6,"end":48.062,"text":"他是不肯领我的情的，可愿他到底得着这份祝福。"},{"start":48.062,"end":49.687,"text":"斯克鲁奇舅舅！"},{"start":49.687,"end":62.55,"text":"斯克鲁奇舅舅不知不觉间变得这般欢欣、心头这般轻快，倘若那鬼魂给他工夫，他真会回敬这浑然不觉的一伙人、用一篇听不见的祝词来谢他们。"},{"start":62.55,"end":70.437,"text":"可整个情景随着他外甥说出最后一个字的那口气消散了；他和那精灵又踏上了游历的路。"},{"start":70.437,"end":76.012,"text":"他们看了许多，走了很远，访了许多人家，可结局总是欢喜的。"},{"start":76.012,"end":91.737,"text":"那精灵立在病榻旁，病榻便有了生气；立在异邦，异邦便恍如近在家乡；立在苦苦挣扎的人身旁，他们便在更大的指望里变得有了耐心；立在贫穷身旁，贫穷便也富足了。"},{"start":91.737,"end":108.525,"text":"在济贫院、在医院、在监狱，在苦难的每一处栖身之所，凡是渺小的人凭着他那短暂卑微的权柄没能把门闩死、没把那精灵关在外头的地方，他都留下了他的祝福，又把他的箴言教给斯克鲁奇。"},{"start":108.525,"end":120.875,"text":"这是一个漫长的夜，倘若这当真只是一夜的话；可斯克鲁奇对此却有几分疑惑，因为那整个圣诞假期仿佛都浓缩进了他们一同度过的这段时光里。"},{"start":120.875,"end":127.05,"text":"还有桩怪事，就是斯克鲁奇外表始终没变，那鬼魂却老了，分明地老了。"},{"start":127.05,"end":140.3,"text":"斯克鲁奇早留意到这变化，却始终没作声，直到他们离开一场孩子们的主显节晚会，他俩一同立在一处空地上，他望着那精灵，注意到它的头发已经灰白了。"},{"start":140.3,"end":143.675,"text":"精灵的寿命就这么短吗？\"斯克鲁奇问。"}]},"en":{"text":"\"It's your Uncle Scro-o-o-o-oge!\"\nWhich it certainly was.\nAdmiration was the universal sentiment, though some objected that the reply to \"Is it a bear?\" ought to have been \"Yes;\" inasmuch as an answer in the negative was sufficient to have diverted their thoughts from Mr. Scrooge, supposing they had ever had any tendency that way.\n\"He has given us plenty of merriment, I am sure,\" said Fred, \"and it would be ungrateful not to drink his health.\nHere is a glass of mulled wine ready to our hand at the moment; and I say 'Uncle Scrooge!'\"\n\"Well!\nUncle Scrooge!\" they cried.\n\"A Merry Christmas and a happy New Year to the old man, whatever he is!\" said Scrooge's nephew.\n\"He wouldn't take it from me, but may he have it, nevertheless.\nUncle Scrooge!\"\nUncle Scrooge had imperceptibly become so gay and light of heart, that he would have pledged the unconscious company in return, and thanked them in an inaudible speech, if the Ghost had given him time.\nBut the whole scene passed off in the breath of the last word spoken by his nephew; and he and the Spirit were again upon their travels.\nMuch they saw, and far they went, and many homes they visited, but always with a happy end.\nThe Spirit stood beside sick beds, and they were cheerful; on foreign lands, and they were close at home; by struggling men, and they were patient in their greater hope; by poverty, and it was rich.\nIn almshouse, hospital, and jail, in misery's every refuge, where vain man in his little brief authority had not made fast the door, and barred the Spirit out, he left his blessing, and taught Scrooge his precepts.\nIt was a long night, if it were only a night; but Scrooge had his doubts of this, because the Christmas Holidays appeared to be condensed into the space of time they passed together.\nIt was strange, too, that while Scrooge remained unaltered in his outward form, the Ghost grew older, clearly older.\nScrooge had observed this change, but never spoke of it, until they left a children's Twelfth Night party, when, looking at the Spirit as they stood together in an open place, he noticed that its hair was gray.\n\"Are spirits' lives so short?\" asked Scrooge.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_III_小节18.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":2.487,"text":"It's your Uncle Scro-o-o-o-oge!"},{"start":2.437,"end":4.662,"text":"Which it certainly was."},{"start":4.662,"end":19.65,"text":"Admiration was the universal sentiment, though some objected that the reply to \"Is it a bear?\" ought to have been \"Yes;\" inasmuch as an answer in the negative was sufficient to have diverted their thoughts from Mr. Scrooge, supposing they had ever had any tendency that way."},{"start":19.65,"end":26.612,"text":"He has given us plenty of merriment, I am sure,\" said Fred, \"and it would be ungrateful not to drink his health."},{"start":26.612,"end":32.387,"text":"Here is a glass of mulled wine ready to our hand at the moment; and I say 'Uncle Scrooge!"},{"start":32.387,"end":33.7,"text":"Well!"},{"start":33.7,"end":36.55,"text":"Uncle Scrooge!\" they cried."},{"start":36.55,"end":42.9,"text":"A Merry Christmas and a happy New Year to the old man, whatever he is!\" said Scrooge's nephew."},{"start":42.9,"end":47.275,"text":"He wouldn't take it from me, but may he have it, nevertheless."},{"start":47.275,"end":49.175,"text":"Uncle Scrooge!"},{"start":49.175,"end":60.225,"text":"Uncle Scrooge had imperceptibly become so gay and light of heart, that he would have pledged the unconscious company in return, and thanked them in an inaudible speech, if the Ghost had given him time."},{"start":60.225,"end":68.075,"text":"But the whole scene passed off in the breath of the last word spoken by his nephew; and he and the Spirit were again upon their travels."},{"start":68.075,"end":74.562,"text":"Much they saw, and far they went, and many homes they visited, but always with a happy end."},{"start":74.562,"end":86.862,"text":"The Spirit stood beside sick beds, and they were cheerful; on foreign lands, and they were close at home; by struggling men, and they were patient in their greater hope; by poverty, and it was rich."},{"start":86.862,"end":100.375,"text":"In almshouse, hospital, and jail, in misery's every refuge, where vain man in his little brief authority had not made fast the door, and barred the Spirit out, he left his blessing, and taught Scrooge his precepts."},{"start":100.375,"end":110.212,"text":"It was a long night, if it were only a night; but Scrooge had his doubts of this, because the Christmas Holidays appeared to be condensed into the space of time they passed together."},{"start":110.212,"end":118.175,"text":"It was strange, too, that while Scrooge remained unaltered in his outward form, the Ghost grew older, clearly older."},{"start":118.175,"end":130.362,"text":"Scrooge had observed this change, but never spoke of it, until they left a children's Twelfth Night party, when, looking at the Spirit as they stood together in an open place, he noticed that its hair was gray."},{"start":130.362,"end":134.162,"text":"Are spirits' lives so short?\" asked Scrooge."}]}},{"id":"III_19","number":19,"zh":{"text":"\"我在这世上的寿命，是很短的，\"那鬼魂答道。\n\"今晚就要到头了。\"\n\"今晚！\"斯克鲁奇嚷道。\n\"今晚午夜。\n听！\n那时辰快到了。\"\n此刻排钟正敲着十一点三刻。\n\"倘若我这一问问得没道理，还请你原谅，\"斯克鲁奇凝神望着那精灵的袍子说，\"可我瞧见有个古怪的、不属于你自己的东西，从你的衣襟底下伸了出来。\n那是一只脚，还是一只爪子！\"\n\"凭那上头那点皮肉，倒也称得上是只爪子了，\"那精灵悲哀地答道。\n\"瞧这儿。\"\n它从袍子的褶皱里牵出两个孩子；可怜、卑贱、骇人、丑陋、凄惨。\n他们跪在它脚边，攀住它衣裳的外缘。\n\"哦，人哪！瞧这儿。\n瞧，瞧，瞧这底下！\"那鬼魂嚷道。\n那是一个男孩和一个女孩。\n面黄肌瘦、衣衫褴褛、横眉怒目、像狼一般；可又匍匐在地，卑微到了极点。\n本该由优雅的青春把他们的面容填得丰满、染上最鲜嫩的光彩的地方，却被一只衰老的、枯萎的、像老年人那样的手掐过、扭过、揪成了一条条褴褛。\n本该是天使端坐为王的地方，却潜伏着魔鬼，凶狠地往外瞪着。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_III_小节19.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":4.262,"text":"我在这世上的寿命，是很短的，\"那鬼魂答道。"},{"start":4.212,"end":6.012,"text":"今晚就要到头了。"},{"start":6.012,"end":8.287,"text":"今晚！\"斯克鲁奇嚷道。"},{"start":8.287,"end":9.7,"text":"今晚午夜。"},{"start":9.7,"end":10.625,"text":"听！"},{"start":10.625,"end":12.437,"text":"那时辰快到了。"},{"start":12.437,"end":15.225,"text":"此刻排钟正敲着十一点三刻。"},{"start":15.225,"end":27.5,"text":"倘若我这一问问得没道理，还请你原谅，\"斯克鲁奇凝神望着那精灵的袍子说，\"可我瞧见有个古怪的、不属于你自己的东西，从你的衣襟底下伸了出来。"},{"start":27.5,"end":30.3,"text":"那是一只脚，还是一只爪子！"},{"start":30.3,"end":35.862,"text":"凭那上头那点皮肉，倒也称得上是只爪子了，\"那精灵悲哀地答道。"},{"start":35.862,"end":36.95,"text":"瞧这儿。"},{"start":36.95,"end":43.85,"text":"它从袍子的褶皱里牵出两个孩子；可怜、卑贱、骇人、丑陋、凄惨。"},{"start":43.85,"end":47.262,"text":"他们跪在它脚边，攀住它衣裳的外缘。"},{"start":47.262,"end":48.85,"text":"哦，人哪！"},{"start":48.85,"end":49.937,"text":"瞧这儿。"},{"start":49.937,"end":53.612,"text":"瞧，瞧，瞧这底下！\"那鬼魂嚷道。"},{"start":53.612,"end":55.975,"text":"那是一个男孩和一个女孩。"},{"start":55.975,"end":63.125,"text":"面黄肌瘦、衣衫褴褛、横眉怒目、像狼一般；可又匍匐在地，卑微到了极点。"},{"start":63.125,"end":76.012,"text":"本该由优雅的青春把他们的面容填得丰满、染上最鲜嫩的光彩的地方，却被一只衰老的、枯萎的、像老年人那样的手掐过、扭过、揪成了一条条褴褛。"},{"start":76.012,"end":81.712,"text":"本该是天使端坐为王的地方，却潜伏着魔鬼，凶狠地往外瞪着。"}]},"en":{"text":"\"My life upon this globe, is very brief,\" replied the Ghost.\n\"It ends to-night.\"\n\"To-night!\" cried Scrooge.\n\"To-night at midnight.\nHark!\nThe time is drawing near.\"\nThe chimes were ringing the three quarters past eleven at that moment.\n\"Forgive me if I am not justified in what I ask,\" said Scrooge, looking intently at the Spirit's robe, \"but I see something strange, and not belonging to yourself, protruding from your skirts.\nIs it a foot or a claw!\"\n\"It might be a claw, for the flesh there is upon it,\" was the Spirit's sorrowful reply.\n\"Look here.\"\nFrom the foldings of its robe, it brought two children; wretched, abject, frightful, hideous, miserable.\nThey knelt down at its feet, and clung upon the outside of its garment.\n\"Oh, Man! look here.\nLook, look, down here!\" exclaimed the Ghost.\nThey were a boy and girl.\nYellow, meagre, ragged, scowling, wolfish; but prostrate, too, in their humility.\nWhere graceful youth should have filled their features out, and touched them with its freshest tints, a stale and shrivelled hand, like that of age, had pinched, and twisted them, and pulled them into shreds.\nWhere angels might have sat enthroned, devils lurked, and glared out menacing.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_III_小节19.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":4.975,"text":"My life upon this globe, is very brief,\" replied the Ghost."},{"start":4.925,"end":6.8,"text":"It ends to-night."},{"start":6.8,"end":9.412,"text":"To-night!\" cried Scrooge."},{"start":9.412,"end":11.437,"text":"To-night at midnight."},{"start":11.437,"end":12.825,"text":"Hark!"},{"start":12.825,"end":15.15,"text":"The time is drawing near."},{"start":15.15,"end":19.4,"text":"The chimes were ringing the three quarters past eleven at that moment."},{"start":19.4,"end":31.075,"text":"Forgive me if I am not justified in what I ask,\" said Scrooge, looking intently at the Spirit's robe, \"but I see something strange, and not belonging to yourself, protruding from your skirts."},{"start":31.075,"end":33.437,"text":"Is it a foot or a claw!"},{"start":33.437,"end":39.175,"text":"It might be a claw, for the flesh there is upon it,\" was the Spirit's sorrowful reply."},{"start":39.175,"end":40.687,"text":"Look here."},{"start":40.687,"end":48.462,"text":"From the foldings of its robe, it brought two children; wretched, abject, frightful, hideous, miserable."},{"start":48.462,"end":53.062,"text":"They knelt down at its feet, and clung upon the outside of its garment."},{"start":53.062,"end":55.05,"text":"Oh, Man!"},{"start":55.05,"end":56.562,"text":"look here."},{"start":56.562,"end":60.687,"text":"Look, look, down here!\" exclaimed the Ghost."},{"start":60.687,"end":63.037,"text":"They were a boy and girl."},{"start":63.037,"end":70.175,"text":"Yellow, meagre, ragged, scowling, wolfish; but prostrate, too, in their humility."},{"start":70.175,"end":81.75,"text":"Where graceful youth should have filled their features out, and touched them with its freshest tints, a stale and shrivelled hand, like that of age, had pinched, and twisted them, and pulled them into shreds."},{"start":81.75,"end":87.062,"text":"Where angels might have sat enthroned, devils lurked, and glared out menacing."}]}},{"id":"III_20","number":20,"zh":{"text":"在那奇妙造化的一切奥秘之中，无论哪一等级，人性纵有种种变异、堕落、扭曲，也生不出比这一半还要可怖、还要骇人的怪物来。\n斯克鲁奇骇得倒退了一步。\n他们就这么被指给他看，他想说他们是俊俏的孩子，可那话宁可哽在喉咙里，也不肯做这等弥天大谎的帮凶。\n\"精灵！他们是你的吗？\"斯克鲁奇再也说不下去了。\n\"他们是人类的，\"那精灵俯视着他们说。\n\"他们攀住我，是要向他们的父辈申诉。\n这男孩是无知。\n这女孩是匮乏。\n对这两个都要提防，对他们这一等的全都要提防，可最要提防的是这男孩，因为我在他眉头上看见了那写着的'毁灭'二字，除非那字被抹去。\n你抵赖吧！\"那精灵嚷道，朝那城市伸出手去。\n\"那些把它说出来的人，你诽谤他们去吧！\n你为着你那结党营私的目的承认它，再把它弄得更糟吧！\n然后等着那结局吧！\"\n\"他们就没有栖身之所，没有别的出路吗？\"斯克鲁奇嚷道。\n\"难道没有监狱吗？\"那精灵最后一次拿他自己的话回敬他。\n\"难道没有济贫院吗？\"\n钟敲十二点了。\n斯克鲁奇四下张望寻那鬼魂，却不见它的踪影。\n当那最后一响的余颤歇尽时，他记起了老雅各布·马利的预言，抬起眼来，望见一个庄严的幽灵，披着衣、罩着兜帽，像贴地而来的一团雾，正朝他飘来。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_III_小节20.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":11.287,"text":"在那奇妙造化的一切奥秘之中，无论哪一等级，人性纵有种种变异、堕落、扭曲，也生不出比这一半还要可怖、还要骇人的怪物来。"},{"start":11.237,"end":13.675,"text":"斯克鲁奇骇得倒退了一步。"},{"start":13.675,"end":23.125,"text":"他们就这么被指给他看，他想说他们是俊俏的孩子，可那话宁可哽在喉咙里，也不肯做这等弥天大谎的帮凶。"},{"start":23.125,"end":24.225,"text":"精灵！"},{"start":24.225,"end":27.962,"text":"他们是你的吗？\"斯克鲁奇再也说不下去了。"},{"start":27.962,"end":31.525,"text":"他们是人类的，\"那精灵俯视着他们说。"},{"start":31.525,"end":34.812,"text":"他们攀住我，是要向他们的父辈申诉。"},{"start":34.812,"end":36.562,"text":"这男孩是无知。"},{"start":36.562,"end":38.325,"text":"这女孩是匮乏。"},{"start":38.325,"end":50.112,"text":"对这两个都要提防，对他们这一等的全都要提防，可最要提防的是这男孩，因为我在他眉头上看见了那写着的'毁灭'二字，除非那字被抹去。"},{"start":50.112,"end":54.487,"text":"你抵赖吧！\"那精灵嚷道，朝那城市伸出手去。"},{"start":54.487,"end":57.837,"text":"那些把它说出来的人，你诽谤他们去吧！"},{"start":57.837,"end":62.637,"text":"你为着你那结党营私的目的承认它，再把它弄得更糟吧！"},{"start":62.637,"end":64.575,"text":"然后等着那结局吧！"},{"start":64.575,"end":69.1,"text":"他们就没有栖身之所，没有别的出路吗？\"斯克鲁奇嚷道。"},{"start":69.1,"end":74.025,"text":"难道没有监狱吗？\"那精灵最后一次拿他自己的话回敬他。"},{"start":74.025,"end":75.925,"text":"难道没有济贫院吗？"},{"start":75.925,"end":77.612,"text":"钟敲十二点了。"},{"start":77.612,"end":81.962,"text":"斯克鲁奇四下张望寻那鬼魂，却不见它的踪影。"},{"start":81.962,"end":94.975,"text":"当那最后一响的余颤歇尽时，他记起了老雅各布·马利的预言，抬起眼来，望见一个庄严的幽灵，披着衣、罩着兜帽，像贴地而来的一团雾，正朝他飘来。"}]},"en":{"text":"No change, no degradation, no perversion of humanity, in any grade, through all the mysteries of wonderful creation, has monsters half so horrible and dread.\nScrooge started back, appalled.\nHaving them shown to him in this way, he tried to say they were fine children, but the words choked themselves, rather than be parties to a lie of such enormous magnitude.\n\"Spirit! are they yours?\" Scrooge could say no more.\n\"They are Man's,\" said the Spirit, looking down upon them.\n\"And they cling to me, appealing from their fathers.\nThis boy is Ignorance.\nThis girl is Want.\nBeware them both, and all of their degree, but most of all beware this boy, for on his brow I see that written which is Doom, unless the writing be erased.\nDeny it!\" cried the Spirit, stretching out its hand towards the city.\n\"Slander those who tell it ye!\nAdmit it for your factious purposes, and make it worse!\nAnd bide the end!\"\n\"Have they no refuge or resource?\" cried Scrooge.\n\"Are there no prisons?\" said the Spirit, turning on him for the last time with his own words.\n\"Are there no workhouses?\"\nThe bell struck twelve.\nScrooge looked about him for the Ghost, and saw it not.\nAs the last stroke ceased to vibrate, he remembered the prediction of old Jacob Marley, and lifting up his eyes, beheld a solemn Phantom, draped and hooded, coming, like a mist along the ground, towards him.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_III_小节20.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":10.775,"text":"No change, no degradation, no perversion of humanity, in any grade, through all the mysteries of wonderful creation, has monsters half so horrible and dread."},{"start":10.725,"end":13.65,"text":"Scrooge started back, appalled."},{"start":13.65,"end":23.55,"text":"Having them shown to him in this way, he tried to say they were fine children, but the words choked themselves, rather than be parties to a lie of such enormous magnitude."},{"start":23.55,"end":25.15,"text":"Spirit!"},{"start":25.15,"end":26.912,"text":"are they yours?"},{"start":26.912,"end":29.45,"text":"Scrooge could say no more."},{"start":29.45,"end":33.625,"text":"They are Man's,\" said the Spirit, looking down upon them."},{"start":33.625,"end":37.137,"text":"And they cling to me, appealing from their fathers."},{"start":37.137,"end":39.475,"text":"This boy is Ignorance."},{"start":39.475,"end":41.55,"text":"This girl is Want."},{"start":41.55,"end":51.225,"text":"Beware them both, and all of their degree, but most of all beware this boy, for on his brow I see that written which is Doom, unless the writing be erased."},{"start":51.225,"end":56.112,"text":"Deny it!\" cried the Spirit, stretching out its hand towards the city."},{"start":56.112,"end":58.6,"text":"Slander those who tell it ye!"},{"start":58.6,"end":62.687,"text":"Admit it for your factious purposes, and make it worse!"},{"start":62.687,"end":64.712,"text":"And bide the end!"},{"start":64.712,"end":68.712,"text":"Have they no refuge or resource?\" cried Scrooge."},{"start":68.712,"end":74.387,"text":"Are there no prisons?\" said the Spirit, turning on him for the last time with his own words."},{"start":74.387,"end":76.6,"text":"Are there no workhouses?"},{"start":76.6,"end":78.875,"text":"The bell struck twelve."},{"start":78.875,"end":82.837,"text":"Scrooge looked about him for the Ghost, and saw it not."},{"start":82.837,"end":95.475,"text":"As the last stroke ceased to vibrate, he remembered the prediction of old Jacob Marley, and lifting up his eyes, beheld a solemn Phantom, draped and hooded, coming, like a mist along the ground, towards him."}]}}]},{"id":"Stave_IV","title":{"zh":"第四章","en":"STAVE IV."},"sections":[{"id":"IV_01","number":1,"zh":{"text":"第四章\n最后一个精灵\n那幽灵缓缓地、庄严地、悄无声息地走近前来。\n等它走到他跟前，斯克鲁奇便屈膝跪下；因为这精灵所经过的那空气里，它仿佛都播撒着阴森与神秘。\n它裹在一件深黑的衣裳里，把它的头、它的脸、它的身形都遮没了，只余一只伸出的手露在外面，此外一概看不见。\n若不是这只手，简直难以把它的身形从夜色里分辨出来、从环绕着它的黑暗里区别开来。\n它走到他身旁时，他觉出它又高又庄严，觉出它那神秘的存在叫他满心是一种肃然的恐惧。\n他再不知道别的了，因为那精灵既不说话也不动弹。\n\"我面前的，可是未来的圣诞之灵？\"斯克鲁奇说。\n那精灵没有回答，只用手往下一指。\n\"你就要给我看那些还没发生、却将在我们眼前的时光里发生的事情的影子，\"斯克鲁奇接着说。\n\"是这样吗，精灵？\"\n那衣裳上半截的褶子刹那间收拢了一下，仿佛那精灵把头点了点。\n他得到的回答就只有这么个。\n斯克鲁奇这会儿虽说早已惯于跟鬼魂作伴，却怕这沉默的身影怕得厉害，两条腿在身子底下直打颤，等他准备跟它走时，发觉自己几乎站立不住。\n那精灵停了一停，仿佛是看出了他这副光景，给他时间缓过来。\n可斯克鲁奇反倒被这一停弄得更难受了。\n他知道那暗沉的尸衣后头有一双鬼魂的眼睛正死死盯着他，而他自己呢，纵然把眼睛瞪到极处，也只看得见一只幽灵似的手和一大团黑——这叫他生出一种说不清、道不明的恐惧，浑身发颤。\n\"未来的鬼魂！\"他嚷道，\"我怕你，比怕我见过的任何一个幽灵都厉害。\n不过，我既然知道你许下的是要为我好，又既然指望着自己能活到脱胎换骨、做个跟从前不一样的人，我便准备好了陪你同行，而且怀着一颗感激的心去陪你。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_IV_小节01.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":1.287,"text":"第四章"},{"start":1.237,"end":2.937,"text":"最后一个精灵"},{"start":2.937,"end":7.575,"text":"那幽灵缓缓地、庄严地、悄无声息地走近前来。"},{"start":7.575,"end":16.5,"text":"等它走到他跟前，斯克鲁奇便屈膝跪下；因为这精灵所经过的那空气里，它仿佛都播撒着阴森与神秘。"},{"start":16.5,"end":26.375,"text":"它裹在一件深黑的衣裳里，把它的头、它的脸、它的身形都遮没了，只余一只伸出的手露在外面，此外一概看不见。"},{"start":26.375,"end":33.887,"text":"若不是这只手，简直难以把它的身形从夜色里分辨出来、从环绕着它的黑暗里区别开来。"},{"start":33.887,"end":42.325,"text":"它走到他身旁时，他觉出它又高又庄严，觉出它那神秘的存在叫他满心是一种肃然的恐惧。"},{"start":42.325,"end":46.675,"text":"他再不知道别的了，因为那精灵既不说话也不动弹。"},{"start":46.675,"end":50.7,"text":"我面前的，可是未来的圣诞之灵？\"斯克鲁奇说。"},{"start":50.7,"end":54.1,"text":"那精灵没有回答，只用手往下一指。"},{"start":54.1,"end":61.337,"text":"你就要给我看那些还没发生、却将在我们眼前的时光里发生的事情的影子，\"斯克鲁奇接着说。"},{"start":61.337,"end":63.325,"text":"是这样吗，精灵？"},{"start":63.325,"end":69.112,"text":"那衣裳上半截的褶子刹那间收拢了一下，仿佛那精灵把头点了点。"},{"start":69.112,"end":71.8,"text":"他得到的回答就只有这么个。"},{"start":71.8,"end":84.075,"text":"斯克鲁奇这会儿虽说早已惯于跟鬼魂作伴，却怕这沉默的身影怕得厉害，两条腿在身子底下直打颤，等他准备跟它走时，发觉自己几乎站立不住。"},{"start":84.075,"end":89.762,"text":"那精灵停了一停，仿佛是看出了他这副光景，给他时间缓过来。"},{"start":89.762,"end":93.362,"text":"可斯克鲁奇反倒被这一停弄得更难受了。"},{"start":93.362,"end":110.225,"text":"他知道那暗沉的尸衣后头有一双鬼魂的眼睛正死死盯着他，而他自己呢，纵然把眼睛瞪到极处，也只看得见一只幽灵似的手和一大团黑——这叫他生出一种说不清、道不明的恐惧，浑身发颤。"},{"start":110.225,"end":115.95,"text":"未来的鬼魂！\"他嚷道，\"我怕你，比怕我见过的任何一个幽灵都厉害。"},{"start":115.95,"end":128.912,"text":"不过，我既然知道你许下的是要为我好，又既然指望着自己能活到脱胎换骨、做个跟从前不一样的人，我便准备好了陪你同行，而且怀着一颗感激的心去陪你。"}]},"en":{"text":"STAVE IV.\nTHE LAST OF THE SPIRITS.\nThe Phantom slowly, gravely, silently, approached.\nWhen it came near him, Scrooge bent down upon his knee; for in the very air through which this Spirit moved it seemed to scatter gloom and mystery.\nIt was shrouded in a deep black garment, which concealed its head, its face, its form, and left nothing of it visible save one outstretched hand.\nBut for this it would have been difficult to detach its figure from the night, and separate it from the darkness by which it was surrounded.\nHe felt that it was tall and stately when it came beside him, and that its mysterious presence filled him with a solemn dread.\nHe knew no more, for the Spirit neither spoke nor moved.\n\"I am in the presence of the Ghost of Christmas Yet To Come?\" said Scrooge.\nThe Spirit answered not, but pointed downward with its hand.\n\"You are about to show me shadows of the things that have not happened, but will happen in the time before us,\" Scrooge pursued.\n\"Is that so, Spirit?\"\nThe upper portion of the garment was contracted for an instant in its folds, as if the Spirit had inclined its head.\nThat was the only answer he received.\nAlthough well used to ghostly company by this time, Scrooge feared the silent shape so much that his legs trembled beneath him, and he found that he could hardly stand when he prepared to follow it.\nThe Spirit paused a moment, as observing his condition, and giving him time to recover.\nBut Scrooge was all the worse for this.\nIt thrilled him with a vague uncertain horror, to know that behind the dusky shroud there were ghostly eyes intently fixed upon him, while he, though he stretched his own to the utmost, could see nothing but a spectral hand and one great heap of black.\n\"Ghost of the Future!\" he exclaimed, \"I fear you more than any Spectre I have seen.\nBut, as I know your promise is to do me good, and as I hope to live to be another man from what I was, I am prepared to bear you company, and do it with a thankful heart.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_IV_小节01.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":1.937,"text":"STAVE IV."},{"start":1.887,"end":4.15,"text":"THE LAST OF THE SPIRITS."},{"start":4.15,"end":8.825,"text":"The Phantom slowly, gravely, silently, approached."},{"start":8.825,"end":17.062,"text":"When it came near him, Scrooge bent down upon his knee; for in the very air through which this Spirit moved it seemed to scatter gloom and mystery."},{"start":17.062,"end":26.325,"text":"It was shrouded in a deep black garment, which concealed its head, its face, its form, and left nothing of it visible save one outstretched hand."},{"start":26.325,"end":33.487,"text":"But for this it would have been difficult to detach its figure from the night, and separate it from the darkness by which it was surrounded."},{"start":33.487,"end":40.562,"text":"He felt that it was tall and stately when it came beside him, and that its mysterious presence filled him with a solemn dread."},{"start":40.562,"end":44.787,"text":"He knew no more, for the Spirit neither spoke nor moved."},{"start":44.787,"end":49.537,"text":"I am in the presence of the Ghost of Christmas Yet To Come?\" said Scrooge."},{"start":49.537,"end":53.737,"text":"The Spirit answered not, but pointed downward with its hand."},{"start":53.737,"end":61,"text":"You are about to show me shadows of the things that have not happened, but will happen in the time before us,\" Scrooge pursued."},{"start":61,"end":63.425,"text":"Is that so, Spirit?"},{"start":63.425,"end":70.137,"text":"The upper portion of the garment was contracted for an instant in its folds, as if the Spirit had inclined its head."},{"start":70.137,"end":73.062,"text":"That was the only answer he received."},{"start":73.062,"end":83.637,"text":"Although well used to ghostly company by this time, Scrooge feared the silent shape so much that his legs trembled beneath him, and he found that he could hardly stand when he prepared to follow it."},{"start":83.637,"end":89.275,"text":"The Spirit paused a moment, as observing his condition, and giving him time to recover."},{"start":89.275,"end":92.225,"text":"But Scrooge was all the worse for this."},{"start":92.225,"end":106.275,"text":"It thrilled him with a vague uncertain horror, to know that behind the dusky shroud there were ghostly eyes intently fixed upon him, while he, though he stretched his own to the utmost, could see nothing but a spectral hand and one great heap of black."},{"start":106.275,"end":111.8,"text":"Ghost of the Future!\" he exclaimed, \"I fear you more than any Spectre I have seen."},{"start":111.8,"end":121.8,"text":"But, as I know your promise is to do me good, and as I hope to live to be another man from what I was, I am prepared to bear you company, and do it with a thankful heart."}]}},{"id":"IV_02","number":2,"zh":{"text":"你不肯跟我说句话吗？\"\n它没有给他回答。\n那只手径直指着他们前方。\n\"领路吧！\"斯克鲁奇说。\n\"领路吧！\n夜眼看就要过去了，我知道这对我是宝贵的光阴。\n领路吧，精灵！\"\n那幽灵像先前朝他走来时那样，移步走开了。\n斯克鲁奇跟在它衣裳的影子里，他觉着那影子托着他，带着他往前走。\n他们仿佛根本没走进那城市；倒像是那城市自个儿在他们四周拔地而起，把他们围拢了进来。\n可他们偏偏就在它的心脏地带；在交易所里，在商人们中间；那些人匆匆地走来走去，把口袋里的钱弄得叮当响，三三两两地交谈，看着各自的表，若有所思地摆弄着他们那大大的金印章；如此种种，正是斯克鲁奇时常见惯的光景。\n那精灵在一小簇生意人旁边停了下来。\n斯克鲁奇见那只手指着他们，便走上前去听他们交谈。\n\"不，\"一个长着骇人下巴的大胖子说，\"这事我也不大清楚，不管哪一头。\n我只知道他死了。\"\n\"他什么时候死的？\"另一个问。\n\"我想是昨儿夜里。\"\n\"咦，他到底得了什么病？\"第三个一面问，一面从一只很大的鼻烟盒里捏出好大一撮鼻烟。\n\"我还当他永远不会死呢。\"\n\"天晓得，\"头一个打着哈欠说。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_IV_小节02.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":2.062,"text":"你不肯跟我说句话吗？"},{"start":2.012,"end":3.812,"text":"它没有给他回答。"},{"start":3.812,"end":6.65,"text":"那只手径直指着他们前方。"},{"start":6.65,"end":8.875,"text":"领路吧！\"斯克鲁奇说。"},{"start":8.875,"end":10.025,"text":"领路吧！"},{"start":10.025,"end":14.225,"text":"夜眼看就要过去了，我知道这对我是宝贵的光阴。"},{"start":14.225,"end":16.012,"text":"领路吧，精灵！"},{"start":16.012,"end":20,"text":"那幽灵像先前朝他走来时那样，移步走开了。"},{"start":20,"end":26.012,"text":"斯克鲁奇跟在它衣裳的影子里，他觉着那影子托着他，带着他往前走。"},{"start":26.012,"end":33.712,"text":"他们仿佛根本没走进那城市；倒像是那城市自个儿在他们四周拔地而起，把他们围拢了进来。"},{"start":33.712,"end":53.537,"text":"可他们偏偏就在它的心脏地带；在交易所里，在商人们中间；那些人匆匆地走来走去，把口袋里的钱弄得叮当响，三三两两地交谈，看着各自的表，若有所思地摆弄着他们那大大的金印章；如此种种，正是斯克鲁奇时常见惯的光景。"},{"start":53.537,"end":56.887,"text":"那精灵在一小簇生意人旁边停了下来。"},{"start":56.887,"end":61.825,"text":"斯克鲁奇见那只手指着他们，便走上前去听他们交谈。"},{"start":61.825,"end":67.387,"text":"不，\"一个长着骇人下巴的大胖子说，\"这事我也不大清楚，不管哪一头。"},{"start":67.387,"end":69.3,"text":"我只知道他死了。"},{"start":69.3,"end":71.9,"text":"他什么时候死的？\"另一个问。"},{"start":71.9,"end":73.675,"text":"我想是昨儿夜里。"},{"start":73.675,"end":81.262,"text":"咦，他到底得了什么病？\"第三个一面问，一面从一只很大的鼻烟盒里捏出好大一撮鼻烟。"},{"start":81.262,"end":83.775,"text":"我还当他永远不会死呢。"},{"start":83.775,"end":86.575,"text":"天晓得，\"头一个打着哈欠说。"}]},"en":{"text":"Will you not speak to me?\"\nIt gave him no reply.\nThe hand was pointed straight before them.\n\"Lead on!\" said Scrooge.\n\"Lead on!\nThe night is waning fast, and it is precious time to me, I know.\nLead on, Spirit!\"\nThe Phantom moved away as it had come towards him.\nScrooge followed in the shadow of its dress, which bore him up, he thought, and carried him along.\nThey scarcely seemed to enter the city; for the city rather seemed to spring up about them, and encompass them of its own act.\nBut there they were, in the heart of it; on 'Change, amongst the merchants; who hurried up and down, and chinked the money in their pockets, and conversed in groups, and looked at their watches, and trifled thoughtfully with their great gold seals; and so forth, as Scrooge had seen them often.\nThe Spirit stopped beside one little knot of business men.\nObserving that the hand was pointed to them, Scrooge advanced to listen to their talk.\n\"No,\" said a great fat man with a monstrous chin, \"I don't know much about it, either way.\nI only know he's dead.\"\n\"When did he die?\" inquired another.\n\"Last night, I believe.\"\n\"Why, what was the matter with him?\" asked a third, taking a vast quantity of snuff out of a very large snuff-box.\n\"I thought he'd never die.\"\n\"God knows,\" said the first, with a yawn.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_IV_小节02.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":2.15,"text":"Will you not speak to me?"},{"start":2.1,"end":4.437,"text":"It gave him no reply."},{"start":4.437,"end":7.4,"text":"The hand was pointed straight before them."},{"start":7.4,"end":10.112,"text":"Lead on!\" said Scrooge."},{"start":10.112,"end":11.75,"text":"Lead on!"},{"start":11.75,"end":16.375,"text":"The night is waning fast, and it is precious time to me, I know."},{"start":16.375,"end":18.725,"text":"Lead on, Spirit!"},{"start":18.725,"end":22.112,"text":"The Phantom moved away as it had come towards him."},{"start":22.112,"end":28.325,"text":"Scrooge followed in the shadow of its dress, which bore him up, he thought, and carried him along."},{"start":28.325,"end":35.575,"text":"They scarcely seemed to enter the city; for the city rather seemed to spring up about them, and encompass them of its own act."},{"start":35.575,"end":52.587,"text":"But there they were, in the heart of it; on 'Change, amongst the merchants; who hurried up and down, and chinked the money in their pockets, and conversed in groups, and looked at their watches, and trifled thoughtfully with their great gold seals; and so forth, as Scrooge had seen them often."},{"start":52.587,"end":56.562,"text":"The Spirit stopped beside one little knot of business men."},{"start":56.562,"end":61.762,"text":"Observing that the hand was pointed to them, Scrooge advanced to listen to their talk."},{"start":61.762,"end":67.737,"text":"No,\" said a great fat man with a monstrous chin, \"I don't know much about it, either way."},{"start":67.737,"end":70,"text":"I only know he's dead."},{"start":70,"end":73.037,"text":"When did he die?\" inquired another."},{"start":73.037,"end":75.525,"text":"Last night, I believe."},{"start":75.525,"end":83.05,"text":"Why, what was the matter with him?\" asked a third, taking a vast quantity of snuff out of a very large snuff-box."},{"start":83.05,"end":85.237,"text":"I thought he'd never die."},{"start":85.237,"end":88.8,"text":"God knows,\" said the first, with a yawn."}]}},{"id":"IV_03","number":3,"zh":{"text":"\"他那笔钱怎么处置了？\"一个红脸膛的绅士问道，他鼻尖上耷拉着一个肉瘤，抖起来活像火鸡的垂肉。\n\"我没听说，\"那大下巴的人又打着哈欠说。\n\"兴许是留给他的公司了吧。\n反正没留给我。\n我就知道这么些。\"\n这句俏皮话引来了哄堂大笑。\n\"这丧事多半办得寒酸得很，\"还是方才那位说道，\"因为我敢拿性命担保，我想不出有谁会去送葬。\n要不咱们凑个伙、自告奋勇去？\"\n\"管饭的话我倒不在乎去一趟，\"那鼻尖长瘤的绅士说。\n\"不过我要去凑这个数，可得管我吃饱。\"\n又是一阵笑。\n\"得，到头来我才是你们当中最不图回报的一个，\"头一个说话的人说，\"因为我从不戴黑手套，也从不吃什么午饭。\n不过只要有别人肯去，我也愿意去。\n仔细一想，我还真说不准我是不是他最要好的朋友呢；因为咱俩每回碰上，总要停下来说几句话。\n再会，再会！\"\n说话的、听话的都散步走开，混进了别的人群里。\n斯克鲁奇认得这些人，便望向那精灵，等它解释。\n那幽灵滑行着拐进一条街。\n它的手指指着两个碰头的人。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_IV_小节03.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":8.012,"text":"他那笔钱怎么处置了？\"一个红脸膛的绅士问道，他鼻尖上耷拉着一个肉瘤，抖起来活像火鸡的垂肉。"},{"start":7.962,"end":11.712,"text":"我没听说，\"那大下巴的人又打着哈欠说。"},{"start":11.712,"end":14.387,"text":"兴许是留给他的公司了吧。"},{"start":14.387,"end":16.05,"text":"反正没留给我。"},{"start":16.05,"end":17.662,"text":"我就知道这么些。"},{"start":17.662,"end":20.562,"text":"这句俏皮话引来了哄堂大笑。"},{"start":20.562,"end":28.862,"text":"这丧事多半办得寒酸得很，\"还是方才那位说道，\"因为我敢拿性命担保，我想不出有谁会去送葬。"},{"start":28.862,"end":31.75,"text":"要不咱们凑个伙、自告奋勇去？"},{"start":31.75,"end":36.362,"text":"管饭的话我倒不在乎去一趟，\"那鼻尖长瘤的绅士说。"},{"start":36.362,"end":39.487,"text":"不过我要去凑这个数，可得管我吃饱。"},{"start":39.487,"end":40.937,"text":"又是一阵笑。"},{"start":40.937,"end":49.975,"text":"得，到头来我才是你们当中最不图回报的一个，\"头一个说话的人说，\"因为我从不戴黑手套，也从不吃什么午饭。"},{"start":49.975,"end":53.162,"text":"不过只要有别人肯去，我也愿意去。"},{"start":53.162,"end":60.787,"text":"仔细一想，我还真说不准我是不是他最要好的朋友呢；因为咱俩每回碰上，总要停下来说几句话。"},{"start":60.787,"end":62.4,"text":"再会，再会！"},{"start":62.4,"end":67,"text":"说话的、听话的都散步走开，混进了别的人群里。"},{"start":67,"end":71.312,"text":"斯克鲁奇认得这些人，便望向那精灵，等它解释。"},{"start":71.312,"end":74.287,"text":"那幽灵滑行着拐进一条街。"},{"start":74.287,"end":77.125,"text":"它的手指指着两个碰头的人。"}]},"en":{"text":"\"What has he done with his money?\" asked a red-faced gentleman with a pendulous excrescence on the end of his nose, that shook like the gills of a turkey-cock.\n\"I haven't heard,\" said the man with the large chin, yawning again.\n\"Left it to his Company, perhaps.\nHe hasn't left it to _me_.\nThat's all _I_ know.\"\nThis pleasantry was received with a general laugh.\n\"It's likely to be a very cheap funeral,\" said the same speaker; \"for upon my life I don't know of anybody to go to it.\nSuppose we make up a party and volunteer?\"\n\"I don't mind going if a lunch is provided,\" observed the gentleman with the excrescence on his nose.\n\"But I must be fed, if I make one.\"\nAnother laugh.\n\"Well, I am the most disinterested among you, after all,\" said the first speaker, \"for I never wear black gloves, and I never eat lunch.\nBut I'll offer to go, if anybody else will.\nWhen I come to think of it, I'm not at all sure that I wasn't his most particular friend; for we used to stop and speak whenever we met.\nBye, bye!\"\nSpeakers and listeners strolled away, and mixed with other groups.\nScrooge knew the men, and looked towards the Spirit for an explanation.\nThe Phantom glided on into a street.\nIts finger pointed to two persons meeting.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_IV_小节03.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":8.787,"text":"What has he done with his money?\" asked a red-faced gentleman with a pendulous excrescence on the end of his nose, that shook like the gills of a turkey-cock."},{"start":8.737,"end":13.237,"text":"I haven't heard,\" said the man with the large chin, yawning again."},{"start":13.237,"end":16.15,"text":"Left it to his Company, perhaps."},{"start":16.15,"end":19.425,"text":"He hasn't left it to _me_."},{"start":19.425,"end":22.375,"text":"That's all _I_ know."},{"start":22.375,"end":25.85,"text":"This pleasantry was received with a general laugh."},{"start":25.85,"end":33,"text":"It's likely to be a very cheap funeral,\" said the same speaker; \"for upon my life I don't know of anybody to go to it."},{"start":33,"end":36.162,"text":"Suppose we make up a party and volunteer?"},{"start":36.162,"end":42.087,"text":"I don't mind going if a lunch is provided,\" observed the gentleman with the excrescence on his nose."},{"start":42.087,"end":45.175,"text":"But I must be fed, if I make one."},{"start":45.175,"end":46.962,"text":"Another laugh."},{"start":46.962,"end":55.887,"text":"Well, I am the most disinterested among you, after all,\" said the first speaker, \"for I never wear black gloves, and I never eat lunch."},{"start":55.887,"end":59.3,"text":"But I'll offer to go, if anybody else will."},{"start":59.3,"end":67.212,"text":"When I come to think of it, I'm not at all sure that I wasn't his most particular friend; for we used to stop and speak whenever we met."},{"start":67.212,"end":69.2,"text":"Bye, bye!"},{"start":69.2,"end":73.712,"text":"Speakers and listeners strolled away, and mixed with other groups."},{"start":73.712,"end":78.487,"text":"Scrooge knew the men, and looked towards the Spirit for an explanation."},{"start":78.487,"end":81.375,"text":"The Phantom glided on into a street."},{"start":81.375,"end":84.412,"text":"Its finger pointed to two persons meeting."}]}},{"id":"IV_04","number":4,"zh":{"text":"斯克鲁奇又侧耳去听，心想那解释兴许就在这儿。\n这两个人他也认得，认得一清二楚。\n他们都是生意人：极有钱，也极有分量。\n他向来把在他们心目中保持好名声当作一桩要紧事：是指生意上的眼光，确切说，纯然是生意上的眼光。\n\"你好啊？\"一个说。\n\"你好啊？\"另一个应道。\n\"嗐！\"头一个说。\n\"那老魔头到底把他自个儿的东西收走啦，嗯？\"\n\"我也听人这么说，\"第二个应道。\n\"挺冷的，是吧？\"\n\"圣诞时节，应当的。\n我看你不滑冰吧？\"\n\"不。不。有别的事要操心。\n再见！\"\n再没有别的话了。\n这就是他们的碰头、他们的交谈、他们的道别。\n斯克鲁奇起初颇感诧异，纳闷那精灵怎么会把这等显然无关紧要的谈话当回事；可他确信这里头必定藏着某种用意，便着意去琢磨那用意大概是什么。\n这些话总不至于跟雅各布——他那老合伙人——的死有什么干系，因为那是过去的事，而这鬼魂管辖的是未来。\n他也想不出有哪个跟他直接相干的人，可以把这些话往他身上套。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_IV_小节04.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":4.487,"text":"斯克鲁奇又侧耳去听，心想那解释兴许就在这儿。"},{"start":4.437,"end":7.662,"text":"这两个人他也认得，认得一清二楚。"},{"start":7.662,"end":11.225,"text":"他们都是生意人：极有钱，也极有分量。"},{"start":11.225,"end":20.287,"text":"他向来把在他们心目中保持好名声当作一桩要紧事：是指生意上的眼光，确切说，纯然是生意上的眼光。"},{"start":20.287,"end":22.212,"text":"你好啊？\"一个说。"},{"start":22.212,"end":24.162,"text":"你好啊？\"另一个应道。"},{"start":24.162,"end":25.062,"text":"嗐！"},{"start":25.062,"end":26.425,"text":"头一个说。"},{"start":26.425,"end":30.4,"text":"那老魔头到底把他自个儿的东西收走啦，嗯？"},{"start":30.4,"end":33.012,"text":"我也听人这么说，\"第二个应道。"},{"start":33.012,"end":34.737,"text":"挺冷的，是吧？"},{"start":34.737,"end":36.887,"text":"圣诞时节，应当的。"},{"start":36.887,"end":38.65,"text":"我看你不滑冰吧？"},{"start":38.65,"end":39.487,"text":"不。"},{"start":39.487,"end":40.325,"text":"不。"},{"start":40.325,"end":42.137,"text":"有别的事要操心。"},{"start":42.137,"end":43.175,"text":"再见！"},{"start":43.175,"end":44.95,"text":"再没有别的话了。"},{"start":44.95,"end":48.937,"text":"这就是他们的碰头、他们的交谈、他们的道别。"},{"start":48.937,"end":62.05,"text":"斯克鲁奇起初颇感诧异，纳闷那精灵怎么会把这等显然无关紧要的谈话当回事；可他确信这里头必定藏着某种用意，便着意去琢磨那用意大概是什么。"},{"start":62.05,"end":70.937,"text":"这些话总不至于跟雅各布——他那老合伙人——的死有什么干系，因为那是过去的事，而这鬼魂管辖的是未来。"},{"start":70.937,"end":76.587,"text":"他也想不出有哪个跟他直接相干的人，可以把这些话往他身上套。"}]},"en":{"text":"Scrooge listened again, thinking that the explanation might lie here.\nHe knew these men, also, perfectly.\nThey were men of business: very wealthy, and of great importance.\nHe had made a point always of standing well in their esteem: in a business point of view, that is; strictly in a business point of view.\n\"How are you?\" said one.\n\"How are you?\" returned the other.\n\"Well!\" said the first.\n\"Old Scratch has got his own at last, hey?\"\n\"So I am told,\" returned the second.\n\"Cold, isn't it?\"\n\"Seasonable for Christmas time.\nYou're not a skaiter, I suppose?\"\n\"No. No. Something else to think of.\nGood morning!\"\nNot another word.\nThat was their meeting, their conversation, and their parting.\nScrooge was at first inclined to be surprised that the Spirit should attach importance to conversations apparently so trivial; but feeling assured that they must have some hidden purpose, he set himself to consider what it was likely to be.\nThey could scarcely be supposed to have any bearing on the death of Jacob, his old partner, for that was Past, and this Ghost's province was the Future.\nNor could he think of any one immediately connected with himself, to whom he could apply them.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_IV_小节04.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":4.6,"text":"Scrooge listened again, thinking that the explanation might lie here."},{"start":4.55,"end":8.037,"text":"He knew these men, also, perfectly."},{"start":8.037,"end":12.637,"text":"They were men of business: very wealthy, and of great importance."},{"start":12.637,"end":20.85,"text":"He had made a point always of standing well in their esteem: in a business point of view, that is; strictly in a business point of view."},{"start":20.85,"end":23.225,"text":"How are you?\" said one."},{"start":23.225,"end":25.912,"text":"How are you?\" returned the other."},{"start":25.912,"end":28.15,"text":"Well!\" said the first."},{"start":28.15,"end":31.5,"text":"Old Scratch has got his own at last, hey?"},{"start":31.5,"end":34.6,"text":"So I am told,\" returned the second."},{"start":34.6,"end":36.6,"text":"Cold, isn't it?"},{"start":36.6,"end":39.175,"text":"Seasonable for Christmas time."},{"start":39.175,"end":41.925,"text":"You're not a skaiter, I suppose?"},{"start":41.925,"end":43.3,"text":"No."},{"start":43.3,"end":44.675,"text":"No."},{"start":44.675,"end":47.012,"text":"Something else to think of."},{"start":47.012,"end":48.575,"text":"Good morning!"},{"start":48.575,"end":50.487,"text":"Not another word."},{"start":50.487,"end":54.512,"text":"That was their meeting, their conversation, and their parting."},{"start":54.512,"end":67.325,"text":"Scrooge was at first inclined to be surprised that the Spirit should attach importance to conversations apparently so trivial; but feeling assured that they must have some hidden purpose, he set himself to consider what it was likely to be."},{"start":67.325,"end":76.1,"text":"They could scarcely be supposed to have any bearing on the death of Jacob, his old partner, for that was Past, and this Ghost's province was the Future."},{"start":76.1,"end":81.575,"text":"Nor could he think of any one immediately connected with himself, to whom he could apply them."}]}},{"id":"IV_05","number":5,"zh":{"text":"可他毫不怀疑：无论这些话应在谁身上，里头总藏着某种供他改过自新的训诫，便打定主意把听到的每一个字、看到的每一桩事都珍藏起来；尤其要留意他自己那个影子，等它一出现就盯住。\n因为他存着个指望：他未来那个自己的所作所为，会给他那遗漏的线索，叫这些谜团迎刃而解。\n他就在那同一个地方四下寻找自己的身影；可他惯常待的那个角落里却站着另一个人，钟虽指着他平日该到那儿的时辰，他却在从门廊涌进来的人群里看不见一个像他自己的。\n不过这倒没怎么叫他诧异；因为他心里头一直在盘算着改变生活，他想着、也指望着自己瞧见的，正是他那新生的决心在这上头付诸了实行。\n那幽灵静悄悄、黑沉沉地立在他身旁，伸着它那只手。\n等他从沉思的求索里回过神来，从那只手的转向、从它相对于他自己的方位，他揣摩那双看不见的眼睛正锐利地盯着他。\n这叫他打了个寒噤，觉着浑身冰凉。\n他们离开那繁忙的场面，走进城里一处偏僻的去处，斯克鲁奇从前从没钻进去过，尽管他认得它的方位、知道它的恶名。\n那些道路又脏又窄；店铺和房屋破败不堪；那里的人半裸着身子，醉醺醺、邋里邋遢、丑陋不堪。\n小巷和拱道像一个个污水坑，把它们那一股股气味、污秽和生计的腌臜，吐到那杂乱无章的街道上；整片街区都散发着犯罪、污垢和苦难的恶臭。\n在这声名狼藉的渊薮深处，有一间矮檐压顶、向外探出的铺子，开在一个披屋顶底下，专收破铁、旧布、瓶子、骨头和油腻的下水。\n铺子里头的地板上，堆着一堆堆生锈的钥匙、钉子、链条、铰链、锉刀、秤、砝码，还有各式各样的废铁。\n没多少人乐意去细察的种种秘密，就在那一座座不堪入目的破布堆、一团团腐臭的油脂、一冢冢白骨里头滋生、藏匿着。\n在他经手的那些货物当中，挨着一只旧砖砌的炭炉，坐着一个白发苍苍的无赖，年近七十；他用晾衣绳上挂着的一幅由杂七杂八的破烂拼成的腌臜帘子，把自己同外头的冷空气隔开；安享着退隐的清闲，抽着他的烟斗。\n斯克鲁奇和那幽灵来到这人跟前，恰好有个女人提着一个沉甸甸的包袱溜进了铺子。\n可她才刚进来，另一个女人也进来了，同样背着东西；紧跟在她后头的是个穿褪了色黑衣的男人，他一见这两人，惊愕之状不亚于她们彼此认出对方时那般。\n在一阵茫然的惊讶过后——抽烟斗的老头儿也加入了她们——他们三个一齐放声大笑起来。\n\"打杂女工头一个到，这还用说！\"头一个进来的女人嚷道。\n\"洗衣妇第二个到，这还用说；殡仪馆那伙计第三个到，这也还用说。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_IV_小节05.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":16,"text":"可他毫不怀疑：无论这些话应在谁身上，里头总藏着某种供他改过自新的训诫，便打定主意把听到的每一个字、看到的每一桩事都珍藏起来；尤其要留意他自己那个影子，等它一出现就盯住。"},{"start":16,"end":23.737,"text":"因为他存着个指望：他未来那个自己的所作所为，会给他那遗漏的线索，叫这些谜团迎刃而解。"},{"start":23.737,"end":38.2,"text":"他就在那同一个地方四下寻找自己的身影；可他惯常待的那个角落里却站着另一个人，钟虽指着他平日该到那儿的时辰，他却在从门廊涌进来的人群里看不见一个像他自己的。"},{"start":38.2,"end":50.325,"text":"不过这倒没怎么叫他诧异；因为他心里头一直在盘算着改变生活，他想着、也指望着自己瞧见的，正是他那新生的决心在这上头付诸了实行。"},{"start":50.325,"end":55.562,"text":"那幽灵静悄悄、黑沉沉地立在他身旁，伸着它那只手。"},{"start":55.562,"end":66.112,"text":"等他从沉思的求索里回过神来，从那只手的转向、从它相对于他自己的方位，他揣摩那双看不见的眼睛正锐利地盯着他。"},{"start":66.112,"end":69.6,"text":"这叫他打了个寒噤，觉着浑身冰凉。"},{"start":69.6,"end":79.712,"text":"他们离开那繁忙的场面，走进城里一处偏僻的去处，斯克鲁奇从前从没钻进去过，尽管他认得它的方位、知道它的恶名。"},{"start":79.712,"end":88.45,"text":"那些道路又脏又窄；店铺和房屋破败不堪；那里的人半裸着身子，醉醺醺、邋里邋遢、丑陋不堪。"},{"start":88.45,"end":101.762,"text":"小巷和拱道像一个个污水坑，把它们那一股股气味、污秽和生计的腌臜，吐到那杂乱无章的街道上；整片街区都散发着犯罪、污垢和苦难的恶臭。"},{"start":101.762,"end":113.637,"text":"在这声名狼藉的渊薮深处，有一间矮檐压顶、向外探出的铺子，开在一个披屋顶底下，专收破铁、旧布、瓶子、骨头和油腻的下水。"},{"start":113.637,"end":123.45,"text":"铺子里头的地板上，堆着一堆堆生锈的钥匙、钉子、链条、铰链、锉刀、秤、砝码，还有各式各样的废铁。"},{"start":123.45,"end":133.6,"text":"没多少人乐意去细察的种种秘密，就在那一座座不堪入目的破布堆、一团团腐臭的油脂、一冢冢白骨里头滋生、藏匿着。"},{"start":133.6,"end":151.762,"text":"在他经手的那些货物当中，挨着一只旧砖砌的炭炉，坐着一个白发苍苍的无赖，年近七十；他用晾衣绳上挂着的一幅由杂七杂八的破烂拼成的腌臜帘子，把自己同外头的冷空气隔开；安享着退隐的清闲，抽着他的烟斗。"},{"start":151.762,"end":158.875,"text":"斯克鲁奇和那幽灵来到这人跟前，恰好有个女人提着一个沉甸甸的包袱溜进了铺子。"},{"start":158.875,"end":171.475,"text":"可她才刚进来，另一个女人也进来了，同样背着东西；紧跟在她后头的是个穿褪了色黑衣的男人，他一见这两人，惊愕之状不亚于她们彼此认出对方时那般。"},{"start":171.475,"end":178.337,"text":"在一阵茫然的惊讶过后——抽烟斗的老头儿也加入了她们——他们三个一齐放声大笑起来。"},{"start":178.337,"end":182.962,"text":"打杂女工头一个到，这还用说！\"头一个进来的女人嚷道。"},{"start":182.962,"end":188.412,"text":"洗衣妇第二个到，这还用说；殡仪馆那伙计第三个到，这也还用说。"}]},"en":{"text":"But nothing doubting that to whomsoever they applied they had some latent moral for his own improvement, he resolved to treasure up every word he heard, and everything he saw; and especially to observe the shadow of himself when it appeared.\nFor he had an expectation that the conduct of his future self would give him the clue he missed, and would render the solution of these riddles easy.\nHe looked about in that very place for his own image; but another man stood in his accustomed corner, and though the clock pointed to his usual time of day for being there, he saw no likeness of himself among the multitudes that poured in through the Porch.\nIt gave him little surprise, however; for he had been revolving in his mind a change of life, and thought and hoped he saw his new-born resolutions carried out in this.\nQuiet and dark, beside him stood the Phantom, with its outstretched hand.\nWhen he roused himself from his thoughtful quest, he fancied from the turn of the hand, and its situation in reference to himself, that the Unseen Eyes were looking at him keenly.\nIt made him shudder, and feel very cold.\nThey left the busy scene, and went into an obscure part of the town, where Scrooge had never penetrated before, although he recognised its situation, and its bad repute.\nThe ways were foul and narrow; the shops and houses wretched; the people half-naked, drunken, slipshod, ugly.\nAlleys and archways, like so many cesspools, disgorged their offences of smell, and dirt, and life, upon the straggling streets; and the whole quarter reeked with crime, with filth, and misery.\nFar in this den of infamous resort, there was a low-browed, beetling shop, below a pent-house roof, where iron, old rags, bottles, bones, and greasy offal, were bought.\nUpon the floor within, were piled up heaps of rusty keys, nails, chains, hinges, files, scales, weights, and refuse iron of all kinds.\nSecrets that few would like to scrutinise were bred and hidden in mountains of unseemly rags, masses of corrupted fat, and sepulchres of bones.\nSitting in among the wares he dealt in, by a charcoal-stove, made of old bricks, was a gray-haired rascal, nearly seventy years of age; who had screened himself from the cold air without, by a frousy curtaining of miscellaneous tatters, hung upon a line; and smoked his pipe in all the luxury of calm retirement.\nScrooge and the Phantom came into the presence of this man, just as a woman with a heavy bundle slunk into the shop.\nBut she had scarcely entered, when another woman, similarly laden, came in too; and she was closely followed by a man in faded black, who was no less startled by the sight of them, than they had been upon the recognition of each other.\nAfter a short period of blank astonishment, in which the old man with the pipe had joined them, they all three burst into a laugh.\n\"Let the charwoman alone to be the first!\" cried she who had entered first.\n\"Let the laundress alone to be the second; and let the undertaker's man alone to be the third.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_IV_小节05.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":13.15,"text":"But nothing doubting that to whomsoever they applied they had some latent moral for his own improvement, he resolved to treasure up every word he heard, and everything he saw; and especially to observe the shadow of himself when it appeared."},{"start":13.1,"end":21.037,"text":"For he had an expectation that the conduct of his future self would give him the clue he missed, and would render the solution of these riddles easy."},{"start":21.037,"end":34.462,"text":"He looked about in that very place for his own image; but another man stood in his accustomed corner, and though the clock pointed to his usual time of day for being there, he saw no likeness of himself among the multitudes that poured in through the Porch."},{"start":34.462,"end":44.15,"text":"It gave him little surprise, however; for he had been revolving in his mind a change of life, and thought and hoped he saw his new-born resolutions carried out in this."},{"start":44.15,"end":49.25,"text":"Quiet and dark, beside him stood the Phantom, with its outstretched hand."},{"start":49.25,"end":59.412,"text":"When he roused himself from his thoughtful quest, he fancied from the turn of the hand, and its situation in reference to himself, that the Unseen Eyes were looking at him keenly."},{"start":59.412,"end":62.787,"text":"It made him shudder, and feel very cold."},{"start":62.787,"end":73.05,"text":"They left the busy scene, and went into an obscure part of the town, where Scrooge had never penetrated before, although he recognised its situation, and its bad repute."},{"start":73.05,"end":81.075,"text":"The ways were foul and narrow; the shops and houses wretched; the people half-naked, drunken, slipshod, ugly."},{"start":81.075,"end":93.612,"text":"Alleys and archways, like so many cesspools, disgorged their offences of smell, and dirt, and life, upon the straggling streets; and the whole quarter reeked with crime, with filth, and misery."},{"start":93.612,"end":105.737,"text":"Far in this den of infamous resort, there was a low-browed, beetling shop, below a pent-house roof, where iron, old rags, bottles, bones, and greasy offal, were bought."},{"start":105.737,"end":116.7,"text":"Upon the floor within, were piled up heaps of rusty keys, nails, chains, hinges, files, scales, weights, and refuse iron of all kinds."},{"start":116.7,"end":125.625,"text":"Secrets that few would like to scrutinise were bred and hidden in mountains of unseemly rags, masses of corrupted fat, and sepulchres of bones."},{"start":125.625,"end":144.2,"text":"Sitting in among the wares he dealt in, by a charcoal-stove, made of old bricks, was a gray-haired rascal, nearly seventy years of age; who had screened himself from the cold air without, by a frousy curtaining of miscellaneous tatters, hung upon a line; and smoked his pipe in all the luxury of calm retirement."},{"start":144.2,"end":151.05,"text":"Scrooge and the Phantom came into the presence of this man, just as a woman with a heavy bundle slunk into the shop."},{"start":151.05,"end":164.6,"text":"But she had scarcely entered, when another woman, similarly laden, came in too; and she was closely followed by a man in faded black, who was no less startled by the sight of them, than they had been upon the recognition of each other."},{"start":164.6,"end":172.65,"text":"After a short period of blank astonishment, in which the old man with the pipe had joined them, they all three burst into a laugh."},{"start":172.65,"end":177.562,"text":"Let the charwoman alone to be the first!\" cried she who had entered first."},{"start":177.562,"end":183.262,"text":"Let the laundress alone to be the second; and let the undertaker's man alone to be the third."}]}},{"id":"IV_06","number":6,"zh":{"text":"瞧瞧，老乔，可巧来了桩好买卖！\n咱们三个偏偏不约而同地碰到了这儿！\"\n\"你们再没有比这儿更好的碰头地方了，\"老乔说着，把烟斗从嘴里取了下来。\n\"上客厅来吧。\n你早就在这儿来去随便了，你知道的；那两位也不是外人。\n等我把铺子的门关上。\n啊！\n它响得多刺耳！\n我看这地方再没有比它那合页更生锈的烂铁了；我也敢说，这儿再没有比我这把更老的骨头了。\n哈，哈！\n咱们都跟自家这行当般配，咱们正是天造地设的一伙。\n上客厅来吧。\n上客厅来吧。\"\n那客厅就是破布帘子后头的那块地方。\n老头儿用一根旧楼梯杆把炉火拨拢到一处，又用烟斗杆拨了拨他那盏冒烟的灯（因为这会儿是夜里），把烟斗重新衔回嘴里。\n他这么忙活的工夫，那个已经开过口的女人把包袱往地上一扔，大模大样地在一只凳子上坐下；两肘搁在膝头交叉着，带着一脸蛮横的挑衅望着另外两人。\n\"那又有什么打紧！\n有什么打紧，迪尔伯太太？\"那女人说。\n\"人人都有权顾着自个儿。他向来就是这么干的！\"","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_IV_小节06.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":3.425,"text":"瞧瞧，老乔，可巧来了桩好买卖！"},{"start":3.375,"end":6.487,"text":"咱们三个偏偏不约而同地碰到了这儿！"},{"start":6.487,"end":12.425,"text":"你们再没有比这儿更好的碰头地方了，\"老乔说着，把烟斗从嘴里取了下来。"},{"start":12.425,"end":14.012,"text":"上客厅来吧。"},{"start":14.012,"end":19.037,"text":"你早就在这儿来去随便了，你知道的；那两位也不是外人。"},{"start":19.037,"end":21.112,"text":"等我把铺子的门关上。"},{"start":21.112,"end":21.987,"text":"啊！"},{"start":21.987,"end":23.7,"text":"它响得多刺耳！"},{"start":23.7,"end":31.575,"text":"我看这地方再没有比它那合页更生锈的烂铁了；我也敢说，这儿再没有比我这把更老的骨头了。"},{"start":31.575,"end":32.85,"text":"哈，哈！"},{"start":32.85,"end":37.612,"text":"咱们都跟自家这行当般配，咱们正是天造地设的一伙。"},{"start":37.612,"end":39.2,"text":"上客厅来吧。"},{"start":39.2,"end":40.787,"text":"上客厅来吧。"},{"start":40.787,"end":44.087,"text":"那客厅就是破布帘子后头的那块地方。"},{"start":44.087,"end":54.012,"text":"老头儿用一根旧楼梯杆把炉火拨拢到一处，又用烟斗杆拨了拨他那盏冒烟的灯（因为这会儿是夜里），把烟斗重新衔回嘴里。"},{"start":54.012,"end":66.925,"text":"他这么忙活的工夫，那个已经开过口的女人把包袱往地上一扔，大模大样地在一只凳子上坐下；两肘搁在膝头交叉着，带着一脸蛮横的挑衅望着另外两人。"},{"start":66.925,"end":68.687,"text":"那又有什么打紧！"},{"start":68.687,"end":72.137,"text":"有什么打紧，迪尔伯太太？\"那女人说。"},{"start":72.137,"end":74.412,"text":"人人都有权顾着自个儿。"},{"start":74.412,"end":76.475,"text":"他向来就是这么干的！"}]},"en":{"text":"Look here, old Joe, here's a chance!\nIf we haven't all three met here without meaning it!\"\n\"You couldn't have met in a better place,\" said old Joe, removing his pipe from his mouth.\n\"Come into the parlour.\nYou were made free of it long ago, you know; and the other two ain't strangers.\nStop till I shut the door of the shop.\nAh!\nHow it skreeks!\nThere an't such a rusty bit of metal in the place as its own hinges, I believe; and I'm sure there's no such old bones here, as mine.\nHa, ha!\nWe're all suitable to our calling, we're well matched.\nCome into the parlour.\nCome into the parlour.\"\nThe parlour was the space behind the screen of rags.\nThe old man raked the fire together with an old stair-rod, and having trimmed his smoky lamp (for it was night), with the stem of his pipe, put it in his mouth again.\nWhile he did this, the woman who had already spoken threw her bundle on the floor and sat down in a flaunting manner on a stool; crossing her elbows on her knees, and looking with a bold defiance at the other two.\n\"What odds then!\nWhat odds, Mrs. Dilber?\" said the woman.\n\"Every person has a right to take care of themselves. _He_ always did!\"","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_IV_小节06.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":3.55,"text":"Look here, old Joe, here's a chance!"},{"start":3.5,"end":6.987,"text":"If we haven't all three met here without meaning it!"},{"start":6.987,"end":12.662,"text":"You couldn't have met in a better place,\" said old Joe, removing his pipe from his mouth."},{"start":12.662,"end":14.625,"text":"Come into the parlour."},{"start":14.625,"end":19.812,"text":"You were made free of it long ago, you know; and the other two ain't strangers."},{"start":19.812,"end":22.762,"text":"Stop till I shut the door of the shop."},{"start":22.762,"end":24.012,"text":"Ah!"},{"start":24.012,"end":25.9,"text":"How it skreeks!"},{"start":25.9,"end":34.15,"text":"There an't such a rusty bit of metal in the place as its own hinges, I believe; and I'm sure there's no such old bones here, as mine."},{"start":34.15,"end":36,"text":"Ha, ha!"},{"start":36,"end":39.637,"text":"We're all suitable to our calling, we're well matched."},{"start":39.637,"end":41.6,"text":"Come into the parlour."},{"start":41.6,"end":43.562,"text":"Come into the parlour."},{"start":43.562,"end":47.237,"text":"The parlour was the space behind the screen of rags."},{"start":47.237,"end":57.1,"text":"The old man raked the fire together with an old stair-rod, and having trimmed his smoky lamp (for it was night), with the stem of his pipe, put it in his mouth again."},{"start":57.1,"end":69.112,"text":"While he did this, the woman who had already spoken threw her bundle on the floor and sat down in a flaunting manner on a stool; crossing her elbows on her knees, and looking with a bold defiance at the other two."},{"start":69.112,"end":71.012,"text":"What odds then!"},{"start":71.012,"end":74.612,"text":"What odds, Mrs. Dilber?\" said the woman."},{"start":74.612,"end":78.137,"text":"Every person has a right to take care of themselves."},{"start":78.137,"end":81.262,"text":"_He_ always did!"}]}},{"id":"IV_07","number":7,"zh":{"text":"\"这话当真不假！\"那洗衣妇说。\n\"再没有比他更这样的人了。\"\n\"那么，就别站在那儿干瞪眼、一副怕事的样子了，婆娘；谁又会知道呢？\n我看咱们总不至于互相挑刺、揭对方的短吧？\"\n\"当然不会！\"迪尔伯太太和那男人一齐说道。\n\"咱们但愿不会。\"\n\"那就好！\"那女人嚷道。\n\"这就够了。\n丢了这么几样东西，谁会少块肉呢？\n我看死人是不会的。\"\n\"当然不会，\"迪尔伯太太笑着说。\n\"他要是死了还想攥着这些个东西不放，那个心狠的老抠门儿，\"那女人接着说，\"他活着的时候怎么就不放和气点呢？\n他要是放和气点，死神找上门来时，自会有人照看他，用不着孤零零一个人躺在那儿咽下最后一口气。\"\n\"这话再真没有了，\"迪尔伯太太说。\n\"这是他的报应。\"\n\"我倒巴望这报应再重些呢，\"那女人答道，\"要是我还能弄到别的什么东西，准会更重，这你尽可放心。\n把那个包袱打开，老乔，让我知道它值多少。\n明明白白地说。\n我不怕头一个来，也不怕让他们瞧见。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_IV_小节07.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":3.1,"text":"这话当真不假！\"那洗衣妇说。"},{"start":3.05,"end":5.275,"text":"再没有比他更这样的人了。"},{"start":5.275,"end":11.262,"text":"那么，就别站在那儿干瞪眼、一副怕事的样子了，婆娘；谁又会知道呢？"},{"start":11.262,"end":15.212,"text":"我看咱们总不至于互相挑刺、揭对方的短吧？"},{"start":15.212,"end":18.925,"text":"当然不会！\"迪尔伯太太和那男人一齐说道。"},{"start":18.925,"end":20.675,"text":"咱们但愿不会。"},{"start":20.675,"end":23.012,"text":"那就好！\"那女人嚷道。"},{"start":23.012,"end":24.325,"text":"这就够了。"},{"start":24.325,"end":27.487,"text":"丢了这么几样东西，谁会少块肉呢？"},{"start":27.487,"end":29.575,"text":"我看死人是不会的。"},{"start":29.575,"end":32.325,"text":"当然不会，\"迪尔伯太太笑着说。"},{"start":32.325,"end":41.112,"text":"他要是死了还想攥着这些个东西不放，那个心狠的老抠门儿，\"那女人接着说，\"他活着的时候怎么就不放和气点呢？"},{"start":41.112,"end":49.212,"text":"他要是放和气点，死神找上门来时，自会有人照看他，用不着孤零零一个人躺在那儿咽下最后一口气。"},{"start":49.212,"end":52.275,"text":"这话再真没有了，\"迪尔伯太太说。"},{"start":52.275,"end":53.912,"text":"这是他的报应。"},{"start":53.912,"end":61.825,"text":"我倒巴望这报应再重些呢，\"那女人答道，\"要是我还能弄到别的什么东西，准会更重，这你尽可放心。"},{"start":61.825,"end":66,"text":"把那个包袱打开，老乔，让我知道它值多少。"},{"start":66,"end":67.562,"text":"明明白白地说。"},{"start":67.562,"end":71.2,"text":"我不怕头一个来，也不怕让他们瞧见。"}]},"en":{"text":"\"That's true, indeed!\" said the laundress.\n\"No man more so.\"\n\"Why, then, don't stand staring as if you was afraid, woman; who's the wiser?\nWe're not going to pick holes in each other's coats, I suppose?\"\n\"No, indeed!\" said Mrs. Dilber and the man together.\n\"We should hope not.\"\n\"Very well, then!\" cried the woman.\n\"That's enough.\nWho's the worse for the loss of a few things like these?\nNot a dead man, I suppose.\"\n\"No, indeed,\" said Mrs. Dilber, laughing.\n\"If he wanted to keep 'em after he was dead, a wicked old screw,\" pursued the woman, \"why wasn't he natural in his lifetime?\nIf he had been, he'd have had somebody to look after him when he was struck with Death, instead of lying gasping out his last there, alone by himself.\"\n\"It's the truest word that ever was spoke,\" said Mrs. Dilber.\n\"It's a judgment on him.\"\n\"I wish it was a little heavier one,\" replied the woman; \"and it should have been, you may depend upon it, if I could have laid my hands on anything else.\nOpen that bundle, old Joe, and let me know the value of it.\nSpeak out plain.\nI'm not afraid to be the first, nor afraid for them to see it.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_IV_小节07.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":3.787,"text":"That's true, indeed!\" said the laundress."},{"start":3.737,"end":5.862,"text":"No man more so."},{"start":5.862,"end":11.587,"text":"Why, then, don't stand staring as if you was afraid, woman; who's the wiser?"},{"start":11.587,"end":15.625,"text":"We're not going to pick holes in each other's coats, I suppose?"},{"start":15.625,"end":20.05,"text":"No, indeed!\" said Mrs. Dilber and the man together."},{"start":20.05,"end":21.962,"text":"We should hope not."},{"start":21.962,"end":25.2,"text":"Very well, then!\" cried the woman."},{"start":25.2,"end":26.862,"text":"That's enough."},{"start":26.862,"end":30.325,"text":"Who's the worse for the loss of a few things like these?"},{"start":30.325,"end":33.225,"text":"Not a dead man, I suppose."},{"start":33.225,"end":37.375,"text":"No, indeed,\" said Mrs. Dilber, laughing."},{"start":37.375,"end":45.212,"text":"If he wanted to keep 'em after he was dead, a wicked old screw,\" pursued the woman, \"why wasn't he natural in his lifetime?"},{"start":45.212,"end":53.887,"text":"If he had been, he'd have had somebody to look after him when he was struck with Death, instead of lying gasping out his last there, alone by himself."},{"start":53.887,"end":58.162,"text":"It's the truest word that ever was spoke,\" said Mrs. Dilber."},{"start":58.162,"end":60.287,"text":"It's a judgment on him."},{"start":60.287,"end":69.125,"text":"I wish it was a little heavier one,\" replied the woman; \"and it should have been, you may depend upon it, if I could have laid my hands on anything else."},{"start":69.125,"end":73.462,"text":"Open that bundle, old Joe, and let me know the value of it."},{"start":73.462,"end":75.475,"text":"Speak out plain."},{"start":75.475,"end":79.65,"text":"I'm not afraid to be the first, nor afraid for them to see it."}]}},{"id":"IV_08","number":8,"zh":{"text":"我看咱们没碰头之前，心里头就都明白自己是在顺手牵羊了。\n这算不得罪过。\n打开包袱吧，乔。\"\n可她那两位朋友碍着面子不肯抢先；于是那穿褪色黑衣的男人头一个上前打破僵局，掏出了他那份赃物。\n那份赃物并不丰厚。\n一两枚印章、一只铅笔盒、一副袖扣，外加一枚不值什么钱的胸针，就这些。\n这些东西一一让老乔验过、估了价，他把自己愿意给每一样的数目用粉笔写在墙上，见再没有别的可掏了，便加起来凑成一个总数。\n\"这就是你那一份账，\"乔说，\"便是为不肯多给而要把我煮了，我也再不肯多掏一个六便士。\n下一个是谁？\"\n下一个是迪尔伯太太。\n床单和毛巾，几件穿戴的衣物，两把老式的银茶匙，一副方糖夹子，还有几双靴子。\n她那一份账也照样写在了墙上。\n\"我对太太们向来给得太多。\n这是我的一桩毛病，我就是这么把自个儿弄垮的，\"老乔说。\n\"这就是你那份账。\n你要是再问我多要一个便士、还非要争个公道，我准懊悔自己这么大方，再给你扣掉半个克朗。\"\n\"现在把我的包袱打开吧，乔，\"头一个女人说。\n乔跪了下去，好打开起来更便当些，解开了好多个结，拖出一大卷沉甸甸的深色料子。\n\"你管这叫什么？\"乔说。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_IV_小节08.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":5.287,"text":"我看咱们没碰头之前，心里头就都明白自己是在顺手牵羊了。"},{"start":5.237,"end":7.025,"text":"这算不得罪过。"},{"start":7.025,"end":9.012,"text":"打开包袱吧，乔。"},{"start":9.012,"end":18.25,"text":"可她那两位朋友碍着面子不肯抢先；于是那穿褪色黑衣的男人头一个上前打破僵局，掏出了他那份赃物。"},{"start":18.25,"end":20.3,"text":"那份赃物并不丰厚。"},{"start":20.3,"end":26.912,"text":"一两枚印章、一只铅笔盒、一副袖扣，外加一枚不值什么钱的胸针，就这些。"},{"start":26.912,"end":38.475,"text":"这些东西一一让老乔验过、估了价，他把自己愿意给每一样的数目用粉笔写在墙上，见再没有别的可掏了，便加起来凑成一个总数。"},{"start":38.475,"end":45.775,"text":"这就是你那一份账，\"乔说，\"便是为不肯多给而要把我煮了，我也再不肯多掏一个六便士。"},{"start":45.775,"end":47.237,"text":"下一个是谁？"},{"start":47.237,"end":49.425,"text":"下一个是迪尔伯太太。"},{"start":49.425,"end":56.687,"text":"床单和毛巾，几件穿戴的衣物，两把老式的银茶匙，一副方糖夹子，还有几双靴子。"},{"start":56.687,"end":59.725,"text":"她那一份账也照样写在了墙上。"},{"start":59.725,"end":62.262,"text":"我对太太们向来给得太多。"},{"start":62.262,"end":67.037,"text":"这是我的一桩毛病，我就是这么把自个儿弄垮的，\"老乔说。"},{"start":67.037,"end":68.837,"text":"这就是你那份账。"},{"start":68.837,"end":76.15,"text":"你要是再问我多要一个便士、还非要争个公道，我准懊悔自己这么大方，再给你扣掉半个克朗。"},{"start":76.15,"end":80.187,"text":"现在把我的包袱打开吧，乔，\"头一个女人说。"},{"start":80.187,"end":87.775,"text":"乔跪了下去，好打开起来更便当些，解开了好多个结，拖出一大卷沉甸甸的深色料子。"},{"start":87.775,"end":90.075,"text":"你管这叫什么？\"乔说。"}]},"en":{"text":"We knew pretty well that we were helping ourselves, before we met here, I believe.\nIt's no sin.\nOpen the bundle, Joe.\"\nBut the gallantry of her friends would not allow of this; and the man in faded black, mounting the breach first, produced _his plunder_.\nIt was not extensive.\nA seal or two, a pencil-case, a pair of sleeve-buttons, and a brooch of no great value, were all.\nThey were severally examined and appraised by old Joe, who chalked the sums he was disposed to give for each upon the wall, and added them up into a total when he found that there was nothing more to come.\n\"That's your account,\" said Joe, \"and I wouldn't give another sixpence, if I was to be boiled for not doing it.\nWho's next?\"\nMrs. Dilber was next.\nSheets and towels, a little wearing apparel, two old-fashioned silver tea-spoons, a pair of sugar-tongs, and a few boots.\nHer account was stated on the wall in the same manner.\n\"I always give too much to ladies.\nIt's a weakness of mine, and that's the way I ruin myself,\" said old Joe.\n\"That's your account.\nIf you asked me for another penny, and made it an open question, I'd repent of being so liberal, and knock off half-a-crown.\"\n\"And now undo _my_ bundle, Joe,\" said the first woman.\nJoe went down on his knees for the greater convenience of opening it, and having unfastened a great many knots, dragged out a large and heavy roll of some dark stuff.\n\"What do you call this?\" said Joe.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_IV_小节08.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":5.5,"text":"We knew pretty well that we were helping ourselves, before we met here, I believe."},{"start":5.45,"end":7.25,"text":"It's no sin."},{"start":7.25,"end":9.762,"text":"Open the bundle, Joe."},{"start":9.762,"end":18.95,"text":"But the gallantry of her friends would not allow of this; and the man in faded black, mounting the breach first, produced _his plunder_."},{"start":18.95,"end":21.137,"text":"It was not extensive."},{"start":21.137,"end":28.462,"text":"A seal or two, a pencil-case, a pair of sleeve-buttons, and a brooch of no great value, were all."},{"start":28.462,"end":39.275,"text":"They were severally examined and appraised by old Joe, who chalked the sums he was disposed to give for each upon the wall, and added them up into a total when he found that there was nothing more to come."},{"start":39.275,"end":46.087,"text":"That's your account,\" said Joe, \"and I wouldn't give another sixpence, if I was to be boiled for not doing it."},{"start":46.087,"end":47.787,"text":"Who's next?"},{"start":47.787,"end":50.3,"text":"Mrs. Dilber was next."},{"start":50.3,"end":58.45,"text":"Sheets and towels, a little wearing apparel, two old-fashioned silver tea-spoons, a pair of sugar-tongs, and a few boots."},{"start":58.45,"end":61.85,"text":"Her account was stated on the wall in the same manner."},{"start":61.85,"end":64.637,"text":"I always give too much to ladies."},{"start":64.637,"end":69.837,"text":"It's a weakness of mine, and that's the way I ruin myself,\" said old Joe."},{"start":69.837,"end":71.712,"text":"That's your account."},{"start":71.712,"end":79.25,"text":"If you asked me for another penny, and made it an open question, I'd repent of being so liberal, and knock off half-a-crown."},{"start":79.25,"end":84.625,"text":"And now undo _my_ bundle, Joe,\" said the first woman."},{"start":84.625,"end":94.175,"text":"Joe went down on his knees for the greater convenience of opening it, and having unfastened a great many knots, dragged out a large and heavy roll of some dark stuff."},{"start":94.175,"end":96.987,"text":"What do you call this?\" said Joe."}]}},{"id":"IV_09","number":9,"zh":{"text":"\"床帐！\"\n\"啊！\"那女人笑着应道，往交叉的胳膊上前倾了倾身子。\n\"床帐！\"\n\"你不是要说，他还躺在那儿，你就把帐子连铜环一齐摘下来了吧？\"乔说。\n\"我就是要这么说，\"那女人答道。\n\"有什么不可以的？\"\n\"你天生就是个发财的命，\"乔说，\"你也准会发起来。\"\n\"看在他那么个人的份上，只要伸手够得着、能弄进手心里的东西，我才不会缩手呢，我跟你说，乔，\"那女人冷冷地答道。\n\"喂，可别把那油滴到毯子上。\"\n\"他的毯子？\"乔问。\n\"你以为是谁的？\"那女人答道。\n\"少了它们，我看他也不至于会着凉吧。\"\n\"我但愿他不是害什么传染病死的？\n嗯？\"老乔停下手里的活儿，抬起头来问。\n\"这个你尽管放心，\"那女人答道。\n\"我可没那么稀罕跟他作伴，他要真是那么死的，我才不会为这么点东西在他跟前耗着呢。\n啊！\n你尽管把那件衬衫看个够、看到眼睛发酸；可你找不出一个破洞来，连一处磨薄的地方也找不着。\n那是他顶好的一件，料子还挺讲究。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_IV_小节09.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":1.25,"text":"床帐！"},{"start":1.2,"end":2.075,"text":"啊！"},{"start":2.075,"end":6.75,"text":"那女人笑着应道，往交叉的胳膊上前倾了倾身子。"},{"start":6.75,"end":7.9,"text":"床帐！"},{"start":7.9,"end":13.85,"text":"你不是要说，他还躺在那儿，你就把帐子连铜环一齐摘下来了吧？\"乔说。"},{"start":13.85,"end":16.65,"text":"我就是要这么说，\"那女人答道。"},{"start":16.65,"end":18.187,"text":"有什么不可以的？"},{"start":18.187,"end":22.4,"text":"你天生就是个发财的命，\"乔说，\"你也准会发起来。"},{"start":22.4,"end":32.137,"text":"看在他那么个人的份上，只要伸手够得着、能弄进手心里的东西，我才不会缩手呢，我跟你说，乔，\"那女人冷冷地答道。"},{"start":32.137,"end":35.125,"text":"喂，可别把那油滴到毯子上。"},{"start":35.125,"end":37.137,"text":"他的毯子？\"乔问。"},{"start":37.137,"end":39.787,"text":"你以为是谁的？\"那女人答道。"},{"start":39.787,"end":43.35,"text":"少了它们，我看他也不至于会着凉吧。"},{"start":43.35,"end":46.225,"text":"我但愿他不是害什么传染病死的？"},{"start":46.225,"end":47.125,"text":"嗯？"},{"start":47.125,"end":50.212,"text":"老乔停下手里的活儿，抬起头来问。"},{"start":50.212,"end":53,"text":"这个你尽管放心，\"那女人答道。"},{"start":53,"end":59.762,"text":"我可没那么稀罕跟他作伴，他要真是那么死的，我才不会为这么点东西在他跟前耗着呢。"},{"start":59.762,"end":60.637,"text":"啊！"},{"start":60.637,"end":68.437,"text":"你尽管把那件衬衫看个够、看到眼睛发酸；可你找不出一个破洞来，连一处磨薄的地方也找不着。"},{"start":68.437,"end":71.762,"text":"那是他顶好的一件，料子还挺讲究。"}]},"en":{"text":"\"Bed-curtains!\"\n\"Ah!\" returned the woman, laughing and leaning forward on her crossed arms.\n\"Bed-curtains!\"\n\"You don't mean to say you took 'em down, rings and all, with him lying there?\" said Joe.\n\"Yes I do,\" replied the woman.\n\"Why not?\"\n\"You were born to make your fortune,\" said Joe, \"and you'll certainly do it.\"\n\"I certainly shan't hold my hand, when I can get anything in it by reaching it out, for the sake of such a man as He was, I promise you, Joe,\" returned the woman coolly.\n\"Don't drop that oil upon the blankets, now.\"\n\"His blankets?\" asked Joe.\n\"Whose else's do you think?\" replied the woman.\n\"He isn't likely to take cold without 'em, I dare say.\"\n\"I hope he didn't die of anything catching?\nEh?\" said old Joe, stopping in his work, and looking up.\n\"Don't you be afraid of that,\" returned the woman.\n\"I an't so fond of his company that I'd loiter about him for such things, if he did.\nAh!\nYou may look through that shirt till your eyes ache; but you won't find a hole in it, nor a threadbare place.\nIt's the best he had, and a fine one too.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_IV_小节09.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":1.887,"text":"Bed-curtains!"},{"start":1.837,"end":6.925,"text":"Ah!\" returned the woman, laughing and leaning forward on her crossed arms."},{"start":6.925,"end":8.712,"text":"Bed-curtains!"},{"start":8.712,"end":14.675,"text":"You don't mean to say you took 'em down, rings and all, with him lying there?\" said Joe."},{"start":14.675,"end":17.7,"text":"Yes I do,\" replied the woman."},{"start":17.7,"end":19.2,"text":"Why not?"},{"start":19.2,"end":24.05,"text":"You were born to make your fortune,\" said Joe, \"and you'll certainly do it."},{"start":24.05,"end":34.337,"text":"I certainly shan't hold my hand, when I can get anything in it by reaching it out, for the sake of such a man as He was, I promise you, Joe,\" returned the woman coolly."},{"start":34.337,"end":37.825,"text":"Don't drop that oil upon the blankets, now."},{"start":37.825,"end":40.525,"text":"His blankets?\" asked Joe."},{"start":40.525,"end":43.812,"text":"Whose else's do you think?\" replied the woman."},{"start":43.812,"end":48,"text":"He isn't likely to take cold without 'em, I dare say."},{"start":48,"end":50.862,"text":"I hope he didn't die of anything catching?"},{"start":50.862,"end":55.425,"text":"Eh?\" said old Joe, stopping in his work, and looking up."},{"start":55.425,"end":58.737,"text":"Don't you be afraid of that,\" returned the woman."},{"start":58.737,"end":64.075,"text":"I an't so fond of his company that I'd loiter about him for such things, if he did."},{"start":64.075,"end":65.325,"text":"Ah!"},{"start":65.325,"end":71.937,"text":"You may look through that shirt till your eyes ache; but you won't find a hole in it, nor a threadbare place."},{"start":71.937,"end":75.475,"text":"It's the best he had, and a fine one too."}]}},{"id":"IV_10","number":10,"zh":{"text":"要不是我，他们准把它给糟蹋了。\"\n\"你管怎样才算糟蹋它？\"老乔问。\n\"还不是给他穿上去入殓呗，\"那女人笑着答道。\n\"有那么个傻瓜真给他穿上了，可我又把它扒了下来。\n要说本色布做这用场都嫌不够好，那它就什么也配不上了。\n拿它来裹身子也一样体面。\n他穿着那件，也不见得比穿这件更难看。\"\n斯克鲁奇满怀恐惧地听着这番对话。\n他们就着老头儿那盏灯吝啬的微光，围坐在那堆赃物旁边，他望着他们，心里头那股憎恶和厌恶，便是他们当真是一伙下流的恶魔、在那儿把尸首本身拿来做买卖，怕也不过如此了。\n\"哈，哈！\"老乔掏出一只装钱的法兰绒口袋、把他们各自所得一一数到地上时，还是那女人笑道。\n\"瞧见没，这就是收场！\n他活着的时候把人人都吓得离他远远的，好叫咱们在他死后捞着好处！\n哈，哈，哈！\"\n\"精灵！\"斯克鲁奇说，从头到脚直打哆嗦。\n\"我明白了，我明白了。\n这倒霉人的下场，兴许就是我自己的下场。\n我这一辈子，眼下就奔着那条路去呢。\n仁慈的上天哪，这是什么！\"\n他骇得往后一缩，因为情景变了，这会儿他几乎挨到了一张床：一张光秃秃、没挂帐子的床：床上一条破床单底下，盖着个什么东西，那东西虽不出声，却用一种可怕的言语昭示着自己。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_IV_小节10.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":3.212,"text":"要不是我，他们准把它给糟蹋了。"},{"start":3.162,"end":6.45,"text":"你管怎样才算糟蹋它？\"老乔问。"},{"start":6.45,"end":10.3,"text":"还不是给他穿上去入殓呗，\"那女人笑着答道。"},{"start":10.3,"end":14.6,"text":"有那么个傻瓜真给他穿上了，可我又把它扒了下来。"},{"start":14.6,"end":19.562,"text":"要说本色布做这用场都嫌不够好，那它就什么也配不上了。"},{"start":19.562,"end":22.237,"text":"拿它来裹身子也一样体面。"},{"start":22.237,"end":25.912,"text":"他穿着那件，也不见得比穿这件更难看。"},{"start":25.912,"end":29.312,"text":"斯克鲁奇满怀恐惧地听着这番对话。"},{"start":29.312,"end":43.512,"text":"他们就着老头儿那盏灯吝啬的微光，围坐在那堆赃物旁边，他望着他们，心里头那股憎恶和厌恶，便是他们当真是一伙下流的恶魔、在那儿把尸首本身拿来做买卖，怕也不过如此了。"},{"start":43.512,"end":51.612,"text":"哈，哈！\"老乔掏出一只装钱的法兰绒口袋、把他们各自所得一一数到地上时，还是那女人笑道。"},{"start":51.612,"end":53.987,"text":"瞧见没，这就是收场！"},{"start":53.987,"end":60.087,"text":"他活着的时候把人人都吓得离他远远的，好叫咱们在他死后捞着好处！"},{"start":60.087,"end":61.775,"text":"哈，哈，哈！"},{"start":61.775,"end":65.762,"text":"精灵！\"斯克鲁奇说，从头到脚直打哆嗦。"},{"start":65.762,"end":67.762,"text":"我明白了，我明白了。"},{"start":67.762,"end":71.337,"text":"这倒霉人的下场，兴许就是我自己的下场。"},{"start":71.337,"end":74.75,"text":"我这一辈子，眼下就奔着那条路去呢。"},{"start":74.75,"end":77.312,"text":"仁慈的上天哪，这是什么！"},{"start":77.312,"end":92.587,"text":"他骇得往后一缩，因为情景变了，这会儿他几乎挨到了一张床：一张光秃秃、没挂帐子的床：床上一条破床单底下，盖着个什么东西，那东西虽不出声，却用一种可怕的言语昭示着自己。"}]},"en":{"text":"They'd have wasted it, if it hadn't been for me.\"\n\"What do you call wasting of it?\" asked old Joe.\n\"Putting it on him to be buried in, to be sure,\" replied the woman with a laugh.\n\"Somebody was fool enough to do it, but I took it off again.\nIf calico an't good enough for such a purpose, it isn't good enough for anything.\nIt's quite as becoming to the body.\nHe can't look uglier than he did in that one.\"\nScrooge listened to this dialogue in horror.\nAs they sat grouped about their spoil, in the scanty light afforded by the old man's lamp, he viewed them with a detestation and disgust, which could hardly have been greater, though they had been obscene demons, marketing the corpse itself.\n\"Ha, ha!\" laughed the same woman, when old Joe, producing a flannel bag with money in it, told out their several gains upon the ground.\n\"This is the end of it, you see!\nHe frightened every one away from him when he was alive, to profit us when he was dead!\nHa, ha, ha!\"\n\"Spirit!\" said Scrooge, shuddering from head to foot.\n\"I see, I see.\nThe case of this unhappy man might be my own.\nMy life tends that way, now.\nMerciful Heaven, what is this!\"\nHe recoiled in terror, for the scene had changed, and now he almost touched a bed: a bare, uncurtained bed: on which, beneath a ragged sheet, there lay a something covered up, which, though it was dumb, announced itself in awful language.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_IV_小节10.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":3.45,"text":"They'd have wasted it, if it hadn't been for me."},{"start":3.4,"end":6.887,"text":"What do you call wasting of it?\" asked old Joe."},{"start":6.887,"end":12,"text":"Putting it on him to be buried in, to be sure,\" replied the woman with a laugh."},{"start":12,"end":15.937,"text":"Somebody was fool enough to do it, but I took it off again."},{"start":15.937,"end":21.025,"text":"If calico an't good enough for such a purpose, it isn't good enough for anything."},{"start":21.025,"end":23.65,"text":"It's quite as becoming to the body."},{"start":23.65,"end":26.725,"text":"He can't look uglier than he did in that one."},{"start":26.725,"end":30,"text":"Scrooge listened to this dialogue in horror."},{"start":30,"end":43.337,"text":"As they sat grouped about their spoil, in the scanty light afforded by the old man's lamp, he viewed them with a detestation and disgust, which could hardly have been greater, though they had been obscene demons, marketing the corpse itself."},{"start":43.337,"end":52.212,"text":"Ha, ha!\" laughed the same woman, when old Joe, producing a flannel bag with money in it, told out their several gains upon the ground."},{"start":52.212,"end":54.912,"text":"This is the end of it, you see!"},{"start":54.912,"end":60.362,"text":"He frightened every one away from him when he was alive, to profit us when he was dead!"},{"start":60.362,"end":62.837,"text":"Ha, ha, ha!"},{"start":62.837,"end":66.962,"text":"Spirit!\" said Scrooge, shuddering from head to foot."},{"start":66.962,"end":69.15,"text":"I see, I see."},{"start":69.15,"end":72.575,"text":"The case of this unhappy man might be my own."},{"start":72.575,"end":75.437,"text":"My life tends that way, now."},{"start":75.437,"end":78.287,"text":"Merciful Heaven, what is this!"},{"start":78.287,"end":93.3,"text":"He recoiled in terror, for the scene had changed, and now he almost touched a bed: a bare, uncurtained bed: on which, beneath a ragged sheet, there lay a something covered up, which, though it was dumb, announced itself in awful language."}]}},{"id":"IV_11","number":11,"zh":{"text":"这屋子很黑，黑得没法看清楚什么，尽管斯克鲁奇顺着一股隐秘的冲动朝四下扫了一眼，急于想知道这是间什么样的屋子。\n一道惨白的光，从外头的空气里升起，直直地落在那张床上；床上躺着这个人的尸首，被洗劫一空、被人遗弃，没人守着，没人哭，没人理。\n斯克鲁奇朝那幽灵瞥了一眼。\n它那只稳稳的手指着头部。\n那盖布盖得马马虎虎，只消极轻地把它一掀、斯克鲁奇这边一根手指头一动，就能露出那张脸来。\n他动过这念头，觉出这事做起来何等容易，也巴望着去做；可他要掀开那遮盖，正如要打发走他身旁那幽灵一样，全然无能为力。\n哦，冰冷、冰冷、僵硬、可怖的死神哪，把你的祭坛安在这儿吧，用你所能调遣的种种恐怖去装点它：因为这儿正是你的疆域！\n可对于一颗被人爱戴、敬重、尊崇的头颅，你却不能为你那可怕的目的拨动它一根头发，也不能使它一处眉目变得可憎。\n不是说那只手沉重、一松开就会垂落；不是说那心脏和脉搏已经停跳；而是说那只手曾是张开的、慷慨的、真诚的；那颗心曾是勇敢的、热忱的、温柔的；那脉搏曾是一个堂堂男子的脉搏。\n动手吧，黑影，动手吧！\n看他那一桩桩善行从伤口里迸涌而出，把不朽的生命播撒到这世上！\n没有谁在斯克鲁奇耳边说出这些话，可他望着那张床时却听见了它们。\n他想，倘若这个人这会儿能复活，他最先想到的会是什么呢？\n贪婪、刻薄的买卖、揪心的算计？\n说真的，它们可把他领到了一个\"富足\"的结局！\n他躺在这黑沉沉的空屋里，没有一个男人、一个女人、一个孩子能说一句他在这事那事上待我好、为着这一句好话的记忆我要好好待他。\n一只猫在抓挠着门，炉床石底下传来老鼠啃咬的声音。\n它们在这死亡之室里要的是什么、又为何这般焦躁不安，斯克鲁奇不敢去想。\n\"精灵！\"他说，\"这是个可怕的地方。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_IV_小节11.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":10.687,"text":"这屋子很黑，黑得没法看清楚什么，尽管斯克鲁奇顺着一股隐秘的冲动朝四下扫了一眼，急于想知道这是间什么样的屋子。"},{"start":10.637,"end":22.975,"text":"一道惨白的光，从外头的空气里升起，直直地落在那张床上；床上躺着这个人的尸首，被洗劫一空、被人遗弃，没人守着，没人哭，没人理。"},{"start":22.975,"end":26.012,"text":"斯克鲁奇朝那幽灵瞥了一眼。"},{"start":26.012,"end":28.625,"text":"它那只稳稳的手指着头部。"},{"start":28.625,"end":37,"text":"那盖布盖得马马虎虎，只消极轻地把它一掀、斯克鲁奇这边一根手指头一动，就能露出那张脸来。"},{"start":37,"end":48,"text":"他动过这念头，觉出这事做起来何等容易，也巴望着去做；可他要掀开那遮盖，正如要打发走他身旁那幽灵一样，全然无能为力。"},{"start":48,"end":58.362,"text":"哦，冰冷、冰冷、僵硬、可怖的死神哪，把你的祭坛安在这儿吧，用你所能调遣的种种恐怖去装点它：因为这儿正是你的疆域！"},{"start":58.362,"end":68.8,"text":"可对于一颗被人爱戴、敬重、尊崇的头颅，你却不能为你那可怕的目的拨动它一根头发，也不能使它一处眉目变得可憎。"},{"start":68.8,"end":86.412,"text":"不是说那只手沉重、一松开就会垂落；不是说那心脏和脉搏已经停跳；而是说那只手曾是张开的、慷慨的、真诚的；那颗心曾是勇敢的、热忱的、温柔的；那脉搏曾是一个堂堂男子的脉搏。"},{"start":86.412,"end":89.075,"text":"动手吧，黑影，动手吧！"},{"start":89.075,"end":95.337,"text":"看他那一桩桩善行从伤口里迸涌而出，把不朽的生命播撒到这世上！"},{"start":95.337,"end":101.312,"text":"没有谁在斯克鲁奇耳边说出这些话，可他望着那张床时却听见了它们。"},{"start":101.312,"end":106.362,"text":"他想，倘若这个人这会儿能复活，他最先想到的会是什么呢？"},{"start":106.362,"end":109.625,"text":"贪婪、刻薄的买卖、揪心的算计？"},{"start":109.625,"end":113.487,"text":"说真的，它们可把他领到了一个\"富足\"的结局！"},{"start":113.487,"end":125.012,"text":"他躺在这黑沉沉的空屋里，没有一个男人、一个女人、一个孩子能说一句他在这事那事上待我好、为着这一句好话的记忆我要好好待他。"},{"start":125.012,"end":129.712,"text":"一只猫在抓挠着门，炉床石底下传来老鼠啃咬的声音。"},{"start":129.712,"end":136.462,"text":"它们在这死亡之室里要的是什么、又为何这般焦躁不安，斯克鲁奇不敢去想。"},{"start":136.462,"end":139.75,"text":"精灵！\"他说，\"这是个可怕的地方。"}]},"en":{"text":"The room was very dark, too dark to be observed with any accuracy, though Scrooge glanced round it in obedience to a secret impulse, anxious to know what kind of room it was.\nA pale light, rising in the outer air, fell straight upon the bed; and on it, plundered and bereft, unwatched, unwept, uncared for, was the body of this man.\nScrooge glanced towards the Phantom.\nIts steady hand was pointed to the head.\nThe cover was so carelessly adjusted that the slightest raising of it, the motion of a finger upon Scrooge's part, would have disclosed the face.\nHe thought of it, felt how easy it would be to do, and longed to do it; but had no more power to withdraw the veil than to dismiss the spectre at his side.\nOh cold, cold, rigid, dreadful Death, set up thine altar here, and dress it with such terrors as thou hast at thy command: for this is thy dominion!\nBut of the loved, revered, and honoured head, thou canst not turn one hair to thy dread purposes, or make one feature odious.\nIt is not that the hand is heavy and will fall down when released; it is not that the heart and pulse are still; but that the hand was open, generous, and true; the heart brave, warm, and tender; and the pulse a man's.\nStrike, Shadow, strike!\nAnd see his good deeds springing from the wound, to sow the world with life immortal!\nNo voice pronounced these words in Scrooge's ears, and yet he heard them when he looked upon the bed.\nHe thought, if this man could be raised up now, what would be his foremost thoughts?\nAvarice, hard dealing, griping cares?\nThey have brought him to a rich end, truly!\nHe lay, in the dark empty house, with not a man, a woman, or a child, to say he was kind to me in this or that, and for the memory of one kind word I will be kind to him.\nA cat was tearing at the door, and there was a sound of gnawing rats beneath the hearth-stone.\nWhat _they_ wanted in the room of death, and why they were so restless and disturbed, Scrooge did not dare to think.\n\"Spirit!\" he said, \"this is a fearful place.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_IV_小节11.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":10.537,"text":"The room was very dark, too dark to be observed with any accuracy, though Scrooge glanced round it in obedience to a secret impulse, anxious to know what kind of room it was."},{"start":10.487,"end":21.775,"text":"A pale light, rising in the outer air, fell straight upon the bed; and on it, plundered and bereft, unwatched, unwept, uncared for, was the body of this man."},{"start":21.775,"end":24.7,"text":"Scrooge glanced towards the Phantom."},{"start":24.7,"end":27.612,"text":"Its steady hand was pointed to the head."},{"start":27.612,"end":36.175,"text":"The cover was so carelessly adjusted that the slightest raising of it, the motion of a finger upon Scrooge's part, would have disclosed the face."},{"start":36.175,"end":45.537,"text":"He thought of it, felt how easy it would be to do, and longed to do it; but had no more power to withdraw the veil than to dismiss the spectre at his side."},{"start":45.537,"end":55.512,"text":"Oh cold, cold, rigid, dreadful Death, set up thine altar here, and dress it with such terrors as thou hast at thy command: for this is thy dominion!"},{"start":55.512,"end":64.337,"text":"But of the loved, revered, and honoured head, thou canst not turn one hair to thy dread purposes, or make one feature odious."},{"start":64.337,"end":77.825,"text":"It is not that the hand is heavy and will fall down when released; it is not that the heart and pulse are still; but that the hand was open, generous, and true; the heart brave, warm, and tender; and the pulse a man's."},{"start":77.825,"end":80.825,"text":"Strike, Shadow, strike!"},{"start":80.825,"end":86.112,"text":"And see his good deeds springing from the wound, to sow the world with life immortal!"},{"start":86.112,"end":92.062,"text":"No voice pronounced these words in Scrooge's ears, and yet he heard them when he looked upon the bed."},{"start":92.062,"end":97.487,"text":"He thought, if this man could be raised up now, what would be his foremost thoughts?"},{"start":97.487,"end":101.087,"text":"Avarice, hard dealing, griping cares?"},{"start":101.087,"end":104.362,"text":"They have brought him to a rich end, truly!"},{"start":104.362,"end":115.562,"text":"He lay, in the dark empty house, with not a man, a woman, or a child, to say he was kind to me in this or that, and for the memory of one kind word I will be kind to him."},{"start":115.562,"end":121.062,"text":"A cat was tearing at the door, and there was a sound of gnawing rats beneath the hearth-stone."},{"start":121.062,"end":129.15,"text":"What _they_ wanted in the room of death, and why they were so restless and disturbed, Scrooge did not dare to think."},{"start":129.15,"end":132.962,"text":"Spirit!\" he said, \"this is a fearful place."}]}},{"id":"IV_12","number":12,"zh":{"text":"我离开这儿时，可不会把它给我的教训也一并撇下，请你相信我。\n咱们走吧！\"\n那鬼魂依旧用一根纹丝不动的手指指着头部。\n\"我懂你的意思，\"斯克鲁奇答道，\"我要是能，准会去做。\n可我没那个力气，精灵。\n我没那个力气。\"\n它仿佛又望了望他。\n\"倘若这城里有哪个人，因这个人的死而动了什么真情，\"斯克鲁奇万分痛苦地说，\"就把那个人指给我看吧，精灵，我求你了！\"\n那幽灵把它那黑袍在他面前像翅膀似的展开了一会儿；再收拢回去时，露出一间白昼里的屋子，屋里有一个母亲和她的孩子们。\n她正等着什么人，焦灼而急切地等着；因为她在屋里走来走去；一有声响就吃一惊；从窗口往外张望；瞅一眼钟；想做做针线，却做不下去；连孩子们玩闹的声音也几乎受不住。\n到末了，那盼了好久的敲门声响了。\n她急忙奔到门口，迎住了她丈夫；那是个一脸愁苦、神情沮丧的男人，虽说他还年轻。\n这会儿他脸上有一种不寻常的表情；一种庄重的喜悦，他为此感到羞愧，又竭力把它压下去。\n他坐下来吃那顿在炉火边给他温着的晚饭；当她有气无力地问他有什么消息时（这还是在好一阵沉默之后），他显得为难，不知如何作答。\n\"是好消息，\"她说，\"还是坏消息？\"——好帮他开口。\n\"坏的，\"他答道。\n\"咱们全完了？\"\n\"不。还有指望呢，卡萝琳。\"\n\"要是他肯心软，\"她惊讶地说，\"那是有指望！","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_IV_小节12.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":5.437,"text":"我离开这儿时，可不会把它给我的教训也一并撇下，请你相信我。"},{"start":5.387,"end":6.675,"text":"咱们走吧！"},{"start":6.675,"end":10.95,"text":"那鬼魂依旧用一根纹丝不动的手指指着头部。"},{"start":10.95,"end":15.362,"text":"我懂你的意思，\"斯克鲁奇答道，\"我要是能，准会去做。"},{"start":15.362,"end":17.687,"text":"可我没那个力气，精灵。"},{"start":17.687,"end":19.212,"text":"我没那个力气。"},{"start":19.212,"end":21.275,"text":"它仿佛又望了望他。"},{"start":21.275,"end":31.512,"text":"倘若这城里有哪个人，因这个人的死而动了什么真情，\"斯克鲁奇万分痛苦地说，\"就把那个人指给我看吧，精灵，我求你了！"},{"start":31.512,"end":41.7,"text":"那幽灵把它那黑袍在他面前像翅膀似的展开了一会儿；再收拢回去时，露出一间白昼里的屋子，屋里有一个母亲和她的孩子们。"},{"start":41.7,"end":57.45,"text":"她正等着什么人，焦灼而急切地等着；因为她在屋里走来走去；一有声响就吃一惊；从窗口往外张望；瞅一眼钟；想做做针线，却做不下去；连孩子们玩闹的声音也几乎受不住。"},{"start":57.45,"end":60.975,"text":"到末了，那盼了好久的敲门声响了。"},{"start":60.975,"end":68.625,"text":"她急忙奔到门口，迎住了她丈夫；那是个一脸愁苦、神情沮丧的男人，虽说他还年轻。"},{"start":68.625,"end":76.425,"text":"这会儿他脸上有一种不寻常的表情；一种庄重的喜悦，他为此感到羞愧，又竭力把它压下去。"},{"start":76.425,"end":87.5,"text":"他坐下来吃那顿在炉火边给他温着的晚饭；当她有气无力地问他有什么消息时（这还是在好一阵沉默之后），他显得为难，不知如何作答。"},{"start":87.5,"end":90.625,"text":"是好消息，\"她说，\"还是坏消息？"},{"start":90.625,"end":92.2,"text":"好帮他开口。"},{"start":92.2,"end":94.025,"text":"坏的，\"他答道。"},{"start":94.025,"end":95.375,"text":"咱们全完了？"},{"start":95.375,"end":96.212,"text":"不。"},{"start":96.212,"end":98.512,"text":"还有指望呢，卡萝琳。"},{"start":98.512,"end":102.525,"text":"要是他肯心软，\"她惊讶地说，\"那是有指望！"}]},"en":{"text":"In leaving it, I shall not leave its lesson, trust me.\nLet us go!\"\nStill the Ghost pointed with an unmoved finger to the head.\n\"I understand you,\" Scrooge returned, \"and I would do it, if I could.\nBut I have not the power, Spirit.\nI have not the power.\"\nAgain it seemed to look upon him.\n\"If there is any person in the town, who feels emotion caused by this man's death,\" said Scrooge quite agonized, \"show that person to me, Spirit, I beseech you!\"\nThe phantom spread its dark robe before him for a moment, like a wing; and withdrawing it, revealed a room by daylight, where a mother and her children were.\nShe was expecting some one, and with anxious eagerness; for she walked up and down the room; started at every sound; looked out from the window; glanced at the clock; tried, but in vain, to work with her needle; and could hardly bear the voices of the children in their play.\nAt length the long-expected knock was heard.\nShe hurried to the door, and met her husband; a man whose face was care-worn and depressed, though he was young.\nThere was a remarkable expression in it now; a kind of serious delight of which he felt ashamed, and which he struggled to repress.\nHe sat down to the dinner that had been hoarding for him by the fire; and when she asked him faintly what news (which was not until after a long silence), he appeared embarrassed how to answer.\n\"Is it good,\" she said, \"or bad?\"--to help him.\n\"Bad,\" he answered.\n\"We are quite ruined?\"\n\"No. There is hope yet, Caroline.\"\n\"If _he_ relents,\" she said, amazed, \"there is!","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_IV_小节12.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":4.15,"text":"In leaving it, I shall not leave its lesson, trust me."},{"start":4.1,"end":5.762,"text":"Let us go!"},{"start":5.762,"end":9.625,"text":"Still the Ghost pointed with an unmoved finger to the head."},{"start":9.625,"end":14.55,"text":"I understand you,\" Scrooge returned, \"and I would do it, if I could."},{"start":14.55,"end":17.475,"text":"But I have not the power, Spirit."},{"start":17.475,"end":19.587,"text":"I have not the power."},{"start":19.587,"end":22.15,"text":"Again it seemed to look upon him."},{"start":22.15,"end":32.525,"text":"If there is any person in the town, who feels emotion caused by this man's death,\" said Scrooge quite agonized, \"show that person to me, Spirit, I beseech you!"},{"start":32.525,"end":42,"text":"The phantom spread its dark robe before him for a moment, like a wing; and withdrawing it, revealed a room by daylight, where a mother and her children were."},{"start":42,"end":57.725,"text":"She was expecting some one, and with anxious eagerness; for she walked up and down the room; started at every sound; looked out from the window; glanced at the clock; tried, but in vain, to work with her needle; and could hardly bear the voices of the children in their play."},{"start":57.725,"end":60.875,"text":"At length the long-expected knock was heard."},{"start":60.875,"end":67.987,"text":"She hurried to the door, and met her husband; a man whose face was care-worn and depressed, though he was young."},{"start":67.987,"end":75.75,"text":"There was a remarkable expression in it now; a kind of serious delight of which he felt ashamed, and which he struggled to repress."},{"start":75.75,"end":86.475,"text":"He sat down to the dinner that had been hoarding for him by the fire; and when she asked him faintly what news (which was not until after a long silence), he appeared embarrassed how to answer."},{"start":86.475,"end":89.65,"text":"Is it good,\" she said, \"or bad?"},{"start":89.65,"end":91.212,"text":"to help him."},{"start":91.212,"end":93.475,"text":"Bad,\" he answered."},{"start":93.475,"end":95.462,"text":"We are quite ruined?"},{"start":95.462,"end":96.837,"text":"No."},{"start":96.837,"end":99.5,"text":"There is hope yet, Caroline."},{"start":99.5,"end":104.75,"text":"If _he_ relents,\" she said, amazed, \"there is!"}]}},{"id":"IV_13","number":13,"zh":{"text":"只要出了这样的奇迹，就没有什么是没指望的。\"\n\"他再不会心软了，\"她丈夫说。\n\"他死了。\"\n若说她的脸不说谎，她便是个温和而耐心的人；可她心底里听了这话却满怀感激，她也这么说了，双手交握着。\n她紧接着便祈求宽恕，又觉着难过；可头一桩才是她心底真正的感情。\n\"昨儿晚上我跟你说过的那个半醉的女人——我去求见他、想宽限一个礼拜时她对我说的话；我原当那不过是搪塞我的托词；如今看来竟全是真的。\n那时他不单是病得很重，而且已经要死了。\"\n\"咱们这笔债会转到谁手里去呢？\"\n\"我不知道。\n不过到那时候之前，咱们的钱总能凑齐；便是凑不齐，要在他的继承人里头碰上这么个狠心的债主，那才真叫倒霉透顶呢。\n今晚咱们可以安安心心地睡了，卡萝琳！\"\n是的。\n任凭他们怎么往轻里说，他们的心到底是轻松了些。\n孩子们的脸安静下来，凑到一处听着这他们不大懂的事，也明亮了些；为着这个人的死，这家里反倒更欢喜了！\n那鬼魂所能指给他看的、由这桩死亡引起的唯一一种真情，竟是一种欢喜。\n\"让我看一看跟死亡相连的某种温情吧，\"斯克鲁奇说，\"不然，精灵，咱们方才离开的那间黑屋子，会永远萦绕在我心头。\"\n那鬼魂领着他穿过几条他脚步熟悉的街道；一路走着，斯克鲁奇东张西望地找他自己，却哪儿也瞧不见他的踪影。\n他们走进了可怜的鲍勃·克拉奇特家；就是他先前到过的那处住所；只见那做母亲的和孩子们围着炉火坐着。\n静悄悄的。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_IV_小节13.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":3.85,"text":"只要出了这样的奇迹，就没有什么是没指望的。"},{"start":3.8,"end":6.487,"text":"他再不会心软了，\"她丈夫说。"},{"start":6.487,"end":7.687,"text":"他死了。"},{"start":7.687,"end":17.175,"text":"若说她的脸不说谎，她便是个温和而耐心的人；可她心底里听了这话却满怀感激，她也这么说了，双手交握着。"},{"start":17.175,"end":23.8,"text":"她紧接着便祈求宽恕，又觉着难过；可头一桩才是她心底真正的感情。"},{"start":23.8,"end":36.162,"text":"昨儿晚上我跟你说过的那个半醉的女人——我去求见他、想宽限一个礼拜时她对我说的话；我原当那不过是搪塞我的托词；如今看来竟全是真的。"},{"start":36.162,"end":40.375,"text":"那时他不单是病得很重，而且已经要死了。"},{"start":40.375,"end":43.187,"text":"咱们这笔债会转到谁手里去呢？"},{"start":43.187,"end":44.487,"text":"我不知道。"},{"start":44.487,"end":54.862,"text":"不过到那时候之前，咱们的钱总能凑齐；便是凑不齐，要在他的继承人里头碰上这么个狠心的债主，那才真叫倒霉透顶呢。"},{"start":54.862,"end":58.237,"text":"今晚咱们可以安安心心地睡了，卡萝琳！"},{"start":58.237,"end":59.237,"text":"是的。"},{"start":59.237,"end":63.6,"text":"任凭他们怎么往轻里说，他们的心到底是轻松了些。"},{"start":63.6,"end":72.887,"text":"孩子们的脸安静下来，凑到一处听着这他们不大懂的事，也明亮了些；为着这个人的死，这家里反倒更欢喜了！"},{"start":72.887,"end":79.412,"text":"那鬼魂所能指给他看的、由这桩死亡引起的唯一一种真情，竟是一种欢喜。"},{"start":79.412,"end":89.75,"text":"让我看一看跟死亡相连的某种温情吧，\"斯克鲁奇说，\"不然，精灵，咱们方才离开的那间黑屋子，会永远萦绕在我心头。"},{"start":89.75,"end":99.687,"text":"那鬼魂领着他穿过几条他脚步熟悉的街道；一路走着，斯克鲁奇东张西望地找他自己，却哪儿也瞧不见他的踪影。"},{"start":99.687,"end":108.937,"text":"他们走进了可怜的鲍勃·克拉奇特家；就是他先前到过的那处住所；只见那做母亲的和孩子们围着炉火坐着。"},{"start":108.937,"end":110.375,"text":"静悄悄的。"}]},"en":{"text":"Nothing is past hope, if such a miracle has happened.\"\n\"He is past relenting,\" said her husband.\n\"He is dead.\"\nShe was a mild and patient creature if her face spoke truth; but she was thankful in her soul to hear it, and she said so, with clasped hands.\nShe prayed forgiveness the next moment, and was sorry; but the first was the emotion of her heart.\n\"What the half-drunken woman whom I told you of last night, said to me, when I tried to see him and obtain a week's delay; and what I thought was a mere excuse to avoid me; turns out to have been quite true.\nHe was not only very ill, but dying, then.\"\n\"To whom will our debt be transferred?\"\n\"I don't know.\nBut before that time we shall be ready with the money; and even though we were not, it would be bad fortune indeed to find so merciless a creditor in his successor.\nWe may sleep to-night with light hearts, Caroline!\"\nYes.\nSoften it as they would, their hearts were lighter.\nThe children's faces hushed, and clustered round to hear what they so little understood, were brighter; and it was a happier house for this man's death!\nThe only emotion that the Ghost could show him, caused by the event, was one of pleasure.\n\"Let me see some tenderness connected with a death,\" said Scrooge; \"or that dark chamber, Spirit, which we left just now, will be for ever present to me.\"\nThe Ghost conducted him through several streets familiar to his feet; and as they went along, Scrooge looked here and there to find himself, but nowhere was he to be seen.\nThey entered poor Bob Cratchit's house; the dwelling he had visited before; and found the mother and the children seated round the fire.\nQuiet.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_IV_小节13.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":4.187,"text":"Nothing is past hope, if such a miracle has happened."},{"start":4.137,"end":7.387,"text":"He is past relenting,\" said her husband."},{"start":7.387,"end":9.087,"text":"He is dead."},{"start":9.087,"end":18.05,"text":"She was a mild and patient creature if her face spoke truth; but she was thankful in her soul to hear it, and she said so, with clasped hands."},{"start":18.05,"end":24.125,"text":"She prayed forgiveness the next moment, and was sorry; but the first was the emotion of her heart."},{"start":24.125,"end":35.487,"text":"What the half-drunken woman whom I told you of last night, said to me, when I tried to see him and obtain a week's delay; and what I thought was a mere excuse to avoid me; turns out to have been quite true."},{"start":35.487,"end":39.437,"text":"He was not only very ill, but dying, then."},{"start":39.437,"end":42.025,"text":"To whom will our debt be transferred?"},{"start":42.025,"end":43.6,"text":"I don't know."},{"start":43.6,"end":52.75,"text":"But before that time we shall be ready with the money; and even though we were not, it would be bad fortune indeed to find so merciless a creditor in his successor."},{"start":52.75,"end":56.55,"text":"We may sleep to-night with light hearts, Caroline!"},{"start":56.55,"end":57.987,"text":"Yes."},{"start":57.987,"end":61.55,"text":"Soften it as they would, their hearts were lighter."},{"start":61.55,"end":70.2,"text":"The children's faces hushed, and clustered round to hear what they so little understood, were brighter; and it was a happier house for this man's death!"},{"start":70.2,"end":75.75,"text":"The only emotion that the Ghost could show him, caused by the event, was one of pleasure."},{"start":75.75,"end":85.512,"text":"Let me see some tenderness connected with a death,\" said Scrooge; \"or that dark chamber, Spirit, which we left just now, will be for ever present to me."},{"start":85.512,"end":95.125,"text":"The Ghost conducted him through several streets familiar to his feet; and as they went along, Scrooge looked here and there to find himself, but nowhere was he to be seen."},{"start":95.125,"end":103.1,"text":"They entered poor Bob Cratchit's house; the dwelling he had visited before; and found the mother and the children seated round the fire."},{"start":103.1,"end":104.55,"text":"Quiet."}]}},{"id":"IV_14","number":14,"zh":{"text":"静极了。\n那几个吵吵闹闹的小克拉奇特像石像一般安静地缩在一个角落里，坐着仰望彼得，彼得面前摊着一本书。\n那做母亲的和女儿们都在做着针线。\n可他们当真静得很哪！\n\"'他领过一个小孩子来，叫他站在他们当中。'\"\n斯克鲁奇在哪儿听过这几句话？\n他可不是在梦里听来的。\n准是他和那精灵跨进门槛时，那男孩把它们念了出来。\n他怎么不往下念了呢？\n那做母亲的把活计搁在桌上，抬手捂住了脸。\n\"这颜色刺得我眼睛疼，\"她说。\n颜色？\n唉，可怜的小蒂姆！\n\"这会儿又好些了，\"克拉奇特的妻子说。\n\"烛光底下做活，眼睛容易发花；说什么我也不愿你们爸爸回家时瞧见我眼睛发花。\n这会儿想必快到他回来的时辰了。\"\n\"倒像是过了点了，\"彼得合上书答道。\n\"不过我看这几个晚上，他走得比往常稍慢了些，妈。\"\n他们又都静了下来。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_IV_小节14.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":1.312,"text":"静极了。"},{"start":1.262,"end":10.225,"text":"那几个吵吵闹闹的小克拉奇特像石像一般安静地缩在一个角落里，坐着仰望彼得，彼得面前摊着一本书。"},{"start":10.225,"end":13.462,"text":"那做母亲的和女儿们都在做着针线。"},{"start":13.462,"end":15.662,"text":"可他们当真静得很哪！"},{"start":15.662,"end":19.375,"text":"他领过一个小孩子来，叫他站在他们当中。"},{"start":19.375,"end":22.1,"text":"斯克鲁奇在哪儿听过这几句话？"},{"start":22.1,"end":24.462,"text":"他可不是在梦里听来的。"},{"start":24.462,"end":29.137,"text":"准是他和那精灵跨进门槛时，那男孩把它们念了出来。"},{"start":29.137,"end":31.2,"text":"他怎么不往下念了呢？"},{"start":31.2,"end":35.4,"text":"那做母亲的把活计搁在桌上，抬手捂住了脸。"},{"start":35.4,"end":38.237,"text":"这颜色刺得我眼睛疼，\"她说。"},{"start":38.237,"end":39.3,"text":"颜色？"},{"start":39.3,"end":41.35,"text":"唉，可怜的小蒂姆！"},{"start":41.35,"end":44.562,"text":"这会儿又好些了，\"克拉奇特的妻子说。"},{"start":44.562,"end":51.8,"text":"烛光底下做活，眼睛容易发花；说什么我也不愿你们爸爸回家时瞧见我眼睛发花。"},{"start":51.8,"end":54.8,"text":"这会儿想必快到他回来的时辰了。"},{"start":54.8,"end":58.037,"text":"倒像是过了点了，\"彼得合上书答道。"},{"start":58.037,"end":62.887,"text":"不过我看这几个晚上，他走得比往常稍慢了些，妈。"},{"start":62.887,"end":64.862,"text":"他们又都静了下来。"}]},"en":{"text":"Very quiet.\nThe noisy little Cratchits were as still as statues in one corner, and sat looking up at Peter, who had a book before him.\nThe mother and her daughters were engaged in sewing.\nBut surely they were very quiet!\n\"'And He took a child, and set him in the midst of them.'\"\nWhere had Scrooge heard these words?\nHe had not dreamed them.\nThe boy must have read them out, as he and the Spirit crossed the threshold.\nWhy did he not go on?\nThe mother laid her work upon the table, and put her hand up to her face.\n\"The colour hurts my eyes,\" she said.\nThe colour?\nAh, poor Tiny Tim!\n\"They're better now again,\" said Cratchit's wife.\n\"It makes them weak by candle-light; and I wouldn't show weak eyes to your father when he comes home, for the world.\nIt must be near his time.\"\n\"Past it rather,\" Peter answered, shutting up his book.\n\"But I think he's walked a little slower than he used, these few last evenings, mother.\"\nThey were very quiet again.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_IV_小节14.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":1.887,"text":"Very quiet."},{"start":1.837,"end":9.2,"text":"The noisy little Cratchits were as still as statues in one corner, and sat looking up at Peter, who had a book before him."},{"start":9.2,"end":12.65,"text":"The mother and her daughters were engaged in sewing."},{"start":12.65,"end":15.387,"text":"But surely they were very quiet!"},{"start":15.387,"end":18.937,"text":"And He took a child, and set him in the midst of them."},{"start":18.937,"end":21.6,"text":"Where had Scrooge heard these words?"},{"start":21.6,"end":23.762,"text":"He had not dreamed them."},{"start":23.762,"end":28.612,"text":"The boy must have read them out, as he and the Spirit crossed the threshold."},{"start":28.612,"end":30.712,"text":"Why did he not go on?"},{"start":30.712,"end":35.387,"text":"The mother laid her work upon the table, and put her hand up to her face."},{"start":35.387,"end":38.525,"text":"The colour hurts my eyes,\" she said."},{"start":38.525,"end":40,"text":"The colour?"},{"start":40,"end":42.525,"text":"Ah, poor Tiny Tim!"},{"start":42.525,"end":46.037,"text":"They're better now again,\" said Cratchit's wife."},{"start":46.037,"end":52.925,"text":"It makes them weak by candle-light; and I wouldn't show weak eyes to your father when he comes home, for the world."},{"start":52.925,"end":55.3,"text":"It must be near his time."},{"start":55.3,"end":59.337,"text":"Past it rather,\" Peter answered, shutting up his book."},{"start":59.337,"end":64.85,"text":"But I think he's walked a little slower than he used, these few last evenings, mother."},{"start":64.85,"end":67.212,"text":"They were very quiet again."}]}},{"id":"IV_15","number":15,"zh":{"text":"末了她开口了，声音平稳而欢快，只哽了那么一回：\"我见过他驮着——我见过他肩上驮着小蒂姆走，走得可快了。\"\n\"我也见过，\"彼得嚷道。\n\"常见呢。\"\n\"我也见过！\"另一个嚷道。\n人人都见过。\n\"可他驮起来很轻巧，\"她接着说，眼睛盯着活计，\"他爸爸又那么疼他，所以一点也不费事——一点也不费事。\n瞧，你们爸爸到门口啦！\"\n她急忙出去迎他；小个子鲍勃裹着围巾走了进来——这可怜人，他可少不了它。\n他的茶早在炉架上给他温好了，他们个个争着抢着要伺候他喝。\n随后那两个小克拉奇特爬上他的膝头，一个孩子一边，各自把小脸蛋贴到他脸上，仿佛在说，\"别往心里去，爸爸。\n别伤心！\"\n鲍勃跟他们在一处很是欢快，对全家人都和颜悦色地说着话。\n他瞧了瞧桌上的活计，夸赞克拉奇特太太和姑娘们手脚勤快、做得又快。\n不到礼拜天准能做完，他说。\n\"礼拜天！\n这么说你今儿去了，罗伯特？\"他妻子说。\n\"去了，我亲爱的，\"鲍勃答道。\n\"我真希望你也能去。\n你要是瞧见那地方多么青葱，准会觉着宽心。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_IV_小节15.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":9.425,"text":"末了她开口了，声音平稳而欢快，只哽了那么一回：\"我见过他驮着——我见过他肩上驮着小蒂姆走，走得可快了。"},{"start":9.375,"end":11.562,"text":"我也见过，\"彼得嚷道。"},{"start":11.562,"end":12.812,"text":"常见呢。"},{"start":12.812,"end":15.05,"text":"我也见过！\"另一个嚷道。"},{"start":15.05,"end":16.675,"text":"人人都见过。"},{"start":16.675,"end":25.85,"text":"可他驮起来很轻巧，\"她接着说，眼睛盯着活计，\"他爸爸又那么疼他，所以一点也不费事——一点也不费事。"},{"start":25.85,"end":28.262,"text":"瞧，你们爸爸到门口啦！"},{"start":28.262,"end":34.775,"text":"她急忙出去迎他；小个子鲍勃裹着围巾走了进来——这可怜人，他可少不了它。"},{"start":34.775,"end":40.475,"text":"他的茶早在炉架上给他温好了，他们个个争着抢着要伺候他喝。"},{"start":40.475,"end":49.712,"text":"随后那两个小克拉奇特爬上他的膝头，一个孩子一边，各自把小脸蛋贴到他脸上，仿佛在说，\"别往心里去，爸爸。"},{"start":49.712,"end":50.937,"text":"别伤心！"},{"start":50.937,"end":56.162,"text":"鲍勃跟他们在一处很是欢快，对全家人都和颜悦色地说着话。"},{"start":56.162,"end":62.762,"text":"他瞧了瞧桌上的活计，夸赞克拉奇特太太和姑娘们手脚勤快、做得又快。"},{"start":62.762,"end":65.525,"text":"不到礼拜天准能做完，他说。"},{"start":65.525,"end":66.775,"text":"礼拜天！"},{"start":66.775,"end":70.425,"text":"这么说你今儿去了，罗伯特？\"他妻子说。"},{"start":70.425,"end":73.012,"text":"去了，我亲爱的，\"鲍勃答道。"},{"start":73.012,"end":74.912,"text":"我真希望你也能去。"},{"start":74.912,"end":78.825,"text":"你要是瞧见那地方多么青葱，准会觉着宽心。"}]},"en":{"text":"At last she said, and in a steady cheerful voice, that only faultered once: \"I have known him walk with--I have known him walk with Tiny Tim upon his shoulder, very fast indeed.\"\n\"And so have I,\" cried Peter.\n\"Often.\"\n\"And so have I!\" exclaimed another.\nSo had all.\n\"But he was very light to carry,\" she resumed, intent upon her work, \"and his father loved him so, that it was no trouble--no trouble.\nAnd there is your father at the door!\"\nShe hurried out to meet him; and little Bob in his comforter--he had need of it, poor fellow--came in.\nHis tea was ready for him on the hob, and they all tried who should help him to it most.\nThen the two young Cratchits got upon his knees and laid, each child a little cheek, against his face, as if they said, \"Don't mind it father.\nDon't be grieved!\"\nBob was very cheerful with them, and spoke pleasantly to all the family.\nHe looked at the work upon the table, and praised the industry and speed of Mrs. Cratchit and the girls.\nThey would be done long before Sunday he said.\n\"Sunday!\nYou went to-day then, Robert?\" said his wife.\n\"Yes, my dear,\" returned Bob.\n\"I wish you could have gone.\nIt would have done you good to see how green a place it is.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_IV_小节15.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":10.925,"text":"At last she said, and in a steady cheerful voice, that only faultered once: \"I have known him walk with--I have known him walk with Tiny Tim upon his shoulder, very fast indeed."},{"start":10.875,"end":13.737,"text":"And so have I,\" cried Peter."},{"start":13.737,"end":15.175,"text":"Often."},{"start":15.175,"end":18.237,"text":"And so have I!\" exclaimed another."},{"start":18.237,"end":20.012,"text":"So had all."},{"start":20.012,"end":28.525,"text":"But he was very light to carry,\" she resumed, intent upon her work, \"and his father loved him so, that it was no trouble--no trouble."},{"start":28.525,"end":31.125,"text":"And there is your father at the door!"},{"start":31.125,"end":37.162,"text":"She hurried out to meet him; and little Bob in his comforter--he had need of it, poor fellow--came in."},{"start":37.162,"end":42.525,"text":"His tea was ready for him on the hob, and they all tried who should help him to it most."},{"start":42.525,"end":51.437,"text":"Then the two young Cratchits got upon his knees and laid, each child a little cheek, against his face, as if they said, \"Don't mind it father."},{"start":51.437,"end":53.25,"text":"Don't be grieved!"},{"start":53.25,"end":58.012,"text":"Bob was very cheerful with them, and spoke pleasantly to all the family."},{"start":58.012,"end":64.112,"text":"He looked at the work upon the table, and praised the industry and speed of Mrs. Cratchit and the girls."},{"start":64.112,"end":67.412,"text":"They would be done long before Sunday he said."},{"start":67.412,"end":69.012,"text":"Sunday!"},{"start":69.012,"end":72.725,"text":"You went to-day then, Robert?\" said his wife."},{"start":72.725,"end":76.012,"text":"Yes, my dear,\" returned Bob."},{"start":76.012,"end":78.125,"text":"I wish you could have gone."},{"start":78.125,"end":81.625,"text":"It would have done you good to see how green a place it is."}]}},{"id":"IV_16","number":16,"zh":{"text":"不过你往后常去就是了。\n我答应过他，每个礼拜天都去那儿走一走。\n我那小小的、小小的孩子呀！\"鲍勃哭喊道。\n\"我那小小的孩子！\"\n他一下子绷不住了。\n他实在忍不住。\n他若是忍得住，他和他的孩子兴许反倒不会像如今这般亲了。\n他离了屋，上楼走进上头那间屋子，那屋里点得喜气洋洋，挂满了圣诞的装点。\n紧挨着那孩子摆着一把椅子，还有迹象表明，近来有人到这儿来过。\n可怜的鲍勃在椅子上坐下，待他想了一会儿、定下神来，便亲了亲那张小脸。\n他跟已经发生的事和解了，又十分欢喜地下了楼。\n他们围拢到炉火边，攀谈起来；姑娘们和母亲仍旧做着活计。\n鲍勃跟他们说起斯克鲁奇先生那位外甥异乎寻常的好心，他统共才见过那人一面，可那人那天在街上碰见他，瞧出他神色有点——\"就那么有点儿沮丧，你们懂的，\"鲍勃说——便问他出了什么伤心事。\n\"于是呢，\"鲍勃说，\"因为他是你听过的最和气的绅士，我就跟他说了。\n'我打心眼里替你难过，克拉奇特先生，'他说，'也打心眼里替你那位贤惠的太太难过。'话说回来，他怎么会知道那个，我可不晓得。\"\n\"知道什么呀，我亲爱的？\"\n\"咳，知道你是个贤惠的妻子呀，\"鲍勃答道。\n\"这谁不知道呀！\"彼得说。\n\"说得好极了，我的孩子！\"鲍勃嚷道。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_IV_小节16.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":2.562,"text":"不过你往后常去就是了。"},{"start":2.512,"end":6.062,"text":"我答应过他，每个礼拜天都去那儿走一走。"},{"start":6.062,"end":9.937,"text":"我那小小的、小小的孩子呀！\"鲍勃哭喊道。"},{"start":9.937,"end":11.662,"text":"我那小小的孩子！"},{"start":11.662,"end":13.662,"text":"他一下子绷不住了。"},{"start":13.662,"end":15.437,"text":"他实在忍不住。"},{"start":15.437,"end":21.012,"text":"他若是忍得住，他和他的孩子兴许反倒不会像如今这般亲了。"},{"start":21.012,"end":27.775,"text":"他离了屋，上楼走进上头那间屋子，那屋里点得喜气洋洋，挂满了圣诞的装点。"},{"start":27.775,"end":33.237,"text":"紧挨着那孩子摆着一把椅子，还有迹象表明，近来有人到这儿来过。"},{"start":33.237,"end":39.512,"text":"可怜的鲍勃在椅子上坐下，待他想了一会儿、定下神来，便亲了亲那张小脸。"},{"start":39.512,"end":43.737,"text":"他跟已经发生的事和解了，又十分欢喜地下了楼。"},{"start":43.737,"end":49.287,"text":"他们围拢到炉火边，攀谈起来；姑娘们和母亲仍旧做着活计。"},{"start":49.287,"end":64.625,"text":"鲍勃跟他们说起斯克鲁奇先生那位外甥异乎寻常的好心，他统共才见过那人一面，可那人那天在街上碰见他，瞧出他神色有点——\"就那么有点儿沮丧，你们懂的，\"鲍勃说——便问他出了什么伤心事。"},{"start":64.625,"end":69.925,"text":"于是呢，\"鲍勃说，\"因为他是你听过的最和气的绅士，我就跟他说了。"},{"start":69.925,"end":80.212,"text":"我打心眼里替你难过，克拉奇特先生，'他说，'也打心眼里替你那位贤惠的太太难过。'话说回来，他怎么会知道那个，我可不晓得。"},{"start":80.212,"end":82.35,"text":"知道什么呀，我亲爱的？"},{"start":82.35,"end":86.012,"text":"咳，知道你是个贤惠的妻子呀，\"鲍勃答道。"},{"start":86.012,"end":88.375,"text":"这谁不知道呀！\"彼得说。"},{"start":88.375,"end":91.412,"text":"说得好极了，我的孩子！\"鲍勃嚷道。"}]},"en":{"text":"But you'll see it often.\nI promised him that I would walk there on a Sunday.\nMy little, little child!\" cried Bob.\n\"My little child!\"\nHe broke down all at once.\nHe couldn't help it.\nIf he could have helped it, he and his child would have been farther apart perhaps than they were.\nHe left the room, and went up stairs into the room above, which was lighted cheerfully, and hung with Christmas.\nThere was a chair set close beside the child, and there were signs of some one having been there, lately.\nPoor Bob sat down in it, and when he had thought a little and composed himself, he kissed the little face.\nHe was reconciled to what had happened, and went down again quite happy.\nThey drew about the fire, and talked; the girls and mother working still.\nBob told them of the extraordinary kindness of Mr. Scrooge's nephew, whom he had scarcely seen but once, and who, meeting him in the street that day, and seeing that he looked a little--\"just a little down you know\" said Bob, enquired what had happened to distress him.\n\"On which,\" said Bob, \"for he is the pleasantest-spoken gentleman you ever heard, I told him.\n'I am heartily sorry for it, Mr. Cratchit,' he said, 'and heartily sorry for your good wife.' By the bye, how he ever knew _that_, I don't know.\"\n\"Knew what, my dear?\"\n\"Why, that you were a good wife,\" replied Bob.\n\"Everybody knows that!\" said Peter.\n\"Very well observed, my boy!\" cried Bob.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_IV_小节16.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":2.187,"text":"But you'll see it often."},{"start":2.137,"end":5.5,"text":"I promised him that I would walk there on a Sunday."},{"start":5.5,"end":8.912,"text":"My little, little child!\" cried Bob."},{"start":8.912,"end":10.887,"text":"My little child!"},{"start":10.887,"end":13.475,"text":"He broke down all at once."},{"start":13.475,"end":15.312,"text":"He couldn't help it."},{"start":15.312,"end":20.887,"text":"If he could have helped it, he and his child would have been farther apart perhaps than they were."},{"start":20.887,"end":27.937,"text":"He left the room, and went up stairs into the room above, which was lighted cheerfully, and hung with Christmas."},{"start":27.937,"end":34.187,"text":"There was a chair set close beside the child, and there were signs of some one having been there, lately."},{"start":34.187,"end":40.825,"text":"Poor Bob sat down in it, and when he had thought a little and composed himself, he kissed the little face."},{"start":40.825,"end":45.55,"text":"He was reconciled to what had happened, and went down again quite happy."},{"start":45.55,"end":50.475,"text":"They drew about the fire, and talked; the girls and mother working still."},{"start":50.475,"end":65.5,"text":"Bob told them of the extraordinary kindness of Mr. Scrooge's nephew, whom he had scarcely seen but once, and who, meeting him in the street that day, and seeing that he looked a little--\"just a little down you know\" said Bob, enquired what had happened to distress him."},{"start":65.5,"end":71.737,"text":"On which,\" said Bob, \"for he is the pleasantest-spoken gentleman you ever heard, I told him."},{"start":71.737,"end":78.137,"text":"I am heartily sorry for it, Mr. Cratchit,' he said, 'and heartily sorry for your good wife."},{"start":78.137,"end":83.025,"text":"By the bye, how he ever knew _that_, I don't know."},{"start":83.025,"end":85.262,"text":"Knew what, my dear?"},{"start":85.262,"end":89.037,"text":"Why, that you were a good wife,\" replied Bob."},{"start":89.037,"end":91.962,"text":"Everybody knows that!\" said Peter."},{"start":91.962,"end":95.787,"text":"Very well observed, my boy!\" cried Bob."}]}},{"id":"IV_17","number":17,"zh":{"text":"\"但愿大家都知道。\n'打心眼里替你难过，'他说，'也替你那位贤惠的太太难过。\n我若能在哪方面帮上你，'他说着，把名片递给我，'我就住在这地方。\n请务必来找我。'这桩事呀，\"鲍勃嚷道，\"叫人这么高兴，倒不全为着他兴许能帮咱们什么，而是为着他那份好心肠。\n那情形真就像他从前认得咱们的小蒂姆，跟咱们一同感同身受似的。\"\n\"我敢说他准是个善心人！\"克拉奇特太太说。\n\"你要是见着他、跟他说上话，我亲爱的，\"鲍勃答道，\"准会更信这话。\n记住我的话，他要是给彼得谋个更好的差事，我一点也不会觉着奇怪。\"\n\"你倒是听听这话，彼得，\"克拉奇特太太说。\n\"到那时候，\"一个姑娘嚷道，\"彼得就要跟人相好、自立门户啦。\"\n\"去你的吧！\"彼得咧嘴笑着回敬道。\n\"这事说不准呢，\"鲍勃说，\"总有那么一天；不过那还早着呢，我亲爱的。\n可不管咱们将来怎样、几时彼此分手，我敢说咱们谁也不会忘了可怜的小蒂姆——会吗——也不会忘了咱们当中头一回有的这场分离吧？\"\n\"永远不会，爸爸！\"他们都嚷道。\n\"我还知道，\"鲍勃说，\"我知道，我亲爱的们，等咱们回想起他多么有耐心、多么温顺——虽说他不过是个小小的、小小的孩子——咱们便不会轻易彼此拌嘴，也不会在拌嘴时把可怜的小蒂姆给忘了。\"\n\"对，永远不会，爸爸！\"他们又都嚷道。\n\"我很快活，\"小个子鲍勃说，\"我很快活！\"\n克拉奇特太太亲了他，他的女儿们亲了他，那两个小克拉奇特亲了他，彼得跟他握了握手。\n小蒂姆的灵魂哟，你那孩童的本真是从上帝那儿来的！","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_IV_小节17.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":1.937,"text":"但愿大家都知道。"},{"start":1.887,"end":6.6,"text":"打心眼里替你难过，'他说，'也替你那位贤惠的太太难过。"},{"start":6.6,"end":12.375,"text":"我若能在哪方面帮上你，'他说着，把名片递给我，'我就住在这地方。"},{"start":12.375,"end":22.012,"text":"请务必来找我。'这桩事呀，\"鲍勃嚷道，\"叫人这么高兴，倒不全为着他兴许能帮咱们什么，而是为着他那份好心肠。"},{"start":22.012,"end":27.825,"text":"那情形真就像他从前认得咱们的小蒂姆，跟咱们一同感同身受似的。"},{"start":27.825,"end":31.575,"text":"我敢说他准是个善心人！\"克拉奇特太太说。"},{"start":31.575,"end":37.312,"text":"你要是见着他、跟他说上话，我亲爱的，\"鲍勃答道，\"准会更信这话。"},{"start":37.312,"end":43.012,"text":"记住我的话，他要是给彼得谋个更好的差事，我一点也不会觉着奇怪。"},{"start":43.012,"end":46.675,"text":"你倒是听听这话，彼得，\"克拉奇特太太说。"},{"start":46.675,"end":51.687,"text":"到那时候，\"一个姑娘嚷道，\"彼得就要跟人相好、自立门户啦。"},{"start":51.687,"end":54.762,"text":"去你的吧！\"彼得咧嘴笑着回敬道。"},{"start":54.762,"end":60.55,"text":"这事说不准呢，\"鲍勃说，\"总有那么一天；不过那还早着呢，我亲爱的。"},{"start":60.55,"end":70.812,"text":"可不管咱们将来怎样、几时彼此分手，我敢说咱们谁也不会忘了可怜的小蒂姆——会吗——也不会忘了咱们当中头一回有的这场分离吧？"},{"start":70.812,"end":73.712,"text":"永远不会，爸爸！\"他们都嚷道。"},{"start":73.712,"end":89.562,"text":"我还知道，\"鲍勃说，\"我知道，我亲爱的们，等咱们回想起他多么有耐心、多么温顺——虽说他不过是个小小的、小小的孩子——咱们便不会轻易彼此拌嘴，也不会在拌嘴时把可怜的小蒂姆给忘了。"},{"start":89.562,"end":93.012,"text":"对，永远不会，爸爸！\"他们又都嚷道。"},{"start":93.012,"end":96.587,"text":"我很快活，\"小个子鲍勃说，\"我很快活！"},{"start":96.587,"end":103.937,"text":"克拉奇特太太亲了他，他的女儿们亲了他，那两个小克拉奇特亲了他，彼得跟他握了握手。"},{"start":103.937,"end":108.25,"text":"小蒂姆的灵魂哟，你那孩童的本真是从上帝那儿来的！"}]},"en":{"text":"\"I hope they do.\n'Heartily sorry,' he said, 'for your good wife.\nIf I can be of service to you in any way,' he said, giving me his card, 'that's where I live.\nPray come to me.' Now, it wasn't,\" cried Bob, \"for the sake of anything he might be able to do for us, so much as for his kind way, that this was quite delightful.\nIt really seemed as if he had known our Tiny Tim, and felt with us.\"\n\"I'm sure he's a good soul!\" said Mrs. Cratchit.\n\"You would be surer of it, my dear,\" returned Bob, \"if you saw and spoke to him.\nI shouldn't be at all surprised, mark what I say, if he got Peter a better situation.\"\n\"Only hear that, Peter,\" said Mrs. Cratchit.\n\"And then,\" cried one of the girls, \"Peter will be keeping company with some one, and setting up for himself.\"\n\"Get along with you!\" retorted Peter, grinning.\n\"It's just as likely as not,\" said Bob, \"one of these days; though there's plenty of time for that, my dear.\nBut however and whenever we part from one another, I am sure we shall none of us forget poor Tiny Tim--shall we--or this first parting that there was among us?\"\n\"Never, father!\" cried they all.\n\"And I know,\" said Bob, \"I know, my dears, that when we recollect how patient and how mild he was; although he was a little, little child; we shall not quarrel easily among ourselves, and forget poor Tiny Tim in doing it.\"\n\"No never, father!\" they all cried again.\n\"I am very happy,\" said little Bob, \"I am very happy!\"\nMrs. Cratchit kissed him, his daughters kissed him, the two young Cratchits kissed him, and Peter and himself shook hands.\nSpirit of Tiny Tim, thy childish essence was from God!","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_IV_小节17.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":1.925,"text":"I hope they do."},{"start":1.875,"end":5.637,"text":"Heartily sorry,' he said, 'for your good wife."},{"start":5.637,"end":11.7,"text":"If I can be of service to you in any way,' he said, giving me his card, 'that's where I live."},{"start":11.7,"end":13.537,"text":"Pray come to me."},{"start":13.537,"end":22.925,"text":"Now, it wasn't,\" cried Bob, \"for the sake of anything he might be able to do for us, so much as for his kind way, that this was quite delightful."},{"start":22.925,"end":27.512,"text":"It really seemed as if he had known our Tiny Tim, and felt with us."},{"start":27.512,"end":31.337,"text":"I'm sure he's a good soul!\" said Mrs. Cratchit."},{"start":31.337,"end":37,"text":"You would be surer of it, my dear,\" returned Bob, \"if you saw and spoke to him."},{"start":37,"end":42.85,"text":"I shouldn't be at all surprised, mark what I say, if he got Peter a better situation."},{"start":42.85,"end":46.525,"text":"Only hear that, Peter,\" said Mrs. Cratchit."},{"start":46.525,"end":53.25,"text":"And then,\" cried one of the girls, \"Peter will be keeping company with some one, and setting up for himself."},{"start":53.25,"end":56.925,"text":"Get along with you!\" retorted Peter, grinning."},{"start":56.925,"end":64.012,"text":"It's just as likely as not,\" said Bob, \"one of these days; though there's plenty of time for that, my dear."},{"start":64.012,"end":72.425,"text":"But however and whenever we part from one another, I am sure we shall none of us forget poor Tiny Tim--shall we--or this first parting that there was among us?"},{"start":72.425,"end":75.537,"text":"Never, father!\" cried they all."},{"start":75.537,"end":89.612,"text":"And I know,\" said Bob, \"I know, my dears, that when we recollect how patient and how mild he was; although he was a little, little child; we shall not quarrel easily among ourselves, and forget poor Tiny Tim in doing it."},{"start":89.612,"end":93.237,"text":"No never, father!\" they all cried again."},{"start":93.237,"end":97.8,"text":"I am very happy,\" said little Bob, \"I am very happy!"},{"start":97.8,"end":105.525,"text":"Mrs. Cratchit kissed him, his daughters kissed him, the two young Cratchits kissed him, and Peter and himself shook hands."},{"start":105.525,"end":109.937,"text":"Spirit of Tiny Tim, thy childish essence was from God!"}]}},{"id":"IV_18","number":18,"zh":{"text":"\"幽灵，\"斯克鲁奇说，\"有什么东西在告诉我，咱们分别的时刻就要到了。\n我知道这一点，却不知道是怎么知道的。\n告诉我，咱们瞧见躺在那儿死去的那个人是谁？\"\n未来的圣诞之灵像先前一样带着他——不过他觉着是在另一个时辰：说实话，这后面这些幻象仿佛全无次序，只除了它们都是在未来——来到生意人出没的地方，却没把他自己指给他看。\n说真的，那精灵不为任何事停留，只一径往前走，仿佛奔着方才所求的那个结局去，直到斯克鲁奇央求它停一停。\n\"这条胡同，\"斯克鲁奇说，\"咱们这会儿匆匆穿过的这条，正是我那营生的所在，而且我在这儿干了好长一段时日了。\n我瞧见那房子了。\n让我看一看我将来会是个什么样吧。\"\n那精灵停住了；那只手却指着别处。\n\"房子在那边呀，\"斯克鲁奇嚷道。\n\"你干吗指着别处？\"\n那只无情的手指丝毫没变。\n斯克鲁奇赶忙奔到他账房的窗前，往里头看去。\n那仍旧是间账房，可不是他的了。\n家具不一样了，椅子上那身影也不是他自己。\n那幽灵还像先前一样指着。\n他又跟它走到一处，纳闷着自己究竟为何、又往何处去了，陪着它一直走到一道铁门跟前。\n进去之前他停下来四下打量了一番。\n一处教堂墓地。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_IV_小节18.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":5.562,"text":"幽灵，\"斯克鲁奇说，\"有什么东西在告诉我，咱们分别的时刻就要到了。"},{"start":5.512,"end":8.787,"text":"我知道这一点，却不知道是怎么知道的。"},{"start":8.787,"end":12.525,"text":"告诉我，咱们瞧见躺在那儿死去的那个人是谁？"},{"start":12.525,"end":27.937,"text":"未来的圣诞之灵像先前一样带着他——不过他觉着是在另一个时辰：说实话，这后面这些幻象仿佛全无次序，只除了它们都是在未来——来到生意人出没的地方，却没把他自己指给他看。"},{"start":27.937,"end":37.787,"text":"说真的，那精灵不为任何事停留，只一径往前走，仿佛奔着方才所求的那个结局去，直到斯克鲁奇央求它停一停。"},{"start":37.787,"end":46.687,"text":"这条胡同，\"斯克鲁奇说，\"咱们这会儿匆匆穿过的这条，正是我那营生的所在，而且我在这儿干了好长一段时日了。"},{"start":46.687,"end":48.512,"text":"我瞧见那房子了。"},{"start":48.512,"end":51.437,"text":"让我看一看我将来会是个什么样吧。"},{"start":51.437,"end":55.287,"text":"那精灵停住了；那只手却指着别处。"},{"start":55.287,"end":58.187,"text":"房子在那边呀，\"斯克鲁奇嚷道。"},{"start":58.187,"end":60.075,"text":"你干吗指着别处？"},{"start":60.075,"end":62.937,"text":"那只无情的手指丝毫没变。"},{"start":62.937,"end":67.3,"text":"斯克鲁奇赶忙奔到他账房的窗前，往里头看去。"},{"start":67.3,"end":70.475,"text":"那仍旧是间账房，可不是他的了。"},{"start":70.475,"end":74.562,"text":"家具不一样了，椅子上那身影也不是他自己。"},{"start":74.562,"end":77.5,"text":"那幽灵还像先前一样指着。"},{"start":77.5,"end":85.2,"text":"他又跟它走到一处，纳闷着自己究竟为何、又往何处去了，陪着它一直走到一道铁门跟前。"},{"start":85.2,"end":88.612,"text":"进去之前他停下来四下打量了一番。"},{"start":88.612,"end":90.4,"text":"一处教堂墓地。"}]},"en":{"text":"\"Spectre,\" said Scrooge, \"something informs me that our parting moment is at hand.\nI know it, but I know not how.\nTell me what man that was whom we saw lying dead?\"\nThe Ghost of Christmas Yet To Come conveyed him, as before--though at a different time, he thought: indeed, there seemed no order in these latter visions, save that they were in the Future--into the resorts of business men, but showed him not himself.\nIndeed, the Spirit did not stay for anything, but went straight on, as to the end just now desired, until besought by Scrooge to tarry for a moment.\n\"This court,\" said Scrooge, \"through which we hurry now, is where my place of occupation is, and has been for a length of time.\nI see the house.\nLet me behold what I shall be, in days to come.\"\nThe Spirit stopped; the hand was pointed elsewhere.\n\"The house is yonder,\" Scrooge exclaimed.\n\"Why do you point away?\"\nThe inexorable finger underwent no change.\nScrooge hastened to the window of his office, and looked in.\nIt was an office still, but not his.\nThe furniture was not the same, and the figure in the chair was not himself.\nThe Phantom pointed as before.\nHe joined it once again, and wondering why and whither he had gone, accompanied it until they reached an iron gate.\nHe paused to look round before entering.\nA churchyard.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_IV_小节18.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":5.612,"text":"Spectre,\" said Scrooge, \"something informs me that our parting moment is at hand."},{"start":5.562,"end":8.375,"text":"I know it, but I know not how."},{"start":8.375,"end":11.7,"text":"Tell me what man that was whom we saw lying dead?"},{"start":11.7,"end":25.362,"text":"The Ghost of Christmas Yet To Come conveyed him, as before--though at a different time, he thought: indeed, there seemed no order in these latter visions, save that they were in the Future--into the resorts of business men, but showed him not himself."},{"start":25.362,"end":34.937,"text":"Indeed, the Spirit did not stay for anything, but went straight on, as to the end just now desired, until besought by Scrooge to tarry for a moment."},{"start":34.937,"end":43.1,"text":"This court,\" said Scrooge, \"through which we hurry now, is where my place of occupation is, and has been for a length of time."},{"start":43.1,"end":45.15,"text":"I see the house."},{"start":45.15,"end":48.737,"text":"Let me behold what I shall be, in days to come."},{"start":48.737,"end":52.562,"text":"The Spirit stopped; the hand was pointed elsewhere."},{"start":52.562,"end":55.987,"text":"The house is yonder,\" Scrooge exclaimed."},{"start":55.987,"end":57.95,"text":"Why do you point away?"},{"start":57.95,"end":61.225,"text":"The inexorable finger underwent no change."},{"start":61.225,"end":65.262,"text":"Scrooge hastened to the window of his office, and looked in."},{"start":65.262,"end":68.45,"text":"It was an office still, but not his."},{"start":68.45,"end":73.3,"text":"The furniture was not the same, and the figure in the chair was not himself."},{"start":73.3,"end":75.962,"text":"The Phantom pointed as before."},{"start":75.962,"end":83,"text":"He joined it once again, and wondering why and whither he had gone, accompanied it until they reached an iron gate."},{"start":83,"end":86.012,"text":"He paused to look round before entering."},{"start":86.012,"end":87.775,"text":"A churchyard."}]}},{"id":"IV_19","number":19,"zh":{"text":"那么，他眼下不得不去打听其姓名的那个倒霉人，就长眠在这地底下了。\n真是个好去处。\n四面让房屋围着；蔓生着野草荒草，那是植物之死、而非植物之生的产物；让埋得太多的尸首壅塞着；让填得过饱的胃口养得肥肥的。\n真是个好去处！\n那精灵立在坟茔之间，往下指着其中一座。\n他哆嗦着朝它走去。\n那幽灵跟先前一模一样，可他害怕自己从它那庄严的身形里看出了新的含义。\n\"在我走近你所指的那块墓石之前，\"斯克鲁奇说，\"请回答我一个问题。\n这些是那些'将要'发生之事的影子呢，还是仅仅那些'可能'发生之事的影子？\"\n那鬼魂依旧朝它脚边的那座坟往下指着。\n\"人所走的路会预示某种结局，倘若一味走下去，便必定通向那结局，\"斯克鲁奇说。\n\"可这路若是被舍弃了，那结局也会随之改变。\n但愿你指给我看的也是如此！\"\n那精灵还是跟先前一样纹丝不动。\n斯克鲁奇哆嗦着一步步爬向它；顺着那手指，他在那座荒废坟墓的石碑上读出了自己的名字：埃比尼泽·斯克鲁奇。\n\"难道我就是躺在那床上的那个人？\"他跪倒在地，嚷道。\n那手指从坟墓指向他，又指了回去。\n\"不，精灵！\n哦不，不！\"","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_IV_小节19.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":5.875,"text":"那么，他眼下不得不去打听其姓名的那个倒霉人，就长眠在这地底下了。"},{"start":5.825,"end":7.525,"text":"真是个好去处。"},{"start":7.525,"end":19.912,"text":"四面让房屋围着；蔓生着野草荒草，那是植物之死、而非植物之生的产物；让埋得太多的尸首壅塞着；让填得过饱的胃口养得肥肥的。"},{"start":19.912,"end":21.6,"text":"真是个好去处！"},{"start":21.6,"end":25.525,"text":"那精灵立在坟茔之间，往下指着其中一座。"},{"start":25.525,"end":27.7,"text":"他哆嗦着朝它走去。"},{"start":27.7,"end":34.337,"text":"那幽灵跟先前一模一样，可他害怕自己从它那庄严的身形里看出了新的含义。"},{"start":34.337,"end":39.65,"text":"在我走近你所指的那块墓石之前，\"斯克鲁奇说，\"请回答我一个问题。"},{"start":39.65,"end":45.8,"text":"这些是那些'将要'发生之事的影子呢，还是仅仅那些'可能'发生之事的影子？"},{"start":45.8,"end":49.912,"text":"那鬼魂依旧朝它脚边的那座坟往下指着。"},{"start":49.912,"end":57.062,"text":"人所走的路会预示某种结局，倘若一味走下去，便必定通向那结局，\"斯克鲁奇说。"},{"start":57.062,"end":61.212,"text":"可这路若是被舍弃了，那结局也会随之改变。"},{"start":61.212,"end":64.025,"text":"但愿你指给我看的也是如此！"},{"start":64.025,"end":67.475,"text":"那精灵还是跟先前一样纹丝不动。"},{"start":67.475,"end":77.187,"text":"斯克鲁奇哆嗦着一步步爬向它；顺着那手指，他在那座荒废坟墓的石碑上读出了自己的名字：埃比尼泽·斯克鲁奇。"},{"start":77.187,"end":82.175,"text":"难道我就是躺在那床上的那个人？\"他跪倒在地，嚷道。"},{"start":82.175,"end":85.537,"text":"那手指从坟墓指向他，又指了回去。"},{"start":85.537,"end":87.025,"text":"不，精灵！"},{"start":87.025,"end":88.425,"text":"哦不，不！"}]},"en":{"text":"Here, then, the wretched man whose name he had now to learn, lay underneath the ground.\nIt was a worthy place.\nWalled in by houses; overrun by grass and weeds, the growth of vegetation's death, not life; choked up with too much burying; fat with repleted appetite.\nA worthy place!\nThe Spirit stood among the graves, and pointed down to One.\nHe advanced towards it trembling.\nThe Phantom was exactly as it had been, but he dreaded that he saw new meaning in its solemn shape.\n\"Before I draw nearer to that stone to which you point,\" said Scrooge, \"answer me one question.\nAre these the shadows of the things that Will be, or are they shadows of the things that May be, only?\"\nStill the Ghost pointed downward to the grave by which it stood.\n\"Men's courses will foreshadow certain ends, to which, if persevered in, they must lead,\" said Scrooge.\n\"But if the courses be departed from, the ends will change.\nSay it is thus with what you show me!\"\nThe Spirit was immovable as ever.\nScrooge crept towards it, trembling as he went; and following the finger, read upon the stone of the neglected grave his own name, EBENEZER SCROOGE.\n\"Am _I_ that man who lay upon the bed?\" he cried, upon his knees.\nThe finger pointed from the grave to him, and back again.\n\"No, Spirit!\nOh no, no!\"","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_IV_小节19.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":5.912,"text":"Here, then, the wretched man whose name he had now to learn, lay underneath the ground."},{"start":5.862,"end":8.075,"text":"It was a worthy place."},{"start":8.075,"end":18.625,"text":"Walled in by houses; overrun by grass and weeds, the growth of vegetation's death, not life; choked up with too much burying; fat with repleted appetite."},{"start":18.625,"end":20.6,"text":"A worthy place!"},{"start":20.6,"end":24.887,"text":"The Spirit stood among the graves, and pointed down to One."},{"start":24.887,"end":27.537,"text":"He advanced towards it trembling."},{"start":27.537,"end":33.4,"text":"The Phantom was exactly as it had been, but he dreaded that he saw new meaning in its solemn shape."},{"start":33.4,"end":39.525,"text":"Before I draw nearer to that stone to which you point,\" said Scrooge, \"answer me one question."},{"start":39.525,"end":45.512,"text":"Are these the shadows of the things that Will be, or are they shadows of the things that May be, only?"},{"start":45.512,"end":49.662,"text":"Still the Ghost pointed downward to the grave by which it stood."},{"start":49.662,"end":57,"text":"Men's courses will foreshadow certain ends, to which, if persevered in, they must lead,\" said Scrooge."},{"start":57,"end":61.1,"text":"But if the courses be departed from, the ends will change."},{"start":61.1,"end":63.975,"text":"Say it is thus with what you show me!"},{"start":63.975,"end":66.737,"text":"The Spirit was immovable as ever."},{"start":66.737,"end":76.312,"text":"Scrooge crept towards it, trembling as he went; and following the finger, read upon the stone of the neglected grave his own name, EBENEZER SCROOGE."},{"start":76.312,"end":82.437,"text":"Am _I_ that man who lay upon the bed?\" he cried, upon his knees."},{"start":82.437,"end":86.275,"text":"The finger pointed from the grave to him, and back again."},{"start":86.275,"end":88.437,"text":"No, Spirit!"},{"start":88.437,"end":90.637,"text":"Oh no, no!"}]}},{"id":"IV_20","number":20,"zh":{"text":"那手指依旧指在那儿。\n\"精灵！\"他紧紧攥住它的袍子嚷道，\"听我说！\n我已不是从前那个我了。\n若不是这番交往，我注定会成为的那个人，我决不再去做了。\n倘若我已万念俱灰、无可救药，你又何苦指给我看这个？\"\n那只手仿佛头一回颤动了一下。\n\"善良的精灵，\"他扑倒在它跟前的地上，接着说，\"你的本性在替我求情，怜悯着我。\n请向我担保：凭着改过的生活，我仍能改变你指给我看的这些影子！\"\n那只仁慈的手颤抖了。\n\"我要在心里头敬重圣诞节，还要努力一年到头都守着它。\n我要活在过去、现在和未来里。\n这三位精灵都要在我心中一同奋力。\n他们教给我的训诫，我决不拒之门外。\n哦，告诉我，我还能把这石碑上的字抹掉！\"\n他在极度的痛苦中，抓住了那只幽灵的手。\n它想挣脱开去，可他求得那样恳切、那样有力，硬把它攥住了。\n那精灵到底力气更大，把他推开了。\n他举起双手，作最后一次祈祷，求把自己的命运扭转过来，正在这时，他瞧见那幽灵的兜帽和衣裳起了变化。\n它缩了、瘪了，渐渐萎缩成了一根床柱。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_IV_小节20.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":2.325,"text":"那手指依旧指在那儿。"},{"start":2.275,"end":6.087,"text":"精灵！\"他紧紧攥住它的袍子嚷道，\"听我说！"},{"start":6.087,"end":8.087,"text":"我已不是从前那个我了。"},{"start":8.087,"end":13.037,"text":"若不是这番交往，我注定会成为的那个人，我决不再去做了。"},{"start":13.037,"end":18.025,"text":"倘若我已万念俱灰、无可救药，你又何苦指给我看这个？"},{"start":18.025,"end":20.975,"text":"那只手仿佛头一回颤动了一下。"},{"start":20.975,"end":28.137,"text":"善良的精灵，\"他扑倒在它跟前的地上，接着说，\"你的本性在替我求情，怜悯着我。"},{"start":28.137,"end":33.775,"text":"请向我担保：凭着改过的生活，我仍能改变你指给我看的这些影子！"},{"start":33.775,"end":36.037,"text":"那只仁慈的手颤抖了。"},{"start":36.037,"end":41.1,"text":"我要在心里头敬重圣诞节，还要努力一年到头都守着它。"},{"start":41.1,"end":44.112,"text":"我要活在过去、现在和未来里。"},{"start":44.112,"end":47.575,"text":"这三位精灵都要在我心中一同奋力。"},{"start":47.575,"end":50.975,"text":"他们教给我的训诫，我决不拒之门外。"},{"start":50.975,"end":54.587,"text":"哦，告诉我，我还能把这石碑上的字抹掉！"},{"start":54.587,"end":58.362,"text":"他在极度的痛苦中，抓住了那只幽灵的手。"},{"start":58.362,"end":63.987,"text":"它想挣脱开去，可他求得那样恳切、那样有力，硬把它攥住了。"},{"start":63.987,"end":67.287,"text":"那精灵到底力气更大，把他推开了。"},{"start":67.287,"end":76.462,"text":"他举起双手，作最后一次祈祷，求把自己的命运扭转过来，正在这时，他瞧见那幽灵的兜帽和衣裳起了变化。"},{"start":76.462,"end":80.437,"text":"它缩了、瘪了，渐渐萎缩成了一根床柱。"}]},"en":{"text":"The finger still was there.\n\"Spirit!\" he cried, tight clutching at its robe, \"hear me!\nI am not the man I was.\nI will not be the man I must have been but for this intercourse.\nWhy show me this, if I am past all hope?\"\nFor the first time the hand appeared to shake.\n\"Good Spirit,\" he pursued, as down upon the ground he fell before it: \"Your nature intercedes for me, and pities me.\nAssure me that I yet may change these shadows you have shown me, by an altered life!\"\nThe kind hand trembled.\n\"I will honour Christmas in my heart, and try to keep it all the year.\nI will live in the Past, the Present, and the Future.\nThe Spirits of all Three shall strive within me.\nI will not shut out the lessons that they teach.\nOh, tell me I may sponge away the writing on this stone!\"\nIn his agony, he caught the spectral hand.\nIt sought to free itself, but he was strong in his entreaty, and detained it.\nThe Spirit, stronger yet, repulsed him.\nHolding up his hands in one last prayer to have his fate reversed, he saw an alteration in the Phantom's hood and dress.\nIt shrunk, collapsed, and dwindled down into a bedpost.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_IV_小节20.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":2.412,"text":"The finger still was there."},{"start":2.362,"end":7.087,"text":"Spirit!\" he cried, tight clutching at its robe, \"hear me!"},{"start":7.087,"end":9.525,"text":"I am not the man I was."},{"start":9.525,"end":13.525,"text":"I will not be the man I must have been but for this intercourse."},{"start":13.525,"end":17.075,"text":"Why show me this, if I am past all hope?"},{"start":17.075,"end":20.15,"text":"For the first time the hand appeared to shake."},{"start":20.15,"end":27.887,"text":"Good Spirit,\" he pursued, as down upon the ground he fell before it: \"Your nature intercedes for me, and pities me."},{"start":27.887,"end":33.375,"text":"Assure me that I yet may change these shadows you have shown me, by an altered life!"},{"start":33.375,"end":35.7,"text":"The kind hand trembled."},{"start":35.7,"end":40.05,"text":"I will honour Christmas in my heart, and try to keep it all the year."},{"start":40.05,"end":43.987,"text":"I will live in the Past, the Present, and the Future."},{"start":43.987,"end":47.387,"text":"The Spirits of all Three shall strive within me."},{"start":47.387,"end":50.562,"text":"I will not shut out the lessons that they teach."},{"start":50.562,"end":54.55,"text":"Oh, tell me I may sponge away the writing on this stone!"},{"start":54.55,"end":57.962,"text":"In his agony, he caught the spectral hand."},{"start":57.962,"end":63.125,"text":"It sought to free itself, but he was strong in his entreaty, and detained it."},{"start":63.125,"end":66.587,"text":"The Spirit, stronger yet, repulsed him."},{"start":66.587,"end":73.662,"text":"Holding up his hands in one last prayer to have his fate reversed, he saw an alteration in the Phantom's hood and dress."},{"start":73.662,"end":78.062,"text":"It shrunk, collapsed, and dwindled down into a bedpost."}]}}]},{"id":"Stave_V","title":{"zh":"第五章","en":"STAVE V."},"sections":[{"id":"V_01","number":1,"zh":{"text":"第五章\n故事的结局\n是的！那床柱是他自己的。\n那床是他自己的，那房间是他自己的。\n最好、最叫人欢喜的是，他眼前的光阴是他自己的，好用来弥补前非！\n\"我要活在过去、现在和未来里！\"斯克鲁奇一面手忙脚乱地爬下床，一面重复道。\n\"这三位精灵都要在我心中一同奋力。\n哦，雅各布·马利！\n为这个，赞美上天，赞美这圣诞时节吧！\n我跪着说这话，老雅各布；跪着说！\"\n他被自己满腔的善念激荡得浑身发热、心潮翻涌，那哽咽的嗓子几乎不听他使唤了。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_V_小节01.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":1.325,"text":"第五章"},{"start":1.275,"end":2.9,"text":"故事的结局"},{"start":2.9,"end":3.937,"text":"是的！"},{"start":3.937,"end":6.087,"text":"那床柱是他自己的。"},{"start":6.087,"end":9.862,"text":"那床是他自己的，那房间是他自己的。"},{"start":9.862,"end":16.1,"text":"最好、最叫人欢喜的是，他眼前的光阴是他自己的，好用来弥补前非！"},{"start":16.1,"end":23.05,"text":"我要活在过去、现在和未来里！\"斯克鲁奇一面手忙脚乱地爬下床，一面重复道。"},{"start":23.05,"end":26.512,"text":"这三位精灵都要在我心中一同奋力。"},{"start":26.512,"end":28.85,"text":"哦，雅各布·马利！"},{"start":28.85,"end":32.487,"text":"为这个，赞美上天，赞美这圣诞时节吧！"},{"start":32.487,"end":35.975,"text":"我跪着说这话，老雅各布；跪着说！"},{"start":35.975,"end":43.412,"text":"他被自己满腔的善念激荡得浑身发热、心潮翻涌，那哽咽的嗓子几乎不听他使唤了。"}]},"en":{"text":"STAVE V.\nTHE END OF IT.\nYes! and the bedpost was his own.\nThe bed was his own, the room was his own.\nBest and happiest of all, the Time before him was his own, to make amends in!\n\"I will live in the Past, the Present, and the Future!\" Scrooge repeated, as he scrambled out of bed.\n\"The Spirits of all Three shall strive within me.\nOh Jacob Marley!\nHeaven, and the Christmas Time be praised for this!\nI say it on my knees, old Jacob; on my knees!\"\nHe was so fluttered and so glowing with his good intentions, that his broken voice would scarcely answer to his call.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_V_小节01.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":1.875,"text":"STAVE V."},{"start":1.825,"end":3.45,"text":"THE END OF IT."},{"start":3.45,"end":4.912,"text":"Yes!"},{"start":4.912,"end":7.362,"text":"and the bedpost was his own."},{"start":7.362,"end":10.7,"text":"The bed was his own, the room was his own."},{"start":10.7,"end":16.175,"text":"Best and happiest of all, the Time before him was his own, to make amends in!"},{"start":16.175,"end":20.112,"text":"I will live in the Past, the Present, and the Future!"},{"start":20.112,"end":23.712,"text":"Scrooge repeated, as he scrambled out of bed."},{"start":23.712,"end":27.112,"text":"The Spirits of all Three shall strive within me."},{"start":27.112,"end":29.137,"text":"Oh Jacob Marley!"},{"start":29.137,"end":32.812,"text":"Heaven, and the Christmas Time be praised for this!"},{"start":32.812,"end":37.037,"text":"I say it on my knees, old Jacob; on my knees!"},{"start":37.037,"end":44.062,"text":"He was so fluttered and so glowing with his good intentions, that his broken voice would scarcely answer to his call."}]}},{"id":"V_02","number":2,"zh":{"text":"方才跟那精灵较劲的时候，他一直在剧烈地抽泣，这会儿满脸是泪。\n\"帐子没被扯下来，\"斯克鲁奇把一幅床帐搂进怀里嚷道，\"帐子没被扯下来，连铜环也都还在。\n它们都在这儿：我也在这儿：那些本会发生之事的影子，是可以驱散的。\n它们一定会被驱散。\n我知道它们一定会！\"\n这一向，他的双手一直在跟衣裳较劲：把它们翻过来、倒着穿、扯破、放错地方，由着它们陪自己闹出各式各样的荒唐。\n\"我简直不知道该怎么办才好！\"斯克鲁奇一口气又哭又笑地嚷道；又拿自己的长袜把自己缠成了一个活脱脱的拉奥孔。\n\"我轻得像根羽毛，我快活得像个天使。\n我欢喜得像个小学生。\n我晕陶陶的像个醉汉。\n祝大家圣诞快乐！","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_V_小节02.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":5.95,"text":"方才跟那精灵较劲的时候，他一直在剧烈地抽泣，这会儿满脸是泪。"},{"start":5.9,"end":13.587,"text":"帐子没被扯下来，\"斯克鲁奇把一幅床帐搂进怀里嚷道，\"帐子没被扯下来，连铜环也都还在。"},{"start":13.587,"end":18.925,"text":"它们都在这儿：我也在这儿：那些本会发生之事的影子，是可以驱散的。"},{"start":18.925,"end":21.15,"text":"它们一定会被驱散。"},{"start":21.15,"end":23.162,"text":"我知道它们一定会！"},{"start":23.162,"end":33.362,"text":"这一向，他的双手一直在跟衣裳较劲：把它们翻过来、倒着穿、扯破、放错地方，由着它们陪自己闹出各式各样的荒唐。"},{"start":33.362,"end":43.1,"text":"我简直不知道该怎么办才好！\"斯克鲁奇一口气又哭又笑地嚷道；又拿自己的长袜把自己缠成了一个活脱脱的拉奥孔。"},{"start":43.1,"end":46.55,"text":"我轻得像根羽毛，我快活得像个天使。"},{"start":46.55,"end":48.75,"text":"我欢喜得像个小学生。"},{"start":48.75,"end":51.237,"text":"我晕陶陶的像个醉汉。"},{"start":51.237,"end":53.175,"text":"祝大家圣诞快乐！"}]},"en":{"text":"He had been sobbing violently in his conflict with the Spirit, and his face was wet with tears.\n\"They are not torn down,\" cried Scrooge, folding one of his bed-curtains in his arms, \"they are not torn down, rings and all.\nThey are here: I am here: the shadows of the things that would have been, may be dispelled.\nThey will be.\nI know they will!\"\nHis hands were busy with his garments all this time: turning them inside out, putting them on upside down, tearing them, mislaying them, making them parties to every kind of extravagance.\n\"I don't know what to do!\" cried Scrooge, laughing and crying in the same breath; and making a perfect Laocoön of himself with his stockings.\n\"I am as light as a feather, I am as happy as an angel.\nI am as merry as a school-boy.\nI am as giddy as a drunken man.\nA merry Christmas to everybody!","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_V_小节02.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":5.937,"text":"He had been sobbing violently in his conflict with the Spirit, and his face was wet with tears."},{"start":5.887,"end":14.062,"text":"They are not torn down,\" cried Scrooge, folding one of his bed-curtains in his arms, \"they are not torn down, rings and all."},{"start":14.062,"end":19.812,"text":"They are here: I am here: the shadows of the things that would have been, may be dispelled."},{"start":19.812,"end":21.45,"text":"They will be."},{"start":21.45,"end":23.375,"text":"I know they will!"},{"start":23.375,"end":34.45,"text":"His hands were busy with his garments all this time: turning them inside out, putting them on upside down, tearing them, mislaying them, making them parties to every kind of extravagance."},{"start":34.45,"end":43.287,"text":"I don't know what to do!\" cried Scrooge, laughing and crying in the same breath; and making a perfect Laocoön of himself with his stockings."},{"start":43.287,"end":47.462,"text":"I am as light as a feather, I am as happy as an angel."},{"start":47.462,"end":50.15,"text":"I am as merry as a school-boy."},{"start":50.15,"end":52.85,"text":"I am as giddy as a drunken man."},{"start":52.85,"end":55.425,"text":"A merry Christmas to everybody!"}]}},{"id":"V_03","number":3,"zh":{"text":"祝普天下新年快乐。\n喂，这边！\n嗬！\n喂！\"\n他蹦蹦跳跳地窜进了起居室，这会儿正站在那儿：上气不接下气。\n\"那只盛麦片粥的小锅还在那儿呢！\"斯克鲁奇又撒起欢来，绕着壁炉蹦跳着嚷道。\n\"那扇门还在那儿，雅各布·马利的鬼魂就是从那儿进来的！\n那个墙角还在那儿，当下的圣诞之灵就坐在那儿！\n那扇窗子还在那儿，我就是在那儿瞧见那些游荡的精灵的！\n全都没错，全都是真的，全都发生过。\n哈哈哈！\"","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_V_小节03.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":2.3,"text":"祝普天下新年快乐。"},{"start":2.25,"end":3.712,"text":"喂，这边！"},{"start":3.712,"end":4.575,"text":"嗬！"},{"start":4.575,"end":5.462,"text":"喂！"},{"start":5.462,"end":11,"text":"他蹦蹦跳跳地窜进了起居室，这会儿正站在那儿：上气不接下气。"},{"start":11,"end":17.975,"text":"那只盛麦片粥的小锅还在那儿呢！\"斯克鲁奇又撒起欢来，绕着壁炉蹦跳着嚷道。"},{"start":17.975,"end":22.687,"text":"那扇门还在那儿，雅各布·马利的鬼魂就是从那儿进来的！"},{"start":22.687,"end":26.675,"text":"那个墙角还在那儿，当下的圣诞之灵就坐在那儿！"},{"start":26.675,"end":31.375,"text":"那扇窗子还在那儿，我就是在那儿瞧见那些游荡的精灵的！"},{"start":31.375,"end":35.087,"text":"全都没错，全都是真的，全都发生过。"},{"start":35.087,"end":36.2,"text":"哈哈哈！"}]},"en":{"text":"A happy New Year to all the world.\nHallo here!\nWhoop!\nHallo!\"\nHe had frisked into the sitting-room, and was now standing there: perfectly winded.\n\"There's the saucepan that the gruel was in!\" cried Scrooge, starting off again, and frisking round the fire-place.\n\"There's the door, by which the Ghost of Jacob Marley entered!\nThere's the corner where the Ghost of Christmas Present, sat!\nThere's the window where I saw the wandering Spirits!\nIt's all right, it's all true, it all happened.\nHa ha ha!\"","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_V_小节03.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":2.9,"text":"A happy New Year to all the world."},{"start":2.85,"end":4.637,"text":"Hallo here!"},{"start":4.637,"end":5.962,"text":"Whoop!"},{"start":5.962,"end":7.437,"text":"Hallo!"},{"start":7.437,"end":12.7,"text":"He had frisked into the sitting-room, and was now standing there: perfectly winded."},{"start":12.7,"end":20.15,"text":"There's the saucepan that the gruel was in!\" cried Scrooge, starting off again, and frisking round the fire-place."},{"start":20.15,"end":24.237,"text":"There's the door, by which the Ghost of Jacob Marley entered!"},{"start":24.237,"end":28.162,"text":"There's the corner where the Ghost of Christmas Present, sat!"},{"start":28.162,"end":31.7,"text":"There's the window where I saw the wandering Spirits!"},{"start":31.7,"end":35.55,"text":"It's all right, it's all true, it all happened."},{"start":35.55,"end":37.212,"text":"Ha ha ha!"}]}},{"id":"V_04","number":4,"zh":{"text":"说真的，对一个荒疏了这么多年的人来说，这一笑笑得真叫漂亮，是再灿烂不过的一笑。\n是一长串、一长串璀璨笑声的鼻祖！\n\"我连今儿是几号都不知道！\"斯克鲁奇说。\n\"我不知道自己在那些精灵中间待了多久。\n我什么都不知道。\n我简直成了个娃娃。\n不打紧。\n我才不在乎呢。\n我宁可做个娃娃。\n喂！\n嗬！","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_V_小节04.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":7.137,"text":"说真的，对一个荒疏了这么多年的人来说，这一笑笑得真叫漂亮，是再灿烂不过的一笑。"},{"start":7.087,"end":10.887,"text":"是一长串、一长串璀璨笑声的鼻祖！"},{"start":10.887,"end":14.262,"text":"我连今儿是几号都不知道！\"斯克鲁奇说。"},{"start":14.262,"end":18.15,"text":"我不知道自己在那些精灵中间待了多久。"},{"start":18.15,"end":19.775,"text":"我什么都不知道。"},{"start":19.775,"end":21.775,"text":"我简直成了个娃娃。"},{"start":21.775,"end":22.962,"text":"不打紧。"},{"start":22.962,"end":24.537,"text":"我才不在乎呢。"},{"start":24.537,"end":26.375,"text":"我宁可做个娃娃。"},{"start":26.375,"end":27.262,"text":"喂！"},{"start":27.262,"end":28.125,"text":"嗬！"}]},"en":{"text":"Really, for a man who had been out of practice for so many years, it was a splendid laugh, a most illustrious laugh.\nThe father of a long, long, line of brilliant laughs!\n\"I don't know what day of the month it is!\" said Scrooge.\n\"I don't know how long I've been among the Spirits.\nI don't know anything.\nI'm quite a baby.\nNever mind.\nI don't care.\nI'd rather be a baby.\nHallo!\nWhoop!","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_V_小节04.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":7.812,"text":"Really, for a man who had been out of practice for so many years, it was a splendid laugh, a most illustrious laugh."},{"start":7.762,"end":12.037,"text":"The father of a long, long, line of brilliant laughs!"},{"start":12.037,"end":15.85,"text":"I don't know what day of the month it is!\" said Scrooge."},{"start":15.85,"end":19.075,"text":"I don't know how long I've been among the Spirits."},{"start":19.075,"end":21.025,"text":"I don't know anything."},{"start":21.025,"end":22.987,"text":"I'm quite a baby."},{"start":22.987,"end":24.725,"text":"Never mind."},{"start":24.725,"end":26.475,"text":"I don't care."},{"start":26.475,"end":28.687,"text":"I'd rather be a baby."},{"start":28.687,"end":30.162,"text":"Hallo!"},{"start":30.162,"end":31.487,"text":"Whoop!"}]}},{"id":"V_05","number":5,"zh":{"text":"喂，这边！\"\n他这一阵狂喜被教堂的钟声打断了，那是他听过的最洪亮的一阵齐鸣。\n当啷、铿锵、捶响、叮、咚、钟鸣。\n钟鸣、咚、叮、捶响、铿锵、当啷！\n哦，妙极了，妙极了！\n他奔到窗前，推开窗子，探出头去。\n没有雾，没有霭；明朗、晴亮、欢快、爽利、清冷；这清冷正催着血脉欢跳；金灿灿的阳光；天堂般的晴空；甜润清新的空气；欢快的钟声。\n哦，妙极了。\n妙极了！\n\"今儿是什么日子？\"斯克鲁奇朝下喊着一个穿礼拜日盛装的孩子，那孩子兴许是闲逛到这儿、东张西望来着。\n\"嗯？\"那孩子使出浑身的诧异回道。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_V_小节05.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":1.562,"text":"喂，这边！"},{"start":1.512,"end":7.85,"text":"他这一阵狂喜被教堂的钟声打断了，那是他听过的最洪亮的一阵齐鸣。"},{"start":7.85,"end":12.212,"text":"当啷、铿锵、捶响、叮、咚、钟鸣。"},{"start":12.212,"end":16.45,"text":"钟鸣、咚、叮、捶响、铿锵、当啷！"},{"start":16.45,"end":19.1,"text":"哦，妙极了，妙极了！"},{"start":19.1,"end":22.8,"text":"他奔到窗前，推开窗子，探出头去。"},{"start":22.8,"end":36.5,"text":"没有雾，没有霭；明朗、晴亮、欢快、爽利、清冷；这清冷正催着血脉欢跳；金灿灿的阳光；天堂般的晴空；甜润清新的空气；欢快的钟声。"},{"start":36.5,"end":38.262,"text":"哦，妙极了。"},{"start":38.262,"end":39.487,"text":"妙极了！"},{"start":39.487,"end":47.925,"text":"今儿是什么日子？\"斯克鲁奇朝下喊着一个穿礼拜日盛装的孩子，那孩子兴许是闲逛到这儿、东张西望来着。"},{"start":47.925,"end":48.825,"text":"嗯？"},{"start":48.825,"end":51.525,"text":"那孩子使出浑身的诧异回道。"}]},"en":{"text":"Hallo here!\"\nHe was checked in his transports by the churches ringing out the lustiest peals he had ever heard.\nClash, clang, hammer, ding, dong, bell.\nBell, dong, ding, hammer, clang, clash!\nOh, glorious, glorious!\nRunning to the window, he opened it, and put out his head.\nNo fog, no mist; clear, bright, jovial, stirring, cold; cold, piping for the blood to dance to; Golden sunlight; Heavenly sky; sweet fresh air; merry bells.\nOh, glorious.\nGlorious!\n\"What's to-day?\" cried Scrooge, calling downward to a boy in Sunday clothes, who perhaps had loitered in to look about him.\n\"EH?\" returned the boy, with all his might of wonder.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_V_小节05.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":1.887,"text":"Hallo here!"},{"start":1.837,"end":7.525,"text":"He was checked in his transports by the churches ringing out the lustiest peals he had ever heard."},{"start":7.525,"end":12.262,"text":"Clash, clang, hammer, ding, dong, bell."},{"start":12.262,"end":17.025,"text":"Bell, dong, ding, hammer, clang, clash!"},{"start":17.025,"end":20.25,"text":"Oh, glorious, glorious!"},{"start":20.25,"end":24.3,"text":"Running to the window, he opened it, and put out his head."},{"start":24.3,"end":37.675,"text":"No fog, no mist; clear, bright, jovial, stirring, cold; cold, piping for the blood to dance to; Golden sunlight; Heavenly sky; sweet fresh air; merry bells."},{"start":37.675,"end":39.9,"text":"Oh, glorious."},{"start":39.9,"end":41.612,"text":"Glorious!"},{"start":41.612,"end":49.312,"text":"What's to-day?\" cried Scrooge, calling downward to a boy in Sunday clothes, who perhaps had loitered in to look about him."},{"start":49.312,"end":53.3,"text":"EH?\" returned the boy, with all his might of wonder."}]}},{"id":"V_06","number":6,"zh":{"text":"\"今儿是什么日子呀，我的好孩子？\"斯克鲁奇说。\n\"今儿！\"那孩子答道。\n\"咳，是圣诞节呀。\"\n\"是圣诞节！\"斯克鲁奇自言自语道。\n\"我没把它错过。\n那些精灵一夜之间就把这一切办成了。\n他们爱干什么就能干什么。\n那是自然。\n那是自然。\n喂，我的好孩子！\"\n\"喂！\"那孩子回道。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_V_小节06.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":3.812,"text":"今儿是什么日子呀，我的好孩子？\"斯克鲁奇说。"},{"start":3.762,"end":5.637,"text":"今儿！\"那孩子答道。"},{"start":5.637,"end":7.612,"text":"咳，是圣诞节呀。"},{"start":7.612,"end":10.85,"text":"是圣诞节！\"斯克鲁奇自言自语道。"},{"start":10.85,"end":12.512,"text":"我没把它错过。"},{"start":12.512,"end":15.95,"text":"那些精灵一夜之间就把这一切办成了。"},{"start":15.95,"end":18.562,"text":"他们爱干什么就能干什么。"},{"start":18.562,"end":20,"text":"那是自然。"},{"start":20,"end":21.45,"text":"那是自然。"},{"start":21.45,"end":23.237,"text":"喂，我的好孩子！"},{"start":23.237,"end":24.125,"text":"喂！"},{"start":24.125,"end":25.637,"text":"那孩子回道。"}]},"en":{"text":"\"What's to-day, my fine fellow?\" said Scrooge.\n\"To-day!\" replied the boy.\n\"Why, CHRISTMAS DAY.\"\n\"It's Christmas Day!\" said Scrooge to himself.\n\"I haven't missed it.\nThe Spirits have done it all in one night.\nThey can do anything they like.\nOf course they can.\nOf course they can.\nHallo, my fine fellow!\"\n\"Hallo!\" returned the boy.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_V_小节06.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":4.037,"text":"What's to-day, my fine fellow?\" said Scrooge."},{"start":3.987,"end":6.55,"text":"To-day!\" replied the boy."},{"start":6.55,"end":8.95,"text":"Why, CHRISTMAS DAY."},{"start":8.95,"end":12.587,"text":"It's Christmas Day!\" said Scrooge to himself."},{"start":12.587,"end":14.462,"text":"I haven't missed it."},{"start":14.462,"end":17.487,"text":"The Spirits have done it all in one night."},{"start":17.487,"end":19.925,"text":"They can do anything they like."},{"start":19.925,"end":21.937,"text":"Of course they can."},{"start":21.937,"end":23.95,"text":"Of course they can."},{"start":23.95,"end":26.625,"text":"Hallo, my fine fellow!"},{"start":26.625,"end":29.212,"text":"Hallo!\" returned the boy."}]}},{"id":"V_07","number":7,"zh":{"text":"\"你知道隔一条街拐角上那家家禽铺吗？\"斯克鲁奇问道。\n\"我要是不知道才怪呢，\"那小子答道。\n\"好个伶俐的孩子！\"斯克鲁奇说。\n\"了不起的孩子！\n你知不知道他们挂在那儿的那只得奖火鸡卖掉没有？\n不是那只小的得奖火鸡：是那只大的？\"\n\"什么，那只跟我一般大的？\"那孩子回道。\n\"多讨人喜欢的孩子！\"斯克鲁奇说。\n\"跟他说话真是桩乐事。\n对喽，我的小伙子！\"\n\"它这会儿还挂在那儿呢，\"那孩子答道。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_V_小节07.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":4.787,"text":"你知道隔一条街拐角上那家家禽铺吗？\"斯克鲁奇问道。"},{"start":4.737,"end":7.925,"text":"我要是不知道才怪呢，\"那小子答道。"},{"start":7.925,"end":10.687,"text":"好个伶俐的孩子！\"斯克鲁奇说。"},{"start":10.687,"end":12.287,"text":"了不起的孩子！"},{"start":12.287,"end":16.55,"text":"你知不知道他们挂在那儿的那只得奖火鸡卖掉没有？"},{"start":16.55,"end":19.862,"text":"不是那只小的得奖火鸡：是那只大的？"},{"start":19.862,"end":23.387,"text":"什么，那只跟我一般大的？\"那孩子回道。"},{"start":23.387,"end":26.4,"text":"多讨人喜欢的孩子！\"斯克鲁奇说。"},{"start":26.4,"end":28.837,"text":"跟他说话真是桩乐事。"},{"start":28.837,"end":30.737,"text":"对喽，我的小伙子！"},{"start":30.737,"end":33.787,"text":"它这会儿还挂在那儿呢，\"那孩子答道。"}]},"en":{"text":"\"Do you know the Poulterer's, in the next street but one, at the corner?\" Scrooge inquired.\n\"I should hope I did,\" replied the lad.\n\"An intelligent boy!\" said Scrooge.\n\"A remarkable boy!\nDo you know whether they've sold the prize Turkey that was hanging up there?\nNot the little prize Turkey: the big one?\"\n\"What, the one as big as me?\" returned the boy.\n\"What a delightful boy!\" said Scrooge.\n\"It's a pleasure to talk to him.\nYes, my buck!\"\n\"It's hanging there now,\" replied the boy.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_V_小节07.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":4.562,"text":"Do you know the Poulterer's, in the next street but one, at the corner?"},{"start":4.512,"end":6.625,"text":"Scrooge inquired."},{"start":6.625,"end":9.812,"text":"I should hope I did,\" replied the lad."},{"start":9.812,"end":13,"text":"An intelligent boy!\" said Scrooge."},{"start":13,"end":15.025,"text":"A remarkable boy!"},{"start":15.025,"end":19.075,"text":"Do you know whether they've sold the prize Turkey that was hanging up there?"},{"start":19.075,"end":22.412,"text":"Not the little prize Turkey: the big one?"},{"start":22.412,"end":25.95,"text":"What, the one as big as me?\" returned the boy."},{"start":25.95,"end":29.225,"text":"What a delightful boy!\" said Scrooge."},{"start":29.225,"end":31.587,"text":"It's a pleasure to talk to him."},{"start":31.587,"end":33.825,"text":"Yes, my buck!"},{"start":33.825,"end":36.95,"text":"It's hanging there now,\" replied the boy."}]}},{"id":"V_08","number":8,"zh":{"text":"\"是吗？\"斯克鲁奇说。\n\"去把它买下来。\"\n\"得了吧您！\"那孩子嚷道。\n\"不，不，\"斯克鲁奇说，\"我是当真的。\n去把它买下来，叫他们送到这儿来，我好告诉他们送去哪儿。\n你跟那伙计一道回来，我给你一个先令。\n你要是不出五分钟就跟他一道回来，我给你半个克朗！\"\n那孩子像颗子弹似的射了出去。\n谁要能扣动扳机射出一枪、有这一半快，那他这扣枪的手准是稳极了。\n\"我要把它送到鲍勃·克拉奇特家去！\"斯克鲁奇搓着手悄声说，笑得快要裂开了。\n\"他不会知道是谁送的。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_V_小节08.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":2.225,"text":"是吗？\"斯克鲁奇说。"},{"start":2.175,"end":3.775,"text":"去把它买下来。"},{"start":3.775,"end":6.187,"text":"得了吧您！\"那孩子嚷道。"},{"start":6.187,"end":9.412,"text":"不，不，\"斯克鲁奇说，\"我是当真的。"},{"start":9.412,"end":14.1,"text":"去把它买下来，叫他们送到这儿来，我好告诉他们送去哪儿。"},{"start":14.1,"end":17.3,"text":"你跟那伙计一道回来，我给你一个先令。"},{"start":17.3,"end":21.625,"text":"你要是不出五分钟就跟他一道回来，我给你半个克朗！"},{"start":21.625,"end":24.537,"text":"那孩子像颗子弹似的射了出去。"},{"start":24.537,"end":30.637,"text":"谁要能扣动扳机射出一枪、有这一半快，那他这扣枪的手准是稳极了。"},{"start":30.637,"end":37.637,"text":"我要把它送到鲍勃·克拉奇特家去！\"斯克鲁奇搓着手悄声说，笑得快要裂开了。"},{"start":37.637,"end":40.087,"text":"他不会知道是谁送的。"}]},"en":{"text":"\"Is it?\" said Scrooge.\n\"Go and buy it.\"\n\"Walk-ER!\" exclaimed the boy.\n\"No, no,\" said Scrooge, \"I am in earnest.\nGo and buy it, and tell 'em to bring it here, that I may give them the direction where to take it.\nCome back with the man, and I'll give you a shilling.\nCome back with him in less than five minutes, and I'll give you half-a-crown!\"\nThe boy was off like a shot.\nHe must have had a steady hand at a trigger who could have got a shot off half so fast.\n\"I'll send it to Bob Cratchit's!\" whispered Scrooge, rubbing his hands, and splitting with a laugh.\n\"He sha'n't know who sends it.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_V_小节08.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":2.537,"text":"Is it?\" said Scrooge."},{"start":2.487,"end":4.25,"text":"Go and buy it."},{"start":4.25,"end":6.85,"text":"Walk-ER!\" exclaimed the boy."},{"start":6.85,"end":10.925,"text":"No, no,\" said Scrooge, \"I am in earnest."},{"start":10.925,"end":16.762,"text":"Go and buy it, and tell 'em to bring it here, that I may give them the direction where to take it."},{"start":16.762,"end":20.087,"text":"Come back with the man, and I'll give you a shilling."},{"start":20.087,"end":24.575,"text":"Come back with him in less than five minutes, and I'll give you half-a-crown!"},{"start":24.575,"end":27.1,"text":"The boy was off like a shot."},{"start":27.1,"end":32.287,"text":"He must have had a steady hand at a trigger who could have got a shot off half so fast."},{"start":32.287,"end":38.625,"text":"I'll send it to Bob Cratchit's!\" whispered Scrooge, rubbing his hands, and splitting with a laugh."},{"start":38.625,"end":41.062,"text":"He sha'n't know who sends it."}]}},{"id":"V_09","number":9,"zh":{"text":"它有小蒂姆两个那么大。\n把它送到鲍勃家去，这玩笑乔·米勒一辈子也开不出这么妙的来！\"\n他写地址的那只手并不稳，可他到底还是好歹把它写了出来，便下楼去开临街的门，预备着家禽铺伙计的到来。\n他站在那儿等他来的工夫，那门环映入了他的眼帘。\n\"我要爱它，爱一辈子！\"斯克鲁奇用手拍着它嚷道。\n\"我从前简直没正眼瞧过它。\n它脸上那表情多么忠厚老实！\n真是个了不起的门环！——火鸡来啦。\n喂！\n嗬！\n你好哇！","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_V_小节09.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":2.5,"text":"它有小蒂姆两个那么大。"},{"start":2.45,"end":7.975,"text":"把它送到鲍勃家去，这玩笑乔·米勒一辈子也开不出这么妙的来！"},{"start":7.975,"end":17.075,"text":"他写地址的那只手并不稳，可他到底还是好歹把它写了出来，便下楼去开临街的门，预备着家禽铺伙计的到来。"},{"start":17.075,"end":21.412,"text":"他站在那儿等他来的工夫，那门环映入了他的眼帘。"},{"start":21.412,"end":25.812,"text":"我要爱它，爱一辈子！\"斯克鲁奇用手拍着它嚷道。"},{"start":25.812,"end":28.587,"text":"我从前简直没正眼瞧过它。"},{"start":28.587,"end":31.487,"text":"它脸上那表情多么忠厚老实！"},{"start":31.487,"end":33.637,"text":"真是个了不起的门环！"},{"start":33.637,"end":35.037,"text":"火鸡来啦。"},{"start":35.037,"end":35.925,"text":"喂！"},{"start":35.925,"end":36.787,"text":"嗬！"},{"start":36.787,"end":37.962,"text":"你好哇！"}]},"en":{"text":"It's twice the size of Tiny Tim.\nJoe Miller never made such a joke as sending it to Bob's will be!\"\nThe hand in which he wrote the address was not a steady one, but write it he did, somehow, and went down stairs to open the street door, ready for the coming of the poulterer's man.\nAs he stood there, waiting his arrival, the knocker caught his eye.\n\"I shall love it, as long as I live!\" cried Scrooge, patting it with his hand.\n\"I scarcely ever looked at it before.\nWhat an honest expression it has in its face!\nIt's a wonderful knocker!--Here's the Turkey.\nHallo!\nWhoop!\nHow are you!","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_V_小节09.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":2.975,"text":"It's twice the size of Tiny Tim."},{"start":2.925,"end":7.3,"text":"Joe Miller never made such a joke as sending it to Bob's will be!"},{"start":7.3,"end":17.6,"text":"The hand in which he wrote the address was not a steady one, but write it he did, somehow, and went down stairs to open the street door, ready for the coming of the poulterer's man."},{"start":17.6,"end":22.212,"text":"As he stood there, waiting his arrival, the knocker caught his eye."},{"start":22.212,"end":27.85,"text":"I shall love it, as long as I live!\" cried Scrooge, patting it with his hand."},{"start":27.85,"end":30.812,"text":"I scarcely ever looked at it before."},{"start":30.812,"end":34.212,"text":"What an honest expression it has in its face!"},{"start":34.212,"end":37.4,"text":"It's a wonderful knocker!--Here's the Turkey."},{"start":37.4,"end":38.875,"text":"Hallo!"},{"start":38.875,"end":40.2,"text":"Whoop!"},{"start":40.2,"end":41.837,"text":"How are you!"}]}},{"id":"V_10","number":10,"zh":{"text":"圣诞快乐！\"\n那可当真是只火鸡！\n那鸟儿断断站不住自己的腿。\n它准会一眨眼就把腿啪地折断，像折断一根根火漆棒似的。\n\"咳，要把那玩意儿提到卡姆登镇去可不行，\"斯克鲁奇说。\n\"你非得雇辆马车不可。\"\n他说这话时的那一阵窃笑，他付火鸡钱时的那一阵窃笑，他付车钱时的那一阵窃笑，他打赏那孩子时的那一阵窃笑——比起来都还赶不上他重新气喘吁吁地往椅子上一坐、笑到流出眼泪来的那一阵窃笑。\n刮胡子可不是桩容易的活儿，因为他的手还抖得厉害；刮胡子是要凝神的，便是你刮的时候没手舞足蹈，也得当心。\n不过他就算把鼻子尖儿削掉一块，也准会贴上一小片橡皮膏，照样心满意足。\n他把自己\"通身打扮得齐齐整整\"，末了走到了街上。\n这会儿人们正纷纷涌出，就像他跟当下的圣诞之灵一道瞧见的那样；斯克鲁奇背着手走着，带着一脸欢喜的微笑打量着每一个人。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_V_小节10.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":1.5,"text":"圣诞快乐！"},{"start":1.45,"end":3.55,"text":"那可当真是只火鸡！"},{"start":3.55,"end":6.25,"text":"那鸟儿断断站不住自己的腿。"},{"start":6.25,"end":11.487,"text":"它准会一眨眼就把腿啪地折断，像折断一根根火漆棒似的。"},{"start":11.487,"end":16.175,"text":"咳，要把那玩意儿提到卡姆登镇去可不行，\"斯克鲁奇说。"},{"start":16.175,"end":18.425,"text":"你非得雇辆马车不可。"},{"start":18.425,"end":34.412,"text":"他说这话时的那一阵窃笑，他付火鸡钱时的那一阵窃笑，他付车钱时的那一阵窃笑，他打赏那孩子时的那一阵窃笑——比起来都还赶不上他重新气喘吁吁地往椅子上一坐、笑到流出眼泪来的那一阵窃笑。"},{"start":34.412,"end":43.837,"text":"刮胡子可不是桩容易的活儿，因为他的手还抖得厉害；刮胡子是要凝神的，便是你刮的时候没手舞足蹈，也得当心。"},{"start":43.837,"end":50.462,"text":"不过他就算把鼻子尖儿削掉一块，也准会贴上一小片橡皮膏，照样心满意足。"},{"start":50.462,"end":54.825,"text":"他把自己\"通身打扮得齐齐整整\"，末了走到了街上。"},{"start":54.825,"end":65.95,"text":"这会儿人们正纷纷涌出，就像他跟当下的圣诞之灵一道瞧见的那样；斯克鲁奇背着手走着，带着一脸欢喜的微笑打量着每一个人。"}]},"en":{"text":"Merry Christmas!\"\nIt _was_ a Turkey!\nHe never could have stood upon his legs, that bird.\nHe would have snapped 'em short off in a minute, like sticks of sealing-wax.\n\"Why, it's impossible to carry that to Camden Town,\" said Scrooge.\n\"You must have a cab.\"\nThe chuckle with which he said this, and the chuckle with which he paid for the Turkey, and the chuckle with which he paid for the cab, and the chuckle with which he recompensed the boy, were only to be exceeded by the chuckle with which he sat down breathless in his chair again, and chuckled till he cried.\nShaving was not an easy task, for his hand continued to shake very much; and shaving requires attention, even when you don't dance while you are at it.\nBut if he had cut the end of his nose off, he would have put a piece of sticking-plaister over it, and been quite satisfied.\nHe dressed himself \"all in his best,\" and at last got out into the streets.\nThe people were by this time pouring forth, as he had seen them with the Ghost of Christmas Present; and walking with his hands behind him, Scrooge regarded every one with a delighted smile.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_V_小节10.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":2.1,"text":"Merry Christmas!"},{"start":2.05,"end":4.95,"text":"It _was_ a Turkey!"},{"start":4.95,"end":8.575,"text":"He never could have stood upon his legs, that bird."},{"start":8.575,"end":13.625,"text":"He would have snapped 'em short off in a minute, like sticks of sealing-wax."},{"start":13.625,"end":18.662,"text":"Why, it's impossible to carry that to Camden Town,\" said Scrooge."},{"start":18.662,"end":20.687,"text":"You must have a cab."},{"start":20.687,"end":36.587,"text":"The chuckle with which he said this, and the chuckle with which he paid for the Turkey, and the chuckle with which he paid for the cab, and the chuckle with which he recompensed the boy, were only to be exceeded by the chuckle with which he sat down breathless in his chair again, and chuckled till he cried."},{"start":36.587,"end":45.725,"text":"Shaving was not an easy task, for his hand continued to shake very much; and shaving requires attention, even when you don't dance while you are at it."},{"start":45.725,"end":52.837,"text":"But if he had cut the end of his nose off, he would have put a piece of sticking-plaister over it, and been quite satisfied."},{"start":52.837,"end":57.862,"text":"He dressed himself \"all in his best,\" and at last got out into the streets."},{"start":57.862,"end":68.35,"text":"The people were by this time pouring forth, as he had seen them with the Ghost of Christmas Present; and walking with his hands behind him, Scrooge regarded every one with a delighted smile."}]}},{"id":"V_11","number":11,"zh":{"text":"一句话，他那副样子和气得叫人没法不动心，三四个好脾气的人便说，\"早上好，先生！\n祝您圣诞快乐！\"斯克鲁奇后来常说，在他听过的一切欢快的声音里，那几声在他耳朵里是最最欢快的。\n他没走多远，便瞧见那位体态富态的绅士迎面朝他走来，正是头一天走进他账房、说\"这里是斯克鲁奇与马利商行吧？\"的那一位。一想到这老绅士跟他碰头时会拿什么眼光看他，他心里头便一阵刺痛；可他知道笔直摆在自己面前的是哪一条路，他便走上了那条路。\n\"我亲爱的先生，\"斯克鲁奇加快脚步、双手握住那老绅士的手说。\n\"您好哇？\n我希望您昨儿募捐顺利。\n您可真是太好心了。\n祝您圣诞快乐，先生！\"\n\"斯克鲁奇先生？\"\n\"正是，\"斯克鲁奇说。\n\"那是我的名字，我怕您听了未必舒坦。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_V_小节11.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":7.35,"text":"一句话，他那副样子和气得叫人没法不动心，三四个好脾气的人便说，\"早上好，先生！"},{"start":7.3,"end":15.775,"text":"祝您圣诞快乐！\"斯克鲁奇后来常说，在他听过的一切欢快的声音里，那几声在他耳朵里是最最欢快的。"},{"start":15.775,"end":26.675,"text":"他没走多远，便瞧见那位体态富态的绅士迎面朝他走来，正是头一天走进他账房、说\"这里是斯克鲁奇与马利商行吧？\"的那一位。"},{"start":26.675,"end":38.112,"text":"一想到这老绅士跟他碰头时会拿什么眼光看他，他心里头便一阵刺痛；可他知道笔直摆在自己面前的是哪一条路，他便走上了那条路。"},{"start":38.112,"end":43.45,"text":"我亲爱的先生，\"斯克鲁奇加快脚步、双手握住那老绅士的手说。"},{"start":43.45,"end":44.637,"text":"您好哇？"},{"start":44.637,"end":46.775,"text":"我希望您昨儿募捐顺利。"},{"start":46.775,"end":48.737,"text":"您可真是太好心了。"},{"start":48.737,"end":51.025,"text":"祝您圣诞快乐，先生！"},{"start":51.025,"end":52.7,"text":"斯克鲁奇先生？"},{"start":52.7,"end":54.887,"text":"正是，\"斯克鲁奇说。"},{"start":54.887,"end":58.137,"text":"那是我的名字，我怕您听了未必舒坦。"}]},"en":{"text":"He looked so irresistibly pleasant, in a word, that three or four good-humoured fellows said, \"Good morning, sir!\nA merry Christmas to you!\" And Scrooge said often afterwards, that of all the blithe sounds he had ever heard, those were the blithest in his ears.\nHe had not gone far, when coming on towards him he beheld the portly gentleman, who had walked into his counting-house the day before and said, \"Scrooge and Marley's, I believe?\" It sent a pang across his heart to think how this old gentleman would look upon him when they met; but he knew what path lay straight before him, and he took it.\n\"My dear sir,\" said Scrooge, quickening his pace, and taking the old gentleman by both his hands.\n\"How do you do?\nI hope you succeeded yesterday.\nIt was very kind of you.\nA merry Christmas to you, sir!\"\n\"Mr. Scrooge?\"\n\"Yes,\" said Scrooge.\n\"That is my name, and I fear it may not be pleasant to you.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_V_小节11.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":7.762,"text":"He looked so irresistibly pleasant, in a word, that three or four good-humoured fellows said, \"Good morning, sir!"},{"start":7.712,"end":9.975,"text":"A merry Christmas to you!"},{"start":9.975,"end":17.162,"text":"And Scrooge said often afterwards, that of all the blithe sounds he had ever heard, those were the blithest in his ears."},{"start":17.162,"end":27.412,"text":"He had not gone far, when coming on towards him he beheld the portly gentleman, who had walked into his counting-house the day before and said, \"Scrooge and Marley's, I believe?"},{"start":27.412,"end":35.837,"text":"It sent a pang across his heart to think how this old gentleman would look upon him when they met; but he knew what path lay straight before him, and he took it."},{"start":35.837,"end":42.55,"text":"My dear sir,\" said Scrooge, quickening his pace, and taking the old gentleman by both his hands."},{"start":42.55,"end":44.162,"text":"How do you do?"},{"start":44.162,"end":46.712,"text":"I hope you succeeded yesterday."},{"start":46.712,"end":48.925,"text":"It was very kind of you."},{"start":48.925,"end":51.825,"text":"A merry Christmas to you, sir!"},{"start":51.825,"end":53.675,"text":"Mr. Scrooge?"},{"start":53.675,"end":56.15,"text":"Yes,\" said Scrooge."},{"start":56.15,"end":60.187,"text":"That is my name, and I fear it may not be pleasant to you."}]}},{"id":"V_12","number":12,"zh":{"text":"请容我向您赔个不是。\n还有，劳您行个好\"——说到这儿斯克鲁奇凑到他耳边悄声说了几句。\n\"上帝保佑我！\"那绅士嚷道，仿佛连气都喘不上来了。\n\"我亲爱的斯克鲁奇先生，您当真？\"\n\"务请笑纳，\"斯克鲁奇说。\n\"一个铜板也不少。\n我向您担保，这里头还包着好多笔欠下的旧账呢。\n您肯赏我这个脸吗？\"\n\"我亲爱的先生，\"那一位跟他握着手说。\n\"叫我对这等慷——慷慨，真不知说什么好——\"\n\"什么也别说，劳驾，\"斯克鲁奇回道。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_V_小节12.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":2.125,"text":"请容我向您赔个不是。"},{"start":2.075,"end":7.45,"text":"还有，劳您行个好\"——说到这儿斯克鲁奇凑到他耳边悄声说了几句。"},{"start":7.45,"end":12.075,"text":"上帝保佑我！\"那绅士嚷道，仿佛连气都喘不上来了。"},{"start":12.075,"end":14.9,"text":"我亲爱的斯克鲁奇先生，您当真？"},{"start":14.9,"end":17.362,"text":"务请笑纳，\"斯克鲁奇说。"},{"start":17.362,"end":19.162,"text":"一个铜板也不少。"},{"start":19.162,"end":23.3,"text":"我向您担保，这里头还包着好多笔欠下的旧账呢。"},{"start":23.3,"end":25.187,"text":"您肯赏我这个脸吗？"},{"start":25.187,"end":28.462,"text":"我亲爱的先生，\"那一位跟他握着手说。"},{"start":28.462,"end":32.062,"text":"叫我对这等慷——慷慨，真不知说什么好——"},{"start":32.062,"end":35.35,"text":"什么也别说，劳驾，\"斯克鲁奇回道。"}]},"en":{"text":"Allow me to ask your pardon.\nAnd will you have the goodness\"--here Scrooge whispered in his ear.\n\"Lord bless me!\" cried the gentleman, as if his breath were gone.\n\"My dear Mr. Scrooge, are you serious?\"\n\"If you please,\" said Scrooge.\n\"Not a farthing less.\nA great many back-payments are included in it, I assure you.\nWill you do me that favour?\"\n\"My dear sir,\" said the other, shaking hands with him.\n\"I don't know what to say to such munifi--\"\n\"Don't say anything, please,\" retorted Scrooge.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_V_小节12.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":2.537,"text":"Allow me to ask your pardon."},{"start":2.487,"end":6.35,"text":"And will you have the goodness\"--here Scrooge whispered in his ear."},{"start":6.35,"end":10.937,"text":"Lord bless me!\" cried the gentleman, as if his breath were gone."},{"start":10.937,"end":14.35,"text":"My dear Mr. Scrooge, are you serious?"},{"start":14.35,"end":17.112,"text":"If you please,\" said Scrooge."},{"start":17.112,"end":19.275,"text":"Not a farthing less."},{"start":19.275,"end":23.512,"text":"A great many back-payments are included in it, I assure you."},{"start":23.512,"end":25.637,"text":"Will you do me that favour?"},{"start":25.637,"end":29.687,"text":"My dear sir,\" said the other, shaking hands with him."},{"start":29.687,"end":32.587,"text":"I don't know what to say to such munifi-"},{"start":32.587,"end":36.525,"text":"Don't say anything, please,\" retorted Scrooge."}]}},{"id":"V_13","number":13,"zh":{"text":"\"来看看我吧。\n您肯来看看我吗？\"\n\"我一定来！\"那老绅士嚷道。\n分明他是当真要来的。\n\"谢谢您，\"斯克鲁奇说。\n\"我承您的情了。\n我谢您五十遍。\n祝福您！\"\n他上教堂去了，又在街上走来走去，看着人们匆匆来往，拍拍孩子们的脑袋，跟乞丐攀谈，朝人家的厨房里张望，又抬头望望那些窗子；他发觉样样东西都能给他带来快乐。\n他做梦也没想到，随便哪一趟散步——随便哪一样东西——竟能给他这么多幸福。\n下午，他举步朝他外甥家走去。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_V_小节13.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":1.55,"text":"来看看我吧。"},{"start":1.5,"end":3.137,"text":"您肯来看看我吗？"},{"start":3.137,"end":5.775,"text":"我一定来！\"那老绅士嚷道。"},{"start":5.775,"end":7.9,"text":"分明他是当真要来的。"},{"start":7.9,"end":10.1,"text":"谢谢您，\"斯克鲁奇说。"},{"start":10.1,"end":11.575,"text":"我承您的情了。"},{"start":11.575,"end":13.162,"text":"我谢您五十遍。"},{"start":13.162,"end":14.337,"text":"祝福您！"},{"start":14.337,"end":29.337,"text":"他上教堂去了，又在街上走来走去，看着人们匆匆来往，拍拍孩子们的脑袋，跟乞丐攀谈，朝人家的厨房里张望，又抬头望望那些窗子；他发觉样样东西都能给他带来快乐。"},{"start":29.337,"end":35.512,"text":"他做梦也没想到，随便哪一趟散步——随便哪一样东西——竟能给他这么多幸福。"},{"start":35.512,"end":38.587,"text":"下午，他举步朝他外甥家走去。"}]},"en":{"text":"\"Come and see me.\nWill you come and see me?\"\n\"I will!\" cried the old gentleman.\nAnd it was clear he meant to do it.\n\"Thank'ee,\" said Scrooge.\n\"I am much obliged to you.\nI thank you fifty times.\nBless you!\"\nHe went to church, and walked about the streets, and watched the people hurrying to and fro, and patted children on the head, and questioned beggars, and looked down into the kitchens of houses, and up to the windows; and found that everything could yield him pleasure.\nHe had never dreamed that any walk--that anything--could give him so much happiness.\nIn the afternoon, he turned his steps towards his nephew's house.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_V_小节13.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":1.887,"text":"Come and see me."},{"start":1.837,"end":3.912,"text":"Will you come and see me?"},{"start":3.912,"end":6.725,"text":"I will!\" cried the old gentleman."},{"start":6.725,"end":9.25,"text":"And it was clear he meant to do it."},{"start":9.25,"end":11.95,"text":"Thank'ee,\" said Scrooge."},{"start":11.95,"end":14.387,"text":"I am much obliged to you."},{"start":14.387,"end":16.775,"text":"I thank you fifty times."},{"start":16.775,"end":18.325,"text":"Bless you!"},{"start":18.325,"end":33.212,"text":"He went to church, and walked about the streets, and watched the people hurrying to and fro, and patted children on the head, and questioned beggars, and looked down into the kitchens of houses, and up to the windows; and found that everything could yield him pleasure."},{"start":33.212,"end":38.137,"text":"He had never dreamed that any walk--that anything--could give him so much happiness."},{"start":38.137,"end":42.637,"text":"In the afternoon, he turned his steps towards his nephew's house."}]}},{"id":"V_14","number":14,"zh":{"text":"他从那门前走过了十几趟，才鼓起勇气走上去敲门。\n可他一鼓作气，到底敲了：\"你家主人在家吗，亲爱的？\"斯克鲁奇问那使女。\n好俊的姑娘！\n真俊。\n\"在家，先生。\"\n\"他在哪儿呀，我的乖乖？\"斯克鲁奇说。\n\"他在餐厅里呢，先生，跟女主人一块儿。\n您要是愿意，我领您上楼去。\"\n\"谢谢你。\n他认得我，\"斯克鲁奇说，一只手已经搭在了餐厅的门闩上。\n\"我就从这儿进去吧，我的乖乖。\"","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_V_小节14.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":4.8,"text":"他从那门前走过了十几趟，才鼓起勇气走上去敲门。"},{"start":4.75,"end":11.162,"text":"可他一鼓作气，到底敲了：\"你家主人在家吗，亲爱的？\"斯克鲁奇问那使女。"},{"start":11.162,"end":12.625,"text":"好俊的姑娘！"},{"start":12.625,"end":13.7,"text":"真俊。"},{"start":13.7,"end":15.362,"text":"在家，先生。"},{"start":15.362,"end":18.6,"text":"他在哪儿呀，我的乖乖？\"斯克鲁奇说。"},{"start":18.6,"end":21.875,"text":"他在餐厅里呢，先生，跟女主人一块儿。"},{"start":21.875,"end":24.262,"text":"您要是愿意，我领您上楼去。"},{"start":24.262,"end":25.412,"text":"谢谢你。"},{"start":25.412,"end":30.212,"text":"他认得我，\"斯克鲁奇说，一只手已经搭在了餐厅的门闩上。"},{"start":30.212,"end":32.837,"text":"我就从这儿进去吧，我的乖乖。"}]},"en":{"text":"He passed the door a dozen times, before he had the courage to go up and knock.\nBut he made a dash, and did it: \"Is your master at home, my dear?\" said Scrooge to the girl.\nNice girl!\nVery.\n\"Yes, sir.\"\n\"Where is he, my love?\" said Scrooge.\n\"He's in the dining-room, sir, along with mistress.\nI'll show you up stairs, if you please.\"\n\"Thank'ee.\nHe knows me,\" said Scrooge, with his hand already on the dining-room lock.\n\"I'll go in here, my dear.\"","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_V_小节14.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":5.375,"text":"He passed the door a dozen times, before he had the courage to go up and knock."},{"start":5.325,"end":11.875,"text":"But he made a dash, and did it: \"Is your master at home, my dear?\" said Scrooge to the girl."},{"start":11.875,"end":13.575,"text":"Nice girl!"},{"start":13.575,"end":15,"text":"Very."},{"start":15,"end":17.062,"text":"Yes, sir."},{"start":17.062,"end":20.662,"text":"Where is he, my love?\" said Scrooge."},{"start":20.662,"end":24.662,"text":"He's in the dining-room, sir, along with mistress."},{"start":24.662,"end":27.925,"text":"I'll show you up stairs, if you please."},{"start":27.925,"end":29.387,"text":"Thank'ee."},{"start":29.387,"end":34.462,"text":"He knows me,\" said Scrooge, with his hand already on the dining-room lock."},{"start":34.462,"end":36.987,"text":"I'll go in here, my dear."}]}},{"id":"V_15","number":15,"zh":{"text":"他轻轻把门闩一拧，侧着脸绕过门探了进去。\n他们正瞧着那张桌子（摆设得好不阔气）；因为这些个年轻媳妇在这类事情上总是提心吊胆，爱亲眼看看是否样样妥帖。\n\"弗雷德！\"斯克鲁奇说。\n我的天哪，他那娶进门的外甥媳妇吓了多大一跳！\n斯克鲁奇一时忘了她正搁着脚凳坐在那角落里，不然他说什么也不会这么干的。\n\"哎呀我的老天！\"弗雷德嚷道，\"那是谁呀？\"\n\"是我呀。\n你舅舅斯克鲁奇。\n我来吃饭了。\n你肯让我进来吗，弗雷德？\"","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_V_小节15.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":4.275,"text":"他轻轻把门闩一拧，侧着脸绕过门探了进去。"},{"start":4.225,"end":14.4,"text":"他们正瞧着那张桌子（摆设得好不阔气）；因为这些个年轻媳妇在这类事情上总是提心吊胆，爱亲眼看看是否样样妥帖。"},{"start":14.4,"end":16.7,"text":"弗雷德！\"斯克鲁奇说。"},{"start":16.7,"end":20.937,"text":"我的天哪，他那娶进门的外甥媳妇吓了多大一跳！"},{"start":20.937,"end":27.675,"text":"斯克鲁奇一时忘了她正搁着脚凳坐在那角落里，不然他说什么也不会这么干的。"},{"start":27.675,"end":31.2,"text":"哎呀我的老天！\"弗雷德嚷道，\"那是谁呀？"},{"start":31.2,"end":32.4,"text":"是我呀。"},{"start":32.4,"end":34.25,"text":"你舅舅斯克鲁奇。"},{"start":34.25,"end":35.662,"text":"我来吃饭了。"},{"start":35.662,"end":38.175,"text":"你肯让我进来吗，弗雷德？"}]},"en":{"text":"He turned it gently, and sidled his face in, round the door.\nThey were looking at the table (which was spread out in great array); for these young housekeepers are always nervous on such points, and like to see that everything is right.\n\"Fred!\" said Scrooge.\nDear heart alive, how his niece by marriage started!\nScrooge had forgotten, for the moment, about her sitting in the corner with the footstool, or he wouldn't have done it, on any account.\n\"Why bless my soul!\" cried Fred, \"who's that?\"\n\"It's I.\nYour uncle Scrooge.\nI have come to dinner.\nWill you let me in, Fred?\"","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_V_小节15.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":4.475,"text":"He turned it gently, and sidled his face in, round the door."},{"start":4.425,"end":13.762,"text":"They were looking at the table (which was spread out in great array); for these young housekeepers are always nervous on such points, and like to see that everything is right."},{"start":13.762,"end":16.3,"text":"Fred!\" said Scrooge."},{"start":16.3,"end":20.375,"text":"Dear heart alive, how his niece by marriage started!"},{"start":20.375,"end":28.062,"text":"Scrooge had forgotten, for the moment, about her sitting in the corner with the footstool, or he wouldn't have done it, on any account."},{"start":28.062,"end":32.025,"text":"Why bless my soul!\" cried Fred, \"who's that?"},{"start":32.025,"end":33.5,"text":"It's I."},{"start":33.5,"end":35.637,"text":"Your uncle Scrooge."},{"start":35.637,"end":37.65,"text":"I have come to dinner."},{"start":37.65,"end":40.025,"text":"Will you let me in, Fred?"}]}},{"id":"V_16","number":16,"zh":{"text":"让他进来！\n他没把他的胳膊摇脱了臼，真算万幸。\n不出五分钟他就跟在自家一样自在了。\n再没有比这更热诚的了。\n他外甥媳妇的样子还是先前那般。\n托珀来的时候也是那般。\n那丰满的姐妹来的时候也是那般。\n人人来的时候也都是那般。\n绝妙的聚会，绝妙的游戏，绝妙的同心同德，绝——妙——的快乐！\n可第二天早上他到账房去得很早。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_V_小节16.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":1.537,"text":"让他进来！"},{"start":1.487,"end":5.025,"text":"他没把他的胳膊摇脱了臼，真算万幸。"},{"start":5.025,"end":8.362,"text":"不出五分钟他就跟在自家一样自在了。"},{"start":8.362,"end":10.5,"text":"再没有比这更热诚的了。"},{"start":10.5,"end":13.55,"text":"他外甥媳妇的样子还是先前那般。"},{"start":13.55,"end":15.987,"text":"托珀来的时候也是那般。"},{"start":15.987,"end":19.412,"text":"那丰满的姐妹来的时候也是那般。"},{"start":19.412,"end":21.975,"text":"人人来的时候也都是那般。"},{"start":21.975,"end":28.3,"text":"绝妙的聚会，绝妙的游戏，绝妙的同心同德，绝——妙——的快乐！"},{"start":28.3,"end":31.437,"text":"可第二天早上他到账房去得很早。"}]},"en":{"text":"Let him in!\nIt is a mercy he didn't shake his arm off.\nHe was at home in five minutes.\nNothing could be heartier.\nHis niece looked just the same.\nSo did Topper when _he_ came.\nSo did the plump sister, when _she_ came.\nSo did every one when _they_ came.\nWonderful party, wonderful games, wonderful unanimity, won-der-ful happiness!\nBut he was early at the office next morning.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_V_小节16.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":1.637,"text":"Let him in!"},{"start":1.587,"end":4.85,"text":"It is a mercy he didn't shake his arm off."},{"start":4.85,"end":7.512,"text":"He was at home in five minutes."},{"start":7.512,"end":9.737,"text":"Nothing could be heartier."},{"start":9.737,"end":12.3,"text":"His niece looked just the same."},{"start":12.3,"end":15.937,"text":"So did Topper when _he_ came."},{"start":15.937,"end":20.262,"text":"So did the plump sister, when _she_ came."},{"start":20.262,"end":23.987,"text":"So did every one when _they_ came."},{"start":23.987,"end":29.825,"text":"Wonderful party, wonderful games, wonderful unanimity, won-der-ful happiness!"},{"start":29.825,"end":32.937,"text":"But he was early at the office next morning."}]}},{"id":"V_17","number":17,"zh":{"text":"哦，他到得可早呢。\n只要他能头一个到、逮住迟到的鲍勃·克拉奇特就成！\n那正是他一门心思盼着的事。\n他果真办成了；是的，他办成了！\n钟敲九点。\n不见鲍勃。\n九点一刻。\n不见鲍勃。\n他足足迟了十八分半钟。\n斯克鲁奇敞开房门坐着，好瞧见他走进那水槽小屋。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_V_小节17.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":2.35,"text":"哦，他到得可早呢。"},{"start":2.3,"end":6.887,"text":"只要他能头一个到、逮住迟到的鲍勃·克拉奇特就成！"},{"start":6.887,"end":9.75,"text":"那正是他一门心思盼着的事。"},{"start":9.75,"end":13.15,"text":"他果真办成了；是的，他办成了！"},{"start":13.15,"end":14.625,"text":"钟敲九点。"},{"start":14.625,"end":15.962,"text":"不见鲍勃。"},{"start":15.962,"end":17.35,"text":"九点一刻。"},{"start":17.35,"end":18.687,"text":"不见鲍勃。"},{"start":18.687,"end":21.225,"text":"他足足迟了十八分半钟。"},{"start":21.225,"end":26.175,"text":"斯克鲁奇敞开房门坐着，好瞧见他走进那水槽小屋。"}]},"en":{"text":"Oh he was early there.\nIf he could only be there first, and catch Bob Cratchit coming late!\nThat was the thing he had set his heart upon.\nAnd he did it; yes he did!\nThe clock struck nine.\nNo Bob.\nA quarter past.\nNo Bob.\nHe was full eighteen minutes and a half, behind his time.\nScrooge sat with his door wide open, that he might see him come into the Tank.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_V_小节17.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":2.275,"text":"Oh he was early there."},{"start":2.225,"end":6.85,"text":"If he could only be there first, and catch Bob Cratchit coming late!"},{"start":6.85,"end":10,"text":"That was the thing he had set his heart upon."},{"start":10,"end":12.737,"text":"And he did it; yes he did!"},{"start":12.737,"end":14.95,"text":"The clock struck nine."},{"start":14.95,"end":16.562,"text":"No Bob."},{"start":16.562,"end":18.512,"text":"A quarter past."},{"start":18.512,"end":20.125,"text":"No Bob."},{"start":20.125,"end":24.362,"text":"He was full eighteen minutes and a half, behind his time."},{"start":24.362,"end":29.537,"text":"Scrooge sat with his door wide open, that he might see him come into the Tank."}]}},{"id":"V_18","number":18,"zh":{"text":"他还没开门，帽子就已经摘了；围巾也摘了。\n他一眨眼就坐到了凳子上；奋笔疾书起来，仿佛要把九点钟给追回来似的。\n\"喂！\"斯克鲁奇用他惯常的嗓音吼道，尽力装得像那么回事。\n\"你这是什么意思，这般时辰才来？\"\n\"我很抱歉，先生，\"鲍勃说。\n\"我是迟了。\"\n\"你迟了？\"斯克鲁奇重复道。\n\"是的。\n我看你是迟了。\n劳驾，到这边来一下。\"","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_V_小节18.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":4.237,"text":"他还没开门，帽子就已经摘了；围巾也摘了。"},{"start":4.187,"end":10.625,"text":"他一眨眼就坐到了凳子上；奋笔疾书起来，仿佛要把九点钟给追回来似的。"},{"start":10.625,"end":11.512,"text":"喂！"},{"start":11.512,"end":16.375,"text":"斯克鲁奇用他惯常的嗓音吼道，尽力装得像那么回事。"},{"start":16.375,"end":19.162,"text":"你这是什么意思，这般时辰才来？"},{"start":19.162,"end":21.75,"text":"我很抱歉，先生，\"鲍勃说。"},{"start":21.75,"end":23.137,"text":"我是迟了。"},{"start":23.137,"end":25.637,"text":"你迟了？\"斯克鲁奇重复道。"},{"start":25.637,"end":26.637,"text":"是的。"},{"start":26.637,"end":28.262,"text":"我看你是迟了。"},{"start":28.262,"end":30.425,"text":"劳驾，到这边来一下。"}]},"en":{"text":"His hat was off, before he opened the door; his comforter too.\nHe was on his stool in a jiffy; driving away with his pen, as if he were trying to overtake nine o'clock.\n\"Hallo!\" growled Scrooge, in his accustomed voice as near as he could feign it.\n\"What do you mean by coming here at this time of day?\"\n\"I'm very sorry, sir,\" said Bob.\n\"I _am_ behind my time.\"\n\"You are?\" repeated Scrooge.\n\"Yes.\nI think you are.\nStep this way, if you please.\"","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_V_小节18.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":4.725,"text":"His hat was off, before he opened the door; his comforter too."},{"start":4.675,"end":11.262,"text":"He was on his stool in a jiffy; driving away with his pen, as if he were trying to overtake nine o'clock."},{"start":11.262,"end":16.5,"text":"Hallo!\" growled Scrooge, in his accustomed voice as near as he could feign it."},{"start":16.5,"end":19.662,"text":"What do you mean by coming here at this time of day?"},{"start":19.662,"end":23.037,"text":"I'm very sorry, sir,\" said Bob."},{"start":23.037,"end":26.362,"text":"I _am_ behind my time."},{"start":26.362,"end":29.175,"text":"You are?\" repeated Scrooge."},{"start":29.175,"end":30.612,"text":"Yes."},{"start":30.612,"end":32.45,"text":"I think you are."},{"start":32.45,"end":35.425,"text":"Step this way, if you please."}]}},{"id":"V_19","number":19,"zh":{"text":"\"一年也就这么一回，先生，\"鲍勃从水槽小屋里现出身来央求道。\n\"下不为例。\n昨儿我可乐过头了，先生。\"\n\"喏，我跟你说，我的朋友，\"斯克鲁奇说，\"这种事我可再不能容忍下去了。\n所以呢，\"他从凳子上一跃而起，往鲍勃背心上猛戳了一指头，戳得他踉踉跄跄又退回了水槽小屋，接着说道，\"所以呢，我打算给你加薪！\"\n鲍勃浑身一抖，往那把戒尺跟前凑近了些。\n他一刹那间动了个念头，想用戒尺把斯克鲁奇打翻在地、按住他，再朝院子里的人喊救命、叫他们拿件束身的紧身衣来。\n\"圣诞快乐，鲍勃！\"斯克鲁奇拍着他的背说，那一片诚意是断断错不了的。\n\"祝你圣诞快乐，鲍勃，我的好伙计，比我多年来给你的任何一个圣诞节都更快乐！\n我要给你加薪，还要尽力帮衬你那苦苦挣扎的一家子，咱们今儿下午就来商量商量你的事，一边喝一碗热气腾腾的圣诞香料酒，鲍勃！","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_V_小节19.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":5.537,"text":"一年也就这么一回，先生，\"鲍勃从水槽小屋里现出身来央求道。"},{"start":5.487,"end":6.837,"text":"下不为例。"},{"start":6.837,"end":9.287,"text":"昨儿我可乐过头了，先生。"},{"start":9.287,"end":15.075,"text":"喏，我跟你说，我的朋友，\"斯克鲁奇说，\"这种事我可再不能容忍下去了。"},{"start":15.075,"end":26.887,"text":"所以呢，\"他从凳子上一跃而起，往鲍勃背心上猛戳了一指头，戳得他踉踉跄跄又退回了水槽小屋，接着说道，\"所以呢，我打算给你加薪！"},{"start":26.887,"end":30.9,"text":"鲍勃浑身一抖，往那把戒尺跟前凑近了些。"},{"start":30.9,"end":41.85,"text":"他一刹那间动了个念头，想用戒尺把斯克鲁奇打翻在地、按住他，再朝院子里的人喊救命、叫他们拿件束身的紧身衣来。"},{"start":41.85,"end":48.212,"text":"圣诞快乐，鲍勃！\"斯克鲁奇拍着他的背说，那一片诚意是断断错不了的。"},{"start":48.212,"end":54.762,"text":"祝你圣诞快乐，鲍勃，我的好伙计，比我多年来给你的任何一个圣诞节都更快乐！"},{"start":54.762,"end":65.262,"text":"我要给你加薪，还要尽力帮衬你那苦苦挣扎的一家子，咱们今儿下午就来商量商量你的事，一边喝一碗热气腾腾的圣诞香料酒，鲍勃！"}]},"en":{"text":"\"It's only once a year, sir,\" pleaded Bob, appearing from the Tank.\n\"It shall not be repeated.\nI was making rather merry yesterday, sir.\"\n\"Now, I'll tell you what, my friend,\" said Scrooge, \"I am not going to stand this sort of thing any longer.\nAnd therefore,\" he continued, leaping from his stool, and giving Bob such a dig in the waistcoat that he staggered back into the Tank again: \"and therefore I am about to raise your salary!\"\nBob trembled, and got a little nearer to the ruler.\nHe had a momentary idea of knocking Scrooge down with it; holding him; and calling to the people in the court for help and a strait-waistcoat.\n\"A merry Christmas, Bob!\" said Scrooge, with an earnestness that could not be mistaken, as he clapped him on the back.\n\"A merrier Christmas, Bob, my good fellow, than I have given you, for many a year!\nI'll raise your salary, and endeavour to assist your struggling family, and we will discuss your affairs this very afternoon, over a Christmas bowl of smoking bishop, Bob!","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_V_小节19.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":5.125,"text":"It's only once a year, sir,\" pleaded Bob, appearing from the Tank."},{"start":5.075,"end":7.312,"text":"It shall not be repeated."},{"start":7.312,"end":10.8,"text":"I was making rather merry yesterday, sir."},{"start":10.8,"end":17.887,"text":"Now, I'll tell you what, my friend,\" said Scrooge, \"I am not going to stand this sort of thing any longer."},{"start":17.887,"end":28.637,"text":"And therefore,\" he continued, leaping from his stool, and giving Bob such a dig in the waistcoat that he staggered back into the Tank again: \"and therefore I am about to raise your salary!"},{"start":28.637,"end":32.3,"text":"Bob trembled, and got a little nearer to the ruler."},{"start":32.3,"end":40.337,"text":"He had a momentary idea of knocking Scrooge down with it; holding him; and calling to the people in the court for help and a strait-waistcoat."},{"start":40.337,"end":47.862,"text":"A merry Christmas, Bob!\" said Scrooge, with an earnestness that could not be mistaken, as he clapped him on the back."},{"start":47.862,"end":54,"text":"A merrier Christmas, Bob, my good fellow, than I have given you, for many a year!"},{"start":54,"end":64.137,"text":"I'll raise your salary, and endeavour to assist your struggling family, and we will discuss your affairs this very afternoon, over a Christmas bowl of smoking bishop, Bob!"}]}},{"id":"V_20","number":20,"zh":{"text":"趁你还没再点一个 i 字上的点儿，先去把炉火生旺，再添置一只煤斗吧，鲍勃·克拉奇特！\"\n斯克鲁奇说到做到，而且做得有过之而无不及。\n他做成了这一切，还远不止于此；至于那个并没有死去的小蒂姆，斯克鲁奇成了他的第二个父亲。\n他变成了一个再好不过的朋友、再好不过的东家、再好不过的人，无论在这座古老善良的城市里，还是在这古老善良的世界上任何别的古老善良的城市、市镇或乡区里，都数得着。\n有些人瞧见他这番变化便发笑，可他由着他们笑，压根不把他们放在心上；因为他这人明白事理，晓得这世上但凡有什么好事临头，开头总免不了有些人要笑个痛快；他既晓得这班人横竖是睁眼瞎，便想，让他们眯起眼睛咧嘴笑去，倒也不坏，总比让那毛病以不那么讨喜的形式发作出来强。\n他自己的心在笑：这对他便十二分地足够了。\n打那以后，他再没跟精灵们打过交道，而是终生奉行了\"滴酒不沾\"的原则；人们也总是这样说他：倘若世上当真有谁深谙怎样把圣诞节过好，那这个人非他莫属。\n但愿这话也能真真切切地落到我们头上，落到我们每一个人头上！\n于是，正如小蒂姆所说的，愿上帝保佑我们，保佑每一个人！\n全书完。","audio":"音频_中文/Stave_V_小节20.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":7.012,"text":"趁你还没再点一个 i 字上的点儿，先去把炉火生旺，再添置一只煤斗吧，鲍勃·克拉奇特！"},{"start":6.962,"end":11.262,"text":"斯克鲁奇说到做到，而且做得有过之而无不及。"},{"start":11.262,"end":19.5,"text":"他做成了这一切，还远不止于此；至于那个并没有死去的小蒂姆，斯克鲁奇成了他的第二个父亲。"},{"start":19.5,"end":33.375,"text":"他变成了一个再好不过的朋友、再好不过的东家、再好不过的人，无论在这座古老善良的城市里，还是在这古老善良的世界上任何别的古老善良的城市、市镇或乡区里，都数得着。"},{"start":33.375,"end":57.237,"text":"有些人瞧见他这番变化便发笑，可他由着他们笑，压根不把他们放在心上；因为他这人明白事理，晓得这世上但凡有什么好事临头，开头总免不了有些人要笑个痛快；他既晓得这班人横竖是睁眼瞎，便想，让他们眯起眼睛咧嘴笑去，倒也不坏，总比让那毛病以不那么讨喜的形式发作出来强。"},{"start":57.237,"end":61.175,"text":"他自己的心在笑：这对他便十二分地足够了。"},{"start":61.175,"end":74.587,"text":"打那以后，他再没跟精灵们打过交道，而是终生奉行了\"滴酒不沾\"的原则；人们也总是这样说他：倘若世上当真有谁深谙怎样把圣诞节过好，那这个人非他莫属。"},{"start":74.587,"end":79.637,"text":"但愿这话也能真真切切地落到我们头上，落到我们每一个人头上！"},{"start":79.637,"end":84.862,"text":"于是，正如小蒂姆所说的，愿上帝保佑我们，保佑每一个人！"},{"start":84.862,"end":86.137,"text":"全书完。"}]},"en":{"text":"Make up the fires, and buy another coal-scuttle before you dot another i, Bob Cratchit!\"\nScrooge was better than his word.\nHe did it all, and infinitely more; and to Tiny Tim, who did NOT die, he was a second father.\nHe became as good a friend, as good a master, and as good a man, as the good old city knew, or any other good old city, town, or borough, in the good old world.\nSome people laughed to see the alteration in him, but he let them laugh, and little heeded them; for he was wise enough to know that nothing ever happened on this globe, for good, at which some people did not have their fill of laughter in the outset; and knowing that such as these would be blind anyway, he thought it quite as well that they should wrinkle up their eyes in grins, as have the malady in less attractive forms.\nHis own heart laughed: and that was quite enough for him.\nHe had no further intercourse with Spirits, but lived upon the Total Abstinence Principle, ever afterwards; and it was always said of him, that he knew how to keep Christmas well, if any man alive possessed the knowledge.\nMay that be truly said of us, and all of us!\nAnd so, as Tiny Tim observed, God Bless Us, Every One!\nTHE END.","audio":"音频_英文/Stave_V_小节20.mp3","srt":[{"start":0.1,"end":5.812,"text":"Make up the fires, and buy another coal-scuttle before you dot another i, Bob Cratchit!"},{"start":5.762,"end":8.375,"text":"Scrooge was better than his word."},{"start":8.375,"end":15.15,"text":"He did it all, and infinitely more; and to Tiny Tim, who did NOT die, he was a second father."},{"start":15.15,"end":25.875,"text":"He became as good a friend, as good a master, and as good a man, as the good old city knew, or any other good old city, town, or borough, in the good old world."},{"start":25.875,"end":48.175,"text":"Some people laughed to see the alteration in him, but he let them laugh, and little heeded them; for he was wise enough to know that nothing ever happened on this globe, for good, at which some people did not have their fill of laughter in the outset; and knowing that such as these would be blind anyway, he thought it quite as well that they should wrinkle up their eyes in grins, as have the malady in less attractive forms."},{"start":48.175,"end":52.025,"text":"His own heart laughed: and that was quite enough for him."},{"start":52.025,"end":64.462,"text":"He had no further intercourse with Spirits, but lived upon the Total Abstinence Principle, ever afterwards; and it was always said of him, that he knew how to keep Christmas well, if any man alive possessed the knowledge."},{"start":64.462,"end":68.112,"text":"May that be truly said of us, and all of us!"},{"start":68.112,"end":73.212,"text":"And so, as Tiny Tim observed, God Bless Us, Every One!"},{"start":73.212,"end":74.725,"text":"THE END."}]}}]}]};